<title>Apr_1993: Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?</title>
<h1>Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 20 Apr 93 16:07:39 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#331">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#331">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#331">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#331">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0332.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0330.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0312.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0334.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; "Therefore do not let anyone judge you by what you eat or drink, or with</i><br>
<i>&gt; regard to a religious festival, a New Moon celebration or a SABBATH DAY."</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	- Col 2:16</i><br>
<p>
<p>
First of all look at the context :<br>
<p>
Col 2:14 Blotting out the handwriting of ordinances that was against us, which <br>
         was contrary to us, and took it out of the way, nailing it to his <br>
         cross; (KJV) <br>
Col 2:15 And having spoiled principalities and powers, he made a shew of them <br>
         openly, triumphing over them in it. (KJV) <br>
Col 2:16 Let no man therefore judge you in meat, or in drink, or in respect of <br>
         an holyday, or of the new moon, or of the sabbath days: (KJV) <br>
Col 2:17 Which are a shadow of things to come; but the body is of Christ. <br>
<p>
<p>
We see that this is the classic antinomian proof text. Now as to what the <br>
ordinances really refer to we have <br>
<p>
Heb 9:10 Which stood only in meats and drinks, and divers washings, and carnal <br>
         ordinances, imposed on them until the time of reformation. (KJV) <br>
 <br>
Ie the ceremonial law.<br>
<p>
Having understood that and knowing that the Greek text says as the KJV more<br>
acurately translates it  "the sabbath days" and not The Sabbath DAY we can<br>
begin to understand what is really going on here.<br>
<p>
Obviously what we should not be judged on is the keeping of the ceremonial<br>
law. In fact the reference to Sabbath days refers specifically to the <br>
ceremonial sabbaths not THE Sabbath because these things were a shadow <br>
of things to come as Hebrews so clearly indicates.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
