<title>Apr_1993: Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ</title>
<h1>Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 20 Apr 93 16:55:35 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#333">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#333">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#333">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#333">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0334.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0332.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0176.html">Tim Swensen: "Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0345.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Ruben says of Christ </i><br>
<i>&gt; "He had never been separated from His father, we often are."</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I agree with this statement fully.  But it seems that when I posted</i><br>
<i>&gt; something similiar (and meant what is above) there were howls of protest</i><br>
<i>&gt; from Ruben and others.  Could it be that there is no difference between</i><br>
<i>&gt; my position and his after all?  (acknowledging that there are many positions</i><br>
<i>&gt; far to the left of me).</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve</i><br>
<p>
Howls of protest would depend on if you saw the lack of separation, or <br>
separations being an automatic consequence of being born. Note that I did<br>
not mention any cause of the separation. Generally when many speak of this<br>
separation they do so in a Reformation/Calvinistic/Augustinian sense implying<br>
an inheretance due to begin born subject to Adam's sin. To which I would<br>
"howl" not true !........"Your sins have separated you from God"<br>
<p>
As to whether our positions would agree, I don't know what your fundamental<br>
assumptions are so I can't comment. If you want to know my position have a <br>
little look at Denis Priebe's next article on sin. That defines my position<br>
quite acurately.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
