<!-- body="start" -->
Steve starts with some interesting citations, considering the argument<br>
he states at the end.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Romans 3:23  All have sinned and come short of the glory of God</i><br>
<i>&gt; Isaiah 4:6   For all of us have become like one who is unclean, and </i><br>
<i>&gt;              all our righteous deeds are like a leaf.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Romans 2:10  There is none righteous, not even one.</i><br>
<i>&gt; And from a unknown place in Psalms [try Ps. 51:5--db]:</i><br>
<i>&gt;              Behold, I was shapen in iniquity, and in sin did</i><br>
<i>&gt;              my mother conceive me.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; If indeed people are born not predisposed to good or evil as Ruben asserts,</i><br>
<i>&gt; then is it possible for some other human being to live a totally sinless</i><br>
<i>&gt; life *from birth*, never having to repent of any sin whatsoever?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; If no, explain what enabled Christ to do so.</i><br>
<i>&gt; If yes, why hasn't it happened?</i><br>
<p>
The answer is, yes.  It hasn't happened yet because the conclusion<br>
is based upon a false premiss.  People are born predisposed to evil.<br>
Praise God that Jesus came to save sinners.<br>
<p>
Dan Blake<br>
