<!-- received="Tue Apr 20 23:46:54 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Tue, 20 Apr 1993 23:46:54 -0400 (EDT)" -->
<!-- name="Steven Timm" -->
<!-- email="st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- subject="What is sin part 2" -->
<!-- id="sfpACie00YUo9RQB4G@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Apr_1993: What is sin part 2</title>
<h1>What is sin part 2</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 20 Apr 1993 23:46:54 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#344">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#344">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#344">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#344">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0345.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0343.html">Steven Timm: "What is sin part 3"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
				SIN AS CHOICE<br>
<p>
Now, I would like to focus on the second definition of sin, namely,<br>
sin as choice. In this definition, we are saying many of the same<br>
things that have been stated in the various definitions of original sin.<br>
<p>
We believe that in Adam's original nature, there was nothing that<br>
led him to rebel against God. There were no desires which led him away<br>
from God's will. For Adam it was natural to do right, and it was very<br>
unnatural to do wrong. But with the fall, something changed in Adam's<br>
very nature, in the innermost part of his being. The fall brought to<br>
Adam a bent to evil. His nature was now distorted and twisted, and<br>
Adam now wanted to do what he had hated to do before, namely, to rebel<br>
against God. Now, for Adam, it was natural to sin. Now, it was un-<br>
natural to do right.<br>
<p>
So when we say that we inherit a fallen nature from Adam we must<br>
understand that in its full rigor. We do inherit badness, weakness, and<br>
corruption from Adam. We have the same desires that Adam, in his sinful<br>
state, had. We desire to do wrong; we desire to rebel against God. It<br>
is hard for us to do right. It is more natural to do wrong. I think if<br>
we're honest with ourselves, we will admit that we are our own tempters<br>
all too often. We really do not need Satan to follow us around and<br>
tempt us with all sorts of ideas, because we tempt ourselves quite well.<br>
Our own natures lead us astray. Selfishness seems to be at the very<br>
root of our lives and it makes us do things we know we shouldn't do, but<br>
are sometimes driven to do. So we do inherit very negative tendencies<br>
from Adam, which lead us to do wrong.<br>
<p>
The one difference in this definition from the previous definition<br>
of sin is that we do not inherit guilt or condemnation. We do inherit<br>
everything that Adam could pass on. We inherit all of the leanings, all<br>
of the tendencies. all of the desires, and we are born in a way that God<br>
did not really intend for man to be born. But this definition says<br>
that sin comes through choice; sin does not come through nature. Guilt<br>
is not by nature, but when we choose, then we become guilty. We must<br>
choose to make Adam's decision, the decision to rebel against God, and<br>
then we are guilty.<br>
<p>
We must admit that sinful nature leads very naturally to sinful<br>
choices, and that the nature with which we are born starts us down a<br>
road that will lead to sinful choices. But the point that I would like<br>
to stress is that we are guilty when we make those choices, not before<br>
we make those choices. Therefore, I believe that we must careful~<br>
distinguish between the concepts of evil and guilt.<br>
<p>
These are the two basic definitions of sin. Depending upon which<br>
definition you choose to believe, all of the issues of righteousness by<br>
faith will be colored differently. The decisions you make about justi-<br>
fication and sanctification will be different depending upon the decision<br>
you make about the nature of sin.<br>
<p>
				EVIL AND GUILT<br>
<p>
If we want to define sin as choice, we must make a distinction<br>
between evil and guilt. There is much evil in the world today. There<br>
is evil even in inanimate objects. There is evil in the animal world.<br>
But we don't impute guilt to all of the evil that is apparent in our<br>
world today.<br>
<p>
One of my favorite illustrations is that of the common household<br>
pet, the cat. We enjoy cats who snuggle up on our laps or on our feet,<br>
who like to be petted, who come for their dish of warm milk. But some-<br>
times we forget that there is another side to this animal that we love<br>
to include in our homes. That side of this animal is a bit more vicious.<br>
Have you noticed that a cat is not too merciful with a mouse that he<br>
chooses to make his next meal? When he is able to catch a mouse, he<br>
does not quickly put it out of its misery, but he plays with the mouse.<br>
He, in fact, tortures that mouse, until the mouse finds it physically<br>
impossible to run away and finally gives up. What would we do to a<br>
human being who would torture an animal or a human being in that same<br>
way? We would consider him guilty of the most heinous of crimes, and<br>
probably lock him up for the rest of his life. But what do we do with<br>
the animal who has done that--with our cat? We say that it is part of<br>
the way life is. It is not good that the mouse suffers, but the cat is<br>
not guilty, either. Thus we see some acts as evil but part of the<br>
natural results of sin, and we see some acts for which a person is<br>
guilty.<br>
<p>
Now, to bring this to the human level. If we are pounding a nail,<br>
and we ask a friend to hold that nail, so that we'll be better able to<br>
drive it, we might miss the nail, and hit our friend's thumb. That<br>
thumb of our friend will hurt and be discolored, and will take some time<br>
to heal, but he will probably not accuse us of any personal guilt. He<br>
will treat it as an unfortunate accident.<br>
<p>
Let us take it even one step farther to make the point. If an<br>
infant finds a gun, and, playing with it, shoots his older brother or<br>
sister, we would take that gun away from the infant and simply make<br>
sure that we locked up our firearms better than before. We would<br>
not condemn or judge that individual as guilty. But if a 20-year-old<br>
person takes that same gun and shoots someone else, we would ask the<br>
question, Why? We would want to know if he is guilty of malice.<br>
<p>
So there is a difference between the concepts of evil and guilt.<br>
The word evil simply means that which is bad, negative, or wrong,<br>
the results of sin in a cursed world. Guilt applies to moral respon-<br>
sibility for evil thoughts or acts.<br>
<p>
What I'm saying is that trees and animals are full of sin and<br>
evil, but they are not condemned nor are they redeemed by God, for<br>
they have no knowledge of moral values. Only man has a knowledge of<br>
moral values, and because of this knowledge he is condemned as guilty.<br>
If we are to believe that sin is by choice, we must make a crucial<br>
distinction between evil and guilt. Guilt demands prior knowledge and<br>
willful rebellion. I am suggesting that God's condemnation is always<br>
based upon prior knowledge.<br>
<p>
			RESULT AND PENALTY<br>
<p>
Now we must try to substantiate the hypothesis that there is a<br>
difference between the concepts of evil and guilt. In Gen. 2:17<br>
there is a distinct and clear penalty given for rebelling against God.<br>
Adam was told by God, "But of the tree of the knowledge of good and<br>
evil, thou shalt not eat of it: for in the day that thou eatest<br>
thereof thou shalt surely die." We've been puzzled about that verse,<br>
because it is just as clear that when Adam did eat of the fruit which<br>
Eve gave to him, he didn't die that day. So we have sometimes said,<br>
Well, he began to die. But the Hebrew simply says, "In the day that<br>
thou eatest thereof, dying, thou shalt die." The translation, "In<br>
the day that thou eatest thereof thou shalt surely die," is a good<br>
one. Then why didn't Adam die that day? "Why was not the death<br>
penalty at once enforced in his case? Because a ransom was found.<br>
God's only begotten Son volunteered to take the sin of man upon himself~<br>
and to make an atonement for the fallen race." (1 BC 1082) "The instant<br>
man accepted the temptations of Satan, and did the very things God had<br>
said he should not do, Christ, the Son of God, stood between the living<br>
and the dead, saying, 'Let the punishment fall on me. I will stand in<br>
man's place. He shall have another chance."' (1 BC 1085) "As soon as<br>
there was sin, there was a Savior. . . . As soon as Adam sinned, the<br>
Son of God presented Himself as surety for the human race, with just<br>
as much power to avert the doom pronounced upon the guilty as when He<br>
died upon the cross of Calvary." (1 BC 1084)<br>
<p>
Why didn't Adam die that day? Because the substitute was placed<br>
between the penalty of death and Adam that day. Jesus Christ took<br>
Adam's place that very day. Perhaps this helps us to understand Rev.<br>
13:8, where the Lamb is said to be slain from the foundation of the<br>
world. He actually did pay the penalty and stepped between Adam and<br>
the death penalty on that day. Very soon Adam offered the first<br>
sacrifice which he understood to mean that the Son of God would die<br>
in his place. Thus the penalty for Adam's sin was paid immediately by<br>
Jesus Christ. Jesus Christ took Adam's place immediately. Then will<br>
Adam ever pay that penalty? Will Adam ever die to pay for his sin?<br>
They why did Adam die 930 years later? Did he ever pay the penalty?<br>
Or did he die simply as the result of sin? In fact, we're told that<br>
his death was a blessing, because he had endured so much agony knowing<br>
that his sin had caused all of the sin and pain and suffering that<br>
he had witnessed for 900 years. Thus his death was actually a relief.<br>
This death, the natural death that Adam died, was the result of sins<br>
rather than the penalty of sin. The penalty had been paid by Jesus<br>
Christ. Adam had offered the lamb showing that he understood that<br>
the death penalty had been paid. But the curse remained.<br>
<p>
This means that we must divide the<br>
basic idea of sin into two separate columns.<br>
The column on the left-hand side is labelled<br>
"EVIL," which includes all the things which		SIN<br>
result from sin, and all of this evil leads		/ \<br>
to death. But it leads to the death which	       /   \<br>
Jesus called a sleep, which is not a final	      /     \<br>
end for man. All of the evil and its re-	     /       \<br>
sults lead to death and suffering and all         EVIL      GUILT<br>
of the negative things we see around us.	   |          |<br>
<i>						   |          |</i><br>
But there is another column on the		  \|/        \|/<br>
right-hand side. This one is labelled		 DEATH       HELL<br>
"GUILT." And this column leads to the		(Result)    (Penalty)	<br>
second death, namely hell, which is the<br>
penalty for sin. So we really have two<br>
consequences of sin, don't we? We have<br>
the curse. which is Placed upon this world<br>
and even upon animals and upon all nature, which leads to death, the<br>
first death. This is the result of sin. Then, on the other side, we<br>
have guilt which leads to the penalty for sin, the second death, which<br>
has been paid by Jesus Christ. If we choose to accept Jesus Christ's<br>
salvation, we will never die the second death.<br>
<p>
Now it is true that the atonement covers both of these consequences<br>
of sin, but I would suggest that the atonement must deal with guilt by<br>
forgiving it. The atonement must recreate in the area of the curse and<br>
the first death. It must restore all things to God's original plan, but<br>
it doesn't forgive on that side. It only forgives on the side of guilt.<br>
It can only forgive the penalty. Thus the terms justification and for-<br>
giveness and salvation and the gospel and righteousness and sanctifica-<br>
tion apply particularly to those issues in the right-hand column, those<br>
issues having to do with guilt and penalty and hell. What I'm suggest-<br>
ing is that there is a basic difference between the result of sin and<br>
the penalty of sin. There is a basic difference between the first death<br>
and the second death, and the issues of condemnation and salvation per-<br>
tain to guilt and its penalty particularly. It is these areas that we must<br>
focus on when we speak about righteousness by faith.<br>
<p>
Now, let's look at some texts in the New Testament to see if we<br>
have further evidence of this distinction. In Luke 13:1-5, a story is<br>
told by Jesus to drive home a lesson. Luke says that there were some<br>
present that told him of the Galilieans whose blood had been mingled<br>
with their sacrifices. In other words, they had been killed. "And<br>
Jesus answering said unto them, Suppose ye that these Galileans were<br>
sinners above all the Galileans, because they suffered such things?<br>
I tell you, Nay: but, except ye repent, ye shall all likewise perish.<br>
Or those 18, upon whom the tower in Siloam fell, and slew them, think<br>
ye that they were sinners above all men that dwelt in Jerusalem?<br>
tell you, Nay: but, except ye repent, ye shall all likewise perish."<br>
Here we see that their death was not the direct result of their sin.<br>
Jesus was saying that these Galileans and the ones upon whom the tower<br>
fell were not proved to be more guilty than others because of their<br>
death. Here it ts clear that the first death that they died was not<br>
tied directly to their guilt.<br>
<p>
In John 9:1-3, the disciples saw a blind man, and they asked<br>
Christ, "Who did sin, this man, or his parents, that he was born blind?<br>
Jesus answered, Neither hath this man sinned, nor his parents: but<br>
that the works of God should be made manifest in him." Once again<br>
Jesus was saying that his blindness, the curse with which he was af-<br>
flicted, was not the result of any personal sin, but was the result of<br>
an inheritance which he had received. Jesus is here making a distinction<br>
between personal guilt and the effects or results of sin.<br>
<p>
One text which is very important for us to consider is John 5:24,25.<br>
Unless we understand this distinction, we have Jesus contradicting Him-<br>
self in this passage. "Verily, verily, I say unto you, He that heareth<br>
my word, and believeth on him that sent me, hath everlasting life, and<br>
shall not come into condemnation, but is passed from death unto life."<br>
Jesus is saying that, right now, today, if we believe, we have ever-<br>
lasting life. Right now, we are passed from death to life. But He<br>
continues by saying, "Verily, verily, I say unto you, The hour is coming,<br>
and now is, when the dead shall hear the voice of the Son of God: and<br>
they that hear shall live." We just read in the previous verse that we<br>
are free from death, that we have everlasting life now. And then in<br>
verse 25 we read that we who are dead shall hear the voice of the Son<br>
of God. Unless we make this distinction between the first death and<br>
the second death, we find ourselves in a rather hopeless contradiction.<br>
Jesus is saying that we have eternal life today in Jesus Christ. We<br>
are freed from the penalty of guilt. We have been delivered and we<br>
will never die the second death. But we will die the death which is<br>
called a sleep in Lazarus' case. Later we will hear the voice of the<br>
Son of God and rise from that death. So even those who are forgiven<br>
and are given eternal life will still die the result of the curse of<br>
Adam's sin. We must die because we are in a world which is dying. The<br>
first death cannot be the penalty for sin, since those who possess<br>
eternal life actually die the first death. Eternal life means no second<br>
death, which is the penalty for sin. Another text which expresses this<br>
thought very clearly is I John 5:12,13, in which we are said to have life<br>
in Christ now, today, and yet we know that we will die.<br>
<p>
So I think that-we have good evidence scripturally that there are<br>
different consequences of sin. There is the curse of sin, which leads<br>
to the first death, and there is the penalty of sin, which leads to the<br>
second death. It is legitimate to say that there is a distinction<br>
scripturally between evil as a result of the sin which Adam brought<br>
into the world, and guilt, which has to do with man's personal decision<br>
about God.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
