<title>Apr_1993: Original sin vs. universal sin</title>
<h1>Original sin vs. universal sin</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 1993 00:00:08 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#327">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#327">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#327">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#327">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0328.html">Steven Timm: "Stars in the Crown"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0326.html">Michael Merginio: "Re: Vitamin B12 and vegetarians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0348.html">Dan Blake: "Re: Original sin vs. universal sin"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I noticed in Dennis Priebe's article he carefully omitted several texts<br>
which do not negate his position but raise a deep problem nevertheless<br>
Romans 3:23  "All have sinned and come short of the glory of God"<br>
Isa 4:6 "For all of us have become like one who is unclean, and <br>
all our righteous deeds are like a leaf"<br>
Rom 2:10 "There is none righteous, not even one"<br>
And from a unknown place in Psalms<br>
<p>
"Behold, I was shapen in iniquity, and in sin did my mother conceive me."<br>
<p>
and other texts of the sort.<br>
I will grant that none of these texts actually claim we are born guilty,<br>
but the argument of being "born guilty" is not a common one among SDA's<br>
of any stripe.  The problem we face is not the theory of original sin,<br>
but the cold honest fact that everyone has sinned. (even the little<br>
babies?  I think so.) So I will ask the most pointed question I know how<br>
to ask<br>
<p>
If indeed people are born not predisposed to good or evil as Ruben asserts,<br>
then is it possible for some other human being to live a totally sinless<br>
life *from birth*, never having to repent of any sin whatsoever?<br>
<p>
If no, explain what enabled Christ to do so.<br>
If yes, why hasn't it happened?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
