<!-- subject="Evil and Guilt" -->
<!-- id="AfpAZnu00YUo5RQCZk@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Apr_1993: Evil and Guilt</title>
<h1>Evil and Guilt</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 1993 00:11:31 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#329">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#329">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#329">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#329">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0330.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Necessity of Divinity of Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0328.html">Steven Timm: "Stars in the Crown"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seems that Dennis Priebe's article paints a dismally forensic view <br>
of evil and guilt, creating a false dichotomy between the two.<br>
<p>
Sin of any stripe leads to death, independent of God's intervention.<br>
(But see 1 John 5:16 for some sins that don't).  It is only through the <br>
grace of God that a world that is living in sin can even survive long<br>
enough to have the chance to repent.  Suppose people are smoking cigarettes.<br>
This is a sin whether they know it is right or not.  God does not have<br>
to reach out of the sky to zap them, they are killing themselves.  If<br>
they can't see what they are doing to their bodies, then the fear of<br>
hell fire won't make a difference either.  <br>
<p>
I do not say that people will necessarily be held accountable for sins<br>
of ignorance that are committed, that's God's problem, not mine.  The<br>
same goes for young children.  But God's laws in all sorts of situations<br>
have immediate consequences if broken.  The grace of God saves us from<br>
ultimate punishment, but it also saves us from enough of the immediate<br>
consequences so we can live long enough to make an informed decision<br>
about God, and it works to reform our characters so we can halt the<br>
cycle of self-destruction.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
