<title>Apr_1993: re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?</title>
<h1>re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?</h1>
<i>beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com</i><br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 93 08:40:54 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#354">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#354">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#354">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#354">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0355.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Relationship theology"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0353.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0312.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0357.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi,<br>
<p>
Others may have already answered this, but for myself, this verse<br>
becomes clearer when the complete context is dealt with, particularly<br>
the following verse:<br>
<p>
COL 2:16  Let no man therefore judge you in meat, or in drink, or in respect<br>
          of an holyday, or of the new moon, or of the sabbath days:<br>
COL 2:17  Which are a shadow of things to come; but the body is of Christ.<br>
<p>
Compare this text to Leviticus 23 and you will see that the 7th day sabbath<br>
was not the only sabbath in the Hebrew system.  The various feasts were<br>
also to be observed much as the 7th day was to be observed.  The feasts <br>
were shadows of things to come (e.g., Passover foreshadowed Christ's<br>
sacrifice on Calvary).  The 7th day sabbath was not a shadow (pointing<br>
forward), but a memorial (pointing back to creation).  Therefore, a<br>
reasonable argument can be made that Paul is not including the 7th day<br>
sabbath in this text.<br>
<p>
Hope this helps,<br>
<p>
Gary Beihl (gary.beihl@columbiasc.ncr.com)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
