<title>Apr_1993: Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce</title>
<h1>Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 1993 09:30:16 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#379">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#379">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#379">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#379">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0380.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Scripture songs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0378.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Stars in my Crown?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0342.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Soy Sauce comes in literally hundreds of versions. La Choy, and Kikkoman are<br>
in my opinion not real soy sauces.  La Choy is not brewed, and kikkoman is a<br>
poor brewing Job.  Soy sauce begins life as cooked soybeans.  These are inocculated<br>
with various molds, and allowed to sit and turn green or black.  After fermenting<br>
the beans are generaly crushed, and one or more other molds, and or bacteria<br>
cultures are added.  They then go through more fermentation steps, until<br>
the beans have ripened.  The the beans get ground, pressed and the resulting<br>
fluid has salt added to it and is bottled.  There are dark, light, soy sauces,<br>
mushroom, etc. etc.  My favorite mushroom sauce is Pearl River (a chinese brand)<br>
.  It is a DARK heavy soy sauce, that is primarily used in cooking.  It is a<br>
bit strong for just sprinkeling on food.  My favorite eating sauce is Pon Lai<br>
another chinese soy sauce.  Has a tart sort of taste.  We buy it in the 5 gallon<br>
pail, and refill used soy sauce bottles as needed.  We generaly use about a<br>
gallon or so per year.  I use it exclusively instead of salt. (Yes it has LOTS<br>
of salt), but I like the flavor.  You can go to any well stocked oriental market<br>
and find 20 or 30 varieties of sauce, each of which has a diffrent flavor, <br>
"texture" and usage.  If I ever ran a chinese/oriental restaurant, I think<br>
I would have a "soy sauce bar" available for the clients.<br>
<p>
The process of fermentation breaks down the complex proteins and sugars, and<br>
releases bound nutrients.  Yeasts (alcohol producers) don't enter into the<br>
processing.   It is much more like pickling cucumbers etc.<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
<p>
woody@knapper.cactus.org
woody@chinacat.unicom.com (temporary) is forwareded to woody@knapper
</pre>
