<title>Apr_1993: SDA-   Plants and Music</title>
<h1>SDA-   Plants and Music</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 1993 09:59:18 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#341">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#341">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#341">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#341">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0342.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0340.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Re: Jack in the Box Lies"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0364.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: SDA-   Plants and Music"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One of my interests is tracking down the sources of modern myths<br>
which pass around through the SDA church. Recently my daughter, Toni<br>
came home from a youth meeting with a story about a university study<br>
on plants and music. Very briefly the report said that when classical<br>
music was played the plants grew toward the source while when<br>
rock music was played they grew away from it.<br>
<p>
I heard the same story myself about 20 years ago. The story when<br>
told never sites the source of the reports. I must admit a fair<br>
degree of skepticism on my part about such stories.<br>
<p>
My questions are:<br>
<p>
Does anyone on the NET know the source of the report?<br>
<p>
Are there any corroborative studies in the same area?<br>
<p>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Avondale College<br>
mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au<br>
   .-_|\<br>
  /     \<br>
  \.--._/<br>
       V<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
