<title>Apr_1993: Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce</title>
<h1>Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 93 10:24:12 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#350">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#350">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#350">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#350">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0351.html">Michael Merginio: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0349.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0342.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0368.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
  (TANG BENG YONG) writes:<br>
<i>&gt; Michael Merginio writes:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Actually another good source of B12 is soy sauce.  Even though it may be</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;fermented, and moderately high in sodium.  But considering, you can</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;replace your MSG or normal table salt with it, it's not so bad a trade.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Although it is fermented, i do not think it has any alcohol in it, at least</i><br>
<i>&gt; i can't smell any. It doesn't smell fermented at all, come to that.</i><br>
<p>
There's fermentation, and there's fermentation.<br>
<p>
I have a friend who has quit eating soy sauce (and bread) because they are<br>
produced partly by fermentation.<br>
<p>
The problem is that she hasn't differentiated between not wanting to<br>
ingest alcohol (produced by fermentation) and using other fermentation<br>
processes to produce CO2 (to raise the bread), to produce soy sauce<br>
which, depending on the type, can have anywhere from none to tiny amounts<br>
of alcohol, or to produce acetic acid for various pickling processes.<br>
<p>
I haven't told her yet that sauerkraut, kim chee, or pickles all use<br>
fermentation to a greater or lesser degree in their production.<br>
<p>
But she read "something in Spirit of Prophecy" attacking fermentation...<br>
I don't think she's seen the quote that recommended restraint in one's<br>
intake of pickled foods (which used to be major part of people's diets<br>
before refrigeration showed up.  Pickled food at every meal is one thing,<br>
pickled veggies on occasion is something else entirely.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
