<title>Apr_1993: Re: Relationship theology</title>
<h1>Re: Relationship theology</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 93 10:49:55 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#355">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#355">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#355">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#355">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0356.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "Re: Relationship theology"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0354.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0130.html">Steven Timm: "Relationship theology"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0356.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "Re: Relationship theology"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Apr 19,  2:16pm, Ruben Gonzalez wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re: Relationship theology</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; &gt; No Adam did not sin because he had a bad relationship, it was his sin that</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; &gt; broke a good relationship.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; What was his "sin", in this case?</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; eating of the fruit !</i><br>
<p>
I would like to propose that eating the fruit was the result of the sin.  I believe<br>
the sin was: not trusting and believing in God.  Yes, God said they were not to eat<br>
of the fruit, but the underlying test was were they going to believe God or self.  I<br>
believe that the sin was already committed moments before they ate the fruit, when<br>
they gave in to doubts and distrust.  The eating was the fulfilment or result of the<br>
decision.<br>
<p>
To me, sin takes place in the mind, not in the actions.  That is why it is possible<br>
to do right actions and still be sinning or doing something wrong because you have<br>
wrong motives.  Actions are the result of a decision you make.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Do we know for a fact that Adam did not keep on sinning?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; This is my understanding from my reading of Patriarchs and Prophets.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
I just read in "The Story of Redemption" by EGW this morning in the chapter entitled<br>
"Cain &amp; Abel" (later part of the chapter) that Adam lived a life of "...continual<br>
repentence" after the fall.  Now this may not be conclusive proof that he sinned<br>
again and again but it begs the question why would he be continualy repenting<br>
(remember this meant sacrificing a lamb each time in those days) if he didn't have<br>
any sins to repent of?  To suggest that he was repenting over and over for the ONE<br>
sin in his life is to suggest that he really didn't believe God had forgiven him.<br>
<p>
I will have to look in P&amp;P for your suggested information.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Bruce G. Holm               503-685-1350      email:  bruceh@wv.mentorg.com
Mentor Graphics Corp.       503-685-7000
8005 SW Boeckman Rd.
Wilsonville, OR 97070-7777     Disclaimer:  Opinions expressed are my own!
</pre>
