</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As an SDA pastor I read with interest the questions rasied by Sherman Cox<br>
and Marcus Stringer.  I posed the problem yesterday to three of my "white"<br>
fellow pastors in the Detroit area.  Actually one of them is the pastor of<br>
the Korean church.<br>
<p>
We all recognize the same problems these men pose.  The Korean pastor had<br>
no input because of his ethnic church.  (I preaced there via the pastor's<br>
translating and had a great time, feeling little or no prejudice.)<br>
<p>
One pastor felt the church had some problems when he arrived and tried to<br>
make it clear that this kind of behaviour was beyond that of a Christian.<br>
The second pastor and I both have "black" families in our "white" churches<br>
that are very much involved in the church activities.  In the past one has<br>
been an elder and is not now because of his decision.  Another is currently<br>
a member of the church board and is very much appreciated for her contribution<br>
to tthe church (contribution = leadership contribution).<br>
<p>
I am very comfortable having a more international type church.  A broblem that<br>
concerns me is this:  How can I activly encourage "blacks" and others to join<br>
and feel welcome in my church and not raise the ire of the pastor of the "black"<br>
church in my community?  It would be the same question if I encouraged members<br>
of a smaller "white" church to join my church.<br>
<p>
I am not trying to hide behind this concern.  I would love to have churches<br>
with more ethnic groups represented.  How can I help bring this about?  I for one am a pastor that is willing to listen.<br>
<p>
Michael L. Nickless<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
