I am not sure if I am sending this to the group or just to you, Steve, so<br>
edit if you please and send it on.<br>
<p>
As a member of the MI Conf. Executive Committee, I feel that the money<br>
definetly should be refused.  I may be a "conservitive" or a "liberal"<br>
but I feel a group, as in the church should be true to the convictions<br>
of the group.  Either side that begins to demand that the other follow<br>
the side with the money is going beyond what a Christian should do.  If<br>
God is with the group, the $100 million will make little difference in the<br>
success or failure of the group.<br>
<p>
A pastor recently remarked that he agreed with a recent editorial in the<br>
REview, we need to advertise.  Some of us agreed with a little comment:<br>
If we are doing something, people will know even without advertising, if<br>
we are doing nothing, the best advertising will do little good.  The same<br>
principle applies to the money.  If it comes with a price tag too high, or<br>
with any tag, it must be refused.<br>
<p>
Michael L. Nickless<br>
