<title>Apr_1993: Evil &amp; guilt</title>
<h1>Evil &amp; guilt</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>21 Apr 1993 15:06:38 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#349">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#349">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#349">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#349">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0350.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0348.html">Dan Blake: "Re: Original sin vs. universal sin"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0390.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I don't think Ruben asserted that people are not born predisposed to good<br>
or evil. If I read Priebe's words correctly then he says that we are all<br>
predisposed to evil, but that this predisposition does not equate to guilt<br>
on the part of the individual.<br>
<p>
It seems, according to Priebe at least, that the term "sinful nature" is<br>
a misnomer, and doesn't really make sense. He very much equates sin with<br>
the concept of guilt. So according to his definitions, Christ actually<br>
has an "evil nature". Predisposed towards evil, but not sinful because he<br>
has never chosen to commit a rebellious act.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
