<title>Apr_1993: Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?</title>
<h1>Re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?</h1>
Juha Helminen (<i>jhelmine@utu.fi</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 1993 17:35:01 +0300</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#347">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#347">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#347">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#347">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0348.html">Dan Blake: "Re: Original sin vs. universal sin"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0346.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Union"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0312.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0354.html">beihl@ncrcol.columbiasc.ncr.com: "re: Col 2:16 Any good explanation?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Forwarded message:<br>
<i>&gt; From:	ruben@ee.uts.edu.au (Ruben Gonzalez)</i><br>
<i>&gt;  &gt; "Therefore do not let anyone judge you by what you eat or drink, or with</i><br>
<i>&gt;  &gt; regard to a religious festival, a New Moon celebration or a SABBATH DAY."</i><br>
<i>&gt;  &gt; 	- Col 2:16</i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<i>&gt;  First of all look at the context :</i><br>
...&gt;<br>
<i>&gt;  Ie the ceremonial law.</i><br>
...&gt;<br>
<i>&gt;  Obviously what we should not be judged on is the keeping of the ceremonial</i><br>
<i>&gt;  law. In fact the reference to Sabbath days refers specifically to the </i><br>
<i>&gt;  ceremonial sabbaths not THE Sabbath because these things were a shadow </i><br>
<i>&gt;  of things to come as Hebrews so clearly indicates.</i><br>
<p>
Yes, that is one way to say it.  (From Lev. 23 you can find some/all? of<br>
those sabbaths).<br>
<p>
There is also another version and Bacciocchi Samuele (in the book Sabbath<br>
vs. Sunday, historical survey of sunday... (the name as twice translated)) <br>
says that this could refer to Sabbath or whole week and there is lots of <br>
stuff about non christian ways of celebrate Sabbath (in those centuries).  <br>
Bacciocchi also writes that there is not much commandments about _drinking_ <br>
and eating (times, ways, ...) in ceremonial law.  Colossians has also<br>
their "own theology" which must be taken in to account.<br>
<p>
The conclusion there were that Paul is referencing to the way of celebration<br>
more than the general purpose of Sabbath.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  Ruben.</i><br>
  <br>
Juha<br>
