<title>Apr_1993: Re:  Stars in my Crown</title>
<h1>Re:  Stars in my Crown</h1>
Ray Mialki (<i>rm1g+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 1993 18:35:20 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#361">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#361">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#361">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#361">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0362.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Col 2:16"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0360.html">Michael Nickless: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Early on in my Christian walk, I was starting to get disturbed at some<br>
of the songs we used to sing in our fellowship groups.  "Lord of the<br>
Dance" was one such song.  There was a line in the song that said about<br>
Christ, "I am the Lord of the dance, said He."  Another song was "Come<br>
to the Water", where Christ is attributed as saying "And I strove to<br>
remind you, for those tears I died."  And all this time I thought it was<br>
for my sins that Christ died.<br>
<p>
These songs, like "Stars in my Crown", were written by humans.  They<br>
were not inspired of God in the sense that Scripture is.  But yet,<br>
because music is so powerful, and words to obscure sounds go over and<br>
over in our minds so easily, that oftentimes when we hear lyrics to<br>
songs, we figure they are teaching sound theology.  <br>
<p>
I have been in churches, Adventist and non-Adventist alike, where the<br>
hymns being sung either had very shallow theological content, or<br>
theology that was in error.  Yet they are sung, and people memorize<br>
them, and people are taught by them.  <br>
<p>
"Let the Word of Christ dwell in you richly as you teach and admonish<br>
one another will all wisdom, and as you sing psalms, hymns, and<br>
spiritual songs with gratitude in your hearts to God."  Colossians 3:16.<br>
<p>
It has been the practice of the Reformed Presbyterian Church of North<br>
America to only sing the Psalms of Scripture in our worship.  That way,<br>
we don't have to worry about getting unsound theology through our<br>
singing.  I even got the SDA Church I attended some years back to try<br>
them out.  <br>
<p>
Although the above Scriptural quote speaks of "hymns and spiritual<br>
songs" in addition to psalms, this cannot possibly mean uninspired man<br>
written hymns that we sing in church.  First of all, the titles to the<br>
individual psalm include hymns and spiritual songs.  And by these hymns<br>
and spiritual songs, the word of Christ is to richly dwell in us.  This<br>
cannot happen with unispired human written hymns.  <br>
<p>
Something to think about.<br>
<p>
Ray the kop<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
