<title>Apr_1993: Speedway shell accounts</title>
<h1>Speedway shell accounts</h1>
Speedway Support (<i>support@speedway.net</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 93 19:16 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#418">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#418">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#418">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#418">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0419.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: PROOF BY CAPS LOCK"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0417.html">Woody Baker: "Re: internet access"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
If you would like a shell account on Speedway, please provide us with<br>
the following information:<br>
	<br>
	Your real name.<br>
<p>
	A permanent address.<br>
<p>
	Date of birth.<br>
<p>
	A telephone number where we can contact you to verify this <br>
	information and the hours that we may call.<br>
<p>
	Three or more choices for a login name.  It must be between <br>
	three and eight characters and be all lower-case.<br>
<p>
	An initial password, consisting of at least five characters and<br>
	including a mixture of letters and numbers.  When you log on the <br>
	first time, please change it.<br>
<p>
	Your name as you wish it to appear on the system.  You can<br>
	change this later with the 'chfn' (CHange Full Name) command.<br>
<p>
If you do not hear from us in the next few days, please try the login <br>
name(s) and password you provided, as we may have approved your account<br>
based on other records.<br>
<p>
Note that Speedway was established to enable more people to be<br>
connected to the Internet and beyond.  Telnet access to our systems may<br>
be restricted in the future, since the ability to telnet indicates that<br>
you already have Internet access and we may need the resources to<br>
instead help out people who have no connectivity at all.<br>
<p>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Support Operations
Speedway Free Access
--------------------------------
Our UUCP node name is access1.  Our site name for news purposes (the
name you use in your sys file) is speedway.net.  Assuming a C-News
style sys file on a Unix system, your entry would look like
<p>
speedway.net:rec,news,misc,talk,alt,comp,sci,soc/all::\
/usr/bin/uux - -r -n access1!rnews
<p>
for the sending of one article at a time, or
<p>
speedway.net:rec,news,misc,talk,alt,comp,sci,soc/all:f:access1/togo
<p>
for news batching.
<p>
Our telephone number is +1 503 520 2222.  The call must arrive via
AT&amp;T.  In most areas of the U.S. this can be accomplished by dialing
10288-1-503-520-2222.  All modems are Digicom Scout+ v.32bis models set
to 8N1.
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Support Operations
Speedway Free Access -- Dial 10288-1-503-520-2222 for info
<p>
More on internet access.  Got this via the uupc list.  Here is a FREE
(except for the LD charge) internet/uupc feed.  A friend of mine has a hookup
at 14,400 (he prevents his modem from changing baudrates, that is he
locks it at 14,4000, and has his computer hang up if the line is noisy, and
then retry.  It is working well for him. While I have an account there, I
have not tried it much.
<p>
<p>
