<title>Apr_1993: Re: Col 2:16</title>
<h1>Re: Col 2:16</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 21 Apr 1993 20:17:23 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#362">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#362">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#362">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#362">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0363.html">CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Jack in the Box Lies"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0361.html">Ray Mialki: "Re:  Stars in my Crown"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I've had trouble getting this from WP to elm, but I think I have succeeded,<br>
with help of several experts.  These are my thoughts...&gt; <br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Several things can be said about Col 2:16:</i><br>
<i>&gt; 1.  The context of Col 2:16 deals with what God has done in Christ:</i><br>
<i>&gt; He has reconciled us, liberated us, united us with himself, made us</i><br>
<i>&gt; alive; he has disarmed the enemy and triumphed over him.  In view</i><br>
<i>&gt; of what Christ is and does for us, there is no need to look for</i><br>
<i>&gt; salvation in any other way, certainly not by self-abasement,</i><br>
<i>&gt; worship of angels, submission to rules and regulations about food</i><br>
<i>&gt; and days.  No, if our salvation has been accomplished, we have a</i><br>
<i>&gt; new nature.  We put away old enmities and practices; we put on </i><br>
<i>&gt; love and compassion.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 2.  It is evident from the epistle that someone was teaching heresy</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the Colossian Christians.  They were being taught that salvation</i><br>
<i>&gt; was accomplished, not by Christ, but by human beings' DOING this or</i><br>
<i>&gt; that.  Whether the heresy was pagan or Jewish or a mixture of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; two, we do not know.  But it looks like someone was teaching a kind</i><br>
<i>&gt; of legalistic perfectionism.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 3.  The nouns for "food" and "drink" would be better translated</i><br>
<i>&gt; "eating" and "drinking."  Paul says that the rules for partaking of</i><br>
<i>&gt; food, as taught by the heretical teachers, were not to be worried</i><br>
<i>&gt; about. Compare 2:20-22.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 4.  Paul's Christians at Colossae were not to worry about the</i><br>
<i>&gt; accusations of the heretical party about HOW they calculated or</i><br>
<i>&gt; kept the special days--whether yearly, monthly, or weekly.  The</i><br>
<i>&gt; essence of Christianity is Christ; all else is but shadow.  Not</i><br>
<i>&gt; that the days were not important--Paul himself celebrated the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Jewish festivals--but Christ was so far above and beyond everything</i><br>
<i>&gt; else that the salvation he provided did not need to be "assisted"</i><br>
<i>&gt; by human observances.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 5.  SDAs have often said that in Col 2:16 we have yearly Sabbaths,</i><br>
<i>&gt; monthly Sabbaths, and again yearly Sabbaths.  Interestingly enough,</i><br>
<i>&gt; in all the other cases where the three kinds of days of rest</i><br>
<i>&gt; appear, we are perfectly happy to let them be yearly, monthly, and</i><br>
<i>&gt; weekly Sabbaths.  It would seem that somebody, somewhere in our</i><br>
<i>&gt; history, thought that the only way to protect the</i><br>
<i>&gt; seventh-day-Sabbath was to take it out of this text.  When one</i><br>
<i>&gt; takes into consideration the whole topic of the epistle, one can</i><br>
<i>&gt; leave the Sabbath in 2:16 and yet not have it destroyed: details of</i><br>
<i>&gt; religious observance, as mandated by the heretical teaching, do not</i><br>
<i>&gt; improve chances for salvation, since salvation comes only from</i><br>
<i>&gt; Jesus.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
