Ray,<br>
<p>
I think sin has brought about MANY tears, would you agree?<br>
Should the truth be told, I'm sure the people of Haiti, Germany,<br>
and anywhere else under the Son, would agree.  We humans<br>
(through the help of the Church - IMHO) are so compartmentalized<br>
that we are raised to be oblivious to how acts and feelings are<br>
connected.  We don't give respect to the role of tears (assuming<br>
they're from pain or sorrow) in expressing how sin hurts people,<br>
and won't "allow" (though theological doctrines and TRADITIONS<br>
of the "Church") Christ to be interested in human feeling.  To me, the<br>
Desire of Ages paints quite a different picture.  So I'd differ with you<br>
on the sin vs. tears.<br>
<p>
As for deciding which songs are inspired and which are not,<br>
I think the decision should be made, understanding the context<br>
of the songs.  Some churches have hymn festivals, which might<br>
"debut" new hymns.  This helps believers get a fuller under-<br>
standing and appreciation for the song.  I personally enjoy old<br>
hymns, rearranging the music in classical and jazz styles, or<br>
interpretating them with greater levels of passion than the scores in<br>
which they were written.  Interesting note, the music to a number of<br>
traditional and famous Protestant "hymns" got their origins in the<br>
pubs of Europe.<br>
<p>
Undoubtedly, there are hymns/songs sung by other churches which<br>
would not make the "first cut" in your church's hymnal, and visa versa.<br>
Even with all the attention, and pickiness, we might still find things<br>
like that good old song "What a worm am I", which does seem to fit<br>
with MANY "Christian's" view of inspired theology.<br>
<p>
By All means necessary, let's continue thinking! = 0)<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
