<title>Apr_1993: Re: The $100 Million Question</title>
<h1>Re: The $100 Million Question</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 22 Apr 93 10:00:11 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#388">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#388">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#388">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#388">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0389.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Stars in my Crown"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0387.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Original sin... again."</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0351.html">Michael Merginio: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0352.html">Stephen Alan Turk: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Michael Merginio writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; A college/university is supposed to be a place where alternate thought</i><br>
<i>&gt; is not only expected, but encouraged.</i><br>
<p>
In it's broadest interpretation, this could be appropriately said for a<br>
secular institution.  It's typical humanist-type statement.  But I recommend<br>
caution in such an application to a Christian college/university.  Why?<br>
Because, like humanism, it leaves God out of the picture.  Two tho'ts:<br>
<p>
1) An example of such folly is the experience of D.M. Canright.  As a trained<br>
and well educated theologian, he persuaded himself that if simple folk<br>
such as James White, Hiram Edson, et al, could "come up" with a body of<br>
truth from studying Scripture, how much more could he (!), given his<br>
qualifications.  But he neglected to account for the humility of heart,<br>
the teachable spirit, and the guidance of the Holy Spirit that is requisite<br>
(Mat 11:29, Col 3:12, 1 Tim 6:11, Num 12:3, Ps 25:9, Is 61:1, Zeph 2:3,<br>
1 Cor 1:26, John 16:13).  In consequence, he made shipwreck of his faith.<br>
<p>
2) There are areas of human experience that God does *not* want us to<br>
have knowledge about .. those which are evil.  This was true before<br>
creation (Gen 2:17) as well as after (Rom 16:19, Phil 4:8).  Satan would<br>
have us arrogantly think otherwise (Gen 3:5).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The college experience is to be one where a person should</i><br>
<i>&gt; be allowed to find the true being within oneself.</i><br>
<p>
Echos from the 60s.  One cannot find oneself independent of Christ.<br>
He has a design and a purpose for each one of us (Ps 139:13-17).  Indeed,<br>
without Him, we could not be (e.g., 1 Sam 1:6,19,20; Acts 17:28); we are<br>
not the result of some random or chance event.<br>
<p>
p.s.  Perhaps I should cite the texts at length; for brevity, I haven't.<br>
Please look them up; Isa 55:11 promises a reward.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
