<title>Apr_1993: Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce</title>
<h1>Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 22 Apr 93 11:00:09 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#368">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#368">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#368">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#368">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0369.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Answer to stars on crown"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0367.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Original sin vs. universal sin"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0342.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0379.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Hix writes:<br>
<i>&gt;The problem is that she hasn't differentiated between not wanting to</i><br>
<i>&gt;ingest alcohol (produced by fermentation) and using other fermentation</i><br>
<i>&gt;processes to produce CO2 (to raise the bread), to produce soy sauce</i><br>
<i>&gt;which, depending on the type, can have anywhere from none to tiny amounts</i><br>
<i>&gt;of alcohol, or to produce acetic acid for various pickling processes.</i><br>
<p>
Well, it is true that yeast produces alcohol, but when the bread is baked,<br>
the alcohol is driven off and only insignificant amounts remain, because<br>
ethyl alcohol is a volatile compound (bp 78 deg C). Besides, different<br>
fermentation processes use different microorganisms, with different<br>
products. In yoghurt for example, i don't think any alcohol is produced.<br>
The tiny amounts of alcohol in some fermented products are physiologically<br>
insignificant, because the liver easily detoxifys it (we were taught that<br>
alcohol is a metabolic substrate, ie food, but from what i see, it is<br>
treated more as a toxin than as a source of energy, by the body).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;before refrigeration showed up.  Pickled food at every meal is one thing,</i><br>
<i>&gt;pickled veggies on occasion is something else entirely.</i><br>
<p>
Well, i never heard about the SOP pronouncements on pickles, but i do know<br>
that there is definitely a link between a regular intake of certain types of<br>
pickled veggies and cancer of the oesophagus.<br>
	Actually, Ellen White wrote on a lot of things which are being<br>
scientifically substantiated, but there are still many areas where her<br>
writings do not agree with contemporary science, like what she says about<br>
the harmfulness of masturbation and about the cause of volcanos and<br>
earthquakes. But usually, science eventually comes to agree with her; like<br>
when she spoke of "cancerous germs" people didn't know of any germs that<br>
could cause cancer, however we now know that in animals, several viruses do<br>
so, and in humans, Hepatitis viruses definitely cause primary cancer of the<br>
liver, and there are several viruses that are associated with certain<br>
cancers.<br>
	While on the topic of health, i've noticed that SDAs stear clear of<br>
any foods or substances which have some unnatural effect on the body,<br>
believing that the body works best by itself and should not be interferred<br>
with unnecessarily, and that natural foods are best. However, the attitude<br>
of many other people is opposite to that, and they are always dosing<br>
themselves with all sorts of things hoping to improove the functioning of<br>
the body or to modify its functioning (eg coffee, tea, medicinal herbs,<br>
miracle foods and so on).<br>
	Another strange difference is that while we believe that humans were<br>
created by God, a lot of people (even Christians!) believe that we evolved<br>
from primates, and so there are whole branches of science investigating how<br>
well we resemble primates, and even fish. I was told that anthropologists<br>
study ape behaviour (more than they do human behaviour) to make theories<br>
about human behaviour, which seems to imply that they expect humans to<br>
behave like animals. While there are many similarities between higher<br>
animals and humans, i think they are taking it too far; even if we were<br>
evolved from apes, we are still too different to warrant applying ape<br>
studies to humans in the way in which they have been doing.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
Internet:  med10014@nusunix1.nus.sg<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
