<title>Apr_1993: Re: Original sin vs. universal sin</title>
<h1>Re: Original sin vs. universal sin</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 22 Apr 93 12:07:54 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#367">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#367">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#367">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#367">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0368.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: Vitamin B12 in Soysauce"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0366.html">Michael Nickless: "Re: Can we all get along?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0327.html">Steven Timm: "Original sin vs. universal sin"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I will grant that none of these texts actually claim we are born guilty,</i><br>
<i>&gt; but the argument of being "born guilty" is not a common one among SDA's</i><br>
<i>&gt; of any stripe.  The problem we face is not the theory of original sin,</i><br>
<i>&gt; but the cold honest fact that everyone has sinned. (even the little</i><br>
<i>&gt; babies?  I think so.) So I will ask the most pointed question I know how</i><br>
<i>&gt; to ask</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Every one agrees that all have sinned, this does not really present any <br>
problems in Priebe's argument, that he didn't mention them is irrelevant,<br>
to the issue.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If indeed people are born not predisposed to good or evil as Ruben asserts,</i><br>
<p>
Now, Now here we go again.<br>
<p>
Ruben does NOT assert that people are born not predisposed to good or evil.<br>
<p>
This is the problem, why must people keep assuming that I assert things I don't<br>
I'll tell that if people would listen a bit more and not assume so much we <br>
wouldn't have so many difficulties in communication. (this of course<br>
does not include those who fully understand the imlpications yet choose to<br>
have funny ideas)<br>
<p>
Ruben fully asserts that people ARE born predisposed to evil. However the <br>
predisposition is NOT sin unless it is cherished! Show me one<br>
single verse in the bible that says that predisposition is sin, and I'll<br>
remind of of James when he says, that tempation does not bring death (GUILT)<br>
until the temptation conceives.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; then is it possible for some other human being to live a totally sinless</i><br>
<i>&gt; life *from birth*, never having to repent of any sin whatsoever?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
EGW makes it very clear that NO one can live a sinless life in their own<br>
power because they of themselves can not resist temptation. It is only in<br>
Christ that this can be done.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If no, explain what enabled Christ to do so.</i><br>
<p>
God's indwelling power, through the Spirit. The same power we can have, read<br>
Rom 8.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If yes, why hasn't it happened?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Because we enjoy sin too much. But Christ did it, we can live from now on<br>
without sin if we surrender so completely to God that it is no longer we<br>
who live but Christ who lives in us.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
