<title>Apr_1993: Re:  Stars in my Crown</title>
<h1>Re:  Stars in my Crown</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix3.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 22 Apr 93 12:17:42 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#389">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#389">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#389">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#389">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0390.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0388.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ray the kop writes:<br>
<i>&gt;Christ, "I am the Lord of the dance, said He."  Another song was "Come</i><br>
<i>&gt;to the Water", where Christ is attributed as saying "And I strove to</i><br>
<i>&gt;remind you, for those tears I died."  And all this time I thought it was</i><br>
<i>&gt;for my sins that Christ died.</i><br>
<p>
Personally, i think there is such a thing as poetic liscence and much<br>
allegory and symbolism in poems and songs. Most people know this and don't<br>
take everything in songs as literal. Even in the bible psalms, there is much<br>
symbolism and poetic expression that i do not think is meant to be literal.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Although the above Scriptural quote speaks of "hymns and spiritual</i><br>
<i>&gt;songs" in addition to psalms, this cannot possibly mean uninspired man</i><br>
<i>&gt;written hymns that we sing in church.  First of all, the titles to the</i><br>
<i>&gt;individual psalm include hymns and spiritual songs.  And by these hymns</i><br>
<i>&gt;and spiritual songs, the word of Christ is to richly dwell in us.  This</i><br>
<i>&gt;cannot happen with unispired human written hymns.  </i><br>
<p>
You seem to be implying that whatever is not in the cannon of the bible is<br>
uninspired. Why do you think this? God inspires many people in many<br>
different ways. The bible has its own function, but it is not the one and<br>
only way in which God communicates with humans. And the bible itself is<br>
written by humans too. How do you know that extrabiblical hymns are<br>
uninspired? The people in say, Enoch's time, must have then had a very<br>
limited repetoire of songs to sing.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
internet:	med10014@nusunix1.nus.sg<br>
