<title>Apr_1993: Re: Can we all get along?</title>
<h1>Re: Can we all get along?</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 22 Apr 93 14:19:05 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#385">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#385">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#385">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#385">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0386.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Jack in the Box Lies"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0384.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "soy sauce and b-12"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0255.html">Steven Timm: "Can we all get along?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Michael, it's exciting to read your response.  Number one, the spirit of<br>
rivalry isn't a part of Christ, from the little I've read.  Racism, and <br>
barriers<br>
are not a part of Christ either - no matter who is infected - at least from<br>
what The Desire of Ages, and New Testament gospel writers say.<br>
"Cast is hateful to God.  He ignores everything of this character.  In His<br>
sight the souls of all men [women] are of equal value." [DA p403<br>
"Barriers Broken Down"]<br>
<p>
The greatest way I know of to have people attracted to a church, is to<br>
address THE PEOPLE'S needs.  Make an effort to know _their_ world<br>
from THEIR perspective.  You will never know it a clearly as they do,<br>
but the level of your effort, passion, and determination will be to<br>
significant factor.  The road isn't easy, and your efforts at times, won't<br>
be appreciated by any group.  You're not going to get it overnight<br>
either, so even before you attempt this, latch hold of Jesus.  Let His<br>
efforts, passion, and determination fill you - you're going to need it.<br>
<p>
Don't be silent.  Speak it from the pulpit, in your home, in your member's<br>
homes.  Express it, act it out in the church school, in the "secular" civic<br>
arena.  Don't put your trust in the arms and opinions of man, waiting for<br>
it to be "safe", or popular.  Some may get angry, but others in whom the<br>
Holy Spirit has been sowing seeds, will be encouraged and respond.<br>
<p>
I think that we are called to follow Christ's example and pursue greater<br>
feats in and through Him (not just in volume, but in scope, and tactic)<br>
than what He did while on earth.  He laid the groundwork, gave us<br>
examples, and now calls us to fulfil our "in His image" by being<br>
"merciful, gracious, longsuffering, and abundant in goodness and truth".<br>
We are to create, new variations on His theme of loving service and<br>
self-sacrifice.<br>
<p>
God bless!<br>
Marcus Stringer<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
