<title>Apr_1993: Original sin... again.</title>
<h1>Original sin... again.</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 22 Apr 1993 15:44:37 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#387">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#387">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#387">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#387">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0388.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0386.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Jack in the Box Lies"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0396.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Original sin... again."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have very carefully read the Dennis Priebe article posted by Ruben Gonzalez<br>
called "Will the Real Gospel Please Stand Up?" and I find it to be<br>
a terribly twisted and misleading attempt at replacing the wonderful Gospel of<br>
Christ's grace with a "new gospel" (under the guise of "historic Adventism")<br>
centered on salvation by human effort.  The article fails to present Christ<br>
and His Atonement as the solution to the mire of sin; rather, it challenges<br>
each of us to become our own "savior"  -- with a little help from above,<br>
of course.<br>
<p>
The author is obsessed with "Christian perfection," which he defines as<br>
"total victory over sin."  He concludes that it is possible for us to work out<br>
"a sinless character in a sinful nature."  I call this hogwash fringing on<br>
blasphemy.  While the quasi-gospel Priebe endorses pays lip service to Christ<br>
and to the Atonement,  what is really at its core is perfection by human<br>
effort.  Christian perfection is possible only through faith in Christ<br>
(Romans 4:3), who gives us the gift of His righteousness to replace the<br>
curse of our own filthy rags.  Salvation is all of Christ and none of us<br>
(Galatians 2:16).  Christ is "made unto us wisdom, and righteousness,<br>
and sanctification, and redemption" (1 Corinthians 1:30).  Our salvation<br>
is 100 percent wrapped up in Christ, and our good works, imperfect as they<br>
may be, flow out of our love and appreciation for our wonderful Savior.<br>
EGW says that the quilt of our salvation does not contain "a single thread<br>
of human devising."<br>
<p>
To those in Priebe's camp, Christ's ministry on earth serves as an example<br>
for us and little else.  If we only follow the example, we can ourselves<br>
accomplish all that Christ accomplished.  The Atonement's main function was<br>
to clear the way for us to work out our own salvation.  Christ's role as<br>
our one and only Savior, there being no other name under heaven which can<br>
save us, is barely mentioned.<br>
<p>
THE NATURE OF SIN<br>
Priebe asserts that predestination and the concept of original sin must<br>
go together.  Clearly he is begging the question.  Original sin has nothing<br>
to do with the Reformation misconcept of predestination.  ALL have sinned,<br>
the Bible says.  No one is excluded.  We are conceived (Ps. 51:5) with the<br>
sin of Adam upon us, to which we add our own sinning, thus making us sinners<br>
twice over.  Christ, as the Second Adam, removes the sin of our first parent<br>
from us, and makes provision to cleanse us of our own sins.  Our inherited<br>
sin is only part of the story, and the concept of inherited sin does not,<br>
as Priebe states, remove our responsibility.<br>
<p>
THE NATURE OF CHRIST<br>
Priebe suggests that to argue that Christ was born with the pre-Fall nature<br>
is to say that He had no connection at all with our sinful nature.  That is not<br>
so.  He was fully human and was encumbered with all post-Fall attributes,<br>
except in having man's post-Fall inclination toward evil.  Notice these<br>
striking EGW statements:<br>
<p>
"[Christ] is a brother in our infirmities, but not in possessing like<br>
passions.  As the sinless One, His nature recoiled from evil." (2T 202).<br>
<p>
"In his humanity, Christ was tried with as much greater temptation, with<br>
as much more persevering energy than man is tried by the evil one, as his<br>
nature was greater than man's." (RH 12/20/1892)<br>
<p>
"He [Christ] vanquished Satan in the same nature over which in Eden Satan<br>
obtained the victory." (5BC 1108)<br>
<p>
"Christ conquered as the sinless, unfallen, perfect Man." (UL 17)<br>
<p>
"Christ did not possess the same sinful, corrupt, fallen disloyalty we<br>
possess, for then He could not be a perfect offering."  (3SM 131)<br>
<p>
JUSTIFICATION<br>
Priebe claims that these views cause an unholy overemphasis on justification,<br>
to the exclusion of sanctification.  Yet 1 Corinthians 1:30 points to Christ<br>
as the only basis for the entirety of salvation -- justification, sanctifi-<br>
cation... you name it.  I remember reading an EGW statement where she clearly<br>
warns that we should not try to drive a wedge between justification and<br>
sanctification, for the two are virtually one and both are completely wrapped<br>
up in our Savior Jesus Christ.  If you want to generalize by saying that<br>
justification occurs at conversion and sanctification is a life-long process,<br>
that's okay -- but the mechanism is the same and the Savior is the Same.  It's<br>
all of Christ and none of us.  There is not a single thread of human devising<br>
in the quilt of our salvation.<br>
<p>
PERFECTION<br>
Priebe warns that people who, in his view, have the wrong gospel avoid any<br>
talk of perfection or sinlessness in this life.  He claims that they<br>
believe that "the very effort to attain perfection results in legalism and<br>
a denial of righteousness by faith."  Again, he is exaggerating his case<br>
and building on a false premise.  If a person's "effort" to attain perfection<br>
is centered in self, then that is obviously legalism; but if a person's<br>
"effort" to attain perfection is based on submitting to Christ's will and<br>
receiving as a grace gift His perfect righteousness, then that is the right<br>
kind of effort and the right kind of perfection.  It is actually not our<br>
"effort" at all.  It is our submission to the efforts of Christ on our behalf.<br>
And yes, even after receiving Christ into our hearts, we remain in our sinful<br>
nature until "this corruptible has put on incorruption" (1 Corin. 15:54) at<br>
the last trumpet. But despite this,  we aspire to the perfection of Christ --<br>
and by His grace we are saved.<br>
<p>
It IS possible to have a sinless character in a sinful nature: it is the<br>
sinless character of Christ imputed to us by grace through faith, thereby<br>
making it possible for us to be accounted righteous in the sight of God.<br>
There is no other name given under heaven whereby we might be saved.<br>
<p>
THE RESULTS<br>
Priebe asserts that persons who believe in what he feels is an incorrect<br>
gospel are bound to participate in the following: lowering church standards,<br>
no health reform, Sabbath not important, law not binding, reducing Ellen<br>
White's authority, no 1844 judgment, and no literal sanctuary.  I say this<br>
assertion is drivel; when righteousness by faith is seen in its true light,<br>
as being all of Christ and none of us, then our obedience and our<br>
adherence to light and truth is greatly enriched and enhanced.  We are serving<br>
God out of a true appreciation of His character and a true love for His ways.<br>
We are no longer rendering the sullen submission of a rebel, who, if he dared<br>
to, would break away in rebellion.  The fresh rainfall of heaven has fallen<br>
on the dry, dusty hills of Gilboa.  The truth has set us free...<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
