<h1>Re: Relationship theology</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 22 Apr 93 16:27:56 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#377">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#377">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#377">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#377">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0378.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Stars in my Crown?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0376.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Stars in my Crown?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0130.html">Steven Timm: "Relationship theology"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; To me, sin takes place in the mind, not in the actions.  That is why it is </i><br>
possible<br>
<i>&gt; to do right actions and still be sinning or doing something wrong because </i><br>
you have<br>
<i>&gt; wrong motives.  Actions are the result of a decision you make.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
The act of chosing or consenting is also an act but takes place in the mind.<br>
The decision you make are action, acts of the will.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; "Cain &amp; Abel" (later part of the chapter) that Adam lived a life of</i><br>
 "...continual<br>
<i>&gt; repentence" after the fall.Now this may not be conclusive proof that he sinned</i><br>
<i>&gt; again and again but it begs the question why would he be continualy repenting</i><br>
<i>&gt; (remember this meant sacrificing a lamb each time in those days) if he didn't</i><br>
 have<br>
<i>&gt; any sins to repent of?  To suggest that he was repenting over and over for the ONE</i><br>
<i>&gt; sin in his life is to suggest that he really didn't believe God had forgiven him.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I will have to look in P&amp;P for your suggested information.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; --Bruce</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
I would suggest that one can live a life of continual repentance after having <br>
comitted just one sin, repentance means much more than just saying, "I'm sorry"<br>
also being continually repentant has nothing to do with whether a sin has been<br>
forgiven or not. Further continual repentance does not imply constantly <br>
sacificing lambs.<br>
<p>
Repentance means a turning away from sin, abandoning sin, if he lived a life<br>
of continuingly turning away from sin then that would mean not doing any more<br>
sin.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben<br>
