<title>Apr_1993: Two in one (just for you Steve)</title>
<h1>Two in one (just for you Steve)</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>22 Apr 1993 17:44:41 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#391">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#391">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#391">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#391">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0392.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Original Sin... again"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0390.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1. Yes, the jive about stars in the crown is definitely in Early Writings.<br>
   I found it a little disturbing, to be honest, to read some of the <br>
   descriptions of the commandment-keepers feeling that they had earned<br>
   the rights to the holy city, and also how they watched with some<br>
   degree of satisfaction as judgment was declared on the unworthy.<br>
   (At least that was the impression I was getting, maybe that wasn't<br>
   quite right).<br>
<p>
   It wasn't that I was "disagreeing" with E.G.White, or questioning<br>
   her inspiration, I was just reading Early Writings to check it out<br>
   and wasn't comfortable with that. I think I myself would feel<br>
   extremely grateful rather than extremely worthy to be walking into<br>
   the holy city!!<br>
<p>
<p>
2. About Adam's sin, eating the fruit and so on. There seems to be some<br>
   discussion over exactly when the "sin" occurred. When he doubted God,<br>
   or when he ate the fruit?<br>
<p>
   I think the discussion *may* be a bit academic, just from reading the<br>
   messages it seems to me that both sides agree. That is, once Adam<br>
   made the decision to disobey, he sinned. It's like basketball, "fouled<br>
   in the act of shooting". The act of eating the fruit commenced when<br>
   he decided to do it.<br>
<p>
   Just to make sure I've judged correctly... would you agree that if<br>
   Adam doubted God, then decided that doubting God was a bad idea and<br>
   didn't eat the fruit, that he didn't sin? If so, then you agree that<br>
   the act of eating the fruit coincided with the severance of his<br>
   relationship with God, and whichever way you define sin, there it is.<br>
<p>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
