<title>Apr_1993: Re: Stars in my Crown?</title>
<h1>Re: Stars in my Crown?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 25 Apr 1993 12:32:24 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#376">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#376">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#376">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#376">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0377.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Relationship theology"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0375.html">Steven Timm: "The Ruben Conspiracy"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hello fellow netters,<br>
<p>
I'd like to respond with a few comments on "Stars in my Crown" and related<br>
issues.<br>
<p>
Thanks Andrew for the reference to Early Writings.  However, your reference<br>
brings up the question again asked earlier (I don't remember who):<br>
<p>
When reading EGW, where do we draw the line between symbolic visions and<br>
reality.  To repeat the earlier comment - EGW is travelling on a road "high<br>
above the earth" etc etc.  We all know that is symbolic.  However, in the<br>
same vision, as she crosses the chasm into heaven, we find "flowers that<br>
will never fade" and children "using their little wings" etc.<br>
<p>
Now I don't at all want to eat up somebody's faith in heaven - but why is<br>
the first part of the vision taken figuratively, and the second part<br>
literally?  I think we must be more careful in interpretation of inspired<br>
writings than we often are.<br>
<p>
Now - back to the crowns.  Maybe we won't have stars in our crowns - or for<br>
that matter, maybe we won't have crowns at all!  But does it really matter?<br>
Isn't the message of the EGW vision (and for that matter the song as well)<br>
that there is infinite satisfaction in knowing the Lord has seen fit to use<br>
(imperfect) me as an instrument in bringing someone else closer to Him?<br>
And then EGW goes further in bringing the message that in heaven there won't<br>
be jelousy as to who gets the most satisfaction!<br>
<p>
So what will heaven be like?  Do we say "if there is no marraige in heaven<br>
I don't want to go"?  A little girl (who I know) asked once "Will there be<br>
peanutbutter in heaven?"  To her, this was an all-important question - but<br>
to us somewhat trivial.  I think God smiles sometimes as he hears our<br>
"peanut butter" questions.<br>
<p>
In closing - another illustration:<br>
<p>
A father found his son crying.  "Why are you crying?"  -  "Because I don't<br>
want to get big."  -  "Why not?"  -  "Because then I won't be allowed to play<br>
with my toys anymore."<br>
<p>
The father explained that when he was big he wouldn't want to play with his<br>
toys anymore, and that it would no longer be an issue.  He then left the room<br>
happy that his son was comforted.  A little later he heard the boy crying <br>
again.  He returned and asked why he was crying again.  The boy answered<br>
"Because I don't want to 'not want' to play with my toys.  I want to 'want'<br>
to play with my toys forever."<br>
<p>
I often hear myself 'not wanting to not want to'.<br>
<p>
"Eye has not seen, nor ear heard, neither has it entered into the heart of<br>
man ....."<br>
<p>
To quote another song "I want to be there - don't you?"<br>
<p>
Maranatha<br>
<p>
Cecil<br>
[As far as the stars, I was well aware of the EGW quote that says we<br>
will have them.  I am wondering more about the urban legend that<br>
suggests each one is <br>
for a soul saved.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
