<!-- subject="Re: Evil &amp; guilt" -->
<!-- id="UfqfuvK00YUoA7FeUg@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="01GX9ZJPJ65E8WYC49@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<title>Apr_1993: Re: Evil &amp; guilt</title>
<h1>Re: Evil &amp; guilt</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 25 Apr 1993 12:39:23 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#390">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#390">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#390">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#390">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0391.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Two in one (just for you Steve)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0389.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Stars in my Crown"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0349.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[The words "sinful nature", which are not Priebe's but Ellen Whites,<br>
are the core of this debate.  Every time I say, "no SDA believs..."  I <br>
find one that does.  Here's a classic "new theology" argument.  See if <br>
they ae defining the terms the same.  I can't tell.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
On 21 Apr 1993 PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It seems, according to Priebe at least, that the term "sinful nature" is</i><br>
<i>&gt; a misnomer, and doesn't really make sense. He very much equates sin with</i><br>
<i>&gt; the concept of guilt. So according to his definitions, Christ actually</i><br>
<i>&gt; has an "evil nature". Predisposed towards evil, but not sinful because he</i><br>
<i>&gt; has never chosen to commit a rebellious act.</i><br>
<p>
I find this a greatly troubling position to take.  In my view, this is a<br>
corner into which perfectionism paints itself:  that Christ had a sinful<br>
human nature, predisposed to evil as we are -- and that, through the help<br>
of some "power" from God, He was able to overcome sin and lead a perfect<br>
life.  Now, if He could do it, we are expected by God to GO AND DO<br>
LIKEWISE.  My question is: where is the Atonement in this view?  Why did<br>
Christ have to die?  Was He just our Example, or is He our Savior also?<br>
<p>
God told Adam and Eve that IN THE DAY that they ate of the<br>
tree of knowledge, they would die.  They were guilty.  They deserved to<br>
die ON THE SPOT, and THEIR SEED SHARES IN THE RESULTS OF THEIR GUILT.  That is<br>
biblical; that is supported by EGW.  It isn't just the predisposition to<br>
sin that was transmitted to future generations, it was the SIN itself --<br>
Adam and Eve's sin, which is passed down to us.  "The sin of Adam plunged<br>
the race in hopeless misery and despair" (4T 293).  <br>
<p>
The Bible says that ALL have sinned (Rom. 3:23); I don't see justification<br>
for excluding (1) persons before the age of accountability, or (2) persons<br>
before they knowingly and willingly commit their first sin.  Galatians 3:22<br>
underscores this fact: "...the scripture hath concluded ALL under sin, that<br>
the promise by faith of Jesus Christ might be given to them that believe."<br>
<p>
"Behold, I was shapen in iniquity," David said, "and in sin did my mother<br>
conceive me" (Ps. 51:5).  David isn't talking about a predisposition to<br>
sin -- he's taking about SIN.<br>
<p>
As I see it, there are two different categories of sin that make men<br>
sinful:<br>
<p>
1) The ONE sin of Adam, which we inherit from conception (Romans 5:12-19;<br>
Ps. 51:5) and over which we have no choice.  This makes us sinful and<br>
worthy of death.  By Christ's perfect life and atoning death, this sin is<br>
removed from the slate of the believer, and he is no longer accounted a<br>
sinner in this respect.<br>
<p>
2) The SINS that are our own, committed in rebellion against God.  This<br>
is the class of sinning that James is referring to, not the class of<br>
sin that Paul refers to in Romans.  Even if we<br>
never reach the point of committing a category 2 sin, we are guilty by<br>
virtue of the category 1 sin of Adam.  Unless we are covered by Christ's<br>
blood, which legally removes us from the effects of category 1 sin: "The<br>
sin of Adam plunged the race in hopeless misery and despair.  But God, in<br>
His wonderful, pitying love, did not leave men to perish in their<br>
hopeless, fallen condition.  He gave His well-beloved Son for their<br>
salvation.  Christ entered the world, His divinity clothed in humanity; He<br>
passed over the ground where Adam fell; He bore the test which Adam failed<br>
to endure; He overcame every temptation of Satan, and thus redeemed Adam's<br>
disgraceful failure and fall (4T 293).<br>
<p>
Boom! The sin of Adam is wiped from our slate (Rom. 5:18, 19).<br>
<p>
We are forgiven and so Christ tells us to GO AND SIN NO MORE.  In other<br>
words, category 2 sins are still possible, and if they become habitual and<br>
if we don't repent and ask forgiveness, category 2 sins will lead us to<br>
lose our crown of life.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
