<title>Apr_1993: Priebe, Ford, Larson, and college</title>
<h1>Priebe, Ford, Larson, and college</h1>
<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>26 Apr 1993 18:36:00 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#393">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#393">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#393">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#393">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0394.html">Ray Mialki: "Re: Stars in my Crown?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0392.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Original Sin... again"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0406.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Priebe, Ford, Larson, and college"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Speaking of college being a broadening experience...  I've already<br>
told the net that I had classes from Des Ford at PUC and enjoyed them<br>
very much.  Well, I also had classes from Dennis Priebe (it is Dennis<br>
isn't it?) and I enjoyed those as well.  Both men were very personable<br>
and I liked them, yet their theology is pretty much set at 180 degrees<br>
from each other.  I also have fond memories of Ralph Larson because<br>
he was an evangelist in Northern California when I was little and I<br>
remember going to his tent meetings where there was sawdust on the floor<br>
and he showed slides of the beasts of Revelation.<br>
<p>
So what, you say?  Well, so what indeed.  I just wanted to interject the<br>
human dimension a bit here, because some of these men have been<br>
thoroughly blasted for their various doctrinal positions, and we should<br>
remember that they are indeed human and that we might be able to disagree<br>
with them without becoming disagreeable.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
