<!-- received="Mon Apr 26 20:37:19 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Mon, 26 Apr 1993 20:37:19 -0500 (CDT)" -->
<!-- name="Daniel D Deavours" -->
<!-- email="ddd42961@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Original Sin... again" -->
<!-- id="199304270137.AA23795@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Apr_1993: Original Sin... again</title>
<h1>Original Sin... again</h1>
Daniel D Deavours (<i>ddd42961@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 26 Apr 1993 20:37:19 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#392">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#392">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#392">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#392">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0393.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "Priebe, Ford, Larson, and college"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0391.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Two in one (just for you Steve)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; The author is obsessed with "Christian perfection," which he defines as</i><br>
<i>&gt; "total victory over sin."  He concludes that it is possible for us to work out</i><br>
<i>&gt; "a sinless character in a sinful nature."  I call this hogwash fringing on</i><br>
<p>
If you read the next sentence, it states "Perfection remains always the<br>
goal, while abiding in Christ is the method."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; blasphemy.  While the quasi-gospel Priebe endorses pays lip service to Christ</i><br>
<i>&gt; and to the Atonement,  what is really at its core is perfection by human</i><br>
<i>&gt; effort.  Christian perfection is possible only through faith in Christ</i><br>
<p>
If you read the next sentence, it states "Perfection remains always the<br>
goal, while abiding in Christ is the method."  Or, "It is not awareness<br>
of our inward holiness, but dependence on Christ."  -- Priebie<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; To those in Priebe's camp, Christ's ministry on earth serves as an example</i><br>
<i>&gt; for us and little else.  If we only follow the example, we can ourselves</i><br>
<i>&gt; accomplish all that Christ accomplished.  The Atonement's main function was</i><br>
<i>&gt; to clear the way for us to work out our own salvation.  Christ's role as</i><br>
<i>&gt; our one and only Savior, there being no other name under heaven which can</i><br>
<i>&gt; save us, is barely mentioned.</i><br>
<p>
I quote Priebie again, "The gospel is both a legal verdict and transforming<br>
power.  Union with Christ is the key to the faith through which justification<br>
must take place."                ^^^<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; THE NATURE OF SIN</i><br>
<i>&gt; from us, and makes provision to cleanse us of our own sins.  Our inherited</i><br>
<i>&gt; sin is only part of the story, and the concept of inherited sin does not,</i><br>
<i>&gt; as Priebe states, remove our responsibility.</i><br>
<p>
I would have to ask, then, how could you describe Jesus as fully man?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; THE NATURE OF CHRIST</i><br>
<i>&gt; Priebe suggests that to argue that Christ was born with the pre-Fall nature</i><br>
<i>&gt; is to say that He had no connection at all with our sinful nature.</i><br>
<p>
I beg to differ.  "Any other condition except in sinful flesh would have<br>
been challenged at once by the enemy, and would have influenced the thinking<br>
of the universe."  Also, "Christ accepted voluntarily the humiliation of<br>
descending, not only to the level of unfallan man, but to the level to which<br>
man had fallen through the sin of Adam and the sins of succeeding<br>
generations."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; JUSTIFICATION</i><br>
<i>&gt; Priebe claims that these views cause an unholy overemphasis on justification,</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the exclusion of sanctification.  Yet 1 Corinthians 1:30 points to Christ</i><br>
<p>
Let me quote again, "The gospel includes justification--a uniting with<br>
Christ by faith.... and sanctification--a growing more like Christ through<br>
the daily exercise of a constantly growing faith..."  If that were the<br>
only statement about sanctification, it would suffice for me.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; PERFECTION</i><br>
[Nothing specific to comment on, perhaps a re-read would help.]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; THE RESULTS</i><br>
<i>&gt; Priebe asserts that persons who believe in what he feels is an incorrect</i><br>
<i>&gt; gospel are bound to participate in the following: lowering church standards,</i><br>
<p>
Actually I find what you description of the gospel and Priebe's are very<br>
similar.  I don't want to be too hard on you, but I think it's obvious<br>
that what he says and what you say he says is very different.<br>
<p>
Which leads me to another train of thought.  It seems that whenever people<br>
get on the works/faith debate, two people can say the same thing but argue<br>
about it.  Why is that?  It seems as people (and I've found myself doing<br>
this) can't hear the word "faith" without butting in the word "works",<br>
or the other way around.<br>
<p>
Not too recently the local pastor got drilled for saying keeping the Sabbath<br>
is not essential for salvation.  Figure that one out... is it?  What about<br>
the Three Angels Messages?  If they're not essential, what is the Mark<br>
of the Beast, and why is it so important?  If it is essential, then why<br>
is it "by His grace we are saved."  If Sabbath is essential, then don't<br>
you have to say "by His grace on the condition that we keep the Sabbath<br>
and ... we are saved?"  What about people who are ignorant?<br>
<p>
The point of asking the question is NOT to get an answer, but to think<br>
about all the different ways different people will answer.  Some will<br>
answer "Yes", some will answer "No."  Could it be that coming from their<br>
perspective that they are both correct answers?!<br>
<p>
 From experience, hashing it out once again on the net isn't going to<br>
solve anything.  My question is, What will?  How can we get an agreement?<br>
<p>
Dan Deavours<br>
zeos@uiuc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
