<!-- body="start" -->
Just a gem from the 70th Birthday celebration for C. Warren Becker, longtime <br>
organ professor at Andrews Univ., which happened over the past weekend.<br>
<p>
Dr. Becker spoke briefly at the close of the tribute in which 10 of his<br>
former and current students performed on the organ.  He said that he had<br>
begun (in the SDA church) the practice of modulating the last stanza of <br>
a hymn to the next higher key.  This was because of what he read in<br>
Great Controversy about how at the 2nd Coming the angels will sing a<br>
note higher as<br>
the redeemed rise to meet Jesus.  And here I had been following this practice<br>
myself as an organist and didn't know the reason.<br>
<p>
I find that the contemporary songs now being written are remarkably<br>
theologically correct.  (there was a time when this was not true.)  But <br>
you will hear Christian singers singing about obedience to God, <br>
the life of Christ, and good and wholesome relationships.  Also there are <br>
the many good scripture songs which Tony mentioned recently.  <br>
<p>
By contrast, look at all the various hymn verses which had to be altered<br>
to make the SDA hymnal.  And probably some weren't that should have been.<br>
For instance:  "When I fall on my knees, with my face to the rising sun,<br>
O Lord have mercy on me."  Is this referred to in Ezekiel 8:16?  On the other<br>
hand, such people are in need of mercy, so maybe the line is good.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
