<title>Apr_1993: Re: Evil &amp; guilt</title>
<h1>Re: Evil &amp; guilt</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 27 Apr 1993 08:13:57 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#408">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#408">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#408">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#408">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0409.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0407.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Church clothes"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0400.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0421.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben,<br>
I'm sorry, but again, I disagree with you totally.  I could fill the<br>
mailboxes of every SDANet member with pages of arguments, as you have<br>
tried to to do, but I won't because I stand by my previously-stated<br>
position.  I believe it is Scriptural, and I believe it<br>
is correct.  I honestly feel there is a grave problem with your<br>
interpretation of sin.  You're soft on sin, despite your emphasis on<br>
overcoming ALL SIN in this life.  You are failing to recognize the<br>
MAGNITUDE of the sin problem in which we are all mired, and IN WHICH WE<br>
ARE MIRED FROM CONCEPTION.  You're afraid that if you acknowledge what a<br>
DEEP PIT of sin we are all in, that you might be led to feel that there's<br>
no way out.  Well, I tell you today that the deeper the pit the GREATER is<br>
our Savior, Jesus Christ!<br>
<p>
When Adam and Eve transgressed, they deserved to die that very moment, and<br>
so did ALL OF US WHO WERE PRESENT THERE IN EDEN IN THE GENETIC CODE OF OUR<br>
FIRST PARENTS.  Yes, we were present there, and we deserved to die as much<br>
as Adam &amp; Eve did.  You complain about God not being fair in attributing<br>
guilt to Adam and Eve's progeny -- to me, that argument just doesn't fly. <br>
Where would we be today if Adam &amp; Eve had received their just punishment<br>
in Eden?  God IS MORE THAN FAIR in providing a way of escape from the pit<br>
of sin in which we are fallen.  It is Satan who has always accused God of<br>
being unfair.<br>
<p>
Also, I have never argued that we are to be saved IN our sins rather than<br>
FROM our sins.  I believe we are saved from our sins by faith in Jesus and<br>
by His grace.  My constant emphasis has been that it is CHRIST'S WORK in<br>
us, and not any of our doing.  There is NOT ONE THREAD OF OUR OWN DEVISING<br>
in the quiltwork of our salvation.  Our role is to accept as a little<br>
child accepts the love of his parents.<br>
<p>
Christ gets all the glory.  That is my burden.  But I have never meant to<br>
suggest that the Christian life involves no effort at all -- that we<br>
simply ride Christ's coattails into heaven (although I can think of no one<br>
better to ride on).  The Christian life remains a struggle even after<br>
conversion, and only by our moment-by-moment reliance on Christ can He<br>
overcome in us.  Once again, it is all of Him and none of us.  The good<br>
works that we do are His -- not ours, just as our salvation is fully<br>
wrapped up in Him.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
