<title>Apr_1993: Re: internet access</title>
<h1>Re: internet access</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 27 Apr 1993 08:52:58 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#417">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#417">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#417">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#417">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0418.html">Speedway Support: "Speedway shell accounts"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0416.html">Steven Timm: "Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
internet access<br>
--------------------------------<br>
<p>
<p>
Source-Info: From (or Sender) name not authenticated.<br>
<p>
Del Mar Communications has established a data center to provide free <br>
Internet connectivity to the general public.  We call it "Speedway".<br>
<p>
We have installed a large bank of V.32bis-capable modems, and more will <br>
be added as usage increases.<br>
<p>
Our first offering is UUCP, SLIP, and PPP connections with unlimited <br>
connect time.  We receive thousands of Usenet newsgroups, including <br>
many regional groups and groups from foreign countries, and will be <br>
happy to pass on any number of them.  Our direct high-speed Internet<br>
connection means there will be few if any delays in the sending and <br>
receiving of electronic mail or news articles.  We can also act as your <br>
site's Internet mail forwarder, and our dial-up modems can be used to <br>
access other sites on the Internet.  Just log in as telnet or rlogin <br>
(when using rlogin, press &lt;Return&gt; at the first Password: prompt to <br>
receive a login prompt from the distant host).<br>
<p>
In the future, we plan to offer a BBS and Unix shell accounts.<br>
<p>
Our services are completely free.  All you pay for is the telephone<br>
call.  Using one of AT&amp;T's "Reach Out" plans, this can be very<br>
inexpensive.  If you currently spend many hours dialed up to a UUCP<br>
feed that is a local call, then clearly our service is not for you.<br>
But if your current feed is a toll call, even in your same area, or if<br>
you are now paying usage charges, you may well find that it would<br>
be cheaper and more convenient to use our "Speedway" service and just <br>
pay for the call.<br>
<p>
Because our only connection to the Public Switched Telephone Network is <br>
via digital connection to AT&amp;T, calls to our service must arrive via AT&amp;T.  <br>
In most of the U.S.A., this can be accomplished by prepending 10ATT to <br>
your dial string, i.e.  10288-1-503-520-2222.  Our data center is <br>
located in Portland, Oregon, so callers from Northern Oregon can not <br>
reach our service at the present time unless they dial 1-800-32-10ATT <br>
and bill the call to their calling card.  This also means that you can <br>
not reach us via PC Pursuit.<br>
 <br>
Calls from foreign countries arrive on various long-distance carriers,<br>
at random.  You may have to try a few times, but you should be able to<br>
get through.  If your call arrives on a carrier other than AT&amp;T, you<br>
will hear a busy signal and will not be charged.<br>
<p>
If you are interested in any of our services, please send e-mail to<br>
support@speedway.net and we will set up a free account for you.<br>
<p>
Thank You,<br>
<p>
Support Operations<br>
Speedway Free Access<br>
<pre>
-- 
Internet:       ahd@kew.com             Voice:          617-641-3739
<p>
"Don't break it if you can't fix it."                   - Marketing manager
--------------------------------
 From speedway.net!support Thu, 22 Apr 1993 08:28:46 CDT remote from cs.utexas.edu
<p>
On Apr 20 at  8:54, woody@knapper.cactus.org ("Woody Baker") writes:
&gt; I would indeed like an internet access account.  I would like to have
&gt; FTP access.  
<p>
We plan to start offering shell accounts in the next few days.  Try
logging in as 'new' in a few days.
<p>
<p>
&gt; Currently I am running UUCP.  My site name is 
&gt; knapper.cactus.org.
&gt; I would like a mail feed for UUCP, with some news groups to be added later.
<p>
If you would like to set up a UUCP account, send us the name of your
site.  If you don't already have a domain name you can use ours.  For
example, if your site's UUCP name is foobar, you would be
foobar.speedway.net, and people would send mail to
user@foobar.speedway.net.  If you have your own registered domain name
and are currently getting your mail from another site, then we have to
arrange to change your nameserver record.  This takes about a week and
we can handle the paperwork for you.
<p>
If you would also like to receive a newsfeed, let us know what groups
you want to get and at about what time (Pacific Time) you expect to call 
in and receive news, so that we can batch it up just before you call.  This 
assumes that you have news software all up and running on your machine.
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Support Operations
Speedway Free Access
--------------------------------
</pre>
