<title>Apr_1993: Re: The $100 Million Question</title>
<h1>Re: The $100 Million Question</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 27 Apr 93 13:04:19 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#409">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#409">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#409">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#409">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0410.html">Steven Timm: "It could never happen here (was $100 million question"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0408.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0339.html">Steven Timm: "The $100 Million Question"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Prelude:<br>
<i>&gt;&gt;[Michael Merginio writes:]</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt; A college/university is supposed to be a place where alternate thought</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;&gt; is not only expected, but encouraged.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;[Fred writes:]</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;In it's broadest interpretation, this could be appropriately said for a</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;secular institution.  It's typical humanist-type statement.  But I recommend</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;caution in such an application to a Christian college/university.  Why?</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;Because, like humanism, it leaves God out of the picture.</i><br>
<p>
[TracyAnne Burtch-Nickless writes:]<br>
<i>&gt;I read 'alternate thought' to mean being able to think on their own.</i><br>
<p>
Fair 'nuff; it just sounded, understood broadly, like what humanists say.<br>
<p>
[Bill Nickless writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; &gt; [Michael] </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; &gt; The college experience is to be one where a person should</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; &gt; be allowed to find the true being within oneself.</i><br>
<i>&gt; [Fred]</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Echos from the 60s.  One cannot find oneself independent of Christ.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; He has a design and a purpose for each one of us (Ps 139:13-17).  Indeed,</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; without Him, we could not be (e.g., 1 Sam 1:6,19,20; Acts 17:28); we are</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; not the result of some random or chance event.</i><br>
[Bill] <br>
<i>&gt; Perhaps I don't understand your response to Michael Merginio, but what I</i><br>
<i>&gt; read disturbs me.</i><br>
<p>
Sorry 8-).  I did not wish to be perceived as slamming Michael or<br>
promoting "know nothing".  That's why I chose to describe my comments<br>
as referring to the "broadest interpretation" (i.e., going beyond<br>
the face value) and "recommend[ing] caution".  Michael's .sig speaks of<br>
being totally honest.  I apologize for evidently being less than tactful.<br>
<p>
Permit me to elaborate somewhat, as I reckon you're actually thinking of<br>
more of my comments than just the above quote.  I was expressing caution<br>
regarding inquiry that recognizes no restraint, that considers all knowledge<br>
amoral.  "Alternate thought" (Michael may well have had a more moderate<br>
connotation in mind) and "academic freedom" have been used to demand license<br>
to be libertine.  Would this be wise policy for a Christian institution?<br>
<p>
For example, when I was at Andrews in the early 70s, I recall students<br>
arguing that a subscription to Playboy magazine at the James White library<br>
would be justified since it contained "serious" material (mingled with<br>
porn); and that to do otherwise would be censorship most reprehensible (!).<br>
(And there were rumors that the library did have such a subscription,<br>
but I have no idea if that was true.)<br>
<p>
In an Education class I took, a question was posed on a test:  In an English<br>
literature class, would it be appropriate to study a book that included<br>
immorality? [*]  At that time, I argued that it was incumbent for us<br>
to be acquainted with the great works of Literature, past and present,<br>
and that we were mature enough adults to handle "Lady Chatterley's Lover"<br>
or Ericha Jong's "Fear of Flying" or whatever.  My teacher may not have<br>
understood me, but I distinctly recall him saying he agreed with me<br>
when I discussed my test paper with him.<br>
<p>
[*} Yes, I know that the Bible contains immorality.  But it does not<br>
detail it (i.e., not lewd) and *does* present its consequences.  Popular<br>
literature often details/celebrates immorality and commonly presents it<br>
as w/o negative consequence.<br>
<p>
(Not long thereafter, I encountered a pastor who felt similarly and whose<br>
library contained Lady Chatterley's Lover and others whose characters<br>
lived immorally.  I confess with grief that I read some of those books<br>
and now dearly wish I hadn't; memories of text passages sometimes come<br>
back to mind.)<br>
<p>
In the twenty years since I hope I have grown wiser.  While I wasn't<br>
aware of Ps 101:3 ("I will set no wicked thing before mine eyes"),<br>
I did know Phil 4:8.  But I had adjusted my view of theology to accomodate<br>
my morality.<br>
<p>
I submit that teachers in Christian institutions should be spiritually-wise,<br>
not worldly-wise, in selecting materials for examination.  That would<br>
exclude many things, unlike secular practice.<br>
<p>
But what about one's personal convictions?  2 Cor 10:5 urges us to make our<br>
thoughts captive to the obedience of Christ, eschewing every imagined or real<br>
thing that exalts itself (Gen 3:5) against the knowledge of God.  Why proscribe<br>
ourselves?  Because of the universal, non-optional principle that our<br>
thoughts and characters are shaped by what comes in thru our senses and<br>
by what we dwell on.  We can use this principle to our spiritual benefit<br>
(2 Cor 3:18, "beholding .. the glory [character] of the Lord,.. changed into<br>
the same image from glory to glory" [character sanctification, imparted<br>
righteousness]; see also GC 478) or to our spiritual detriment (see PP 459,<br>
context of Balaam's revenge in "Apostasy at the Jordan").<br>
<p>
Why not heed 2 Cor 6:14-18 ("... wherefore come out from among them, and be<br>
ye separate, saith the Lord, and touch not the unclean thing; and I will<br>
receive you ...") and Rom 12:2?  Why not center education on the Source of<br>
true education ("the knowledge of the holy is understanding", Prov 9:10;<br>
"acquaint now thyself with him", Job 22:21; in Him "are hid all the<br>
treasures of wisdom", Col 2:3)?  Are we missing out on the fullness possible<br>
in restoring in mankind the image of God physically, mentally, and spiritually?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Starting from first principles: I believe that it was God's intent to</i><br>
<i>&gt; create humanity with intelligence, creativity, and the capacity for</i><br>
<i>&gt; independent thought.  (God created man in his own image; Genesis 1:27.)</i><br>
<p>
Absolutely!  We agree.  My caution is that an "independent spirit" (e.g.,<br>
Rev 3:17) can be mistaken for "independent thought".  Anyway .. here's a<br>
quote on godly independent thought (Education p17-19):<br>
<p>
  Every human being, created in the image of God, is endowed with a power<br>
  akin to that of the Creator - individuality, power to think and to do.<br>
  ... It is the work of true education to develop this power, to train the<br>
  youth to be thinkers, and not mere reflectors of other men's thoughts.<br>
  Instead of confining their study to that which men have said or written<br>
  [textbooks, the library - fgc], let students be directed to the sources<br>
  of truth, to the vast fields opened for research in nature and revelation.<br>
  Let them contemplate the great facts of duty and destiny, and the mind<br>
  will expand and strengthen.  Instead of educated weaklings, institutions<br>
  of learning may send forth men [and women] strong to think and to act,<br>
  men who are masters and not slaves of circumstances, men who possess<br>
  breath of mind, clearness of thought, and the courage of their<br>
  convictions [stand alone, despite peer pressure].<br>
<p>
  Such an education provides more than mental discipline; it provides<br>
  more than physical training.  It strengthens character, so that truth<br>
  and uprightness are not sacrificed to selfish desire or worldly<br>
  ambition.  It fortifies the mind against evil.  Instead of some master<br>
  passion becoming a power to destroy, every motive and desire are<br>
  brought into conformity to the great principles of right.  As the<br>
  perfection of His character is dwelt upon, the mind is renewed, and<br>
  the soul is re-created in the image of God.<br>
<p>
  What education can be higher than this? ... Higher than the highest<br>
  human thought can reach is God's ideal for His children.  [I often<br>
  heard this one, but it needs the next to be complete -fgc]  Godliness --<br>
  godlikeness -- is the goal to be reached.  Before the student is<br>
  opened a path of continual progress.  He has an objective to achieve,<br>
  a standard to attain, that includes everything good, and pure, and<br>
  noble.  He will advance as fast and as far as possible in every<br>
  branch of true knowledge [hence, there is false knowledge -fgc].  But<br>
  his efforts will be directed to objects as much higher than mere<br>
  selfish and temporal interests as the heavens are higher than the earth.<br>
<p>
  .. an education that cannot be completed in this life, but that will be<br>
  continued in the life to come; ...<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It's not very far from the statement you make above "One cannot find</i><br>
<i>&gt; oneself independent of Christ" to "our children cannot find Christ</i><br>
<i>&gt; unless we apply great pressure on them to conform to our beliefs, both</i><br>
<i>&gt; in thought and action."</i><br>
<p>
I'm afraid I see a large chasm to be leaped between them.  I was thinking<br>
of Prov 18:2:  "A fool hath no delight in understanding, but that his heart<br>
may discover itself."  Surely you remember that "find myself" was a<br>
trendy phrase during the 60s and 70s.  Vast hordes of people rejected<br>
the morality/mores/manners/materialism of their parents, and not always<br>
without good reason, and sought meaning and purpose.  They tried drugs,<br>
free love, Maharishi Mahesh Yogi, TM, the Peace Corps, and sometimes<br>
Jesus.  Many (most?), without a moral compass, without a Scriptural basis,<br>
ended up opting for hedonism.  I think we would agree that what they<br>
were searching, unmindfully, to fulfill was that which only Christ<br>
can supply in a relationship that accepts Him as Lord and Savior.<br>
<p>
I appreciate your concern for how we treat those who step out "out<br>
of bounds", so to speak.  Reminds me of Isa 42:3:  "A bruised reed shall<br>
he not break, and the smoking flax shall he not quench .."  Wisdom,<br>
indeed, is needed.  I would submit, tho, that rebellion need not be<br>
considered a normal part of adolescence.  Questioning to learn,<br>
and not just to hassle, is commendable:  1 Pet 3:15, "be ready always to<br>
give an answer to every man that asketh you a reason of the hope that is<br>
in you with meekness and fear."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; A much more successful method is to make the</i><br>
<i>&gt; truth attractive, relevant, and available.  But beyond that, it must be</i><br>
<i>&gt; tolerant of discussion against it.</i><br>
<p>
Agreed.  I've read some of Francis Schaeffer's books and it appears he<br>
understood how rather well.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Have faith that the truth is the truth, and that reasonable, growing</i><br>
<i>&gt; young minds will be capable of seeing it for what it is.</i><br>
<p>
Again a caution:  Rom 8:7 ".. the carnal mind is enmity against God:<br>
for it is not subject to the law of God, neither indeed can be."<br>
1 Cor 2:14 "But the natural man receiveth not the things of the Spirit of God:<br>
for they are foolishness unto him: neither can he know them, because they are<br>
spiritually discerned."<br>
Reasonable, growing young minds that are not resisting God's Spirit, yes,<br>
which emphasizes the need for intercessory prayer, IMHO.<br>
<p>
Isa 55:11 "So shall my word be that goeth forth out of my mouth: it shall not<br>
return unto me void, but it shall accomplish that which I please, and it<br>
shall prosper in the thing whereto I sent it."<br>
My faith rests in God, not in logic.  On reflection, I imagine you'd agree.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Be a channel</i><br>
<i>&gt; for the Holy Spirit to gently persuade, and not a tool of the devil,</i><br>
<i>&gt; making the Gospel irritating and bitter.</i><br>
<p>
Amen!<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
