<title>Apr_1993: Re: Original sin... again.</title>
<h1>Re: Original sin... again.</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 27 Apr 93 13:22:22 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#396">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#396">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#396">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#396">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0397.html">Steven Timm: "If you have to ask...."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0395.html">Steven Timm: "The $5 million dollar question"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0387.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Original sin... again."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I would disagree with Noe that Gospel presented in Priebe's article is a <br>
"new gospel" (under the guise of "historic Adventism") centered on salvation <br>
by human effort. <br>
<p>
The Adventist gospel has always uplifted Christ far higher than the reformation<br>
gospel because it elevates what Christ can do, is doing and will do for man<br>
many times higher than conceived by those who only assert Christ's forgiving<br>
(justifying) ministry. It also brings into view the restoration that Christ<br>
makes in every human being. Yes effort is involved the effort of choosing<br>
Christ above self and sin, and yes it is a hard and difficult choice to make<br>
being against the natural desires of the human heart. The centre of this<br>
gospel is not human effort it is Christ without whom the effort is useless<br>
but the effort is a necessary component. Those of you who have an index<br>
to the writings of EGW look up how many references there are to Effort<br>
and you will see many pages of refereces where EGW affirms the important<br>
and necessary role of human effort in the process of salvation. AND NO this<br>
is not legalism and before you all jump to false conclusions, look up the<br>
index and see exactly what type of effort she refers to.<br>
<p>
Regarding the concept of total victory over sin, is this not scriptural ?<br>
<p>
Matt 1:21 And she shall bring forth a son, and thou shalt call his name JESUS:<br>
          for he shall save his people from their sins. (KJV)<br>
<p>
<p>
Jesus came to save us FROM sin not IN sin ! IF Jesus isn't saving you from<br>
your sins then you are not being saved.<br>
<p>
1 Cor 10:13 There hath no temptation taken you but such as is common to man:<br>
            but God is faithful, who will not suffer you to be tempted above<br>
            that ye are able; but will with the temptation also make a way to<br>
            escape, that ye may be able to bear it. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Now if God won't allow you to be tempted more than you can resist and thereby<br>
not commits sin, then why is it that we continue sinning, is it because we can<br>
not overcome, NO NEVER !, it is because we don't really want to overcome.<br>
<p>
Heb 12:4 Ye have not yet resisted unto blood, striving against sin. (KJV)<br>
<p>
This is the secret why, we don't overcome, we give in too easily.<br>
<p>
2 Cor 10:4 (For the weapons of our warfare are not carnal, but mighty through<br>
           God to the pulling down of strong holds;) (KJV)<br>
2 Cor 10:5 Casting down imaginations, and every high thing that exalteth<br>
           itself against the knowledge of God, and bringing into captivity<br>
           every thought to the obedience of Christ; (KJV)<br>
<p>
Now if every thought is in obedience to Christ, will we do wrong actions,<br>
will we think perverse thoughts ?, NO impossible. then what is the cause of<br>
our shortcomming... we don't use the weapons of our warfare that  Christ has<br>
provided, we prefer to use our own weapons.<br>
<p>
1 Cor 15:57 But thanks be to God, which giveth us the victory through our Lord<br>
            Jesus Christ. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Yes, He does, total and complete, a perfect victory, for those who really<br>
seek it with ALL their heart.<br>
<p>
Phil 4:13 I can do all things through Christ which strengtheneth me. (KJV)<br>
<p>
That is ALL not some ALL things, including victory over sin !<br>
<p>
Gal 5:16 This I say then, Walk in the Spirit, and ye shall not fulfil the lust<br>
         of the flesh. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Again, if we WALK in the Spirit we will not sin. because the fulfilling the<br>
lust of the flesh as James tells us is sin.<br>
<p>
Gal 2:20 I am crucified with Christ: nevertheless I live; yet not I, but<br>
         Christ liveth in me: and the life which I now live in the flesh I<br>
         live by the faith of the Son of God, who loved me, and gave himself<br>
         for me. (KJV)<br>
<p>
If in verity Christ lives His perfect life in you, as He truely desires to<br>
do, will He commit sin in you ?, If you are truely dead to self, and you<br>
no longer reign in your body but you are subect in all to the Lord (Note this<br>
is why He is called Lord) will you disobey ?, NO impossible, Christ life<br>
was a life of perfect obedience and if you let Christ live His life perfectly<br>
in you, your life will be a life of perfect obedience too.<br>
<p>
1 Pet 2:21 For even hereunto were ye called: because Christ also suffered for<br>
           us, leaving us an example, that ye should follow his steps: (KJV)<br>
1 Pet 2:22 Who did no sin, neither was guile found in his mouth: (KJV)<br>
<p>
Thats it the example, and this is not a carrot on the stick philosophy either.<br>
God does not treat us like mules.<br>
<p>
2 Pet 2:9 The Lord knoweth how to deliver the godly out of temptations, and to<br>
          reserve the unjust unto the day of judgment to be punished: (KJV)<br>
<p>
Does He really know how to deliver me from temptation ? or is this just a <br>
literary ploy to grab our attention. Why do we doubt God ? Isn't faith supposed<br>
to mean that we beleive and trust his Word. ?<br>
<p>
Jude 1:24 Now unto him that is able to keep you from falling, and to present<br>
          you faultless before the presence of his glory with exceeding joy,<br>
<p>
And again <br>
<p>
Rev 3:21 To him that overcometh will I grant to sit with me in my throne, even<br>
         as I also overcame, and am set down with my Father in his throne.<br>
<p>
How did Jesus overcome ?, part time ?<br>
<p>
1 Cor 9:24 Know ye not that they which run in a race run all, but one<br>
           receiveth the prize? So run, that ye may obtain. (KJV)<br>
1 Cor 9:25 And every man that striveth for the mastery is temperate in all<br>
           things. Now they do it to obtain a corruptible crown; but we an<br>
           incorruptible. (KJV)<br>
1 Cor 9:26 I therefore so run, not as uncertainly; so fight I, not as one that<br>
           beateth the air: (KJV)<br>
1 Cor 9:27 But I keep under my body, and bring it into subjection: lest that<br>
           by any means, when I have preached to others, I myself should be a<br>
           castaway. (KJV)<br>
<p>
As for effort Paul tells us that sure enough he hasn't been shadow boxing <br>
against temptation, its been a real fight.<br>
<p>
<p>
1 John 2:1 "My little children, these things I write unto you, that ye sin not.<br>
            And if any man sin we have an advocate with the Father, <br>
            Jesus Christ the righteous." <br>
<p>
<p>
Here are a few EGW quotes :<br>
<p>
"Not even by a thought did He yield to temptation. So it may be with us." <br>
							DA 123<br>
<p>
"Jesus revealed no qualities, and exercised no powers, that men may not<br>
have through faith in Him. His perfect humanity is that which all His <br>
followers may possess, if they wil be insubjection to God as He was." DA 664<br>
<p>
"He has made it possible for you to be an overcomer. Do not say it is<br>
impossible to overcome. Do not say. 'It is my nature to do thus and so, <br>
and I cannot do otherwise. I have inhereted weaknesses that make me <br>
powerless before temptation." We know you cannot overcome in your own<br>
strength; but help has been laid upon One who is mighty to save." ST II, 295<br>
<p>
"Christ has given us no assurance that to attain to perfection of<br>
character is an easy matter. It is a conflict, a battle, and a march,<br>
day by day." RH VI, 33<br>
<p>
"He says to them, "Be ye therefore perfect, even as your father which<br>
is in heaven is perfect." And He says this because He knows that it is <br>
possible for them to reach perfection." ST IV,216<br>
<p>
"Exact obedience is required and those that say that it is not possible<br>
to live a perfect life throw upon God the imputation of injustice and<br>
untruth." Ms 147; RH Feb7, 1957<br>
<p>
<p>
This is not " hogwash fringing on blasphemy" This is the 1888 message, the<br>
loud cry message rejected by the church then and now, no wonder Christ<br>
still hasn't come.<br>
<p>
As to the point that our good works flow out of our love and appreciation for <br>
our wonderful Savior, this is completely true. No our works do not earn us <br>
salvation, no matter how good they are, Never-the-less our sins surely<br>
cause our damnation. <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; To those in Priebe's camp, Christ's ministry on earth serves as an example</i><br>
<i>&gt; for us and little else.  If we only follow the example, we can ourselves</i><br>
<i>&gt; accomplish all that Christ accomplished. </i><br>
<p>
Christs life serves as our example and His atoning death as our substitute.<br>
Christ's life verily is our example.<br>
<p>
<p>
John 5:19 Then answered Jesus and said unto them, Verily, verily, I say unto<br>
          you, The Son can do nothing of himself, but what he seeth the Father<br>
          do: for what things soever he doeth, these also doeth the Son<br>
          likewise. (KJV)<br>
<p>
John 14:10 Believest thou not that I am in the Father, and the Father in me?<br>
           the words that I speak unto you I speak not of myself: but the<br>
           Father that dwelleth in me, he doeth the works. (KJV)<br>
John 14:12 Verily, verily, I say unto you, He that believeth on me, the works<br>
           that I do shall he do also; and greater works than these shall he<br>
           do; because I go unto my Father. (KJV)<br>
<p>
<p>
"By His perfect obedience He has made it possible for every human being<br>
to obey God's commandments. When we submit ourselves to Christ, the heart <br>
is united with his heart, the will is merged in His will, the mind becomes<br>
one with His mind, the thoughts are brough into captivity to Him; we live <br>
His life. This is what it means to be clothed with the garment of His<br>
righteousness." COL 312.<br>
<p>
<p>
"Jesus revealed no qualities, and exercised no powers, that men may not<br>
have through faith in Him. His perfect humanity is that which all His <br>
followers may possess, if they wil be insubjection to God as He was." DA 664<br>
<p>
<p>
"Satan....is constantly seeking to deceive the followers of Christ<br>
with his fatal sophistry that it is impossible for them to overcome...<br>
Let none, then, regard their defects as incurable. God will give faith<br>
and grace to overcome them." GC 489<br>
<p>
<p>
Regarding the statment<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The Atonement's main function was</i><br>
<i>&gt; to clear the way for us to work out our own salvation.  Christ's role as</i><br>
<i>&gt; our one and only Savior, there being no other name under heaven which can</i><br>
<i>&gt; save us, is barely mentioned.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
This really is a misunderstanding of the whole process of sanctification<br>
and the role it plays in our lives. Christ's death is necessary to justify us<br>
or in plain language to forgive us our sins. His life is necessary to<br>
give us power and victory over sin, in neither case do we work out<br>
our own salvation, the victory over sin isn't for us to save ourselves, its<br>
for us to stop doing those things which crucified Christ. Do we wish to<br>
continue indulging in the things that caused Christ's death ?<br>
<p>
<p>
Mind you, even those who have attained moral perfection and live without sin<br>
are still SAVED ONLY through the grace of God. The present lives<br>
do not and can not atone for passed sin, which can be forgiven only through the<br>
blood of Christ and the power to live a holy life is only received as we <br>
partake of Him daily. "Christ in you is the hope of glory" Col 1:27.<br>
<p>
As to the use of Ps. 51:5 to uphold the doctrine of original sin, this is<br>
incorrect because it is only through eisogesis that this can be affirmed.<br>
The verse does not say that guilt is inhereted.<br>
<p>
<p>
Regarding the notion of Christ being excempt from mans post fall incliination<br>
to sin, then how is it that He was tempted in all points like as we are ?<br>
<p>
James tells us very clearly that our temptations arise from our own lust<br>
ie our own (post fall) inclination to sin. If Christ did not have the same<br>
inclination to sin that we have then He could not have been tempted in the<br>
same way we are and so the clear teaching of scripture must be put aside.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
