<title>Apr_1993: Re: If you have to ask....</title>
<h1>Re: If you have to ask....</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 27 Apr 93 17:08:53 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#412">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#412">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#412">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#412">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0413.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Adventist Congressmen"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0411.html">Steven Timm: "PROOF BY CAPS LOCK"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0397.html">Steven Timm: "If you have to ask...."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Well, Steve, you've done it now! 8-)  You've gone from preaching to meddling.<br>
I mean, did you have to go from theory to reality?  (groan) ;-) 8-)<br>
<p>
[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; I had never heard any SDA's consider soy sauce _verboten_ before.  But I </i><br>
<i>&gt; guess there's a first for everything.</i><br>
<p>
Was that me?  I think I just said our family found Bragg's "Liquid<br>
Aminos" (what a name!) preferable for a couple of reasons.  No big deal.<br>
Just trying to go for the best.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 1)  Your co-workers invite you home for supper.  They are well aware</i><br>
<i>&gt; that you are a vegetarian, and have fixed you several vegetarian dishes</i><br>
<i>&gt; of Chinese food.  [wine? lard? not wish to offend]</i><br>
<p>
OK, I'll take an on-the-spot stab, given that's what I'd be under.<br>
Pray for wisdom and right words.  Wine's specific gravity is different<br>
enough that you might be able to detect it and simply not eat more; dunno.<br>
You could gently ask the cook what the ingredients were and how they<br>
were cooked, showing genuine interest; after all, they went to a lot of<br>
work.  Keep the results under your hat.  Carefully consider what to do.<br>
Reflect on what you may or may not know about Luke 10:8, and 1 Cor 10:27.<br>
Consider the merits of perhaps better preparing prospective hosts.<br>
<p>
I'll tell one on myself.  I'm 4 years old, family is in India, and we're<br>
invited to a wedding feast.  The mutton pulao (sp?) is served.  I'd<br>
never seen meat served before, except to our dog.  I pipe up, "Mom!<br>
Why are they feeding us dog food?"  Much embarrasment ...<br>
<p>
Btw, in India, it would be totally proper to indicate that your religion<br>
led you to eat/not eat certain foods.  No host would be offended, given<br>
forewarning.  That sort of thing is quite common.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 2)  You are in Switzerland and the professor you are visiting is taking</i><br>
<i>&gt; you out for dinner.  [pizza with ?? or fondue?]</i><br>
<p>
Pizza Hut in paradise?  Horrors!  Seriously, take your best shot and adapt,<br>
if necessary.  Oh .. fondue has the alcohol (wine *and* cherry liqueuer)<br>
cooked out it .. usually.  Don't forget to wipe your caquelon with garlic.<br>
It's not easy being vegetarian while travelingin Europe, or at least it<br>
sure wasn't 20 years ago.  Hooray for yoghurt, petit Suisses, and baguettes!<br>
Where's the nearest Migros? (no better yoghurt anywhere!)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 3)  You are at a classy party where numerous hors d'oeuvres are available.</i><br>
<i>&gt; [crackers, dip, shellfish? lard? pig pepsin?]</i><br>
<p>
Tell her you found the taste fascinatingly unique, a certain mysterious<br>
arriere gout.  As casually as possible, scan the terrain and chose your<br>
targets.  Save the embarrasing questions and lectures; it's probably the<br>
wrong time (cf. Prov 27:14).  Consider having the party at your place<br>
next time and wow 'em with delicious natural and whole foods.  Weimar's<br>
Country Kitchen recipe book has lots of nifty ideas.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Alternative if your mates prefer Taco Bell:  You vaguely remember from</i><br>
<i>&gt; your Christian Education at Adventist Schools that even the Taco Bell</i><br>
<i>&gt; bean burritos are cooked with lard.  You think your mates are also aware</i><br>
<i>&gt; of this. But you are fiendishly hungry for some anyway.  What should you do?</i><br>
<p>
Preferring to "make a run for the border", I'll take the alternative.  'Sides,<br>
it was a pastor who told me TB beans were lard-free, an' you can always<br>
believe them, right? 8-)  Consider the benefits of stocking your grad<br>
student office mini-fridge (you do have one, right?) with munchables such<br>
as fresh fruit, dried fruit, nuts, herb crackers and other delicacies.<br>
Unless you're willing to share, you might end up having to put a lock<br>
on it.  Even "carnivores" have been known to exhibit tastes for such. 8-)<br>
<p>
Btw, I recently referred to Drs Diehl, Lee, MacDougal, et al having cooking<br>
materials on vegan diets.  I was probably inaccurate.  I checked with<br>
a vegetarian friend here at work; "vegan" seems to have a connotation<br>
which I do not totally grasp, beyond vegetarian, so I may have misapplied<br>
the term.  Nevertheless, I do like what these Drs have to say.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
