<title>Apr_1993: It could never happen here (was $100 million question</title>
<h1>It could never happen here (was $100 million question</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 27 Apr 1993 22:01:58 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#410">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#410">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#410">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#410">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0411.html">Steven Timm: "PROOF BY CAPS LOCK"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0409.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The $100 Million Question"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The outpouring of faith in the leadership, and the incredible amount of <br>
standing for principle here, has taken me by surprise.  Not even those<br>
who support that theological view have written in support of taking<br>
the money.  So why did I bring it up?<br>
<p>
As I said, the situation is a paraphrase of an episode that is driving the <br>
Christian Science church into schism even as we speak.  $40 million or so<br>
will go to the church if they publish this book and promote it in all <br>
their reading rooms.  Problem is, the book effectively says that Mary Baker<br>
Eddy was divine, which most Christian Scientists don't believe.  If they <br>
don't promote the book, the money goes to Stanford.  The leadership decided<br>
to publish the book, because their television efforts have left them strapped<br>
for cash.  But there is a lawsuit going on claiming that the church is not <br>
promoting the book vigorously enough and thus the conditions of the will <br>
are not met.<br>
<p>
So that could never happen here?  How soon we forget Dr. Davenport (who<br>
didn't even have any preconditions.)  If we were to ask church leaders<br>
in <br>
the SDA church, I'm sure they would say with one voice that they are forced<br>
to pay much more attention to fiscal woes than they would like.  (Leaders<br>
are welcome to respond.)  Vigilance in financial matters is well worth<br>
the time to discuss.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
