<title>Apr_1993: PROOF BY CAPS LOCK</title>
<h1>PROOF BY CAPS LOCK</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 27 Apr 1993 22:17:30 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#411">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#411">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#411">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#411">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0412.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: If you have to ask...."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0410.html">Steven Timm: "It could never happen here (was $100 million question"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0419.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: PROOF BY CAPS LOCK"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
IT HAS RECENTLY BECOME APPARENT THAT SOME PEOPLE THINK THAT USING THE CAPS <br>
LOCK KEY IS THE COMPUTER EQUIVALENT OF SHOUTING.  THIS IS ESPECIALLY<br>
TRUE WHEN CHARACTERIZING THE OTHER PERSON'S VIEWPOINT.  THE PROBLEM WITH <br>
THIS IS THAT CAPSLOCKING IS BECOMING COMMON ENOUGH THAT IT IS LOSING ITS <br>
EFFECT.  FOR INSTANCE, YOU CAN'T TELL WHETHER I'M CAPSLOCKING TO DRIVE<br>
HOME A POINT OR WHETHER MY CAPS LOCK IS STUCK ON.<br>
<p>
SO FOR THE PEOPLE IN THE TRENCHES, I OFFER NEW POINTS OF EMPHASIS:<br>
_UNDERLINE_  (GREAT WAY TO MAKE A WORD STAND OUT)<br>
****ASTERISKS****   (ALSO COMMON NET EMPHASIS)<br>
lowercase!   THIS REVERSE-PSYCHOLOGY TECHNIQUE GIVES EMPHASIS DUE TO    <br>
                SURPRISE.<br>
OR YOU CAN USE REGULAR PUNCTUATION SUCH AS !!!!! AND ?????<br>
<p>
However, I would like to see more smileys  :-) than any of these.<br>
The discussion particularly on what is sin and what are we like, etc,<br>
is a discussion that could benefit from some inquisitive questioning<br>
and attempting to understand the other position.  I've been trying to <br>
do that but the crossfire is too high right now.  The one point of agreement<br>
we have established so far is that each side thinks the other is wrong.<br>
There's a real theological difference trying to get out here, but it's mired<br>
in terminology on both sides.  <br>
<p>
I heard someone accused of "exegesis" recently.  I thought this was a good <br>
thing to do.  The idea of exegesis as I understand it is to study the Bible<br>
to try to extract the meanings from the verse, rather than coming to the <br>
Bible with a preconceived idea and gathering ammunition to support it.<br>
<p>
Let's try to be people of the Book, and let it speak to us, rather<br>
than presuming to speak for it.<br>
<p>
We now return you to the regularly scheduled war coverage.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
