<title>Apr_1993: WWC and Internet News</title>
<h1>WWC and Internet News</h1>
David Klein - EECS (<i>dklein@eecs.wsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 27 Apr 93 22:36:55 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#420">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#420">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#420">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#420">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0421.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0419.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: PROOF BY CAPS LOCK"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0411.html">Steven Timm: "PROOF BY CAPS LOCK"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0427.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hey all you netters, I got a good one for you.  Walla Walla College is<br>
presently having a rather large debate on whether there should be any<br>
monitoring and possible deletion of news groups such as alt.sex and<br>
other similar groups.  I think this is going to become a greater issue<br>
as more SDA colleges are connected to Internet and I'm curious on what<br>
you have to say.<br>
<p>
As far as I know, the debate at WWC is presently confined to a forum<br>
called RNS, but I think it will spred.  At present, it appears that<br>
the forum members are about evenly divided between those that think<br>
policing the news groups is wrong and those who think it is the<br>
morally the right thing to do.<br>
<p>
A sampling of reasons why those who think it is wrong to police follow:<br>
1. It is a form of thought control.<br>
2. Where does the line get drawn on?  If you police one group, should<br>
   you police them all?<br>
3. It is not a part of WWC but rather a window to the rest of the<br>
   world and thus should not fall under the rules and regulations of<br>
   WWC.<br>
4. The students should be old enough to makethe decision for themselves<br>
   on whether to read the garbage or not.  Give them a chance to use<br>
   what they have hopefully learned while growing up.<br>
etc.<br>
<p>
A sampling of the reasons why the news groups should be policed is:<br>
1. It is a service provided by WWC and, in various shades, is at odds with<br>
   WWC's believes and reason for existence.<br>
2. What happens when a parent finds out that their child has access to<br>
   the kind of junk that can be found in news through WWC.<br>
3. It's morally wrong, so we shouldn't support it.<br>
etc.<br>
<p>
I believe Andrews subscribes to news.  If so, has this ever been an issue<br>
there?  If it was, how was it dealt with?<br>
<p>
David<br>
<pre>
-- 
David J. Klein - dklein@eecs.wsu.edu
Electrical Engineering - Computer Science
Washington State University - Pullman
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
