<title>Apr_1993: What Is The "Will of God"?</title>
<h1>What Is The "Will of God"?</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Apr 93 10:16:29 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#424">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#424">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#424">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#424">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0425.html">Steven Timm: "Chicago Tribune:  ADRA in Yugoslavia"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0423.html">Bruce Holm: "Earthquake Predictions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0438.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  What Is The "Will of God"?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In an attempt to start a new thread...<br>
<p>
I have a work mate who in non-SDA but a very sincere conservative Christian.  I<br>
respect his opinion alot.  We were talking the other day about what the "will of<br>
God" is.  He spoke of an "individual will" and the "moral will" of God.  He also<br>
strongly stated that there is no Biblical evidence for such a thing he calls the<br>
individual will of God and therefore does not believe in it.  To define what he<br>
meant by individual will, he describes it as being a specific will for each and<br>
every individual on earth as opposed to the moral will of God given to all mankind<br>
in the Bible.<br>
<p>
What this boils down to is that God does not have a specific list of things for<br>
each one of us to do...marry so-in-so, go into occupation x, work for company y<br>
for 5 years then go to company z, you can buy a two door refrigorator but not<br>
till 1995 when you can afford it, etc.  His reasoning includes the question, <br>
where would you draw the line?  Does God care what color socks I put on in the<br>
morning?  What car I drive to work?  Whether I drink lemonade or orage juice?<br>
Does He care about such "trivia"?  He also asks, if there is a specific will of<br>
God for each person, how do we find out what it is?  It would be to admit that<br>
God has a hidden aggenda for each of us.  <br>
<p>
But yet I have grown up with the idea being ingrained in me that we pray to <br>
God for His will for each major decision we make...who we marry, what profession,<br>
etc.  My friend believes that yes, God as a moral will for all mankind to follow<br>
that includes guidelines for everyday living but they apply to all and is not<br>
specific to any individual over another.  What applies to me applies to you.<br>
This would include guidelines on how we spend our money, how and what we eat, etc.<br>
<p>
What do you all think about this??  If you know of Biblical evidence that<br>
supports the concept of an "individual will" of God, please let me know.  I would<br>
also be interested in EGW references but I don't think they would have any <br>
weight with my friend since he is non-SDA.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Bruce G. Holm               503-685-1350      email:  bruceh@wv.mentorg.com
Mentor Graphics Corp.       503-685-7000
8005 SW Boeckman Rd.
Wilsonville, OR 97070-7777     Disclaimer:  Opinions expressed are my own!
</pre>
