<title>Apr_1993: SDA various discusions this last week</title>
<h1>SDA various discusions this last week</h1>
Maurice George Ashton (<i>mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Apr 1993 13:29:58 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#415">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#415">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#415">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#415">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0416.html">Steven Timm: "Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0414.html">lsusers: "Original sin"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I would like to comment on several areas that have been discussed on<br>
the net recently.<br>
<p>
1.  Plants and Music<br>
<p>
  Thankyou to all those who replied to my query on this topic both on<br>
  the net and privately. Your replies confirmed my thoughts that the<br>
  research was fairly shallow. Just because a research paper/news item/<br>
  argument etc supports our particular view does not make it a good<br>
  argument.<br>
<p>
2. Meat and Vegetarianism etc<br>
<p>
  Once again we need to be careful about accepting arguments because they<br>
  support our point of view. The arguments that meat is unhealthy because<br>
  of pollution and disease applies at leat in part to plants as well.<br>
<p>
  I heard a doctor of tropical medicine say that you should not eat salad<br>
  vegetables in tropical areas because they are uncooked and carry all<br>
  sorts of diseases we humans are susceptible to. Yet no one would deny<br>
  that nutritionally, salads are good for you.<br>
<p>
  Our health message is surely to eat the best that is available at the time.<br>
<p>
  I think that sometimes we make great issues about small instances. The<br>
  recent mail item that listed several senarios about eating is a case in<br>
  point. In most of those situations I would do the best I could without<br>
  giving offense. (even if it meant eating shellfish or ham) I am a vegetarian<br>
  by lifestyle. I do not believe that eating a particular item of food is a<br>
  sin. The number of times I find myself in difficult situations<br>
  are quite rare. I would rather stand before the judgement bar of God to<br>
  justify the eating of a mouthful of pork, than have to justify the offense<br>
  I gave to someone who would have been in the kingdom of God had it not<br>
  been for my insistence that I will never eat ham.<br>
<p>
3. The Nature of Christ and Sin etc<br>
<p>
  The recent discussion on the nature of Christ and our own sinful natures<br>
  has been very interesting from my point of view. (some of the mail items<br>
  were too long to read at one sitting and I hope that some correspondents<br>
  learn quickly how to do a precis  - I only get to read my mail about<br>
  twice a week)<br>
<p>
  I grew up during a period of time when these issues were being discussed<br>
  vigorously here in Australia and NZ. I saw the bitterness of the argument.<br>
  People left the church because of it. Others refused to join for the same<br>
  reason. What is more, when I started to read about history, I found that<br>
  the same arguments have been going on since the time of Christ Himself.<br>
<p>
  I am concerned that we let the mechanistic side of salvation make such<br>
  a major impact on our relationship with one another. If we spent as<br>
  much or more time dwelling on the fact that salvation is offered<br>
  freely to all by the blood of Christ, we would be able to discuss<br>
  the nature of Christ without coming to blows.<br>
<p>
4. Music - Stars in Crown - Dancing etc<br>
<p>
  I like Beethoven's Missa Solemnis, a Catholic Mass. I have read the words<br>
  translated from Latin. I agree with most of them. I enjoy the "Credo" -<br>
  I believe in the Father, the Son and the Holy Spirit. Is there any hope for<br>
  me or do I stand condemned for listening to Papal music?<br>
<p>
PS How do some of you find the time to write so much and do your work/study/<br>
research at the same time? Maybe you don't have families.<br>
<p>
Maurice Ashton<br>
Avondale College<br>
mashton@moria.cs.su.oz.au<br>
   .-_|\<br>
  /     \<br>
  \.--._/<br>
       V<br>
