<title>Apr_1993: Re: Evil &amp; guilt</title>
<h1>Re: Evil &amp; guilt</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Apr 93 15:05:41 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#421">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#421">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#421">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#421">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0422.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Stars in My Crown"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0420.html">David Klein - EECS: "WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0426.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Noe and all<br>
<p>
I'm not soft on sin ! Sin in my books is worse that for those who believe<br>
guilt is inhereted because there is no one else to blame for it but ourselves.<br>
In the other view sin is God's fault because He is the one that originally<br>
fixed it so that you could do anything about it. The magnitude of the <br>
sin problem remains the same either way its only the responisbility<br>
for it that is shifted.<br>
<p>
I'm certain of the honesty of those who believe differently from the<br>
way I do and do not question their honesty for a moment. <br>
<p>
If I have done wrong by filling the mailboxes of every SDAnet member<br>
with pages of arguments I'm sorry but I was only replying to issues<br>
which you brought up. You brought up a lot of issues and as you know <br>
it always takes less words to assert something than to analyse the assertions.<br>
<p>
I would like to ask, since we are now in the process of mapping out<br>
all the human genes, which gene would you like to propose as the "guilt"<br>
gene ? Does such a thing exist ? If so then genetic engineering is the<br>
greatest saviour of man/woman kind because we will be able to edit out <br>
the "guilt" gene from our gene sequences and therefore attain sinlessness !!!<br>
<p>
[ Good one hey ?:^)) ]<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; FIRST PARENTS.  Yes, we were present there, and we deserved to die as much</i><br>
<i>&gt; as Adam &amp; Eve did.  You complain about God not being fair in attributing</i><br>
<i>&gt; guilt to Adam and Eve's progeny -- to me, that argument just doesn't fly. </i><br>
<p>
But the bible clearly teaches in those 'volumous' articles that<br>
I posted, The child will not die for the sin of the father !!!<br>
<p>
Are you implying that God doesn't really mean that  ?<br>
<p>
What about when Jesus clearly teaches that there is no sin where there<br>
is no knowledge ?<br>
<p>
<p>
God would not be fair in arbitrarily condemning all the death and then<br>
giving us away out if we would like to chose it. That would be akin<br>
to a cat playing with a mouse. God doesn't play with us in that way.<br>
<p>
We both agree that salvation is only through the grace of Christ and <br>
that our works can not and do not atone for our sin in any way. The emphasis<br>
is surely Christ's work in us, "Christ in you hte hope of glory" Col 1:27 (?)<br>
<p>
Our role as you say is more than just accepting, its striving in all things<br>
to glorify God. "Present your selves a living sacrifice" "Be ye transformed"<br>
Salvation is not a passive experience, its an active one, Paul says its a<br>
warfare in which we should strive even unto death. EGW says that the battle<br>
over self is the hardest battle which must be fought and won, nothing about<br>
lounging around.<br>
<p>
Yes Christ does get all the glory because we wouldn't even aspire to<br>
the divine nature if it wasn't for what Christ has done, is doing and will<br>
do for us. Any effort required on our part is useless, like ropes of sand<br>
without the empowering grace of Christ. The effort on our part is to<br>
choose, that all we can do we have no other recourse, the battle is to<br>
choose not to sin, to chose to glorify God in all things. God's strenght makes<br>
our choosing a reality.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
