<title>Apr_1993: Original sin</title>
<h1>Original sin</h1>
lsusers (<i>LSARCHER@scifac.indstate.edu</i>)<br>
<i>28 Apr 93 17:22:45 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#414">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#414">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#414">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#414">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0415.html">Maurice George Ashton: "SDA various discusions this last week"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0413.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Adventist Congressmen"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0209.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Original sin"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
      Original Sin...<br>
<p>
I have read some arguments for and positions on original sin.  It<br>
seems that there is no way changes of opinions will occur.  Is anyone<br>
listening to anyone else?  I certainly appreciate the discussion.<br>
Has anyone read some of the arguments published in "Our Firm<br>
Foundation?  Unforyunately, I,m new to the net so I don't know how<br>
this conversation began.<br>
<p>
Personally, I do not believe that accepting either view affects my<br>
relationship with God, though it will undoubtedly affect the concept<br>
of salvation.  I do believe however, that those who try<br>
to enforce their rigid ideas on this controversial topic on others as<br>
a test of salvation (as many are wont to do) will not only be a<br>
stumbling block to some, but also place undue burdens on themselves.<br>
<p>
That's all folks!<br>
<p>
Len<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
