<title>Apr_1993: Original sin (and guilt)</title>
<h1>Original sin (and guilt)</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Apr 1993 20:04:08 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#416">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#416">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#416">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#416">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0417.html">Woody Baker: "Re: internet access"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0415.html">Maurice George Ashton: "SDA various discusions this last week"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0430.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben Gonzalez says:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I'm not soft on sin ! Sin in my books is worse that for those who believe</i><br>
<i>&gt;guilt is inhereted because there is no one else to blame for it but ourselves.</i><br>
<p>
How can we blame Adam &amp; Eve for the disease to which they exposed us, when<br>
Christ has given us the antidote?  That's what Paul is saying in Romans:<br>
we had no choice in the death sentence (and guilt) conferred upon us due<br>
to Adam's transgression, and we had no choice or part in Christ's<br>
Atonement, which sets us free of that guilt and death.<br>
<p>
Ruben's argument, if I understand it correctly, is that no guilt or sin<br>
passes to us from the transgression at Eden -- only the "sinful nature"<br>
(meaning, presumably, the effects of centuries of sin on the human<br>
organism).   We begin life with a "blank slate" and actually<br>
***could*** bypass Christ's Atonement and accomplish our own salvation<br>
if we tap into enough "power" (whatever that is).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;In the other view sin is God's fault because He is the one that originally</i><br>
<i>&gt;fixed it so that you could do anything about it.</i><br>
<p>
Ruben is being so tricky!  I never once would even suggest that God was at<br>
fault.  This is Satan's argument.  The Bible is clear as to who the<br>
originator of sin was, and actually, Ruben's argument would accuse God<br>
of not providing enough ***power*** to allow Adam and Eve to overcome<br>
sin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I'm certain of the honesty of those who believe differently from the</i><br>
<i>&gt;way I do and do not question their honesty for a moment.</i><br>
<p>
Sounds patronizing in view of the zeal with which Ruben attacks "those who<br>
believe differently."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;as you know it always takes less words to assert something than to analyse</i><br>
<i>&gt;the assertions.</i><br>
<p>
Not necessarily -- unless you are straining so badly to prove marginal<br>
points....<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;...we are now in the process of mapping out all the human genes, which gene</i><br>
<i>&gt; would you like to propose as the "guilt" gene ?</i><br>
<p>
Despite Ruben's attempt to belittle this point, let's keep<br>
in mind that, if we are all descended from Adam and Eve, as Scripture<br>
reveals, our genetic material was present there in Eden and, by<br>
extension, so were we.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;But the bible clearly teaches in those 'volumous' articles that</i><br>
<i>&gt;I posted, The child will not die for the sin of the father !!!</i><br>
<p>
The child will not die for sins committed by the father in knowing and<br>
willful rebellion against God.  Those kinds of sins are not what this<br>
whole discussion is about.  We're talking about ***original*** sin.  This is<br>
the guilt condition that transcends our will and our actions.  This is<br>
the condition we are in until we accept Jesus Christ as our Savior, who,<br>
as our Second Adam, lifts that guilt from us.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;What about when Jesus clearly teaches that there is no sin where there</i><br>
<i>&gt;is no knowledge ?</i><br>
<p>
There is no knowing, willful rebellion against God when there is no<br>
knowledge of God -- but there remains the original sin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;God would not be fair in arbitrarily condemning all the death and then</i><br>
<i>&gt;giving us away out if we would like to chose it.</i><br>
<p>
God had no part in the transgression of our first parents.  You should<br>
be careful in how you state that.  There was nothing arbitrary about it.<br>
He gave Adam and Eve every possible warning, but the bottom line was<br>
that "in the day that thou eatest the fruit thereof, thou shalt surely<br>
die."  Adam, the legal father of our race, in choosing rebellion against<br>
God, passed down the effects of that rebellion to all his progeny.  We<br>
are not each born as new Adams and Eves to be tested all over again.<br>
The test ***failed***.  It wasn't God's fault; it was our's.  Ruben<br>
doesn't seem to see this point.<br>
<p>
Now Christ has paid the price of Adam's trangression, and by accepting<br>
Him as our personal Savior, we are freed of the penalty due us from<br>
Adam's fall.  But Christ does much more for us.   He doesn't ransom us<br>
from the fall just to allow us to go on sinning.  By faith we becoming<br>
attached to Him and seek to do His will.  We draw strength from Him,<br>
through His Word and through His Spirit, which will protect us from sin<br>
and temptation.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; ... [our] battle is to choose not to sin....</i><br>
<p>
No, that battle was won by Christ nearly 2,000 years ago.  Our battle is<br>
to choose Jesus Christ day-by-day, moment-by-moment -- to love Him and<br>
serve Him and be faithful to Him.  That is to be the peak of our<br>
experience.  That is to be our drive and motivation.  The obedience that<br>
flows from such an experience is the only kind of obedience that is acceptible<br>
to God.  If we are striving to choose not to sin, we are rendering the sullen<br>
submission of a rebel.<br>
<p>
CLOSING NOTE TO MY FRIEND RUBEN: Ruben, although sometimes our words<br>
seem to carry anger, I hope you understand that I write what I write<br>
from my heart -- and that I do appreciate you and your well-considered<br>
responses to my posts.  I feel we can disagree on these issues and still<br>
serve our Lord Jesus in the ways He has in mind for us.  Discussion to<br>
me is enlightening, and I don't really mean to be as sour as some of my<br>
posts may occassionally appear to be.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
With apologies to Steve for the occassional use of CAPS.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
