<title>Apr_1993: Re: Stars in My Crown</title>
<h1>Re: Stars in My Crown</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Apr 1993 20:20:25 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#422">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#422">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#422">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#422">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0423.html">Bruce Holm: "Earthquake Predictions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0421.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0431.html">Dan Drazen: "Re: Stars in My Crown"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Perhaps the most interesting description of heaven I have heard in song<br>
is found in the fourth symphony of Mahler, the last movement,<br>
"Wir geneissen die Himmlischen Freuden... or something like that<br>
It's properly sung by a boy soprano and is a description of a child's view<br>
of heaven.  <br>
<p>
Various imaginations in the song include St. Luke as the keeper of livestock<br>
and St. Martha as the heavenly cook, and this is just the beginning.  <br>
Intriguing concepts (though not Historically Correct to be sure).  And<br>
it's a beautiful piece of music as well.<br>
<p>
Now blending the description of heaven with the question on God's will:<br>
It's one of the most true truths I know that God answers prayer.  So would<br>
urgent prayer for the Second Coming hasten that event or not?  Can prayer<br>
change the will of God?  Some examples in the Bible would indicate yes.<br>
(Moses' intercession for Israel).<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
