<!-- body="start" -->
Noe wrote:<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; Ruben is being so tricky!  I never once would even suggest that God was at</i><br>
<i>&gt; fault.  This is Satan's argument.  The Bible is clear as to who the</i><br>
<i>&gt; originator of sin was, and actually, Ruben's argument would accuse God</i><br>
<i>&gt; of not providing enough ***power*** to allow Adam and Eve to overcome</i><br>
<i>&gt; sin.</i><br>
<p>
No We would accuse Adam and Eve for letting go of the power.  I don't care<br>
how much poer you have it you let go of the source you have nothing.  Adam<br>
and Eve let go of the source which is God.  Today when I sin, it is because<br>
I let go of the power that God has made available to me, for He is able to<br>
keep me from falling.  Jude 24.  Also as Gal 2:17-19 says if I fall back into<br>
my old life of sin, blame me don't blame God.  Forgive me for my very loose<br>
paraphrase.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;as you know it always takes less words to assert something than to analyse</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;the assertions.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Not necessarily -- unless you are straining so badly to prove marginal</i><br>
<i>&gt; points....</i><br>
8-)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The child will not die for sins committed by the father in knowing and</i><br>
<i>&gt; willful rebellion against God.  Those kinds of sins are not what this</i><br>
<i>&gt; whole discussion is about.  We're talking about ***original*** sin.  This is</i><br>
<p>
Wasn't Adam our father.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; the guilt condition that transcends our will and our actions.  This is</i><br>
<i>&gt; the condition we are in until we accept Jesus Christ as our Savior, who,</i><br>
<i>&gt; as our Second Adam, lifts that guilt from us.</i><br>
<p>
Yes this is the question we are discussing.  Is their a guilt condition that<br>
transcends our will and actions.<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;What about when Jesus clearly teaches that there is no sin where there</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;is no knowledge ?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; There is no knowing, willful rebellion against God when there is no</i><br>
<i>&gt; knowledge of God -- but there remains the original sin.</i><br>
<p>
That is the question.  Is their an original sin that remains?  This gives<br>
me another question.  If Christ forgives us of original sin, can we ever lose<br>
this forgiveness?  This question probably was not clear.<br>
<p>
Can we lose our forgiveness of original sin like we can lose our forgiveness of<br>
sin due to our willfull acts?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; God had no part in the transgression of our first parents.  You should</i><br>
<i>&gt; be careful in how you state that.  There was nothing arbitrary about it.</i><br>
<i>&gt; He gave Adam and Eve every possible warning, but the bottom line was</i><br>
<p>
What was our part in the transgression of the first parents?<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Now Christ has paid the price of Adam's trangression, and by accepting</i><br>
<i>&gt; Him as our personal Savior, we are freed of the penalty due us from</i><br>
<i>&gt; Adam's fall.  But Christ does much more for us.   He doesn't ransom us</i><br>
<i>&gt; from the fall just to allow us to go on sinning.  By faith we becoming</i><br>
<i>&gt; attached to Him and seek to do His will.  We draw strength from Him,</i><br>
<i>&gt; through His Word and through His Spirit, which will protect us from sin</i><br>
<i>&gt; and temptation.</i><br>
<p>
Just change Adam to Sherman and the whole paragraph sounds good to me. 8-)<br>
you state we draw strenght form Christ.  That strenth is the "power" I talk<br>
about.  You see it cannot be separated from Christ or his atonement, or<br>
his ministry in Heaven, or The Holy Ghost.<br>
<p>
