<title>Apr_1993: Re: WWC and Internet News</title>
<h1>Re: WWC and Internet News</h1>
Daniel Turk (<i>turk@isengard.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 29 Apr 1993 09:55:00 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#436">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#436">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#436">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#436">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0437.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "vege questions and Chinese food"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0435.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0420.html">David Klein - EECS: "WWC and Internet News"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0447.html">Dan Hamstra: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to the newsgroup "censorship" issue:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Hey all you netters, I got a good one for you.  Walla Walla College is</i><br>
<i>&gt; presently having a rather large debate on whether there should be any</i><br>
<i>&gt; monitoring and possible deletion of news groups such as alt.sex and</i><br>
<i>&gt; other similar groups.  I think this is going to become a greater issue</i><br>
<i>&gt; as more SDA colleges are connected to Internet and I'm curious on what</i><br>
<i>&gt; you have to say.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; As far as I know, the debate at WWC is presently confined to a forum</i><br>
<i>&gt; called RNS, but I think it will spred.  At present, it appears that</i><br>
<i>&gt; the forum members are about evenly divided between those that think</i><br>
<i>&gt; policing the news groups is wrong and those who think it is the</i><br>
<i>&gt; morally the right thing to do.</i><br>
<p>
Well, yes, Andrews does subsribe to news.  But we do not subscribe to<br>
all the news groups.  Probably I can express my feelings by an analogy.<br>
Just because the campus bookstore provides lots of magazines for<br>
purchase does not mean it provides all possible magazines available.<br>
Our bookstore provides things like Popular Photography, etc., but it<br>
does not provide Playboy, etc.  We do not feel that this is censorship<br>
or "thought control", we as an institution simply feel that these types<br>
of magazines do not represent what the Adventist Church stands for.<br>
Clearly if someone wants these magazines they can get them elsewhere.<br>
<p>
The same is true for news.  We do not subscribe to the alt newsgroups,<br>
yet they _can_ be obtained (by persistent users) from other places.<br>
Hopefully we are teaching our students how to evaluate and develop<br>
strong moral and ethical ideals and they will _choose_ quality<br>
publications and newsgroups to read.<br>
<p>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Dan Turk     Computer Science &amp; Information Systems     Andrews University<br>
Berrien Springs, MI          turk@andrews.edu               (616) 471-3426<br>
==========================================================================<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
