<title>Apr_1993: Re: Earthquake Predictions</title>
<h1>Re: Earthquake Predictions</h1>
Alan Fargusson (<i>70751.2436@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>29 Apr 93 12:21:39 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#428">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#428">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#428">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#428">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0429.html">Alan Fargusson: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0427.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0423.html">Bruce Holm: "Earthquake Predictions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0434.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Re: Earthquake Predictions"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I grew up in California.  We had so many people making predictions like this<br>
that I just ignore them.  What is actually surprising is that there are so many<br>
earthquakes in California that it is hard to be wrong when predicting that<br>
there will be one.  If I were to tell you that there will be an earthquake<br>
between May 16 and June 12 in California I would probably be right.  In fact<br>
there will probably be several.  Given this the track record of the predictors<br>
is very poor.  They tend to be wrong more often then I would expect, mostly<br>
from trying to give an exact time.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
