<title>Apr_1993: Re:  What Is The "Will of God"?</title>
<h1>Re:  What Is The "Will of God"?</h1>
Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473 (<i>jwiley@law.usc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 29 Apr 93 14:09:33 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#438">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#438">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#438">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#438">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0439.html">Steven Timm: "SDAnet charter"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0437.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "vege questions and Chinese food"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0424.html">Bruce Holm: "What Is The "Will of God"?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ah, what fun.<br>
What do you mean by "specific"?  Your socks and car questions?<br>
<p>
What do you mean by "the will of God"?  Exact or general, that is,<br>
a precise answer to every question, or a bringing of my will into<br>
harmony with His principles?  <br>
<p>
I find that on those occasions when I'm nearest to the latter idea<br>
and ask God, "What would you have me do?"  He usually reponds with,<br>
"What did you have in mind?"  Indeed, if my will is in harmony with<br>
His, then whatever I have in mind may be a quite satisfactory answer<br>
to the question.<br>
<p>
That's a rather short and practical response without "proof texts."<br>
<p>
--Jerry Wiley<br>
USC Law Center<br>
Los Angeles, CA 90089-0071<br>
(213)740-6473<br>
