<title>Apr_1993: vege questions and Chinese food</title>
<h1>vege questions and Chinese food</h1>
<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i><br>
<i>29 Apr 1993 14:52:56 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#437">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#437">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#437">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#437">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0438.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  What Is The "Will of God"?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0436.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve's questions about what would you do in various eating situations<br>
rang true for me!  I've been in nearly everyone of those, except the<br>
European setting.  Our Chinese grad student friends were aware of our<br>
vegetarian lifestyle when they invited us to dinner.  One set of friends<br>
had dried shrimp in everything, because to them it is not meat.  WE<br>
(oops, didn't mean to cap that) picked it out discretely.  The other<br>
set didn't have anything so obvious, but when I inquired about the<br>
wonderful dipping sauce (after dinner), they showed me a bottle of<br>
oyster sauce that was a key ingredient!  Oh well...  For me this is<br>
not a salvific issue at all, and I would rather drink oyster sauce by<br>
the cupful rather than offend my friends.  However, I might have<br>
explained our lifestyle further if they had invited us again, thus<br>
heading off the problem a third time.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
