<title>Apr_1993: Re: Original sin (and guilt)</title>
<h1>Re: Original sin (and guilt)</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 29 Apr 93 15:41:22 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#435">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#435">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#435">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#435">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0436.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0434.html">Healy, Tammy R: "Re: Earthquake Predictions"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0416.html">Steven Timm: "Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0446.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Ruben's argument, if I understand it correctly, is that no guilt or sin</i><br>
<i>&gt; passes to us from the transgression at Eden -- only the "sinful nature"</i><br>
<i>&gt; (meaning, presumably, the effects of centuries of sin on the human</i><br>
<i>&gt; organism).   We begin life with a "blank slate" and actually</i><br>
<i>&gt; ***could*** bypass Christ's Atonement and accomplish our own salvation</i><br>
<i>&gt; if we tap into enough "power" (whatever that is).</i><br>
<p>
_*_NO_*_ !! :)<br>
<p>
We are powerless to overcome sin, only with Christ imparted grace can<br>
we ever overcome. That power is what John tells us when he says "He gave them<br>
power to be sons of God, even to those who believe in his name." John 1 <br>
also Paul tells us that we should "know Him and the power of his resurrection."<br>
Are we not aquainted with God's power ?<br>
So we can not "accomplish our own salvation, whatever way you look at it.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; Ruben is being so tricky!  I never once would even suggest that God was at</i><br>
<i>&gt; fault.  This is Satan's argument.  The Bible is clear as to who the</i><br>
<i>&gt; originator of sin was, and actually, Ruben's argument would accuse God</i><br>
<i>&gt; of not providing enough ***power*** to allow Adam and Eve to overcome</i><br>
<i>&gt; sin.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
I know you didn't but that is the conclusion I must come to, because <br>
in that view He created me already a sinner, guilty of sin, and <br>
reasoning in a systematic (theological) manner unable to ever overcome sin.<br>
<p>
Thus (and EGW says so) the blame sin must fall on God.<br>
"Exact obedience is required and those that say that it is not possible<br>
to live a perfect life throw upon God the imputation of injustice and<br>
untruth." Ms 147; RH Feb7, 1957<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;I'm certain of the honesty of those who believe differently from the</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;way I do and do not question their honesty for a moment.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Sounds patronizing in view of the zeal with which Ruben attacks "those who</i><br>
<i>&gt; believe differently."</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Thanks Noe, but I didn't mean to be patronizing in the slightest, I was just<br>
stating my respect for your conclusions. <br>
<p>
I hope (and don't believe) that I have ever attacked you personally once<br>
in this entire discussion, so I don't believe the above statement is acurate.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;as you know it always takes less words to assert something than to analyse</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;the assertions.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Not necessarily -- unless you are straining so badly to prove marginal</i><br>
<i>&gt;points....</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
Marginal ? straining ? nah, they were dead simple, its just that overwelming<br>
evidence takes more space to present than single assertions.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;....</i><br>
<i>&gt; Despite Ruben's attempt to belittle this point, let's keep</i><br>
<i>&gt; in mind that, if we are all descended from Adam and Eve, as Scripture</i><br>
<i>&gt; reveals, our genetic material was present there in Eden and, by</i><br>
<i>&gt; extension, so were we.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Yes the dust  (raw chemical material) did exist, But I didn't, saying<br>
otherwise is getting to close to saying that we prexist our births which<br>
is getting too close to the immortality of the soul for my liking.<br>
<p>
 <br>
<i>&gt; The child will not die for sins committed by the father in knowing and</i><br>
<i>&gt; willful rebellion against God.  Those kinds of sins are not what this</i><br>
<i>&gt; whole discussion is about.  We're talking about ***original*** sin.  This is</i><br>
<p>
It is exactly the same principle if Adam, our father's sin holds then so<br>
does our immediate father's sin. God does not change the rules.<br>
This dicotemy you present of original sin verses normal sin is artificial<br>
and again extrabiblical.. and dare I say it Augustinian in origin, not<br>
a man I would put much trust in.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; &gt;What about when Jesus clearly teaches that there is no sin where there</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;is no knowledge ?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; There is no knowing, willful rebellion against God when there is no</i><br>
<i>&gt; knowledge of God -- but there remains the original sin.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
The bible doesn't say that anywhere. As such this idea is extra-biblical,<br>
and not something I would build my faith on.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;God would not be fair in arbitrarily condemning all the death and then</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;giving us away out if we would like to chose it.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; God had no part in the transgression of our first parents.  You should</i><br>
<i>&gt; be careful in how you state that.  There was nothing arbitrary about it.</i><br>
<i>&gt; He gave Adam and Eve every possible warning, but the bottom line was</i><br>
<i>&gt; that "in the day that thou eatest the fruit thereof, thou shalt surely</i><br>
<i>&gt; die."  Adam, the legal father of our race, in choosing rebellion against</i><br>
<i>&gt; God, passed down the effects of that rebellion to all his progeny.  We</i><br>
<i>&gt; are not each born as new Adams and Eves to be tested all over again.</i><br>
<i>&gt; The test ***failed***.  It wasn't God's fault; it was our's.  Ruben</i><br>
<i>&gt; doesn't seem to see this point.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
It isn't my fault at all, I wasn't there and had no say whatsoever.<br>
God does not blame me for something I didn't. That is unjust and contrary<br>
to God's nature!  Niether did I say that God was the cause of Adam's <br>
transgression, but the doctrine of original sin leads to the concept<br>
that sin is unavoidable and therefore God is responsible for our sin.<br>
see EGW's quote above.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; ... [our] battle is to choose not to sin....</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; No, that battle was won by Christ nearly 2,000 years ago.  Our battle is</i><br>
<i>&gt; to choose Jesus Christ day-by-day, moment-by-moment -- to love Him and</i><br>
<i>&gt; serve Him and be faithful to Him.  That is to be the peak of our</i><br>
<p>
Same thing, you either choose Christ or sin, you can't have both<br>
unless you are part of the harlot Babylon who want's to unite in fornication<br>
the holy and the profane.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; CLOSING NOTE TO MY FRIEND RUBEN: Ruben, although sometimes our words</i><br>
<i>&gt; seem to carry anger, I hope you understand that I write what I write</i><br>
<i>&gt; from my heart -- and that I do appreciate you and your well-considered</i><br>
<i>&gt;....</i><br>
<p>
As I have privately mentioned, and tried to explain in my last post (see above)<br>
I appreciate your responses. I hope that none of my replies have appeared<br>
to carry any anger, because there is none.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
