<title>Apr_1993: Chicago Tribune:  ADRA in Yugoslavia</title>
<h1>Chicago Tribune:  ADRA in Yugoslavia</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 29 Apr 1993 19:28:40 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#425">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#425">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#425">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#425">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0426.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Evil &amp; guilt"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0424.html">Bruce Holm: "What Is The "Will of God"?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Excerpts from an article on the front page of today's Chicago Tribune.<br>
By Thom Shanker of the Chicago Tribune<br>
<p>
"...The Seventh-day Adventists, with only a handful of adherents<br>
in all of the former Yugoslavia, already have delivered almost 80000<br>
letters and parcels across front lines and into beseiged enclaves,<br>
providing the only reliable link among loved ones in a land filled with<br>
hatred.<br>
<p>
The future of the mail service is in doubt since the Adventists' aid agency<br>
is just about broke.  Each convoy run costs $30000.  But thus far, nothing <br>
has stopped this mail run from getting through.<br>
<p>
"We have been successful because we are exclusively a humanitarian<br>
organization that is not violating any rules of delivering our aid," said<br>
Ratko Kuburic, secretary of the Adventist Development and Relief Agency<br>
(ADRA).<br>
<p>
"We get through because we are not helping just one nationality," he said.<br>
"We are helping everyone.  This is our biblical principle.  ...<br>
<p>
Since the first mail run last September, ADRA has taken 40000 letters<br>
and parcels into Sarajevo.  It also has brought another 38000 out to<br>
Belgrade for<br>
local delivery here or shipment to Croatia, still at war with its Serb <br>
minority, and to addresses in Europe and North America.<br>
<p>
On their first deliver the ADRA postal carriers drove around Sarajevo by<br>
themselves and got shot at by snipers, Kuburic said.  "There is no<br>
electricity in the apartment buildings, so no elevators.  They had to<br>
walk<br>
up 16 flights of stairs.<br>
<p>
ADRA now delivers mail to a central location in Sarajevo, and the names<br>
of recipients are cirulated on a computer printout for pickup.<br>
<p>
The refugee network has heard about ADRA--an estimated 2.5 million people<br>
have been displaced by the war--and the demand is so overwhelming that the <br>
aid agency had to turn down 150000 people who wanted packages delivered<br>
on Wednesday's mail run.  "Letters and medicine we never turn down,"<br>
Kuburic said, andno packages are accepted if they contain cigarettes, <br>
alcohol, coffee, or food items that spoil, like meat or cheese.  No postage<br>
is required.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
