<title>Apr_1993: SDAnet charter</title>
<h1>SDAnet charter</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 29 Apr 1993 19:41:52 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#439">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#439">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#439">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#439">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0440.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Church clothes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0438.html">Vice-Dean Jerry Wiley - x06473: "Re:  What Is The "Will of God"?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Everyone who joins the net receives a copy of the charter when he/she joins.<br>
But the charter has evolved quite a bit recently, and was recently approved<br>
in its revised version by the SDAnet board.  Those who have been on the net<br>
a long time will be amazed to see how much legalese has crept in over<br>
the years.<br>
<p>
Here it is<br>
<p>
<p>
SDAnet Charter:<br>
<p>
What SDAnet is:<br>
<p>
     SDAnet is a Seventh-day Adventist electronic discussion list.  <br>
     Messages are distributed around the world through electronic mail.  <br>
     All messages are approved by a moderator and are private in the sense <br>
     that they are sent only to those who subscribe. <br>
<p>
Purposes of SDAnet:<br>
<p>
     1)  To encourage contact between SDA's on various public campuses, <br>
     industry, and Adventist campuses.<br>
<p>
     2)  To supply information on what Seventh-day Adventists believe.<br>
     We have the SDA "Statement of Fundamental Beliefs" on line, and anyone<br>
     is welcome to ask questions or discuss what they mean.<br>
<p>
     3)  To discuss practical issues of relevance to the Adventist subculture<br>
     and the world in general.<br>
<p>
     4)  To allow for announcement of gatherings and conferences of interest<br>
     to the college and university community.<br>
<p>
     5)  To discuss issues in human relations.<br>
<p>
Legal Disclaimers:<br>
<p>
     This list is not an official arm of the Seventh-day Adventist church.<br>
     Steve Timm, the moderator, is a member of the church, but holds no  <br>
     position within the church and draws no salary from it.  <br>
<p>
     Some government and military sites restrict participation in private <br>
     mailing lists.  If you are in doubt you should check with your system <br>
     administrator to make sure it is all right.  SDAnet management assumes <br>
     no responsibility for illegal subscriptions.  SDAnet management reserves<br>
     the right to desubscribe people who persistently violate the charter.<br>
     SDAnet management attempts to prevent postings of confidential material<br>
     and illegal use of copyrighted material, but cannot assume responsibility<br>
     for ensuring that all posts sent by its members are legal and appropriate.<br>
     Responsibility for each post rests with the individual poster.<br>
<p>
     Opinions expressed on SDAnet do not necessarily reflect the opinions or <br>
     policies of the organizations that supply SDAnet with computer access.<br>
     Carnegie Mellon University is so undecided that its official colors<br>
     are plaid.  It has no opinions.<br>
<p>
Associated lists:<br>
<p>
     Posts from SDA-L, a fellowship and support list for Adventists in <br>
     the college community, are forwarded to SDAnet.  Enoch Hwang is <br>
     SDA-L listowner in charge of system management, and Steve Timm is in<br>
     charge of membership and subscriptions.  SDA-L posts sent to the SDAnet<br>
     address will be forwarded if they have SDA-L in the subject line.  SDA-L<br>
     is a LISTSERV-based list which can be subscribed to directly by sending <br>
     SUB SDA-L YOURNAME to LISTSERV@LLUVM.Bitnet    Attempts to post by non-<br>
     members to that list will be rejected.  SDA-L currently generates 3-10<br>
     messages per month.<br>
<p>
Moderatorial policies:<br>
<p>
     Opinions expressed on <br>
     this list will not necessarily reflect the official position of the SDA <br>
     church.  They should, however, reflect the Christian ideals of love and <br>
     courtesy.  Inflammatory comments will therefore be either heavily edited <br>
     or rejected.  Long articles should be broken into segments of 200 lines <br>
     or less.  SDAnet is not intended to duplicate the general discussion for <br>
     which specific public forums already exist, such as abortion or evolution.<br>
     SDAnet is not intended for advertising the sale of goods and services,<br>
     but members may notify the net of the availability of a product or service<br>
     and invite interested readers to obtain the details via electronic mail,<br>
     provided that the product is in keeping with the mission of SDAnet.<br>
  <br>
     A board of seven SDAnet members oversees the management of SDAnet.<br>
     They serve one-year terms beginning in February and October.  <br>
     At the beginning of each term the moderator will announce the number<br>
     of vacancies to be filled and those members interested in serving<br>
     will submit applications.  If more applications are received than<br>
     seats are available, the names will be submitted to the net for a vote,<br>
     with each net member casting votes for a number of persons equal <br>
     to the number of open seats.  If the previous chairperson is not <br>
     re-elected to the board, he or she shall stay on the board for another<br>
     year as an ex officio (non-voting) member.  The moderator is an<br>
     ex officio member of the board as well.  Vacancies during a board<br>
     term may be filled by the board, or by the moderator at the request<br>
     of the board.  If no volunteers exist for a board seat, the seat<br>
     shall be filled by choosing SDAnet members in order of decreasing<br>
     seniority on the net.  <br>
<p>
     Complaints concerning the conduct of the moderator should be directed<br>
     to the board members at sdanetboard@andrews.edu.<br>
     The board members can set moderatorial policy for SDAnet and <br>
     find a replacement or substitute moderator if the present moderator<br>
     becomes incapacitated or loses net access.  The board also serves<br>
     as advisors to the moderator on technological improvements to the net,<br>
     new and expanded services offered by the net, and publicity and growth<br>
     of the net.<br>
<p>
Technical information:<br>
<p>
     SDAnet typically generates 80-200 messages per month, sent in bunches<br>
     once or twice a day.  Persons with limited disk space should notify <br>
     the moderator if they are on vacation so that messages can be halted<br>
     for that period.  Users whose account is unreachable for more than <br>
     a week and do not or cannot notify the moderator about this will be<br>
     automatically desubscribed.<br>
<p>
     Anyone may post to this list, and anyone may subscribe.  To do either,<br>
     send electronic mail to Steve Timm, the moderator, at <br>
<p>
     Internet:<br>
     st0o+SDA@andrew.cmu.edu<br>
<p>
     Bitnet:<br>
     st0o+SDA@ANDREW.Bitnet   (JNET%"st0o+SDA@ANDREW")<br>
<p>
     UUCP:<br>
     ..!uunet!andrew.cmu.edu!st0o+SDA<br>
<p>
     Compuserve:*<br>
		INTERNET:st0o@andrew.cmu.edu<br>
     Genie:*<br>
           st0o@andrew.cmu.edu#INET<br>
<p>
     We also serve users with X.400 protocol, America Online, Genie,<br>
     AT+T mail, and MCI mail.  Prodigy connections will soon be possible.<br>
<p>
     *Compuserve and Genie apply extra charges for receiving messages<br>
     from and sending messages to Internet.  For this purpose these<br>
     users and others for whom high traffic is a problem may subscribe<br>
     to the weekly SDAnet digest in which all the messages arrive as one<br>
     huge message per week.  The digest is not recommended for America Online<br>
     subscribers.<br>
<p>
     US mail to Steve Timm, Carnegie Mellon Univ. Department of Physics,<br>
                       Pittsburgh PA  15213<br>
	Phone:  (708) 840-4873<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
