<title>Apr_1993: Thought...</title>
<h1>Thought...</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 29 Apr 93 22:06:56 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#454">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#454">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#454">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#454">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0455.html">CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za: "Re: The will of God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0453.html">Steven Timm: "Internet/Usenet news"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
While reading in the Desire of Ages this evening [Is Not This The <br>
Carpenter's Son]<br>
I was intrigued by this passage:<br>
<p>
"If Christ had called attention to the Pharisees, and had extoled their <br>
learning<br>
and piety, they (Israel) would have hailed Him with joy.  But when He <br>
spoke of the<br>
kingdom of heaven as a dispensation of mercy for all mankind, He was presenting<br>
a phase or religion they would not tolerate.  Their own example and <br>
teaching had<br>
never been such as to make the service of God seem desirable.  When they saw<br>
Jesus giving attention to the very ones they hated and repulsed, it <br>
stirred up the<br>
worst passions of their proud hearts.  Notwithstanding their boast that <br>
under the<br>
'Lion of the tribe of Judah,' (Rev 5:5) Israel should be exalted to <br>
pre-eminence over<br>
all nations, they could have borne the disappointment of their ambitious hopes<br>
better than they could bear Christ's reproof of their sins, and the <br>
reproach they felt<br>
even from the presence of His purity."<br>
<p>
Some paragraphs before it discusses their prejudice, bigotry, <br>
self-righteousness,<br>
worship of status, wealth, and mercilessness.  I wonder what the time <br>
cycle is for<br>
the repetition of history in "the Church" or "Christened"?  How would <br>
we respond if<br>
Christ came to<br>
town pointing up &gt;OUR&lt; prejudices, bigotry, self-righteousness, worship <br>
of status,<br>
wealth, and mercilessness today?  Better still in what specific ways do we act<br>
out "self-righteously", in prejudice/bigotry, seeking status/wealth, and being<br>
unmerciful?  ISN'T THERE AN *overcoming* DEBATE SOMEWHERE ON<br>
SDA NET?<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
