<title>Apr_1993: Re: Original sin (and guilt)</title>
<h1>Re: Original sin (and guilt)</h1>
Noe Torres | ECISD (<i>noe@tenet.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 30 Apr 1993 07:38:58 -0500 (CDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#446">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#446">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#446">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#446">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0447.html">Dan Hamstra: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0445.html">Steven Timm: "Sodom and Gomorrah"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0435.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0441.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben,<br>
I would like to thank you for keeping your responses on such a positive<br>
level, and for defining that the "power" that saves is none other than the<br>
grace of Christ.  I apologize for suggesting that, in some of your<br>
statements, you seemed to be patronizing your opponents.  I just<br>
misunderstood you.<br>
<p>
The more clearly we define our terms, the more room for agreement I find<br>
in your positions, especially with regard to the sanctified life.  The<br>
statement you've quoted several times, where EGW says that if we say we<br>
cannot keep the law perfectly we are accusing God of being unjust, is very<br>
good.  What it means is that we ***can*** keep God's law perfectly by<br>
accepting the perfect righteousness of Christ.  Christ kept the law<br>
perfectly and his perfection is credited to our account.  We can add<br>
nothing to the transaction.<br>
<p>
Concerning original sin, I disagree that it is "extra-biblical," as you<br>
state.  I think it is quite "intra-biblical."  It is such a prevalent<br>
concept, a "given," that there would have been little reason for extended<br>
discourses explaining it in detail.  Because Adam sinned, we are all<br>
conceived in sin.  To be guilty before God a human being does not have to<br>
personally re-experience Adam's fall.  "By one man's disobedience many<br>
were made sinners" (Romans 5:19).  A person is not a sinner solely because<br>
he sins; rather, he is a sinner because he is born from a sinful being. <br>
"Behold I was shapen in iniquity; and in sin did my mother conceive me"<br>
(Psalm 51:5).  "The wicked are estranged from the womb: they go astray as<br>
soon as they are born, speaking lies" (Psalm 58:3).  Paul states that even<br>
if a person were to never actually commit a sinful act, he would still be<br>
accounted a sinner "after the similitude of Adam's transgression" (Romans<br>
5:14).  <br>
<p>
Concerning original sin, the Bible calls Eve "the mother of all living"<br>
(Genesis 3:20), and the Bible says "Who can bring a clean [sinless] thing<br>
out of an unclean? not one" (Job 14:4).  Concerning the fact that God<br>
holds us responsible for the actions of our forefathers, consider that God<br>
credited Levi with paying tithes while he was yet "in the loins" of<br>
Abraham, four hundred years prior to his birth (Hebrews 7:9,10)!  <br>
<p>
This concludes my part in the discussions related to this thread.  I think<br>
both sides have presented articulate viewpoints.  I appreciate the<br>
contributions of my friend Ruben Gonzalez and others on the net.  These<br>
discussions, I feel, have helped me immensely.  From my perspective, the<br>
matter is now concluded.<br>
<p>
NOE@TENET.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
