<title>Apr_1993: Re: PROOF BY CAPS LOCK and other mysteries of email</title>
<h1>Re: PROOF BY CAPS LOCK and other mysteries of email</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 30 Apr 93 10:12:35 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#442">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#442">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#442">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#442">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0443.html">Steven Timm: "Has anyone heard of NLP?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0441.html">Sherman Cox: "Re: Original sin (and guilt)"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0419.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: PROOF BY CAPS LOCK"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0420.html">David Klein - EECS: "WWC and Internet News"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve's note on CAPS being regarded as shouting reminded me that a fair<br>
number of SDAnetters may be fairly new to the world of email, especially<br>
its arcane features.  I am thinking that some aspects of email communication<br>
style may surprise or offend them.<br>
<p>
I recall, altho only vaguely, that some psychologists, a few years back,<br>
studied how people communicated via email versus how they communicated<br>
face-to-face versus how people write to each other (anyone remember more<br>
specifics?).  Their observations, as I recall, were that communication via<br>
email tended to encourage negative traits.  For example, email seemed to<br>
encourage quick, impetuous answers rather than moderated, carefully-thought<br>
ones.  While face-to-face communication has near instant turn-around,<br>
societal customs and the body language feedback we get tend to constrain us<br>
from being offensive.  However, email is without these constraints<br>
and feedback.<br>
<p>
Anyone who can speak more knowledgably or eloquently than I on netiquette,<br>
please do so.  I think it would be helpful to our gentle subscribers.<br>
<pre>
-- 
