<title>Apr_1993: Re: The will of God</title>
<h1>Re: The will of God</h1>
<i>CHURMS@nacdh4.nac.ac.za</i><br>
<i>30 Apr 1993 10:23:59 +0200</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#455">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#455">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#455">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#455">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0456.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Prayer request"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0454.html">Marcus Stringer: "Thought..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hello there<br>
<p>
Bruce posted an interesting question as to the "will of God": is it individual<br>
or is it just moral?  Does He have a will for me, or does He just know what<br>
I should do now based on a general "will guideline" based on certain<br>
principles?<br>
<p>
I would also like to answer without textual evidence at this stage, but I<br>
think this is an important question.<br>
<p>
I have experienced what I percieve as God's will for ME, personally. I was<br>
conscripted into the army while teaching at one of our mission schools. (The<br>
alternative to going was either deferment, or prison.) It's a long story, but<br>
in brief: I asked the Lord whether He wished me to work for Him amoung my<br>
mates in the army, or rather back at the school. I entered the army (as a<br>
non-combattant), and spent just over a week there. A telex then came through<br>
from military headquarters declaring me permanently medically unfit. This<br>
might not seem strange, except for two factors:<br>
<p>
    1. The telex arrived the day before I went for the full medical checkup<br>
    they required. Up to the time of the telex, two army doctors had declared<br>
    they found nothing wrong with me.<br>
<p>
    2. I was so medically fit that about six months before, I had come third<br>
    in Helderberg College's cross country race, and had been running about 3<br>
    miles a day up to the time I went into the army.<br>
<p>
There are many more bits to the jig-saw puzzle of God's will, which allowed me<br>
to see in retrospect, how God had led in various unrelated circumstances.<br>
However here's the last piece of the jig-saw.<br>
<p>
Suddenly, I was without work - a missionary had been sent from the US to take<br>
my place. I phoned the principal. The story he told me was just as<br>
unbelievable. The 'wrong' missionary had been sent. He taught biology and had<br>
basically no Physics/Chemistry training (my subject). However, their biology<br>
teacher had already had to leave due to moral problems. And thus the 'wrong'<br>
missionary was there to teach biology, but they were again without a science<br>
teacher!<br>
<p>
I know this sounds rather personal, but It's just a testimony to the wonderful<br>
way God can lead in a personal way.<br>
<p>
Now, back to the question.  It would seem that witnessing both in the army and<br>
at school was within the 'moral will' of God for me. (Let's leave out the<br>
implications of combatancy versus consciencious objection versus pacifism just<br>
to keep things a little more simple.)  However it would seem that God wanted<br>
me back at our mission school. It makes one feel very humble on the one hand.<br>
On the other hand, it's wonderful to know God is interested in MY life.<br>
<p>
Yes, my personal view is that God is concerned with my every choice.<br>
<p>
CAUTION 1: - I don't believe that if I make one wrong choice, I have "blown<br>
it". God's will for our lives is not one long linear line of choices that He<br>
wishes I would make. It is rather a tree, where at each fork, He can lead us<br>
into the best decision at that point. If we don't see it that way, it is so<br>
easy to say something like "Well, I chose the wife God didn't want me to have<br>
- so I should divorce her and look for the one God did want me to have". And<br>
if I subsequently find she whom I think is the "right" one, and she's married<br>
already, the obvious conclusion is that she also made the wrong choice! Hey<br>
presto, we have another divorce on our hands. Sorry this sounds a little<br>
unreal, but in less important decisions, one can find oneself thinking that<br>
way.<br>
<p>
CAUTION 2: - I don't believe God's will makes my relationship a type of "yes<br>
sir, no sir" relationship. God's primary will for my life is a "moral will"<br>
principle - that I be happy - in the broadest and longest term sense possible.<br>
This includes taking my wishes into account. His interest in me becomes most<br>
personal when He goes out of His way to find out what would make me happiest -<br>
and then leads me into that happyness.<br>
<p>
PSALMS 37:3-5<br>
Trust in the LORD, and do good; so shalt thou dwell in the land, and verily<br>
thou shalt be fed.<br>
Delight thyself also in the LORD; and he shall give thee the desires of thine<br>
heart.<br>
Commit thy way unto the LORD; trust also in him; and he shall bring it to<br>
pass.<br>
<p>
This isn't a theological treatise - it's a testimony. It would be nice if<br>
some of you out there would reply with some texts, or further testimonies.<br>
<p>
Maranatha<br>
<p>
Cecil<br>
CHURMS@NACDH4.NAC.AC.ZA<br>
<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
