<!-- body="start" -->
[Healy, Tammy R writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; I am a student at WWC and I think that Internet shouldn't be policed.  If </i><br>
<i>&gt; they start with alt.sex, will they later decide to ban alt.vampyres or </i><br>
<i>&gt; alt.pagan, too.  I admit some of it is morally incorrect, but I figure </i><br>
<i>&gt; we're old enough now to make decisions on what we read.</i><br>
  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
True enough.  But you're not the only party involved in the communication;<br>
the college, via its computers, is also.  Therefore, I submit that they are<br>
under the same obligation, corporately, as you (and I) are, individually,<br>
to "make no provision for the flesh, to fulfil the lusts thereof" (Rom 13:14),<br>
to "flee also youthful lusts" (2 Tim 2:22), to have no contact with<br>
unclean things (cf 2 Cor 6:17), etc, etc.<br>
<p>
Let me give an example:  If I were to buy pornography from an "adult"<br>
store and defile my mind with it, would God only hold me to account?<br>
Or would the owners of the store, the providers, also bear a responsibility?<br>
I submit that they are also accountable to God for what they purvey.  I base<br>
this on another example.<br>
<p>
The children of Israel were old enough to make their own decisions<br>
and most chose of their own free will to follow in the worship of Baal.<br>
Were they responsible for their decisions?  Oh, yes.  And what about<br>
the priests, the providers/purveyors of Baal worship?  Were they also<br>
responsible?  Indeed!  And more so (see 1 Kings 18, esp v.40).<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
