<title>Apr_1993: Scaled Fish</title>
<h1>Scaled Fish</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 30 Apr 93 12:50:24 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#449">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#449">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#449">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#449">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0450.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Earthquake Predictions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0448.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: WWC and Internet News"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Hi Beng,</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I was just wondering about tuna not having scales. When I lived in Papua</i><br>
<i>&gt;New Guinea we caught some tuna once from the mission boat, and the national</i><br>
<i>&gt;workers cleaned it and ate it. It sure as heck appeared to have scales - </i><br>
<i>&gt;quite substantial ones, from memory. And I'm almost 100% sure it was tuna.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Are there different kinds of tuna, or what??</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Not that it worries me much, I don't eat fish any more myself anyway.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Tony</i><br>
<p>
Well, as far as I know, Tuna and Mackarel do not have scales. However, horse<br>
mackerel or Spanish Mackeral and certain kinds of fish which resemble tuna<br>
in appearence, do have scales, so that might have been the fish the workers<br>
caught.<br>
<p>
Actually, I'm not sure that scales is the issue, it could be that Leviticus<br>
was referring to fish in general. But as a rule of thumb, fish that come in<br>
strange shapes, puff up or otherwise look unusual, are very often poisonous<br>
or have venomous spines on their fins. Also, as an aquarium hobbyist, i can<br>
say from experience, that fishes which do not have a protective covering of<br>
scales are much more prone to infection, diseases and parasites than fishes<br>
with scales or body armour. As a matter of interest, the common carp has<br>
been bred into varieties which have only a few large scales on their bodies,<br>
or even no scales at all, whereas the natural wild form has a full covering<br>
of scales, and the migratory european and american eels, although they look<br>
scaleless and slimy, do have very small scales in their skin.<br>
<p>
-beng<br>
med10014@nusunix1.nus.sg<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
