<title>Apr_1993: Re: WWC and Internet News</title>
<h1>Re: WWC and Internet News</h1>
<i>CHURMS@nacdh7.nac.ac.za</i><br>
<i>02 May 1993 19:37:25 +0200</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#457">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#457">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#457">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#457">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0456.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Prayer request"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0420.html">David Klein - EECS: "WWC and Internet News"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Isn't the *news* issue something like verbal "news"?  I don't have to<br>
repeat all the garbage I hear by accident, but neither can I shout <br>
"stop talking - I don't agree with you" so that someone else won't hear<br>
what is being said.  <br>
<p>
It might sound over-simplified - but to me censorship is preventing <br>
someone else saying something, whereas a loose tongue is repeating what<br>
someone else has said.  <br>
<p>
So to me the issue is whether WWC or whoever, is actively partaking in<br>
spreading what they don't agree with - especially morally.<br>
<p>
Thus I'd suggest cutting the clear-cut dirty groups - while not disciplining<br>
students who use "devious" means to read them elsewhere.  The fact that<br>
they are available elsewhere restores the student's freedom of choice.<br>
However, the fact that they are cut is a clear statement of belief on the<br>
part of administration.<br>
<p>
I agree it's not a simple issue - but how's this for an approach to<br>
a clearly defined christian  standpoint.<br>
<p>
Cecil (churms@nacdh4.nac.ac.za)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
