Steve you've asked a hard question.  Hard in not in the sense that there is no<br>
solution, only in that it calls us to make some difficult decisions, <br>
and put for a<br>
not-before-exerted amount of energy.  It means that we must rearrange our<br>
priorities.  It means that the "church" and "family" realize that <br>
neither _just_<br>
the one or _just_ the other can fulfill the needs our children are facing.<br>
Even though I have no children of my own, I say "our children" because as<br>
a member in the body of Christ, I too am responsible to help ALL people<br>
around me.<br>
<p>
TV used correctly, can be a great tool to educate in all areas not just in<br>
religion.  Television used abusively can desensitize, and cloud the mind<br>
from spiritual things as well as "secular" mental exercise (let the grades in<br>
our school systems testify).  Granted that Television can be affecting the<br>
attention spans of our kids, other things might be at work also.  There might<br>
be problems going on in the home, the child may be dealing with issues<br>
which seem urgent, or troublesome thus they give less attention to the<br>
brief escape the puppet show offers.  Don't write these children off, you'll<br>
be surprised what you'll discover in getting close to them to understand<br>
their "world."<br>
<p>
Keep the faith - Hold ON!<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
