<title>Apr_1993: RE: Power for victory</title>
<h1>RE: Power for victory</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 13 May 93 22:59:38 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#277">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#277">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#277">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#277">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0278.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Power for victory"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0276.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "Re: Humanity of Christ"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0279.html">Noe Torres | ECISD: "RE: Power for victory"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To me, Christ painting the picture of dependence on the Father,<br>
is more for our pee-wee brain than for what actually might have<br>
happened.  If Jesus DID depend on the Father, I have *NO*<br>
problem with this.  The crux of the matter is, we had - AND STILL<br>
DO to a great degree - an incorrect view/mental picture of the<br>
Father.<br>
<p>
So as a teacher and mediator, Jesus comes to earth does good<br>
things, reaffirms the principles which God's character and kingdom<br>
are built on and then starts slipping in hints of the reason for it all.<br>
"Psst, hey!  See what I'm doing, its not me - it's the Father!"<br>
And earthlings say, "Oh NOW we get it!  God isn't the fearsome tyrant<br>
waiting to burden us with oppressive law, and zap us out of existence<br>
if/when we fail!"  Of course that didn't happen but for a few whom we<br>
are latter told, turned the then known world upside-down, and even<br>
then weren't *mini-saviours*.<br>
<p>
Again we must come to the essence of it all... Jesus Christ and<br>
Him crucified.  If we try to get into the sheep fold bypassing the<br>
"Gate", we become thieves.<br>
<p>
Marcus<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
