<title>Apr_1993: RE: Jeremiah, and comparisons of prophets &amp; present critics</title>
<h1>RE: Jeremiah, and comparisons of prophets &amp; present critics</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 May 93 12:29:37 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#268">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#268">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#268">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#268">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0269.html">ELAINE KENNEDY: "DINOSAURS"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0267.html">HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU: "Re: Spiritual head of the family"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think this is a good start.  Criticism has been going both ways in <br>
this relationship.<br>
And on both sides of the fence there may be those who criticism out of <br>
the pride<br>
and self-righteousness of their hearts, and those who criticize out of <br>
the pain and<br>
love for what they view are the principles of God's character, law, and <br>
kingdom.<br>
<p>
So how are we - who only see the outside - to differentiate between the two?<br>
Does the present truth/everlasting gospel make that one of our action items as<br>
last day believers?  Or should we all be making a "B-line" to the cross, and<br>
encouraging ever nation, kindred, tongue, and people group to do the same?<br>
<p>
Marcus Stringer<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0269.html">ELAINE KENNEDY: "DINOSAURS"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0267.html">HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU: "Re: Spiritual head of the family"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
