</DOCHDR>
<!-- received="Fri May 14 18:06:11 1993 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Fri, 14 May 93 18:06:11 PDT" -->
<!-- name="Marcus Stringer" -->
<!-- email="marcuss@microsoft.com" -->
<!-- subject="RE: Job and the GC" -->
<!-- id="9304150105.AA00280@netmail.microsoft.com" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Apr_1993: RE: Job and the GC</title>
<h1>RE: Job and the GC</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 May 93 18:06:11 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#282">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#282">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#282">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#282">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0283.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Marriage hints &amp; tips file"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0281.html">Susan Harrington: "Re: Spiritual head of the family"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Are God and Satan the only ones involved?  Are we to sit back and <br>
say... well God<br>
and Satan have the leading roles in this drama, and we are just <br>
onlookers?  If the<br>
example of Christ's life says nothing else, it says (at least to me) <br>
that WE are<br>
participants in this drama.  Did Jesus sit by and allow people to be <br>
oppressed...<br>
"oh well there's a Great Controversy going these are the results of sin, the<br>
uncontrollable casualties, so we better not get involved."  (see Matt <br>
25: 31-46)<br>
<p>
Are we so "heavenly minded" that we are useless on this earth?  ADRA or <br>
community<br>
service don't count unless you are involved personally - - physically <br>
or financially.<br>
Even then, is our outreach such that it's only a "cover" to get people <br>
into our church,<br>
or is it because we have a genuine burden for them - church or no <br>
church?  We don't<br>
_have_ to be useless on this earth.  And I'm sure that if we (myself as <br>
Chief) spend more<br>
time helping other people, we would have less interest in poking at <br>
splinters in our<br>
neighbor's eyes while whole forests grow in our own.  It's harder to <br>
sit back and point the<br>
finger and call names like "conservative", "liberal", "legalistic", <br>
"immoral" when we are<br>
intimately involved in each other's lives, serving one another.  When <br>
we are being<br>
humane.<br>
<p>
Enough already!  I'm not one who expects a reign of peace [Christ's <br>
peace isn't the<br>
peace of this world (absence of problems differences of opinion) but <br>
complete trust in<br>
Him WHILE the winds of problems, and differences blow] on this earth, this will<br>
only come when Christ returns and smashes this earthly kingdom of <br>
"sacrificed integrity<br>
disregarded conscience, and indulged selfishness" - Desire of Ages <br>
p131.  This earth<br>
kingdom is not just in the hearts of "worldlings", but it's in some of <br>
us who profess to<br>
follow Christ.<br>
<p>
[God, help me to keep my eyes fixed on *You* and cling to the Cross <br>
were I belong.]<br>
<p>
Marcus Stringer<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
