<title>Mar_1992: Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</title>
<h1>Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 14 Mar 1992 22:43:24 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#60">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#60">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#60">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#60">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0061.html">callen roy: "Creationist mailing list net"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Dave Buxton: "Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0066.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul Gates writes:<br>
<i>&gt;Steve, I would be interested in you enlarging how Mich. Conf leaders have</i><br>
<i>&gt;taken EGW out of context in answering "Our Firm Foundation". I presume</i><br>
<i>&gt;this what you are referring to??? Correct?</i><br>
<p>
I don't recall whether or not I said "out of context".  But in context<br>
or not, the use was inappropriate.  Even the Devil can quote the Bible<br>
when it  is to his advantage.<br>
  In the fall of 1990 I posted a detailed series summarizing in detail<br>
the position taken by those published in Our Firm Foundation about the<br>
nature of Christ. The series also included a letter that was sent to the<br>
membership of the Michigan conference criticizing Hope International,<br>
its publishers, with holding camp meetings in Michigan without bothering<br>
to ask the conference leadership.  The pamphlet included a one-line<br>
quote from EGW that workers should always consult with the local leaders<br>
in a field before holding an effort.<br>
<p>
While this principle is a good principle, the tactic being used was using <br>
Ellen White to bolster their argument.  The theological term for this is<br>
"isogesis"--roughly, drawing out of a text what you wish to get of it. <br>
I reject the use of inspired writings as projectiles, no matter who does<br>
it.<br>
I would use Ellen White's statement that "The testimonies are never to<br>
be used as a club or whip" to back me up, but that would be an argument<br>
to authority, which would not be valid.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;It would almost seem from some of the email that God has nothing to do</i><br>
<i>&gt;with appointing church leaders any more? Is this true in your opinion?</i><br>
God still does have something to do with appointing church leaders, and<br>
I believe He has led in the appointing of the leadership in my<br>
conference, <br>
union, division, and world church.  Our conference president is a<br>
dedicated man who puts his money where his mouth is, opening his home to<br>
the young people of the "Twentysomething" age bracket such as myself. <br>
However, as these dedicated leaders attempt to apply themselves to<br>
preserving the institutions that absorb 90% of our tithe, they are<br>
fighting a losing battle, I believe.  In the small churches, the age of<br>
post-institutional, post-subculture Adventism has already begun.  If our<br>
leaders lose the battle for institutions but win the battle for souls,<br>
it will be a job well done, and I want to support them in every way I<br>
can.  <br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Is it true that we can prove anything "under the sun" from EGW?</i><br>
<p>
Pretty close.  But those who try are setting the rules of logic and<br>
debate above the guidance of the Holy Spirit.  <br>
<p>
For those of you who have not read books of Ellen G. White, I would urge <br>
you to do so, not to try to score a point here or there, but to hear<br>
what she has to say.  And accept the counsel not as a "magic hand-down"<br>
of a book <br>
of "don'ts", but for the reason she would want you to accept it--it's<br>
good counsel and makes sense.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
