<title>Mar_1992: Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</title>
<h1>Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>13 Mar 92 21:37:35 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#58">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#58">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#58">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#58">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Dave Buxton: "Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0059.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To David Buxton<br>
<p>
Dave, I perceive from what  you say that we should not over react on this<br>
business of Unity. EGW says that there is unity in diversity.<br>
<p>
I notice in Manuscript 111, written in 1903 that EGW said, "Unity with<br>
Christ establishes a bond of unity with one another. this unity is the<br>
most convincing proof to the world of the majesty and virtue of Christ,<br>
and of His power to take away sin." <br>
<p>
In John 17:20-23 it talks about the unity that is to exist between Christ<br>
and His followers. RH June 1, 1905, EGW is making the point that the unity<br>
that is to exist bwtween Christ and His followers does not destroy the<br>
personality of either. They are to one with Him as he is one with the<br>
Father.<br>
<p>
In the RH, July 4 1899 EGW also says, "The strength of God's people lies<br>
in their union with Him through His only begotten Son, and their union<br>
with one another. There are no two leaves of a tree precisely alike;<br>
neither do all minds run in the same direction. But while this is so,<br>
there may be unity in diversity. Christ is our root, and all who are<br>
grafted into this root will bear the fruit which Christ bore. They will<br>
reveal the frangrance of His character in the talent of speech, in the<br>
cultivation of hospitality, of kindness, of christian courtesy and<br>
heavenly politeness."<br>
<p>
 From your message you seem to be indicating that Unity is really on the<br>
side of Antichrist but not on the part of Christians. Do you mean to say<br>
this? How do you feel about having a relationship with Christ through the<br>
Holy Spirit? Is it possible not to have a relationship with Christ and<br>
still have the assurance of salvation?<br>
<p>
&lt;&lt;Pastor Paul&gt;&gt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
