<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Wed, 11 Mar 92 09:08:03 PST" -->
<!-- name="Dave Buxton" -->
<!-- email="davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com" -->
<!-- subject="Defining Catholic vs Protestant" -->
<!-- id="9203111708.AA15928@loowit.WR.TEK.COM" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Mar_1992: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</title>
<h1>Defining Catholic vs Protestant</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 11 Mar 92 09:08:03 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: 1 John 3:4"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0047.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In discussing Catholic vs Protestant it is not so much my objective to  talk<br>
about  the  RCC  vs  the  various Protestant churches.  Rather to talk about<br>
certain philosophies that are Catholic vs Protestant.<br>
<p>
Protestant, as I am defining it, places  the  individual  conscience  first.<br>
The  individual  conscience  before  God,  as he/she seeks to understand the<br>
Bible is what stands supreme.  Church and state must be subservient  to  the<br>
individual conscience.  This was the basis of the Protestant reformation and<br>
the United States Constitution.  This is what took men's necks  out  of  the<br>
stocks  of  the  early  pioneer days.  Even those in the minority can have a<br>
conscience that church and state must be subservient to.<br>
<p>
Catholic, in any church or state, places the church (or state) in command of<br>
man's conscience.  It is the clergy, of what ever church, who define what is<br>
doctrine and what is the creed of the church.  Only the eminent men  at  the<br>
top are seen to have the training necessary to properly interpret scripture.<br>
Members are  expected  to  place  their  individual  conscience  and  belief<br>
subservient  to that of such learned men.  "The greater good of the people",<br>
"the greater good of the church", "Unity"; these are the banners under which<br>
the  individual  is made subservient.  We see some of the same undertones in<br>
the Supreme  Court  judiciary  where  separation  of  church  and  state  is<br>
increasingly  questioned  and  the greater good for the majority is becoming<br>
more important than the individual conscience.<br>
<p>
The Protestant Reformation started out Protestant.   But  in  many  ways  it<br>
became  increasingly  Catholic.  Example -- Luther urged his followers to be<br>
friendly and warm to  the  Jews,  anticipating  that  they  would  join  the<br>
Protestant  Reformation.   But  when  they  planted  their  feet  firmly  in<br>
rejection of both the RCC and  the  Reformation,  then  Luther  became  very<br>
strong  against the Jews, even in a persecuting way.  The Annabaptists urged<br>
that the individual conscience stood supreme above the greater good  of  the<br>
Protestant  Movement.   And so Calvin, Luther and other leaders turned, in a<br>
Catholic way, against these Protestant dissidents.<br>
<p>
Catholic dogma can, interestingly enough,  tend  to  be  more  liberal  than<br>
conservative.  Let me explain.  Rome, the soil upon which Catholic grew, was<br>
the melting pot of religions from around the  world.   Those  peoples  whose<br>
religions  melted  into  the  Roman pot were accepted into the Roman Empire.<br>
Otherwise, Rome attempted  to  melt  those,  such  as  the  Jews  and  early<br>
Christians, out of existence.  Catholicism has learned much from Rome in its<br>
ability to be a melting pot of religions and  yet  to  persecute  those  who<br>
refuse  to be melted.  Catholicism embraces the largest spectrum of doctrine<br>
of any Christian church and yet can be very  inflexible  against  those  who<br>
refuse to be swept up in her broad net.<br>
<p>
Carl Rahner  is  one  of  the   better   known   Jesuit  architects  of  the<br>
Ecumenical  Movement.    In  one of his books he responds to the concerns of<br>
some of his friends that there  could  be  a  grass  roots  rebellion  among<br>
Protestants  against  the  Ecumenical  Movement.   He  writes, in one of his<br>
books, that they need not worry  because  the  Protestant  memberships  have<br>
become just as subservient to their leadership as the Catholics are to their<br>
Papacy.  This is virtually to say that most Protestants have already  become<br>
Catholic,  already  willing  to yield personal conscience to the moulding of<br>
their leadership.  Right now the ecumenical plan is to cast out as  large  a<br>
net  as  possible.  There will be plenty of time later to tighten in the net<br>
and to squeeze out the  dissidents  who  are  not  willing  to  yield  blind<br>
allegiance to church authority.<br>
<p>
What about the Seventh-Day-Adventist membership?  Are we  still  Protestants<br>
upholding  the  individual  conscience?   Do we continue to promote the idea<br>
that God inspired the Bible  as  a  book  that  laymen  can  understand  for<br>
themselves?   Or  are  we  becoming  Catholic,  with  belief  and conscience<br>
increasingly subservient to  church  leadership?   What  does  our  church's<br>
declaration  of  war  against  the  "Independent  Ministries" (including Joe<br>
Crews), have to say about the Catholic vs Protestant nature of  our  church?<br>
Have  the "independents" become what the Annabaptists were to the Protestant<br>
Churches of that erra?  Is  our  reaction  to  the  'independents'  becoming<br>
increasingly Catholic?  And, have some of the 'independents' become Catholic<br>
in their treatment of the rest of the church?<br>
<p>
Do we uphold the individual conscience, making church and state subservient?<br>
Are  we  Protestant?   Or  are  we  Catholic, insisting that "Unity" and the<br>
greater good for the church assert authority over the individual conscience?<br>
<p>
Dave (David E. Buxton)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
