<title>Mar_1992: Coffin on Creation</title>
<h1>Coffin on Creation</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 28 Feb 92 07:54:07 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#0">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#0">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#0">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#0">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Anyone want a job--low pay, lots of satisfaction...."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Last week-end Dr. Coffin was the guest and brought a lot of slides<br>
on geology, presenting, as a paleantologist, the creation perspective.<br>
<p>
I wish I had taken lots of notes, but I didn't.<br>
<p>
Quotes from Darwin that the lack of gradations or links could prove<br>
a problem for his theory, but a firm expection that this was a new<br>
area of geologic study and in time these links would be found.  But<br>
they have not been found.  The life forms in the Plaestocene are<br>
rather complex.  Todays versions of these life forms are often less<br>
complex.<br>
<p>
An 'early' bird with feathers and bones that match the format of a<br>
bird that flew, and yet claimed to be a grounded 'link' between the<br>
reptile and the bird.  But there is no record of feathers evolving.<br>
Also, more recent discoveries of these bird skelitons with more<br>
'modern' birds at deaper levels.  Can the son be the father of his<br>
grandfather?<br>
<p>
No hint at all of anything in the geological 'record' that would lead<br>
up to the turtle.<br>
<p>
He brought fossils of whole bodied fish with scales in good form.<br>
They have about a 1/4 to 1/2 inch of petrified casing that is best<br>
explained by body fluids oozing out into the surrounding sand or<br>
what ever.  That area of Brazil is litered with these fish that look<br>
like smooth loaves of french bread, each with a whole bodied fish inside.<br>
Studies have shown that in about 6.5 days a fishes flesh will completely<br>
rot away and the bones disconnect.  Cross sections through the gill<br>
chambers of these fossil fish from Brazil show the gills in a form<br>
that would only be found minutes after death.  Elsewhere deposits of<br>
thousands of square miles of fish scales that cannot possibly be from<br>
natural sedimentation since fish scales do not naturally deposit on the<br>
bottom of lakes and oceans, they rot and/or are devoured.<br>
<p>
Some years ago geologists were mostly of the catastrophy, even Bible<br>
flood philosophy.  One key reason a lot of these geologists converted to<br>
the evolutionary position was the finding of a lot of upright trees<br>
in deep coal beds.  But more recently there have been upside down trees<br>
found in coal beds.  When St. Helens blew, a lot of trees were blown<br>
over and thousands of trees were swept into spirit lake.  Coffin was<br>
the first to take a team of scientists up to Spirit lake as soon as<br>
the road was bulldozed.  They went scuba diving with cameras.  Most<br>
of the trees were still floating horizontal on the surface.  But quite<br>
a few were upright with a foot or two up above surface.  Some were<br>
floating free and some were grounded.  The scuba divers found that<br>
thousands of trees were standing upright, grounded on the bottom of<br>
the lake.  These are not trees standing where they grew, rather trees<br>
swept off the mountain by the blast of the erruption and/or the mud<br>
flows.  Many scientists are referring to Spirit lake as a coal field<br>
in the making.<br>
<p>
More and more Christians are espousing the idea that creation week took<br>
thousands of years.  Coffin offered a long list of objections to this<br>
theory.  I can recall a few of them:<br>
<p>
 * Yes, the old Hebrew did at times mean more than a day when the word<br>
   for day is used.  But not so in the context of "evening and morning<br>
   were the first day . . . .  Also, when Hebrew speaks of 1st day, or<br>
   2nd day, or 3'd day, it never means anything but a single day.  The<br>
   days of Abraham's life may have been more than a few days, but the<br>
   day his son was born was a single day.<br>
<p>
 * When did sin enter this earth?  Christians answer that it happened<br>
   when Eve and Adam sinned.  So, no death and dying before then.  But<br>
   if you insist that creation week was thousands of years long, then<br>
   you have to examine the geologic record as spanning many many<br>
   thousands of years; hence it is not the flood that explains the<br>
   'ancient' geology, but supposed God guided evolution.  So, the story<br>
   of Noah must be a fable.  Also, consider that the geologic record<br>
   shows animal predation, a lot of dog eat dog, in the layers before<br>
   man shows up.  Clearly, if creation week took thousands of years,<br>
   then there was sin in this earth long before Adam and Eve.<br>
<p>
 * A lot of Christians who have been taught the thousands of years<br>
   theory find it difficult to believe in the soon return of Jesus<br>
   to take us home with Him.  Some question that He will even return.<br>
   If the Bible says it took a week but it took thousands, even millions<br>
   of years, then will it yet be thousands, even millions of years<br>
   before His return.  If God lacks the power of creation week, then<br>
   how can He ressurect the dead?<br>
<p>
Problems with carbon 14 dating.  Assumption of uniformity.  But lots<br>
of examples that uniformity does not hold up.  That Carbon 14 and<br>
other dating schemes fail past a few thousand years.<br>
<p>
New lava flows that at sea level date ~0 years old.  But with depth<br>
the dates get to be thousands and millions of years old.  Evidently<br>
water pressure slows the de-gassing of these structures.<br>
<p>
A cave down in grand canyon.  The petrified dung heap of a giant sloth.<br>
Dating back through that dung heap.  The giant sloth must have been<br>
horribly constipated.<br>
<p>
Magnetic reversal, that the earth takes many thousands of years to<br>
reverse its magnetism.  But recently discovered lava formations in<br>
which have been found several magnetic reversals.  These lava formations<br>
could not possibly have taken many thousands of years to cool and set<br>
their magnetic fields in place.<br>
<p>
One theory is that all basic animal types marched off the ark, across<br>
the land bridges and around the globe, but in time they extincted in<br>
different areas of the earth.  This theory would propose that there<br>
might well have been kangaroos elsewhere, but they died out, except<br>
for Australia.  This theory would propose a richer variety of animals<br>
closer to where the ark settled.  Coffin points out that while this<br>
theory makes some sense for the animals; the widest variety of birds<br>
are to be found in South America.  But of course the birds would have<br>
more mibility to scatter across the earth.<br>
<p>
What about plate tectonics?  He finds that a valid theory.  But at some<br>
time things must have moved a whole lot faster.  At present sedementing<br>
rates and continental movement rates the sedementing would have more than<br>
kept up with the opening rifts.  There would be no deep ocean depths.<br>
Sedementation would easily have filled those deep trenches as fast<br>
as they opened up.  It appears that the continents did move around, but<br>
it could not have happened at the slow rate we see today.<br>
<p>
I asked him about DNA.  I had read a few years ago about scientists<br>
confidant that DNA studies would establish the animal family tree,<br>
perhaps re-aranging some of the branches, yet more properly establishing<br>
the family tree of the animal kingdom.  These studies have not proven out<br>
as anticipated.<br>
<p>
Dave (David E. Buxton)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
