<title>Mar_1992: NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue</title>
<h1>NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 02 Mar 92 10:11:49 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#2">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#2">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#2">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#2">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  NLP"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Anyone want a job--low pay, lots of satisfaction...."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0011.html">Paul Gates: "Re: NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The latest issue of McCall's describes behavior modification and NLP.<br>
<p>
  "The effective use of both behavior modification and NLP involves not<br>
  telling the other person what you're up to.  If that seems manipulative,<br>
  behavioral scientist Karen Pryor, a former dolphin trainer recognized as<br>
  one of the foremost researchers of animal and human behavior, offers<br>
  reassurance.  "We all go around trying to manipulate one another's<br>
  behavior all the time," she says -- and usually with tactics that don't<br>
  work.  Pryor, who is the author of the practical and delightful<br>
  behavior-modification handbook, Don't Shoot the Dog!  The New Art of<br>
  Teaching and Training, points out that "discussing your stragegies will<br>
  only interfere with and weaken their power."<br>
<p>
The article also explains B.F. Scinner techniques that you are probably<br>
all familiar with.  Sounds like what animal trainers have learned are<br>
the techniques more and more being used on humans.<br>
<p>
NLP techniques described.  For example tapping the table with finger<br>
tips in synch with the other person's breathing.  Once link is<br>
subconciously established, then tap faster to create a feeling of<br>
excitement or slower for relaxation.  Seeing that you can speed up<br>
or slow down their breathing, try other "leading" techniques.  Quoting:<br>
<p>
  "If you really want to see magic, try using two or more NLP techniques<br>
  together," says Brooks.  "Once your'e on the same wavelength, you can<br>
  verbally disagree without jeopardizing the relationship."<br>
<p>
The author of the McCall's article, in the last paragraph:<br>
<p>
  Does all this sound far-fetched?  Someone once used NLP on me, and it<br>
  was spookily powerful.  . . . . .<br>
<p>
Well, the debate rages on, at least out here, as to whether NLP is<br>
innocent or dangerous, whether its innocent hypnotism, dangerous<br>
hypnotism or not even hypnotism.  The article names those who 'invented'<br>
NLP.  Their books call it hypnotism of a form that is not readily<br>
detectable as hypnotism, hense it's greater power, they claim.<br>
<p>
Dave<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
