<title>Mar_1992: Re:  NLP</title>
<h1>Re:  NLP</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  2 Mar 1992 20:44:03 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#3">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#3">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#3">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#3">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "Patty Cabrera en Espanol"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Dave Buxton: "NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
We discussed NLP a couple months ago, but let me define terms for those who<br>
weren't with us then.  NLP is Neuro-linguistic Programming, and B.F.Skinner<br>
is the (in)famous behaviorist psychologist who developed the theory and<br>
practice of operant conditioning.<br>
<p>
This thing shows me how careful we should be to guard the avenues of the <br>
subconscious.  If there is hypnotism or mind control of any sort, it doesn't<br>
belong in our church.<br>
<p>
Recently William Johnsson wrote an editorial in the Adventist Review<br>
saying how he opposed hypnotism but didn't necessarily oppose Lab 1,<br>
the first step in the series towards NLP.  He tried to suggest that only <br>
Lab I was approved by the conference, but didn't say anything of those<br>
pastors who may be taking lab 2 on their own.  <br>
<p>
I know there are some people on the list who have mentioned going through <br>
Lab 1 before.  Does that involve some of the techniques described by Dave<br>
in his article?<br>
<p>
If we abandon the ultimate persuading power of the Holy Spirit for<br>
these mind games, we have a problem.  If we spend all our energy fighting<br>
these techniques, we have a problem, too.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
