<title>Mar_1992: Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc.</title>
<h1>Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc.</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  2 Mar 1992 21:25:00 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#5">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#5">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#5">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#5">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Steven Timm: "Majoring in Minors"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "Patty Cabrera en Espanol"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0019.html">Gross: "Re: Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I had heard several times before that in the New Testament, there<br>
are several very specific, but related words having to do with sin.<br>
When Ruben Gonzalez was talking a while back about a very narrow definition<br>
of sin (only the act), I looked this up, but the Greek concordance in <br>
Strong's didn't tell me very much.  <br>
<p>
Could it be possible, given the definition of sin in the Bible, <br>
that there are some things which are not sin, but are still wrong?<br>
I would appreciate insight on the meaning of such words as offense,<br>
iniquity, transgression, and sin, and the shades of meaning between them.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
