<title>Mar_1992: Majoring in Minors</title>
<h1>Majoring in Minors</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  2 Mar 1992 20:59:37 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Steven Timm: "Monopolies on truth?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Steven Timm: "Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0014.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Majoring in Minors"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
At our Twentysomething young adult program here in the Chicago area,  we<br>
spent last Friday night in lively discussion about several "hot" issues<br>
for Adventists, including if one ought to go to a friend's farewell party<br>
on Friday night and if it was OK to model in a fashion show wearing <br>
jewelry.  <br>
<p>
I was in the small group discussing jewelry.  Also in this group was <br>
Lynette, a first-time visitor with a Catholic background, and earrings in <br>
her ears.  Everyone in the group was careful not to condemn her, but<br>
she remarked afterwards that some people were avoiding eye contact with her.<br>
She also told us, "It seems like there's a lot more important things to <br>
talk about than jewelry."<br>
<p>
Now, while I believe standards are important and have defended them in <br>
this forum before, I'm forced to agree with her.  [Note:  if anyone<br>
responds to this thread arguing either the merits or the demerits of <br>
jewelry, I will reject the post.]   What are some issues that do have <br>
more import that one can discuss at such a meeting where non-Adventists<br>
are usually present.  I think that sometimes SDAnet suffers from the <br>
same disease of majoring in minors.  I can always use a good discussion <br>
topic here and at this young adults group, as it's my turn to lead it in<br>
three months.  <br>
<p>
Consider this topic for a minute:  If all the people from the local area<br>
of your church that visited it stayed, how much would your church grow?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
