<title>Mar_1992: Greek meanings for sin, iniquity, etc. (LONG)</title>
<h1>Greek meanings for sin, iniquity, etc. (LONG)</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 3 Mar 1992 06:09 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#9">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#9">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#9">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#9">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Monopolies on truth?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Health Messages of 1850-1877 by nonSDA religious leaders"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve asked for some definitions and distinctions for the <br>
words, sin, iniquity, transgression, etc.  I have taken the <br>
following from "AN EXPOSITORY DICTIONARY OF NEW TESTATMENT <br>
WORDS with their Precise Meanings for English Readers" by W. <br>
E. Vine.  I have not tried to list all the verses that use <br>
each word as these should be available in your concordance.  <br>
 From the previous discussion about perfection, it might be <br>
very revealing to look up the verses and see which actual <br>
Greek word was used to assist in the interpretation.<br>
<p>
*************************************************************<br>
<p>
WORDS FOR *SIN*<br>
<p>
1.  HAMARTIA (noun) is, literally, a missing of the mark, but <br>
this etymological meaning is largely lost sight of in the NT.  <br>
It is the most comprehensive term for moral obliquity.  It is <br>
used of sin as<br>
<p>
	(a) a principle or source of action, or an inward <br>
element producing acts, e.g., Rom. 3:9; 5:12,13,20; 6:1,2; <br>
7:7,8,9,11,13, "sin, that it might be shewn to be sin,"  <br>
i.e., "sin became death to me, that it might be exposed in <br>
its heinous character:  in the last clause, "sin might become <br>
exceeding sinful,"  i.e., through the holiness of the Law, <br>
the true nature of sin was designed to be manifested to the <br>
conscience;<br>
<p>
	(b) a governing principle or power, e.g., Rom. 6:6, <br>
"(the body) of sin", here sin is spoken of as an organized <br>
power, acting through the members of the body, though the <br>
seat of sin is in the will (the body is the organic <br>
instrument);  in the next clause, and in other passages, as <br>
follows, this governing principle is personified, e.g., Rom. <br>
5:21; 6:12,14,17; 7:11,14,17,20,23,25; 8:2; I Cor. 15:56; <br>
Heb. 3:13; 11:25; 12:4; Jas. 1:15 (2nd part);<br>
<p>
	(c) a generic term (distinct from specific terms such as <br>
HAMARTEMA, yet sometimes inclusive of concrete wrong doing, <br>
e.g., John 8:21,34,46; 9:41; 15:22,24; 19:11); in Rom. 8:3, <br>
"God, sending his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh," <br>
literally, 'flesh of sin,' the flesh stands for the body, the <br>
instrument of indwelling sin [Christ, pre-existently the Son <br>
of God, assumed human flesh, "of the substance of the Virgin <br>
Mary;" the reality of incarnation was His, without taint of <br>
sin (for homoioma, likenss], "and as an offering for sin,"  <br>
i.e., 'a sin-offering', "condemned sin in the flesh,"  i.e., <br>
Christ, having taken human nature, sin apart (Heb. 4:15), and <br>
having lived a sinless life, died under the condemnation and <br>
judgment due to our sin; for the generic sense see further, <br>
e.g., Heb. 9:26; 10:6,8,18; 13:11; I John 1:7,8; 3:4 (1st <br>
part; in the 2nd part, sin is defined as "lawlessness"), 8,9; <br>
in these verses the A.V. use of the verb to commit is <br>
misleading; not the commital of an act is in view, but a <br>
continuous course of sin, as indicted by the R.V., "doeth."  <br>
The Apostle's use of the present tense of poieo, to do, <br>
virtually expresses the meaning of prasso, to practise, which <br>
John does not use (it is not infrequent in this sense in <br>
Paul's Epp., e.g., Rom 1:32 RV; 2:1; Gal 5:21; Phil 4:9); I <br>
Pet 4:1 (singular in the best texts, literally, 'has been <br>
made to cease from sin,' i.e., as a result of suffering in <br>
the flesh, the mortifying of our members, and of obedience to <br>
a Saviour who suffered in flesh.  Such no longer lives in the <br>
flesh, "to the lusts of men, but to the will of God;"  <br>
sometimes the word is used virtually equivalent to a <br>
condition of sin, e.g., John 1:29, "the sin (not sins) of the <br>
word;"  I Cor 15:17; or a course of sin, characterized by <br>
continuous acts, e.g., I Thes 2:16; in I John 5:16 (2nd part) <br>
the RV margin, is probably to be preferred, "there is sin <br>
unto death," not a special act of sin, but the state or <br>
condition producing acts; in ver 17, "all unrighteousness is <br>
sin" is not a definition of sin (as in 3:4), it gives a <br>
specification of the term in its generic sense;<br>
<p>
	(d) a sinful deed, an act of sin, e.g., Matt 12:31; Acts <br>
7:60; Jas 1:15 (1st part); 2:9; 4:17; 5:15,20; I John 5:16 <br>
(1st part).<br>
<p>
Notes: (1)  Christ is predicated as having been without sin <br>
in every respect, e.g., (a),(b),(c) above, 2 Cor 5:21 (1st <br>
part); I John 3:5; John 14:30; (d) John 8:46; Heb 4:15; I Pet <br>
2:22.  (2) In Heb 9:28 (2nd part) the reference is to a sin <br>
offering.  (3) In 2 Cor 5:21, "Him. . . He made to be sin" <br>
indicates that God dealt with Him as He must deal with sin, <br>
and that Christ fulfilled what was typified in the guilt <br>
offering.  (4) For the phrase "man of sin" in 2 Thes 2:3, see <br>
Iniquity, ANOMIA.<br>
<p>
HAMARTENA (noun), akin to HAMARTIA, denotes an act of <br>
disobedience to Divine law [as distinct from HAMARTIA <br>
(a),(b),(c)].<br>
<p>
ANAMARTETOS (adj), without sin, negative form of HAMARTIA <br>
(c).is found in John 8:7.<br>
<p>
HAMARTANO (verb), literally, to miss the mark<br>
<p>
PROAMARTANO (verb), to sin previously<br>
<p>
*************************************************************<br>
<p>
Words for *Iniquity*<br>
<p>
ANOMIA, literally, lawlessness, is used in a way which <br>
indicates the meaning as being lawlessness or wickedness.  <br>
Its usualy rendering in the NT is "iniquity," which literally <br>
mean unrighteousness.  It occurs frequently in the Sept., <br>
especially in the Psalms, where it is found about 70 times.  <br>
It is used (a) of iniquity in general; (b) in the plural, of <br>
acts or manifestations of lawlessness<br>
<p>
ADIKIA denotes unrighteousness, literally, 'unrightness', a <br>
condition of not being right, whether with God, according to <br>
the standard of His holiness and righteousness, or with man, <br>
according to the standard of what man knows to be right by <br>
his conscience.<br>
<p>
ADIKEMA denotes a wrong, injury, misdeed, the concrete act, <br>
in contrast to the general meaning of ADIKIA.<br>
<p>
PONERIA, akin to PONEO, to toil, denotes wickedness and is so <br>
translated in Matt 22:18; Mark 7:22; Luke 11:39; Rom 1:29; I <br>
Cor 5:8; Eph 6:12; Acts 3:26.<br>
<p>
PARANOMIA, law-breaking, denotes transgression<br>
<p>
*************************************************************<br>
<p>
Words for *transgress*<br>
<p>
PARABAINO (verb), literally, to go aside, hence to go beyond, <br>
is chiefly used metaphorically in transgressing the tradition <br>
of the elders, Matt 15:2; the commandment of God, 15:3; in <br>
Acts 1:25, of Judas "by transgressions fell away";<br>
<p>
HUPERBAINO (verb), literally, to go over, used metaphorically <br>
and rendered "transgress" in I Thes 4:6, i.e., of <br>
overstepping the limits separating chastity from <br>
licentiousness, sanctification from sin.<br>
<p>
PARERCHOMAI (verb), to come by, pass over, and hence, <br>
metaphorically, to transgress, is so used in Luke 15:29.<br>
<p>
PARABASIS (noun), primarily a going aside, then, an <br>
overstepping, is used metaphorically to denote transgression <br>
(always of a breach of law):  (a) of Adam, Rom. 5:14; (b) of <br>
Eve, I Tim 2:14; (c) negatively, where there is no law, since <br>
transgression implies the violation of law, none having been <br>
enacted between Adam's transgression and those under the Law, <br>
Rom 4:15;  (d) of transgressions of the Law, Gal 3:19, where <br>
the statement "it was added because of transgressions" is <br>
best understood according to Rom 4:15; 5:13 and 5:20; the Law <br>
does not make men sinners, but makes them trangressors; hence <br>
sin becomes "exceeding sinful," Rom 7:7,13.  Conscience thus <br>
had a standard external to itself;  by the Law men are taught <br>
their inability to yield complete obedience to God, that <br>
thereby they may become convinced of their need of a Saviour.<br>
<p>
PARANOMIA (noun), law-breaking (contrary to law)<br>
<p>
PARABATES, literally and primarily, one who stands beside, <br>
then, one who oversteps the prescribed limit, a transgressor.<br>
<p>
ANOMOS, without law is translated "trangressor" is Luke 22:37 <br>
is really lawlessness.<br>
<p>
*************************************************************<br>
<p>
Words for *fault*<br>
<p>
AITION (noun), causative of, responsible for, is used as a <br>
noun, a crime, a legal ground for punishment<br>
<p>
AMEMPTOS (adj), without blame, is render "faultless" in Heb <br>
8:7; without any shortcoming, in Jude 24, and "without fault" <br>
in Rev. 14:5.<br>
<p>
MEMPHOMAI (verb), to blame, is translated "to find fault" in <br>
Rom 9:19 and Heb 8:8.<br>
<p>
ELENCHO (verb), to convict, reprove, rebuke, is translated <br>
"shew (him) his fault" in Matt 18:15.<br>
<p>
*************************************************************<br>
<p>
Words for *error*<br>
<p>
PLANE, a wandering, a forsaking of the right path, see Jas <br>
5:20, whether in doctrine, 2 Pet 3:17; I John 4:6, or in <br>
morals, Rom 1:27; 2 Pet 2:18; Jude 11, though, in scripture, <br>
doctrine and morals are never divided by any sharp line.  <br>
Errors in doctrine are not infrequently the effect of relaxed <br>
morality, and vice versa.<br>
<p>
AGNOEMA, a sin of ignorance, is used in the plural in Heb 9:7<br>
<p>
*************************************************************<br>
<p>
Words for *disobedience*<br>
<p>
APIETHEIA (noun), literally, the condition of being <br>
unpersuadable, denotes obstinacy, obstinate rejection of the <br>
will of God; hence, "disobedience;"  Eph 2:2; 5:6; Col 3:6; <br>
Rom 11:30,32 and Heb 4:6,11 speaking of Isreal, past and <br>
present.<br>
<p>
PARAKOE (noun), primarily, hearing amiss, hence signifies a <br>
refusal to hear; hence, an act of disobedience, Rom 5:19; 2 <br>
Cor 10:6; Heb 2:2.  It is broadly to be distinguished from <br>
APEITHEIA, as an act from a condition, though PARAKOE itself <br>
is the effect, in transgression, of the condition of failing <br>
or refusing to hear.  Carelessness in attitude is the <br>
precursor of actual disobedience.  In the OT disobedience is <br>
frequently described as a refusing to hear.<br>
<p>
APEITHES (Adj), signifies unwilling to be persuaded, spurning <br>
belief, disobedient<br>
<p>
APEITHEO (verb), to refuse to be persuaded, to refuse belief<br>
<p>
*************************************************************<br>
<p>
Words for *perfect*<br>
<p>
TELEIOS (adj) signifies having reached its end, finished, <br>
complete, perfect.  It is used of (I) persons (a) primarily <br>
of physical development, then, with ethical import, fully <br>
grown, mature, I Cor 2:6; 14:20; Eph 4:13; Phil 3:15; Col <br>
1:28; 4:12;  (2) complete, conveying the idea of goodness <br>
without necessary reference to maturity or what is expressed <br>
under (a), Matt 5:48; 19:21; Jas 1:4; 3:2  It is used thus of <br>
God in Matt 5:48;  (II) of things, complete, perfect, Rom <br>
12:2; I Cor 13:10 (referring to the complete revelation of <br>
God's will and ways, wheter in the completed Scriptures or in <br>
the hereafter); Jas 1:4 (of the work of patience); ver 25; I <br>
john 4:18.<br>
<p>
TELEIOTEROS (adj), the comparative degree of TELEIOS, is used <br>
in Heb 9:11, of the very presence of God.<br>
<p>
ARTIOS (adj) is translated "perfect" in 2 Tim 3:17 is really <br>
form of *complete*<br>
<p>
TELEIOO (verb), to bring to an end by completing or <br>
perfecting is used (I) of accomplishing; (II) of bringing to <br>
completeness<br>
<p>
EPITELEO (verb), to bring through to the end, is used in the <br>
Middle Voice in Gal 3:3, "are ye (now) perfected," continuous <br>
present tesne, indicating a process, literally, 'are ye now <br>
perfecting yourselves;'<br>
<p>
KATARTIZO (verb), to render fit, complete.  It does not <br>
necessarily imply, nowever, that that to which it is applied <br>
has been damaged, though it may do so; it signifies, rather, <br>
right ordering and arrangement.  It indicates a close <br>
relationship between character and destiny.<br>
<p>
AKRIBOS (adv), accurately, is tranlated "perfectly" in I Thes <br>
5:2 where it suggests that Paul and his companions were <br>
careful ministers of the Word.<br>
<p>
AKRIBESTERON (adv), the comparative degree of AKRIBOS, <br>
carefully, exactly.<br>
<p>
TELEIOS (adv), perfectly, is so translated in I Pet 1:13 RV <br>
of setting one's hope on coming grace.<br>
<p>
*************************************************************<br>
<p>
Hope this helps clarify things for you. If any of you would <br>
like a specific verse or word (any word) looked up, I'd be <br>
glad to answer you personally.  Just send me a note via <br>
email.  I have found this book very helpful in my own <br>
personal Bible study and can recommend it highly. I also have <br>
"DICTIONARY OF OLD TESTAMENT WORDS FOR ENGLISH READERS" by <br>
Aaron Pick which gives the root meanings of Hebrew words. <br>
<p>
Cheryl Berthelsen<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
