<title>Mar_1992: Re: NLP</title>
<h1>Re: NLP</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 03 Mar 92 06:25:25 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Majoring in Minors"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Paul Gates: "Re:  NLP"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[NLP discussion]<br>
<i>&gt; If we abandon the ultimate persuading power of the Holy Spirit for</i><br>
<i>&gt; these mind games, we have a problem.  If we spend all our energy fighting</i><br>
<i>&gt; these techniques, we have a problem, too.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<p>
I think that it is important to know enough about NLP, and other methods<br>
of mind control, so that we can recognize it when someone attempts to use<br>
it on us.  The other side of the coin is that repeated exposure to<br>
anything, will in time tend to legitimize it in our minds and reading<br>
the material is to expose oneself to the arguments that attempt to<br>
legitimize it -- such as -- hypnosis is something we all do nearly every<br>
day and we just don't realize it.  So, instead of being nieve hypnotists<br>
lets become sophisticated hypnotists.<br>
<p>
Back when I was a student at Blue Mt. Academy it was popular in our<br>
academies and colleges to hold temperance orations.  But all too often<br>
the young man who won the contest with his speach on tobacco went out<br>
that night and tried his first smoke.  Or alchohol . . . . .  That is<br>
the explanation given as to why we no longer have these contests.  If<br>
indeed this is true, then spending a lot of time being negative about<br>
something, say like NLP, can actually condition our minds to be<br>
receptive to using NLP techniques on others.<br>
<p>
I think it is important to know enough about it to be able to recognize<br>
it when someone is using it on us.  But not to get too carried away with<br>
it, even in a negative way.<br>
<p>
Dave (David E. Buxton)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
