<title>Mar_1992: Re: Majoring in Minors</title>
<h1>Re: Majoring in Minors</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 3 Mar 92 10:29:20 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Scott Mattes: "Re: NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Majoring in Minors"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0006.html">Steven Timm: "Majoring in Minors"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0020.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Majoring in Minors"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks for re-instating me on SDANet.  I have comments on a couple matters.<br>
<p>
It would be wise for people to look at where the hypnotism and NLP accusation<br>
came from.  As far as we can tell, it came from some extreme right fringe of<br>
the church.  As reasonable, educated people, we usually consider the source<br>
of what we bother to listen to.  Check the accuracy rate of John Osborne,<br>
Our Firm Foundation, Pilgrim's Rest, Runner, etc.  I have just finished<br>
reading a response by Wm. Loveless to an Osborne video.  I am amazed at how<br>
terribly the facts had been misconstrued.  Sure NLP is bad, but who says the<br>
pastors are being trained in it or using it?  I have yet to meet one.  Certainlythis is not part of the seminary training.  As I understand it, when LAB I was<br>
recommended by the church, several years ago, there was no NLP or hypnotism in<br>
the program.  As the instructor changed direction to include some of these<br>
items, the SDA pastors were no longer encouraged to attend.  <br>
<p>
Perhaps it would be of interest to note that in the same accusation there was<br>
the statement that a certain book was used as a textbook on several SDA<br>
campuses.  We were told Andrews used it.  No one has ever heard of it.  No one<br>
has ever heart of such things being taught here.  Yet some people keep repeating<br>
the information without checking their facts.<br>
<p>
What the Bible itself--as opposed to Bible interpreters--says about sin:<br>
Romans 14:23:  "Whatever is not from faith is sin - hamartia."  Faith includes<br>
more than believing.  It includes trust and obedience.  Whatever is outside of<br>
that sphere is sin.<br>
<p>
Fortunately, there are verses that simplify my quandary about how much or how<br>
little is sin.  I read Jude 24, 25: "Now to Him who is able to keep you from <br>
stumbling, and to make you stand in the presence of His glory blameless with <br>
great joy, to the only God our Savior, through Jesus Christ our Lord, be glory, majesty, dominion and authority, before all time and now and forever.  Amen."<br>
<p>
God can keep me in whatever state is needed for me to reach his glory with <br>
great joy.  So what if I cannot specifically define how this happens?  Must<br>
everything be totally rational?  Have you ever tried to define being in love?<br>
<p>
Enough for today.<br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
