<!-- body="start" -->
# I had heard several times before that in the New Testament, there<br>
# are several very specific, but related words having to do with sin.<br>
# When Ruben Gonzalez was talking a while back about a very narrow definition<br>
# of sin (only the act), I looked this up, but the Greek concordance in <br>
# Strong's didn't tell me very much.  <br>
# <br>
# Could it be possible, given the definition of sin in the Bible, <br>
# that there are some things which are not sin, but are still wrong?<br>
# I would appreciate insight on the meaning of such words as offense,<br>
# iniquity, transgression, and sin, and the shades of meaning between them.<br>
 <br>
I'll do a little digging, Steve, and report back in a few days.<br>
<p>
One thing to keep in mind though, Paul says all things (no exceptions)<br>
are lawful, but not all things are expedient to the Faith.  So even<br>
though as Christians, we have incredible liberty in Christ (because of<br>
our baptism into His death -- we are therefore dead), we are to view<br>
everything from the perspective of how expedient to the Faith is it.<br>
<p>
I used to be very uncomfortable with this, but have come to really<br>
appreciate what gift it really is.<br>
<p>
En Agape,<br>
<p>
Gene <br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
