<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I just had a thought as I have read your message David. What about</i><br>
<i>&gt; evangelists manipulating people to be baptized and join a church. Is</i><br>
<i>&gt; that wrong?</i><br>
<p>
It's quite all right for evangelists to make their pitch to adults.<br>
However, for children of baptism age I think much of what goes on is<br>
questionable at best.<br>
<p>
For example, I attended San Pasqual Academy starting in 1970 (age 14).<br>
I recall a Week of Prayer in which there was a Friday night altar<br>
call.  The altar call lasted two hours, and was characterized by<br>
endless repetition of the hymn "Jesus is tenderly calling" etc. and by<br>
people who had already come forward going back to recalcitrant members<br>
of the audience and urging them to come forward.  All but 12 souls out<br>
of 200-300 eventually caved in.<br>
<p>
Was God present in this gathering?  I very much doubt it.  God's<br>
system is not based on pressure.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
