<title>Mar_1992: Manipulating people to become members?</title>
<h1>Manipulating people to become members?</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 4 Mar 1992 02:55 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#22">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#22">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#22">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#22">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Lola: "manipulation and evangelism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0021.html">McCluskey G: "NLP and baptism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm intrigued by the idea of "manipulating" people to get <br>
them to be baptized and join a church.  What constitutes <br>
manipulation?  The Bible is full of examples of how people <br>
are persuaded to follow the Lord.  Here are some examples.  <br>
Do these constitute manipulation?<br>
<p>
Genesis 6.  The Lord told Noah that He was going to destroy <br>
every living thing on the face of the earth.  But if Noah <br>
would make a covenent with Him and build an ark, he and his <br>
family would be preserved.  (Do it to live. What did Noah <br>
have to lose?)<br>
<p>
In Genesis 19, we have to story of the destruction of Sodom <br>
and Gomorrah.  Lot was lingering and indecisive about whether <br>
to leave the city.  The Bible says, "While he lingered, the <br>
men (angels) laid hold upon his hand and upon the hand of his <br>
wife and upoin the hand of his two daughters; the Lord being <br>
merciful unto him:  and they brought him forth and set him <br>
without the city."  He was then told to "Escape for thy <br>
life."  (Lot saved against his will?)<br>
<p>
Exodus 20.  When the Lord gave the 10 commandments to Israel <br>
at Sinai, he manifested himself with thunder, lightening, <br>
noise of trumpets, and smoking mountain.  The people were <br>
extremely fearful and begged for Moses to speak to them and <br>
not God.  (Scare tactics)<br>
<p>
Joshua 24.  Joshua says to the people, "choose you this day <br>
whom ye will serve."  After they say they want to serve the <br>
Lord, he says:  "If ye forsake for Lord and serve strange <br>
gods, then he will turn and do you hurt and consume you."  <br>
(You must decide TODAY.  If you decide not to, you'll die.)<br>
<p>
I Samuel 12.  Israel demands a king so King Saul is crowned.  <br>
verse 18.  "The Lord sent thrunder and rain that day and all <br>
the people greatly feared the Lord and Samuel."  (Use fear)<br>
<p>
II Chronicles 7.  The dedication of Solomon's temple.  "Fire <br>
came down from heaven and consumed the burnt offering and <br>
glory filled the house."  Glory was so great, the priests <br>
could not enter the temple.  When the people saw the fire and <br>
the glory of the Lord, they bowed and worshipped and praised <br>
the Lord.  (Overwhelm them.)<br>
<p>
Major and Minor Prophets of OT.  Isaiah, Jeremiah, .. all the <br>
prophets offered two basic enticements to Isreal to return to <br>
the Lord.  Return or you'll be destroyed.  Return and the <br>
Lord will bless you.<br>
<p>
Peter at Pentecost.  Peter preaches to the Jews invoking <br>
strong feelings of guilt.  Jesus Christ, "ye have taken and <br>
by wicked hands have crucified and slain."  "Pricked in their <br>
hearts".   The Holy Spirit was clearly present with <br>
manifestation of the gift of tongues which amazed the people.  <br>
(Impress them with eloquence.  Use guilt.)<br>
<p>
Saul on the Road to Damascus.  Jesus Christ manifested <br>
himself to Saul as a bright light and spoke to him audibly.  <br>
Saul "trembling and astonished".acknowledged Jesus Christ.<br>
<p>
Paul before Felix in Acts 24:25.  "And he reasoned of <br>
righteousness, temperance, and judgment to come.  Felix <br>
trembled and answered, Go thy way for this time:  When I have <br>
a convenient season I will call for thee." (Force a decision <br>
TODAY.  Use the threat of the judgment.)<br>
<p>
Paul before King Agrippa.  Pauls says, "(I) speak forth the <br>
words of truth and soberness.  For the king knoweth of these <br>
things, before who also I speak freely:  for I am persuaded <br>
that none of these things are hidden from him; for this thing <br>
was not done in a corner.  King Agrippa, believest thou the <br>
prophets?  I know that thou believest.  Then Agrippa said <br>
unto Paul, Almost thou persuadest me to be a Christian.  (Use <br>
logic.  Appeal to their knowledge and intelligence.  Use <br>
persuasion.  State you KNOW they believe and that they know <br>
the truth.  Since they believe, no reason not to become a <br>
member.)<br>
<p>
So, the ways people were persuaded in the Bible are:<br>
<p>
	Focus on the rewards to be had as a member<br>
	Force them against their will<br>
	Invoke fear for their eternal well being<br>
	Overwhelm them<br>
	Impress them<br>
	Pressure them for a decision TODAY<br>
	"Hell-fire damnation" approach--the judgment is coming<br>
	Use eloquence<br>
	Invoke strong feelings of personal guilt<br>
	Don't ask IF they believe.  Say you KNOW they believe.<br>
	Use strong persuasion with unassailable logic<br>
<p>
So what do you think about this?<br>
<p>
Cheryl Berthelsen<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
