<title>Mar_1992: manipulation and evangelism</title>
<h1>manipulation and evangelism</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 04 Mar 92 14:22:44 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Paul Gates: "Re: NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "Manipulating people to become members?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0036.html">Paul Gates: "Re: manipulation and evangelism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I agree with Dan Deavours stance:  when we try to use manipulative<br>
techniques to bring people into the church we are treading on the<br>
territory of the Holy Spirit.  We had a big series in OKC by an<br>
evangelist (who is no longer in the work).  He was scheduled to come<br>
preach at our church on Sabbath a.m.  Well, time for sermon came and<br>
went and he was a no-show.  We found out later that he was closeted with<br>
some of the people from the meetings who had said they wanted to be<br>
baptized, but had backed out at the last minute (the baptism was<br>
scheduled for that afternoon).  So he was urging them to reconsider<br>
during the time he was supposed to be preaching to us.  I found that<br>
incredible!  Shouldn't joining any church be something you approach<br>
with much study and prayer?  And if you aren't sure about it, it strikes<br>
me as wise to put it off a bit longer!  These people had only attended<br>
one series of meetings and now were being labored with to take an<br>
immense step at short notice.  I don't know if NLP was involved in<br>
the negotiations or not.<br>
 <br>
Speaking of NLP -- it was a hot topic in educational research circles<br>
about ten years ago.  Lots of studies with it, none of them showing<br>
much except the ones carried out by the practitioners of the stuff<br>
themselves -- that made everyone else suspicious and it has been<br>
pretty thoroughly discredited in education now.  Still around, but not<br>
popular with the "mainline" people -- only the fringe is hanging on.<br>
 <br>
Anyway, back to the Holy Spirit...  The H.S. brings people to conviction<br>
and repentance, and I'm not sure that he/she/it needs the help of<br>
hypnosis to do it!<br>
 <br>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
