<title>Mar_1992: Re: NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue</title>
<h1>Re: NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>04 Mar 92 15:08:47 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#25">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#25">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#25">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#25">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re:  Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Paul Gates: "Re: NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0002.html">Dave Buxton: "NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To Scott: <br>
<p>
Yes Scott, Manipulating is wrong at any time in my "book." I was just<br>
throwing that concept out to see if any would bite!! Nothing grinds me<br>
more than manipulating people even for a good cause.<br>
<p>
Probably others on the net could give you a more descriptive definition of<br>
Lab 1. I will enumerate some of the concepts.<br>
<p>
1. Fogging: Agreeing with a person to try to disarm them. If a church<br>
member is being destructively critical of you. You might agree to what you<br>
can and ask them to pray for you.<br>
<p>
2. Another concept we learned that when you visit an inactive member, say<br>
for the first time, they are not going to tell you the real reason for not<br>
attending church. This happened to me a few weeks ago. What really happens<br>
is when that person feels comfortable with you and feels he has rapport<br>
with you he will confide in you the real reason.<br>
<p>
In one church where I was pastoring there was a single daughter and her<br>
mother that would never attend church. My wife and I visited them many<br>
times. When we visited them on Saturday afternoons they both in my opinion<br>
where dressed for church but stayed home. The reason given to us was the<br>
health of her mother prevented them from attending. During my stay at that<br>
church I mentored 2 ministerial interns and I would take them with me when<br>
I visited them.<br>
<p>
On one occasion, after we had finished praying, the daughter said, "Pastor<br>
Gates, do you want me to tell you the real reason for not attending<br>
church?" Then she blurted out the reason. You see, Scott, she felt<br>
comfortable in telling us now. What actually happened was when her dad was<br>
still living they had bought a house next to the church. They felt when<br>
they became elderly they would not have to worry about driving to church.<br>
<p>
Well, what happened before my time, was the present church became too<br>
small and inadequate for the congregation so they purchased another church<br>
building practically downtown. When this happened the daughter and the<br>
mother vowed they would never attend church again even though the daughter<br>
was in good health and could have driven to church.<br>
<p>
The story has a sad ending. They both were eccentric people. When other<br>
members tried to visit them they would not come to the door. When I went<br>
to visit I had not problem they also welcomed me with open arms.<br>
<p>
They never returned to church. They did not seek medical care when it was<br>
needed and relatives found them near death one day. The daughter was<br>
rushed to hospital and had inoperative cancer and died within 2 weeks. In<br>
the meantime I had been transferred to another pastorate. The daughter<br>
while in the hospital called me several times and I had prayer for her.<br>
Her request was that I have her funeral service which I did.<br>
<p>
My point of course you can see, I know. When they felt comfortable with me<br>
they were willing to express their real reason for not attending.<br>
<p>
I was counseling with a member a couple of weeks ago and he said his<br>
problem was that his daughter had betrayed his confidence in her by<br>
getting herself pregnant by her finacee. And, he simple could not cope<br>
with that experience. After a few visits I knew it was something else and<br>
talked to him further along this vein. He finally said that the thing with<br>
his daughter was just an excuse -- for his real problem was that his wife<br>
was going to school and would be soon finishing the Registered Nurse<br>
course and then she would be more educated than he was, etc.<br>
<p>
There are other concepts that I could mention. The bottom line is that<br>
Lab I just enhances your listening skills. If a person keeps talking in a<br>
certain vein if you are trained in listening skills you can pick up on<br>
things that they are saying.<br>
<p>
A person told me one time that when there neighbor's house caught on fire<br>
it took the fireman "forever" to get there. Then they related how their<br>
business had failed, and then they told me the story about their son who<br>
did not attend church any longer. What I perceived they were saying, was<br>
that no one cared. After some additional visits by me and other church<br>
members they returned to church and felt that they were really cared for.<br>
<p>
Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
