<title>Mar_1992: Re:  Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc.</title>
<h1>Re:  Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc.</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 5 Mar 92 10:30:35 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Glen Pringle: "Re: NLP and baptism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Paul Gates: "Re: NLP and McCall's March 1992 issue"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">Patricio Navia: "Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0028.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re:  Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;When Ruben Gonzalez was talking a while back about a very narrow definition</i><br>
<i>&gt;of sin (only the act), I looked this up, but the Greek concordance in </i><br>
<i>&gt;Strong's didn't tell me very much.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Could it be possible, given the definition of sin in the Bible, </i><br>
<i>&gt;that there are some things which are not sin, but are still wrong?</i><br>
<i>&gt;I would appreciate insight on the meaning of such words as offense,</i><br>
<i>&gt;iniquity, transgression, and sin, and the shades of meaning between </i><br>
<i>&gt;them.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;	Steve Timm</i><br>
<p>
<p>
I'm not sure of what you actually understood by the definition of sin that<br>
I use. Acording to 1 John 3:4 sin is the transgression of the law<br>
and that is all sin is. Now how narrow that definition of sin becomes<br>
really is a question of how narrow one's view of the law is. The Law not only<br>
condemns wrong (physical) acts but also condemns wrong thoughts and desires<br>
which are cherished. To me the spiritual claims of the law are so vast that<br>
we can not even begin to see the level of righteousness which the law exposes.<br>
To ultimately know the claims of the law we must ultimately know God because<br>
the law is the transcript of His character. How many of us know God well enough<br>
to draw a line saying this is as far the the law goes and no further. Wherever<br>
we draw that line depends on our knowledge of God and determines what sin is<br>
to us.<br>
<p>
Again I say EGW says clearly that the ONLY definition given for sin in<br>
the bible is that of 1 John 3:4 "sin is the transgression of the law" <br>
if this is a narrow definition then fine. The definition is not my own<br>
I did not originate it, it is the inspired definition from the SoP.<br>
<p>
To answer your 2nd question. When a cat kills an inoccent sparrow, is that<br>
sin ? is it evil ? Obviously the act of a cat killing a bird is not <br>
sin because it has no moral judment and is not capable of such and so it is<br>
not sin. it will not be condemned in the judgment because it broke the law<br>
of God or acted out apart from faith. However this act is not right it is an<br>
evil act an act that comes about due to the results of sin present in this <br>
world. God does not impute sin when there is no knowledge, where there is no<br>
law there is no sin. However these evil acts to which sin is not attributed<br>
are still wrong and this is why Paul says JEsus came to reveal the law<br>
(His cahracter) to us that sin may be imputed.<br>
<p>
So that we see that we have the notion of evil or wrong acts which may or <br>
may not be sin depending on whether the perpetrator (a) is capable of moral<br>
judgment and (b) is aware of the law. This is why EGW says the closer we<br>
come to God the more sinful we see ourselves. This is because we come to<br>
know God better and therefore the claims of the law. Before we knew God<br>
as well we committed these evil acts but we were not aware that they were<br>
sinful. Sin is willful rebellion against God and His law it is an act of the<br>
will.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
