<title>Mar_1992: Re: NLP and baptism</title>
<h1>Re: NLP and baptism</h1>
Glen Pringle (<i>pringle@bruce.cs.monash.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 5 Mar 92 12:42:09 GMT-10:00</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#27">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#27">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#27">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#27">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re:  Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re:  Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0021.html">McCluskey G: "NLP and baptism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0029.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: NLP and baptism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
McCluskey G writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; It's quite all right for evangelists to make their pitch to adults.</i><br>
<i>&gt; However, for children of baptism age I think much of what goes on is</i><br>
<i>&gt; questionable at best.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; For example, I attended San Pasqual Academy starting in 1970 (age 14).</i><br>
<i>&gt; I recall a Week of Prayer in which there was a Friday night altar</i><br>
<i>&gt; call.  The altar call lasted two hours, and was characterized by</i><br>
<i>&gt; endless repetition of the hymn "Jesus is tenderly calling" etc. and by</i><br>
<i>&gt; people who had already come forward going back to recalcitrant members</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the audience and urging them to come forward.  All but 12 souls out</i><br>
<i>&gt; of 200-300 eventually caved in.</i><br>
<p>
I can really relate to that.  At my high school, Lilydale Adventist<br>
Academy every week of prayer they would have the high pressure altar<br>
calls.  Almost every time every student would stand up when the call<br>
came for those who wanted to give their lives to Christ to stand.  A<br>
comment from a friend typifies those calls.  He said to me, "We might<br>
as well stand, everybody else is."  And that's all it was to most of<br>
the students, I'm sure.  To this day I usually cringe when an altar<br>
call is made, especially when they're not happy with the numbers and<br>
start putting on the pressure.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Was God present in this gathering?  I very much doubt it.  God's</i><br>
<i>&gt; system is not based on pressure.</i><br>
<p>
Looking back, I'm sure that some of the people who responded were<br>
genuine, but they were lost amongst the crowds.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; Glen McCluskey</i><br>
<i>&gt; glenm@usl.com</i><br>
<p>
