<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0032.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Unfortunately the KJV totally obscures the definition of sin in 1 Jn 3:4.  <br>
The Greek uses the word "anomia" which is much closer to "lawlessness"<br>
although the term is not easy to translate.  The first letter of "anomia"<br>
shows that what follows is absent--like "amoral"--a person with no sense<br>
of morality.  The second part of the word "anomia" is a derivative of<br>
<p>
"nomos"--law.  But it refers to the general principle of law rather than<br>
to a specific law.<br>
<p>
So what constitutes sin, according to 1 Jn 3:4, is an attitude of "law-<br>
lessness," the attitude of one who defies law, acts as if it did not<br>
exist.  Such a one places his or her personal whims above law or obedience.<br>
This kind of definition is much more in harmony with Rom 14:23, where<br>
sin is whatever is not of faith.  <br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
