<p>
I would like to further add that John uses yet another definition<br>
of sin.  I don't have a bible in my office (so I can't look it up), but<br>
I still remember from a 'Concurso biblico del congreso de jovenes (<br>
Youth congress, biblical contest) some 8 years ago (in Chile) that<br>
there is a verse in John that says (roughly translated from Spanish):<br>
 <br>
...to convince of sin, judgment and justice. Of since, for they don't<br>
believe in me.... (para convencerlos de pecado, juicio y justica, de<br>
pecado por cuanto no creen en mi).<br>
So, here, Jesus implies that sin is the act of not believin in<br>
Jesus.<br>
 <br>
I feel much more relief and hopeful with such a definition.<br>
 <br>
Patricio navia.<br>
 <br>
(--I ask your understanding for my using of the Spanish whenever I<br>
refer to the bible. I have always attended Spanish speaking churches<br>
and truly feel more comfortable worshiping in my mother's tongue.)<br>
