<title>Mar_1992: Re: NLP and baptism</title>
<h1>Re: NLP and baptism</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri,  6 Mar 1992 11:32:34 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#33">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#33">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#33">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#33">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Steven Timm: "Forwarded note below"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Iniquities, Transgressions, Sins, etc."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;The president of our conference lead out in an evangelistic series.</i><br>
<i>&gt;A couple of the church elders at the sponsoring church approached him</i><br>
<i>&gt;asking that at the alter call, ...</i><br>
<p>
  What is an 'alter call' and what is it used for and what part does it<br>
play in normal/special Sabbath services?<br>
<p>
  Thanks.<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints<br>
<p>
<p>
[I suspect that an "alter call" is a call for people to alter their lives!<br>
More commonly seen is the altar call, which works in the SDA church about<br>
the same as it would in any Protestant denomination although there is nothing<br>
in an SDA church which can be considered an altar per se.<br>
It generally involves asking people to make a public committment for <br>
Christ by coming to the front of the church.  It may involve an expression<br>
of the desire for baptism, or it may not.<br>
<p>
Some SDA churches (particularly the Black churches) will have an altar call<br>
almost every Sabbath.  At the Elmhurst church where I attend, there hasn't<br>
been one since I started attending.  Altar calls are more commonly seen <br>
at evangelistic meetings such as the one referred to above, which are <br>
generally not held during the Sabbath worship service.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
