<title>Mar_1992: LAB I and NLP</title>
<h1>LAB I and NLP</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 5 Mar 92 19:33:56 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#35">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#35">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#35">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#35">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Paul Gates: "Re: manipulation and evangelism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Steven Timm: "Forwarded note below"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Today I talked with Doug Kilcher who took Lab I and II several years ago.  He<br>
told me that the basis for these workshops was a piece of information found<br>
in church research: if a person misses church for six weeks in a row, it will<br>
be next to impossible to win that person back to church.  John Savage took<br>
this information and designed a workshop to teach church workers how to deal<br>
with people in such a way as to win them back before the deadline.  His<br>
emphasis was on listening and visitation skills.  The workshop participants<br>
were taught to listen to what the almost-former church member had to say with<br>
total empathy and respond non-defensively.  A lot of emphasis was put on<br>
listening to what the person did not really say but suggested.<br>
 <br>
LAB I and LAB II were two levels dealing with the save topic.<br>
 <br>
John Savage broadened his interests.  He began offering workshops in conflict<br>
management.  About three years ago he began doing workshops on NLP at four<br>
different levels.  He includes auto-suggestion, self-hypnosis, patterning, and<br>
audio hypnosis in these workshops, which are not the church-oriented Lab I<br>
workshops.<br>
 <br>
The only mention of NLP in the LAB materials is found on p.44 of the workbook.<br>
I transcribe the whole page.<br>
Neuro-linguistic Programming<br>
Verbal Accessing Cues<br>
Definition: Listening for and responding in the dominant mode of the speaker<br>
language.<br>
 <br>
Clue words:<br>
VISUAL: bright, clear/vague, envision, examine, focus, imagine, inspect, look,<br>
observe, perspective, picture, viewpoint, visualize, witness<br>
AUDITORY: amplify, ask, call, click, harmonize, hear, listen, loud/quiet,<br>
overhear, question, shout/whisper, speak, talk, tell<br>
KINESTHETIC: cool/warm, feel fresh, grasp, handle, hold, link, rough/smooth,<br>
smell, solid, struggle, sweet/sour, taste, touch<br>
UNSPECIFIED: aware, be, believe, consider, contemplate, know, learn, ponder,<br>
remember, respectful, sense, think, trusting, understand<br>
 <br>
Additional Notes:<br>
VISUAL:<br>
 <br>
AUDITORY:<br>
 <br>
KINESTHETIC<br>
 <br>
Practicae Exercise:<br>
1. "I would like to hear about your church.  Tell me about it."<br>
2.  "How do you see your church ten years from now?"<br>
3.  "Can you share the most rewarding experience you have had this year?"<br>
 <br>
After reading the page I told Doug I was not sure what all this meant.  He<br>
told me that Savage taught that people "spoke" in different "languages"<br>
because people think and feel differently.  A person who is "visual" speaks<br>
using "visual" terms.  If one interacts with that person using "visual"<br>
terms, the person opens up and responds better.  Likewise, some people operate<br>
on an auditory basis. You find that out by listening for the clue words.  If<br>
you think a person is auditory, you use auditory language in dealing with him<br>
or her.<br>
 <br>
In Savage's workbook for LAB there is one book on NLP:<br>
Bandler, Richard, and John Grinder.  Frogs into Princes: Neuro Linguistic<br>
Programming.  Utah: Real People Press, 1979.<br>
 <br>
Doug also told me that whereas LAB I used to be highly recommended as an<br>
activity of the seminary's 9th quarter, it no longer is part of the program.<br>
 <br>
Having come to the end of my information, I'll close my posting.<br>
 <br>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
 <br>
Bandler, Richard, and John Grinder.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
