<title>Mar_1992: 1 John 3:4</title>
<h1>1 John 3:4</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 9 Mar 92 13:11:41 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#39">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#39">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#39">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#39">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Dave: "Dr. Loveless and new forms of prayer"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Paul Gates: "Re: NLP and baptism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0045.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: 1 John 3:4"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	1 John 3:4 reads literally, I believe, ``Whoever sins commits<br>
lawlessness, for sin is lawlessness.''  The Greek word used for<br>
lawlessness is anomia.  This verse shows that sin is an act, a<br>
commission of lawlessness.  Even in English, to say someone is<br>
lawless, or an outlaw, signifies that the person is a law breaker.<br>
Romans 7 gives a similar thought, ``I had not known sin, but by the<br>
law; for I had not known lust, except the law had said, Thou shalt not<br>
covet.''  Therefore, the King James rendering, ``Sin is the<br>
transgression of the law,'' rightly expresses the sense of 1 John 3:4.<br>
Sin is the transgression of the law of God, expressed in the Ten<br>
Commandments, which contain the commandment ``Thou shalt not covet.''<br>
Of course, the law is fulfilled by love, and Jesus gave the two great<br>
commandments, love to God and love to man, as summarizing the law.<br>
<p>
	This thought, that sin is the transgression of the law, has<br>
been contained in numerous evangelistic meetings and Bible studies<br>
that I have seen, not to mention sermons and the writings of Ellen<br>
White.  Of course, the Bible testimony is primary.  But it's not an<br>
idea I dreamed up.  This is a key thought for helping people to see<br>
that Sabbath breaking is sin, since it is a violation of the fourth<br>
commandment.  Of course, it is only a faith relationship with Christ<br>
that enables us to keep the law.  Whatever is not of faith is sin,<br>
because whatever is done out of Christ is basically selfish and in<br>
conflict with the law of love expressed by the Ten Commandments.  I<br>
don't see any benefit or Bible justification for giving up the<br>
teaching that sin is the transgression of the law.  If I am wrong, I'm<br>
sure someone will point that out to me.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
