</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
	I have been sitting back for the past year or so, reading the many<br>
posts which appear.  I rearly write, but I am in somewhat of a delema.<br>
	As far back as I can remember, I have always wanted to be one of two<br>
things: a minister of the Adventist church or an engineer.  In 1986, I <br>
entered college, thinking I had finally made my choice, as a Theology major.   <br>
I went throught the typical classes that were required until my junior year<br>
and then began having doubts.  The summer prior to my junior year I worked as<br>
an associate pastor in Guyana, South America.  I suppose it was then that I<br>
actually saw what ministering was all about.  I realized it was more than<br>
the preaching and the "performance" that the church saw on Sabbath.  Needless<br>
to say I was afraid of the "real ministry" which was revealed.<br>
	During the spring quarter of my junior year, I changed my major to<br>
Computer Science.  I finished in May of 1991 and am presently a Ph.D<br>
student at the University of Alabama.  I am doing fine in my classes, but<br>
I'm having doubts again.  Many of my friends are telling me that I am<br>
acting like a modern Jonah. Could that be true? <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
