<title>Mar_1992: Re: Jonah</title>
<h1>Re: Jonah</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 10 Mar 92 14:48:18 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Lola: "Alden Thompson's book"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Am I a Modern Johah?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0041.html">Dwain E. Woode: "Dr. Loveless and new forms of prayer"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Jonah was running away from God as much as from Niniveh.  You could only<br>
be a Jonah if you try to ignore the God-given task of all Christians.<br>
<p>
I love two short quotations from Ellen White: "Every true disciple is born into<br>
the kingdom of God as a missionary.  He who drinks the living water becomes a fountain of life.  The receiver becomes a giver." (DA 195)<br>
<p>
"Here was a work for them to do--go to a heathen home and tell of the blessing<br>
they had received from Jesus.... In doing this work they could receive a <br>
greater blessing than if, merely for benefit to themselves, they had remained in<br>
His presence.  It is in working to spread the good news of salvation that we<br>
are brought near to the Saviour" (DA 339-340)<br>
<p>
My experience of teaching students who want to be pastors suggests to me that<br>
many of them misunderstand their calling.  All laypeople have the duty of<br>
sharing and being missionaries.  Not all people are called to minister.  The<br>
work that a consecrated lay person can do may be far greater than what a<br>
minister can accomplish.<br>
<p>
I'm all for laypeople sharing their joy and faith--outside the church.  On<br>
the other hand, when the Lord lets a person know clearly that he or she<br>
should be a full-time pastor, that person will have to deal with conse-<br>
quences of being a Jonah.  <br>
<p>
As an SDA in a non-Christian environment, you have a marvelous opportunity.<br>
As you give, you will receive.  Don't let people talk you into receiving <br>
and receiving and receiving before you give.  Yes, you have to have something<br>
to give, but as soon as you start giving, you'll find yourself receiving.<br>
<p>
God bless you!<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
