I bought Alden Thompson's book _Inspiration_ when the bookmobile was<br>
around a weekend ago.  So far I doubt find anything too startling (I'm<br>
halfway through with it), but then perhaps I am not considered very<br>
conservative.  (Oops, in the above sentence "doubt" was supposed to be<br>
"don't".)  What was interesting to me was that at our winter camp<br>
meeting here in the Kentucky Tennessee conference the invited speaker<br>
was Raymond Holmes from Andrews, who spoke on the topic of inspiration!<br>
He was speaking about the Bible and Ellen White, and using EGW to<br>
bolster his interpretation of Biblical inspiration.  This seems to me to<br>
be entirely backwards -- shouldn't we use the Bible instead to decide<br>
whether EGW was inspired?  Anyway, someone asked him his opinion of the<br>
Holmes book and he would not answer because he was being taped!  That is<br>
what "inspired" me to buy the book....  I find Thompson very practical<br>
and clear -- he's probably an excellent teacher.  Some of the stuff he<br>
quotes his students as saying remind me of myself in college when one<br>
professor merely suggested that the story of Jonah or Job was not<br>
literally true in every detail.  I was completely shocked!<br>
 <br>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
