<title>Mar_1992: Re: 1 John 3:4</title>
<h1>Re: 1 John 3:4</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 9 Mar 92 20:07:22 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#45">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#45">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#45">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#45">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0046.html">Dave Buxton: "Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Lola: "Alden Thompson's book"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0039.html">David Plaisted: "1 John 3:4"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
1 Jn 3:4 does use the word anomia.  Lawlessness is one translation of the word.<br>
Another might be contempt of law.  The verb poieo, to do or make does not <br>
necessarily mean to perform an action, although that is an important trans<br>
lation.  In Greek trees make fruit--Matt 3:10; 7:17-19; Jesus makes his <br>
disciples fishers of men--Matt 4:19; and the believer does the will of God--<br>
Matt 12:50; Jesus tells the disciples to do his words, meaning far more than<br>
committing certain acts.<br>
<p>
Sin is the commission of acts forbidden by the Ten Commandments.  That is a<br>
good definition.  But it is partial.  Unfortunately, behind every sinful act is<br>
a sinful thought coming from a sinful heart.  So Mk 7:20-23. <br>
<p>
If some of you have access to The Illustrated Bible Dictionary, look up the<br>
article on "SIN."  I find it excellent.  <br>
<p>
Yours for the solution of the sin problem--Christ the Saviour...<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 	1 John 3:4 reads literally, I believe, ``Whoever sins commits</i><br>
<i>&gt; lawlessness, for sin is lawlessness.''  The Greek word used for</i><br>
<i>&gt; lawlessness is anomia.  This verse shows that sin is an act, a</i><br>
<i>&gt; commission of lawlessness.  Even in English, to say someone is</i><br>
<i>&gt; lawless, or an outlaw, signifies that the person is a law breaker.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Romans 7 gives a similar thought, ``I had not known sin, but by the</i><br>
<i>&gt; law; for I had not known lust, except the law had said, Thou shalt not</i><br>
<i>&gt; covet.''  Therefore, the King James rendering, ``Sin is the</i><br>
<i>&gt; transgression of the law,'' rightly expresses the sense of 1 John 3:4.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Sin is the transgression of the law of God, expressed in the Ten</i><br>
<i>&gt; Commandments, which contain the commandment ``Thou shalt not covet.''</i><br>
<i>&gt; Of course, the law is fulfilled by love, and Jesus gave the two great</i><br>
<i>&gt; commandments, love to God and love to man, as summarizing the law.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 	This thought, that sin is the transgression of the law, has</i><br>
<i>&gt; been contained in numerous evangelistic meetings and Bible studies</i><br>
<i>&gt; that I have seen, not to mention sermons and the writings of Ellen</i><br>
<i>&gt; White.  Of course, the Bible testimony is primary.  But it's not an</i><br>
<i>&gt; idea I dreamed up.  This is a key thought for helping people to see</i><br>
<i>&gt; that Sabbath breaking is sin, since it is a violation of the fourth</i><br>
<i>&gt; commandment.  Of course, it is only a faith relationship with Christ</i><br>
<i>&gt; that enables us to keep the law.  Whatever is not of faith is sin,</i><br>
<i>&gt; because whatever is done out of Christ is basically selfish and in</i><br>
<i>&gt; conflict with the law of love expressed by the Ten Commandments.  I</i><br>
<i>&gt; don't see any benefit or Bible justification for giving up the</i><br>
<i>&gt; teaching that sin is the transgression of the law.  If I am wrong, I'm</i><br>
<i>&gt; sure someone will point that out to me.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 	Dave Plaisted</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<!-- body="end" -->
