<title>Mar_1992: Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</title>
<h1>Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 11 Mar 1992 14:31:37 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#47">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#47">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#47">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#47">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0046.html">Dave Buxton: "Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Dave Buxton: "Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0048.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
David raised some very important points in his article about <br>
protestant and catholic viewpoints.  I'd like to amplify his point <br>
regarding especially views of authority.  Some people may think that <br>
people who subscribe to the Catholic view as portrayed by the Great<br>
Controversy are few and far between.  If you read the Usenet news, you <br>
know that is not true--they are all over the place, decrying everything<br>
from Vatican II to religious freedom, defending the Inquisition as a good<br>
thing.  <br>
<p>
One thing that irritates such people more than most is the posting<br>
of Catholic-leaning Episcopalians.  Such a person could be defending a <br>
Catholic view on the Apocrypha or Mary, and the Catholics will still <br>
flame her.  The message is that if you don't recognize that the Church<br>
has the final authority, nothing else matters.  On the other hand,<br>
my pro-choice, pro-communist, pro gay rights feminist friend in S. Africa<br>
considers herself a good Catholic, and her priest doesn't disagree.<br>
<p>
Definitely some Catholic interpretations of authority are used in our <br>
church, both by the independent ministries and the church leadership.<br>
In fact, even the liberal movement within the SDA church could be seen<br>
as an attempt as rejection of that kind of authority.  I have posted<br>
examples of various "gems" from the Michigan Conference office, who <br>
decry the mis-compilation of Ellen G. White quotes with compilations <br>
that are worse than the ones they decry.  (So far the administration<br>
has been blissfully unaware of *this* independent ministry, despite <br>
my best attempts to let them know.)<br>
<p>
I am slightly worried by the lumping of unity into the Catholic<br>
characteristics, and saying that the individual conscience is predominant<br>
over church and state.  I suspect this idea is foreign in many cultures,<br>
be they catholic or protestant.  We cannot neglect that at Pentecost the <br>
Holy Spirit was given to a church in one accord, not just because 120<br>
people "had a personal relationship".  I do not claim that unity should <br>
be gained by "shut up and follow the leadership" but it nevertheless can <br>
and must be attained, and it is a proper goal for Protestants to follow.<br>
In such a group reached by mutual consent, the good of the group will <br>
indeed dominate the good of the individual.<br>
.<br>
So we see that unity is not necessarily catholic, but it is by nature<br>
communist.  Since heaven is a communist place, and we follow a group <br>
of early church leaders who were communist,  it's not bad company to be in.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
