I sympathize with you.  I am now a cs faculty and enjoy it.  But,<br>
witnessing etc. also has a strong appeal.  I would stay in CS for<br>
a while since you already tried ministry.  If it doesn't work out<br>
you can go back.  What doubts are you having about CS?<br>
<p>
Most of the people in my social group are in service related fields and<br>
I suppose associating with them is allowing me to see why I originally<br>
wanted to become a minister.  Also, I'm in the process of planning my <br>
wedding (June 28, 1992), my fiance is a first year medical student.  We<br>
talk frequently about the future and the only thing in service related,<br>
in  my mind about computer science is teaching.  Although teaching is <br>
something I could see myself doing, I don't want to teach immediately<br>
after finishing.  <br>
<p>
Recently I became an elder in a local congregation.  I find it very  <br>
refreshing after sitting at a terminal all week.  Being active again<br>
has renewed my interest for pastoral ministry.<br>
<p>
[This came to me from Dwain Woode, but from what I know of his situation<br>
it can't be his voice.  It's probably a personal reply that someone sent<br>
to him.  Dwain, can you clarify?  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
