<title>Mar_1992: Re: modern day Jonah</title>
<h1>Re: modern day Jonah</h1>
Richard Guy (<i>rguy@cup.portal.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 11 Mar 92 23:08:41 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#49">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#49">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#49">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#49">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Steven Timm: "posting"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My recent/current experience in the missionary/computer science arena<br>
may be of interest here.<br>
 <br>
 From 1987-89, my wife had a deferred medical missionary appointment to<br>
Taiwan Adventist Hospital.  Then, overnite, the Taiwan govt made significant<br>
changes in the rules allowing foreign doctors to work in Taiwan--essentially<br>
requiring her to write medical boards in Chinese.<br>
 <br>
So, she was reappointed to Penang Adventist Hospital in Penang, Malaysia.<br>
She finished her residency in June, 1990, and the hospital started on the visa<br>
application process.  In February, '91 she accepted a temporary appointment<br>
to Guam SDA Clinic pending licensure/visa approval in Malaysia.  On Nov. 1,'91<br>
she accepted a permanent position on Guam, after waiting 15 months for<br>
Malaysia to work out.<br>
<p>
On my part, I finished my PhD in CS in June, '91.  I had solid job offers<br>
for both university/commercial opportunities in Taiwan, Malaysia, Singapore,<br>
and now Guam.  None of the prospective employers could envision any trouble<br>
getting me a visa, in part because no licensure was involved.  Also, CS folks<br>
are in sufficient demand that red tape sometimes can be avoided.<br>
<p>
I'm teaching part-time this semester as a lead-in to a tenure-track position]<br>
next fall at the University of Guam.  It's not as fancy as National Taiwan U<br>
or National Univ of Singapore or even Universiti Sains Malaysia, but it<br>
is a university...<br>
<p>
As the world matures, especially the second/third world, the "magic" of<br>
being a teacher/preacher/doctor wears a bit thin.  Perhaps its time for<br>
the left hand of the Message to grab hold and shake the world.<br>
<p>
richard<br>
<p>
Internet:  guy@cs.ucla.edu<br>
Portal:    rguy@cup.portal.com<br>
Compuserve:71151.3220@compuserve.com<br>
<p>
ps  An increasing portion of the world is e-mail accessible, including<br>
    universities in Singapore, Taiwan, Malaysia, Guam, Australasia,<br>
    and hundreds of institues in Russia and her former fellow republics.<br>
    Being a computer scientist is actually quite fascinating out here!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
