<title>Mar_1992: Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</title>
<h1>Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 12 Mar 92 07:41:51 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#51">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#51">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#51">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#51">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Dwain E. Woode: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Steven Timm: "posting"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Dave Buxton: "Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0054.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; . . . . . . .</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I am slightly worried by the lumping of unity into the Catholic</i><br>
<i>&gt; characteristics, and saying that the individual conscience is predominant</i><br>
<i>&gt; over church and state.  I suspect this idea is foreign in many cultures,</i><br>
<i>&gt; be they catholic or protestant.  We cannot neglect that at Pentecost the </i><br>
<i>&gt; Holy Spirit was given to a church in one accord, not just because 120</i><br>
<i>&gt; people "had a personal relationship".  I do not claim that unity should </i><br>
<i>&gt; be gained by "shut up and follow the leadership" but it nevertheless can </i><br>
<i>&gt; and must be attained, and it is a proper goal for Protestants to follow.</i><br>
<i>&gt; In such a group reached by mutual consent, the good of the group will </i><br>
<i>&gt; indeed dominate the good of the individual.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; . . . . .</i><br>
<p>
This reminds me of an email dialog that grew out of something I posted<br>
on s.r.c.  The other side of the email was a young man from the south,<br>
a member of a Protestant church, I thought perhaps Baptist, but he was<br>
not Baptist.  He spoke of the need for unity as if that was something<br>
to be prophetically expected.  That there is an expectation that<br>
perhaps the Pope is the only one who is capable of bringing about this<br>
unity and so many Protestants are praying for the success of the Pope.<br>
I asked him if he had any prophetic texts to support his expectation.<br>
While he sees that it is prophetic that there shall be unity he can<br>
offer no scriptural prophecies.  His response was that thousands, perhaps<br>
millions of folks in the south are praying for unity, how can God deny<br>
these thousands and thousands of prayers.  I pointed out that Bible<br>
prophecy does not fortell any such unity.  That prophecy does tell us<br>
about unity under the Papacy -- the wondering after the beast.  But to<br>
pray for such unity is to pray for Ishmaal and not Isaac.<br>
<p>
There seems to be a lot of missunderstanding about what Ellen White<br>
meant when she said that the church will go through.  The legal system<br>
has been defining that a "church" is not the bricks plus the<br>
establishment of leadership, it not really the visible obvious church.<br>
Rather a "church" is a system of belief and those who subscribe to it.<br>
Let us say that another war springs up with a draft for soldiers.  Lets<br>
say you are drafted and ordered to bear arms and work on the Sabbath.<br>
Certain precidents have occured, with JWs for example, that make it<br>
likely that a judge hearing your case will set asside the fact that you<br>
happen to be a card carrying member of the SDA church.  You will have<br>
to stand up for what you personally believe and be able to prove that<br>
it is your personal belief and not simply something you do out of peer<br>
preassure or the popular preassures of church/social membership.  The<br>
legal system is no longer interrested in supporting you in terms of<br>
the doctrines of your church.  Only if you can convince the court that<br>
it is your personal honest conviction will the court be responsive.<br>
Mere belief is not enough.  Mere church doctrine is not enough.  It must<br>
be real conviction on your part.<br>
<p>
My mother was born the year EGW died.  Through her mom, a past friend<br>
of EGW, my mother is acquainted with some of Ellen White's later years<br>
un-published visions.  Others than my mom are also acquainted with the<br>
same and similar visions.  Example - a vision of the church as a stage<br>
coach going through with the leadership at the reins.  But then her<br>
attention is taken elsewhere for awhile.  When the vision returns to<br>
the scene of the stage coach she is startled to see that the leadership<br>
are no longer at the reins.  It looks like the end for the church, but<br>
then it is the laymen who pick up the reins and the church does go<br>
through to the end.  Back to legal precident.  The church is a belief<br>
system and those who honestly believe in it.  The church is not the<br>
bricks and the established leadership, unless of course they are honest<br>
subscibers to the belief system.  The church going through that EGW was<br>
talking about is the belief system as she knew it and there are those<br>
who do indeed subscribe to it eagerly, even with a conviction.<br>
<p>
Does a call for unity imply a call to rally under the present leadership<br>
that does not necessarily subscribe to the beliefs of SDA?  Are there<br>
Bible texts that call for such unity?  No.  Are we to pray for such an<br>
Ishmael? No!  Let us rather pray that the members of our church pursue<br>
a course a diligent Bible study and S.O.P. with urgent prayers that the<br>
Holy Spirit guide us into a knowledge of what is really the truth.<br>
While the Bible does call upon us to love our neighbor, even those who<br>
hate us and despitefully use us; I do not see the Bible prophecying that<br>
unity be a prime object of our prayers.  Those who hold high the banner<br>
of unity are all too often wondering after the beast.  That is<br>
especially so outside the SDA church.  But there is also a strong move<br>
for the ecumenical within our church.  Such ecumenicism is not "the<br>
church going through" that EGW prophcied.  Rather it is the church in<br>
great peril on its way through the time of the end.<br>
<p>
No, I do not pray for unity.  There will be for a time a unity of<br>
wondering after the beast.  That I do not pray for.  Rather I pray that<br>
our people will get back to basics found in really diligent Bible study<br>
and S.O.P.  I do believe the Bible must authenticate EGW and not the<br>
other way around.  I do find her to be authenticated and her writings<br>
fit for study for these times.  We are in the time of the end, the<br>
final hours, which will be rapid ones.  In the news we find the pace<br>
is clearly picking up.<br>
<p>
Dave (David E. Buxton)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
