<title>Mar_1992: FYI:  Organized Denominations in the US</title>
<h1>FYI:  Organized Denominations in the US</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 13 Mar 1992 14:07:28 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#53">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#53">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#53">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#53">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Dwain E. Woode: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0064.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re:  FYI:  Organized Denominations in the US"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnetters,<br>
<p>
I was browsing some reference books in the Univ. library this evening and<br>
found some interesting statistics about religions in the U.S.  Nothing<br>
earth-shaking here but something that might be interesting when we watch<br>
the political tone of the coming elections based on regions and states.<br>
This comes for the book, "THE NEW BOOK OF AMERICAN RANKINGS" published in<br>
1984 by Facts on File Inc.  These religion rankings were taken from the<br>
"Report from Churches and Church Membership in the US 1980".  The report<br>
ranks each state according the percent of population for that organized<br>
religion.  The "US average" is the average percent of that religion over<br>
the 50 states.<br>
<p>
	Catholic<br>
		21% US average<br>
		Rank #1 - Rhode Island - 63.7% of population<br>
		Rank #2 - Massachusetts - 53.0%<br>
<p>
	Methodist<br>
		5.1% US average<br>
		Rank #1 - West Virginia - 11.3%<br>
		Rank #2 - Kansas - 11.1%<br>
<p>
	Baptist<br>
		8% US average<br>
		Rank #1 - Alabama - 30.4%<br>
		Rank #2 - Mississippi - 30.2%<br>
<p>
	Presbyterians<br>
		1.8% US average<br>
		Rank #1 - Pennsylvania - 4%<br>
		Rank #2 - Nebraska - 3.7%<br>
<p>
	Lutherans<br>
		3.6% US average<br>
		Rank #1 - North Dakota - 31.9%<br>
		Rank #2 - Minnesota - 26.0%<br>
<p>
	Jewish<br>
		2.6% US average<br>
		Rank #1 - New York - 12.2%<br>
		Rank #2 - California - 3.2%<br>
<p>
	Mormon<br>
		1.2% US average<br>
		Rank #1 - Utah - 67.4%<br>
		Rank #2 - Idaho - 25.5%<br>
<p>
	Seventh-day Adventist<br>
		0.3% US average<br>
		Rank #1 - Oregon - 1.2%<br>
		Rank #2 - Washington - 0.8%<br>
<p>
Some of this didn't surprise me at all.  However, it is interesting to<br>
note that the highest concentration of SDAs is in OREGON.  I didn't<br>
expect that at all.  Also, the fact that the state average percent of<br>
Roman Catholics at 21% should be considered significant.<br>
<p>
One other interesting note.  This book said that Seventh-day Adventists<br>
are "Fundamentalist Pentecostal Protestants."  Although SDAs deny that<br>
they are "pentecostal", the real world thinks SDAs ARE!  I wonder what<br>
this is based on.  I would venture that as more "Celebration Churches"<br>
form, this opinion will get stronger among outsiders.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<p>
[Some of us will also deny that we are fundamentalist.  As I remember,<br>
1 in 12 people in the county that includes Portland, OR is SDA.  This is <br>
the highest in the country, dwarfing such places as Berrien county , MI<br>
(1 in 60).  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
