<title>Mar_1992: Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</title>
<h1>Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 13 Mar 1992 14:55:44 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Dave: "Dr. Loveless and new forms of prayer"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Cheryl Berthelsen: "FYI:  Organized Denominations in the US"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0051.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0063.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Information Please!"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I don't want to detract from David Buxton's points about unity.  I agree<br>
that we should watch for trends about which way is the crowd going, and <br>
then consider going the opposite way.  The kingdom of Christ has no<br>
communion with the kingdom of Satan, to follow the ecumenical movement<br>
as it exists today we cannot and should not agree.<br>
<p>
Having said this,  I wish to make a few points on unity which he does not <br>
consider.  I would not be surprised if we someday find, as he related the <br>
vision, that the leadership is no longer at the reins.   If there is a group<br>
of lay people prepared to assume the reins at that time, it will be because<br>
they are well grounded in the truth and ready to share the love of<br>
Christ, and ready to receive the power of the Holy Spirit in the latter<br>
rain.<br>
So when I speak of unity, I speak of unity within the remnant, not <br>
unity with the world.  This type of unity must have as its base a proactive<br>
love for Christ, not a reactive fighting of some group external or<br>
internal to the Church organization.<br>
<p>
As for the leadership losing the reins, this is to some extent already<br>
happening.  I believe already that a splinter group is forming which<br>
will swear to all of the 27 Fundamental Beliefs but swear at everyone<br>
else, being totally ignorant about how Christ's love affects the<br>
practical life.   Another splinter group is forming which will emphasize<br>
love at the cost to doctrine.  The leadership may follow this group, or<br>
collapse under its own weight.  So we could be faced with a 3-way tug of<br>
war in which none <br>
of the sides is right.  This is where the few faithful ones will come to the<br>
fore as David says.   If we were to look closely, we would find they are <br>
at the reins even now.<br>
<p>
On the other side, we should not expect from spiritual Babylon a greater<br>
degree of unity than we ourselves can muster.   Remember how it was in<br>
the <br>
days of Christ.  The Pharisees and Sadducees hated Jesus for the very reasons<br>
they hated each other.  But they were able to cooperate to get rid of him.<br>
Satan's kingdom is divided against itself, and cannot stand.  It is a<br>
place of confusion.  People may agree on an action for opposing reasons.<br>
Those who have seen God's love in action, as Christ showed it, will<br>
either accept it and be changed by it, or reject it and try to destroy<br>
it.  The fact that our church is not the object of hate or persecution<br>
today should be a signal to us that we are not yet showing this<br>
incontrovertible love.<br>
<p>
Finally, what the Bible has to say about unity.<br>
John 17:11  "And now I am no more in the world, but these are in the<br>
world, and I come to thee.  Holy Father, keep through thine own name<br>
those whom thou hast given me, that they may be one, as we are.<br>
John 17:22  "And the glory which thou gavest me I have given them; that<br>
they may be one, even as we are one."<br>
John 17:23 "I in them, and thou in me, that they may be made perfect in one;<br>
and the world may know that thou has sent me, and hast loved them, as<br>
thou has loved me.<br>
Acts 2:1  "And when the day of Pentecost was fully come, they were all<br>
with one accord in one place."<br>
Acts 2:46  "And they, continuing daily with one accord in the temple,<br>
and breaking bread from house to house, did eat their meat with gladness<br>
and singleness of heart."<br>
Acts 4:32  "And the multitude of them that believed were of one heart<br>
and of one soul..."<br>
Ephesians 4:13  "Till we all come in the unity of the faith, and of the<br>
knowledge of the Son of God, unto a perfect man, unto the measure of the<br>
stature of the fullness of Christ.<br>
<p>
I don't say that any of these verses ar a prophecy of ecumenical unity<br>
to come.  But they do stress its importance.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
