<title>Mar_1992: SDA subculture</title>
<h1>SDA subculture</h1>
Alice Fay Martin (<i>armg9488@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 13 Mar 1992 13:24:31 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#56">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#56">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#56">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#56">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Dave: "Dr. Loveless and new forms of prayer"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0062.html">Steven Timm: "Re: SDA subculture"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The recent weeks have been somewhat troublesome and find myself at odds<br>
with my church.   The anger and doubt that I have been experiencing I <br>
believe is maybe no different than that others have experienced. <br>
So, in my search for resolve to several issues I thought I would break my<br>
silent watch on the net and seek some feedback.<br>
<p>
Let me start with a story.  I have a new friend.  He is a non-Adventist<br>
and has been attending church with me for several weeks.  He first <br>
learned of our church through a mutual Adventist friend whom he works<br>
with.  Over the time we have known each other he has developed a <br>
distinct impression that our church is filled with rules.  The rules <br>
obviously make no sense to him and seem to have no logical basis.<br>
I am saddened that I have been unable to saticfactorily answer his<br>
questions and that much of what I do does seem more of a habit or<br>
way of life than within religous conviction.<br>
<p>
I am also saddened as I am asked to explain some of the inconsistencies<br>
within my church.  For example:  Our mutual friend.... wears jewelry,<br>
I do not....she goes out to lunch on Sabbath... I do not...  she herself<br>
is in real disbelief and trust of the Adventist motives and<br>
practices.  <br>
<p>
As I look at my present situation I look back and am frustrated with <br>
the way I was raised, protected if you will, within the Adventist environment.<br>
(SDA schools since 4th grade... all the way through college.... worked<br>
for adventist hospitals, camps and campus jobs, even spent a year as<br>
an SDA missionary......yep.... I am a product of the Adventist system!)<br>
The subculture as I call it, has kept me within its confines and I<br>
have been unable to make friends outside the church for most of my<br>
life.  Now as l do so... I feel inept,  unable to communicate,  and odd.<br>
<p>
Am I a product of the age in which I live?  <br>
As I look around at those in my age group.... 20's....very few are <br>
deeply commited christians...As far as that goes I look at the adults<br>
and find few role models. Am I looking for an excuse to be like the crowd?<br>
<p>
Interestingly, I picked up the recent issue of the Adventist Review and<br>
noted the new AnchorPoint Series which seems to be addressing just such issues<br>
as I face.  Roy Adams states "The greatest threat facing our church<br>
today is the emergence of a generation of Adventists held together by <br>
culture rather than conviction; a generation that has not made its own<br>
the message that moved the Founding Fathers and Mothers; a generation of<br>
young Adventists that has lost the sense of our uniqueness as a people."<br>
<p>
So it seems there are several issues here.  First are my questions and doubts.<br>
How can I deal with these and grow from the situation without rejecting<br>
the truth?  without placing myself on dangerous ground in the meantime?<br>
How can I know the culture from the important issues when I have parents<br>
and church patriarches telling me what I've heard already for 26 years?<br>
Sometimes I feel like I'm playing with the devil and he's having a good<br>
time with me.  And Yet I feel as if I must come to grips with the <br>
many "why's" I am now faced with.<br>
<p>
I want to know how to live in the world and still be an<br>
Adventist.  I want to belong to a church which appleals not only to<br>
those raised within the subculture but to those on the "outside".<br>
I am wondering how to be a witness in the midst of my own stuggle to<br>
my new friend. <br>
<p>
On another note, maybe someone could help me understand the perspective<br>
of a new attendee to an Adventist church.  How did you feel initially? <br>
What was it that attracted you to the belief system and subculture you <br>
now adapt to?<br>
<p>
<p>
-alice<br>
<p>
armg9488@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
