I can identify to some extent with Alice's post, being at least as much<br>
a product of the SDA system as she is, and also a graduate student at a<br>
secular university with a close non-SDA friend (although nowhere near as<br>
close as a few months ago when I posted before).  Perhaps in my field I<br>
am more likely to encounter atheists, Jews, and nominal Christians than<br>
someone like Alice's friend.  <br>
<p>
I have been at enough parties where I am the only sober one, and the<br>
only vegetarian, that the standards I keep are well-known to my friends<br>
and co-workers.  Everyone notices that I don't come in on Saturday in<br>
what is a 24-hour a day 7-day a week business.  But many of them have<br>
also heard from me what I do while I'm at church (the puppets, the youth<br>
group, the organ playing, the volleyball nights, etc.)  In other words,<br>
I try to portray my <br>
religion as something I do, rather than something I don't.  When the<br>
questions come, as they invariably do, they are about deeper issues than<br>
the standards I observe.<br>
<p>
I must say that in my interactions I have compromised more than I ought<br>
to sometimes.  I have learned a lot about myself and why the standards<br>
are what they are in the process, but then I am forced to deal with the<br>
various impressions made on my mind by the activities I have<br>
participated in.  <br>
In distinguishing culture from God's word, examine your motives and ask<br>
why are you keeping, or rejecting a particular standard.  <br>
<p>
<p>
The whole questions of why we have standards, or why we have 27 doctrines <br>
instead of one, I will defer to another day.  But perhaps the best way<br>
to make the faith your own is to share it with someone else.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
