<title>Mar_1992: Album Review:  Tom Prasada-Rao  "Incoming"</title>
<h1>Album Review:  Tom Prasada-Rao  "Incoming"</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 16 Mar 1992 17:46:50 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#67">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#67">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#67">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#67">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  FYI:  Organized Denominations in the US"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tom Prasada-Rao's new solo album, "Incoming", is on Crossroads Records, <br>
distributed by Spectra.  He has performed in various private label<br>
recordings with his family, and as backup guitarist on other recordings,<br>
but this is his solo debut.  The album is produced by Mark Heard.<br>
<p>
I expected good guitar playing on this album, and Tom delivers.  But he also <br>
delivers witty and thought-provoking lyrics and is quite a good vocalist.<br>
His lyrics are colored by being from Washington DC, and sometimes take on <br>
a political tinge.  A sample:<br>
"We'll harvest all the tourists, and winnow them like wheat<br>
bring in all the right kind, not those people off the street<br>
it's a losing proposition to champion their cause<br>
when we can bring the folks in here who pay taxes and heed laws."<br>
(from "Driftwood")<br>
<p>
"Who are these true disciples, seekers of the truth<br>
who coat the word with pleasure, then swallow down their youth."<br>
"How have the mighty fallen , soldiers of the cross<br>
who pacify the vicious and crucify the lost.<br>
(from "How have the mighty fallen.)<br>
<p>
You will find this a comfortable album to listen to.  It's the folk music of <br>
the 60's given a 090's twist by new arrangements and orchestrations.<br>
There's nothing on this album that could really be described as rock and<br>
roll.   But it is all enjoyable and musically complex.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve's rating:  Four thistles!  (on a scale of -5 to 5)<br>
This is a must-buy!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  FYI:  Organized Denominations in the US"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Defining Catholic vs Protestant"</a>
