<title>Mar_1992: SDA-Net</title>
<h1>SDA-Net</h1>
Lorin Christensen (<i>christen@brutus.aa.ab.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 18 Mar 92 16:19:17 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#70">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#70">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#70">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#70">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0071.html">Eric: "SDA and Evangelism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0069.html">Danny Kumamoto: "3rd-year Adventist responds to "SDA subculture""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Danny,<br>
<p>
Following are my comments on the letter you included; feel free to<br>
post all or part of them, as you see fit.  By the way, what IS SDA-Net?<br>
<p>
                                        - Lorin<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Over the time we have known each other he has developed a </i><br>
<i>&gt;distinct impression that our church is filled with rules.  The rules </i><br>
<i>&gt;obviously make no sense to him and seem to have no logical basis.</i><br>
<i>&gt;I am saddened that I have been unable to saticfactorily answer his</i><br>
<i>&gt;questions and that much of what I do does seem more of a habit or</i><br>
<i>&gt;way of life than within religous conviction.</i><br>
<p>
As a new Adventist (3 years) who entered the church at age 24, I've<br>
experienced some of this, too.  I think your friend's reaction is<br>
natural, considering that (1) most Protestant churches have almost NO<br>
guidelines that they enforce, and (2) our own message is often<br>
mis-handled and, from the wrong person, can sound very like the<br>
Pharisees of old.  I've noticed that we can unintentionally send the<br>
wrong message ourselves, with phrases like, "I *can't* do that today,<br>
it's sabbath." or "I can't eat pork."  Such phrasing implies that we<br>
really WANT to chow down on porkchops and go dancing on sabbath, but<br>
our church doesn't LET us.  Compare to something like "I don't want<br>
to...", "I choose not to...", which takes ownership of the decision.<br>
<p>
Nonetheless, there are some of our doctrines which I have a hard time<br>
defending.  In many cases, though, these are NOT official church <br>
positions, but just extreme beliefs held by a vocal few.  For example,<br>
many folks oppose wedding rings.  I don't believe this position can<br>
be defended scripturally, and I choose to wear one.  The "church" does<br>
NOT forbid the wedding ring.  Likewise, I refuse to place the writings <br>
of Ellen White on the same level as the Bible. This is in total<br>
harmony with the official "party line", per the book "Questions on<br>
Doctrine" (A SUPER book, by the way). However, we have some very<br>
vocal, very pious members who consider EGW the standard by which the<br>
Bible is to be interpreted, and, in fact, quote her writings FAR more than<br>
they quote the Bible.  Again, I don't have to assume this extreme stance<br>
to be an Adventist, and to respect EGW for her counsels.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I am also saddened as I am asked to explain some of the inconsistencies</i><br>
<i>&gt;within my church.  For example:  Our mutual friend.... wears jewelry,</i><br>
<i>&gt;I do not....she goes out to lunch on Sabbath... I do not...  she herself</i><br>
<i>&gt;is in real disbelief and trust of the Adventist motives and</i><br>
<i>&gt;practices.  </i><br>
<p>
You don't have to explain them.  In any group, some will take their<br>
faith more seriously than others.  Also, a great many things are<br>
matters of personal conviction; "let each be firmly convinced in his<br>
own mind."  I choose not to eat out on sabbath, but I know of nothing <br>
which prohibits one from so doing, if they feel it acceptable.  Many<br>
consider my simple gold wedding band to be forbidden "adornment".<br>
That is their right. Naturally, if a member if blatantly trampling <br>
on church standards, that member should be counseled by the pastor, and<br>
the standard procedures followed.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The subculture as I call it, has kept me within its confines and I</i><br>
<i>&gt;have been unable to make friends outside the church for most of my</i><br>
<i>&gt;life.  Now as l do so... I feel inept,  unable to communicate,  and odd.</i><br>
<p>
You're not alone.  I've heard the same comment from others with<br>
your background.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;How can I deal with these and grow from the situation without rejecting</i><br>
<i>&gt;the truth?  without placing myself on dangerous ground in the meantime?</i><br>
<i>&gt;How can I know the culture from the important issues when I have parents</i><br>
<i>&gt;and church patriarches telling me what I've heard already for 26 years?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Sometimes I feel like I'm playing with the devil and he's having a good</i><br>
<i>&gt;time with me.  And Yet I feel as if I must come to grips with the </i><br>
<i>&gt;many "why's" I am now faced with.</i><br>
<p>
The secret, and the key to one's Christian walk (in my opinion), is to<br>
make it a personal relationship with Jesus Christ.  I've felt many similar<br>
doubts and questions; prayer and Bible study has helped me remain secure<br>
in my faith.  DON'T take the word of the "church patriarchs"; DON'T<br>
repeat your beliefs like some denominations do their creeds, by memorizing.<br>
Dig into it and see; you'll grow, and have fun at the same time!  If you're<br>
not convicted that the investigative judgement began in 1844 (for example),<br>
that's FINE! But don't stop there. Paul commended the Bereans because,<br>
rather than taking his word for his new teachings, they went home and<br>
studied it out for themselves.  God doesn't expect us to accept the word<br>
of the church fathers; it is our priviledge (responsibility?) to search<br>
the Word for ourselves.<br>
<p>
Jesus DOES have the answers to all of our "whys". Not all things are<br>
immediately apparent; some are as "treasure hidden in a field." The<br>
searching and exploring is half the fun!<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I want to know how to live in the world and still be an</i><br>
<i>&gt;Adventist.  I want to belong to a church which appleals not only to</i><br>
<i>&gt;those raised within the subculture but to those on the "outside".</i><br>
<p>
I agree that it would be nice if we could always show our best side<br>
to the public.  There are limits, though, to how far we can go.  Sadly,<br>
most people will NEVER be attracted to the SDA church; through no<br>
fault of ours.  The good news is that there are MANY of us who WERE, <br>
and ARE, attracted enough to join.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;On another note, maybe someone could help me understand the perspective</i><br>
<i>&gt;of a new attendee to an Adventist church.  How did you feel initially? </i><br>
<i>&gt;What was it that attracted you to the belief system and subculture you </i><br>
<i>&gt;now adapt to?</i><br>
<p>
My first impressions: (1) Amazed and worried that there were no crosses in<br>
the church; are these guys Christians or not? Maybe they're like<br>
Jehovah's Witnesses, and don't uplift Jesus as the source of salvation...<br>
(2) Impressed with the sincerity and dedication of the members. Clearly,<br>
they live what they believe.  Church for Adventists is not just a <br>
once-a-week "fire insurance" policy. (3) All their beliefs can be<br>
defended from the Bible (some better than others!  :-)  ) They<br>
consistently appeal to scripture as the source of their teachings. All<br>
the members bring their Bibles to church.  (4) The adults have sabbath<br>
school, and it's well-attended. Hmm... that means they emphasize<br>
continuing learning and growth.  (5) The comprehensive nature of<br>
our message!!!!  We reach out spiritually through evangelistic meetings,<br>
Bible studies, etc.  We reach out physically through community services,<br>
ADRA, food basket programs, etc.  The whole SDA structure seems geared<br>
toward helping and serving, on local, regional, even international levels.<br>
And, given Jesus' instructions on how to treat people, THAT's something<br>
to be proud of.<br>
<p>
In summary, I'm still learning, still growing, and still having fun!<br>
I'm not convicted on every church doctrine, but I'm secure in my<br>
knowledge of salvation through Jesus. The rest will come in time. <br>
Meanwhile, the SDA church is a sincere, effective, committed group of<br>
Christians, with Bible-based principles, and one which I'm very<br>
happy to associate myself with.<br>
<p>
- Lorin Christensen<br>
  christen@brutus.aa.ab.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
