<title>Mar_1992: Re: SDA and Evangelism</title>
<h1>Re: SDA and Evangelism</h1>
Bill Oblitey (<i>OBLITEY@grove.iup.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 20 Mar 1992 08:28 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#72">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#72">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#72">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#72">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Steven Timm: "South Africa votes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0071.html">Eric: "SDA and Evangelism"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0071.html">Eric: "SDA and Evangelism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;      This is another SDA question from a Non-SDA..</i><br>
<i>&gt;      I have picked up on the net some discussions on witnessing</i><br>
<i>&gt;      and evangelism.  Do any SDA churches do any "door to door"</i><br>
<i>&gt;      evangelism ?  At this time, I don't have any strong convictions</i><br>
<i>&gt;      either way regarding door to door, but am just curious.  Also,</i><br>
<i>&gt;      are there any certain formats for alter calls ? Does every church</i><br>
<i>&gt;      use them, or only some?  Is it at every service or only from time</i><br>
<i>&gt;      to time ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;      Thanks in advance</i><br>
<i>&gt;      Eric</i><br>
<i>&gt;      Hershey, Pa.</i><br>
<p>
Eric, I am originally from Africa.  I grew up in the SDA faith, and, in<br>
Africa, we BELIEVE that it is the duty of every member to share his/her<br>
faith: House-to-house, door-to-door, office-to-office - wherever the<br>
opportunity arrives.  Ever wondered why evangelism has a 90+% success<br>
in Africa?<br>
<p>
I came to America and although the members SEEM to believe the same as<br>
we do in Africa, they tend to leave visitation, etc, to the pastors and<br>
elders.  Only a few of the members seem to follow the door to door "visitation"<br>
process.  I guess it's culture difference - in Africa, I'm ALWAYS welcome<br>
to a stranger's house and I can discuss any legitimate topic.  In America,<br>
I'm careful that I do not get on the person's nerves and have to be sure<br>
that I am really invited.  (In America, I have only visited members - not<br>
nonmembers, to specifically discuss religion.)<br>
<p>
I think the alter call is left to the preacher.  Most preachers do the alter<br>
call anyway.  Many tend to turn it into an affirmation of faith.<br>
<p>
In Hershey, you are very close to most of our wonderful and caring preachers<br>
and I hope you will one Saturday show your face in one of our churches and<br>
approach the preacher at the close of service with your questions.  I assure<br>
you he/she will be delighted that someone has questions.<br>
<p>
Did I help or did I raise more questions?<br>
<p>
Bill Oblitey<br>
[OBLITEY@GROVE.IUP.EDU]<br>
----------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 "The direction in which education starts a 'man' will determine 'his'<br>
  future life." -- Plato, The Republic.<br>
