<title>Mar_1992: South Africa votes</title>
<h1>South Africa votes</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 24 Mar 1992 10:28:24 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#73">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#73">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#73">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#73">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Steven Timm: "Re: South Africa Votes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: SDA and Evangelism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0075.html">Patricio Navia: "Re: South Africa votes"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was impressed and encouraged recently when the population of (white)<br>
South Africa voted to continue with reforms.  Also in the past few months,<br>
the two unions in South Africa have voted to merge, bringing a racially<br>
unified church structure in South Africa.<br>
<p>
Never mind that we were the last major denomination in South Africa to do so,<br>
even after the Dutch Reformed.  We've done it, and the churches in South <br>
Africa need our support.  The main obstacle for so many years was money,<br>
and it still is.  Bringing the pastors of different races to the same<br>
pay level will take a lot, and supporting two colleges, etc.  A portion of <br>
the next Week of Sacrifice offering will be designated for this purpose.<br>
<p>
Now the next question.  When will all the American Black pastors who lobbied<br>
so hard for this action of merging racially separate conferences wake up <br>
and realize that they are calling for exactly the opposite here?<br>
Why was apartheid unacceptable in South Africa, but required in the USA?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
