<title>Mar_1992: Re: South Africa Votes</title>
<h1>Re: South Africa Votes</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>20676LKC%MSU.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 24 Mar 92 12:26 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#74">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#74">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#74">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#74">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Patricio Navia: "Re: South Africa votes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Steven Timm: "South Africa votes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0077.html">Steven Timm: "Re: South Africa Votes"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve,<br>
I did not quite understand your reference to African American pastors and<br>
their lobbying efforts.  Would you please clarify with a little background<br>
information?<br>
 <br>
As to South Africans, I agree that this is a step in the right direction.  It<br>
remains to be seen just how involved (administratively and socially) Black<br>
South Africans will be ALLOWED to be.  It may well be that with time, Black<br>
South Africans will become even more dissatisfied with the role GIVEN them in<br>
the church, and decide to TAKE on roles that allow them to participate more<br>
fully. Possibly in matters where Black/White issues are concerned this can be<br>
accomplished best through separate systems, if everyone is given the same<br>
amount of financial and moral support across the board.<br>
 <br>
Frankly, I am disappointed that the Adventist church allowed itself to be<br>
influenced by the popular political policies of the day regarding race<br>
relations, both in South Africa and in this country initially (maybe even to<br>
some degree today?).<br>
 <br>
Linda<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
