<title>Mar_1992: Re: South Africa votes</title>
<h1>Re: South Africa votes</h1>
Patricio Navia (<i></i>)<br>
<i>24 March 1992 11:56:29 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#75">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#75">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#75">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#75">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0076.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: South Africa votes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0074.html">Steven Timm: "Re: South Africa Votes"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0073.html">Steven Timm: "South Africa votes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0076.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: South Africa votes"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Comment: "Political Science/ Sociology"<br>
Comment: "University of Illinois at Chicago"<br>
Comment: "1803 University Hall M/C 219"<br>
Comment: "Box 4348 Chicago Il 60680"<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Now the next question.  When will all the American Black pastors who lobbied</i><br>
<i>&gt; so hard for this action of merging racially separate conferences wake up</i><br>
<i>&gt; and realize that they are calling for exactly the opposite here?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Why was apartheid unacceptable in South Africa, but required in the USA?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
I CANT' SPEAK for the black pastors, but I have been acquainted with the<br>
situation of Latino (hispanic, Spanish, Mexican, Puerto Rican, etc, or<br>
whatever name they receive --or adopt-- [by the way, all those names<br>
are correct, except Spanish --it should be Spanish-speaking]).<br>
 <br>
It seems to me that the situation in South Africa and the US is quite<br>
different.  While there racism was legally institutionalized (and thus,<br>
an act of merging conferences was a way to protest such institutionalization),<br>
the situation in the Us is the opposite.  Here, in most states, racism has<br>
completely dissapeared from the laws, but racist attitudes are still<br>
very much present. Pat Buchanan, David Duke and others have a track record<br>
of opposing blacks, Jews and Latinos.  Buchanan did not hesitate to suggest<br>
building a wall between the U.S.-Mexican border to prevent illegal<br>
migration [here the situation needs to be clarified: there was no Mexican<br>
migration in the southwest, five Us states were mexican!!!, the people<br>
who migrated to California, Texas, Arizona, New Mexico and parts of<br>
other states were actually the migrants; Puerto Rico was annexed to<br>
the US by the US in 1898; and one could further argue that most of<br>
the recent migration from central America and the caribbean has been caused<br>
by the wars fought with US and Soviet money by local guerillas and armies].<br>
 <br>
I am sure that all these cases of racist attitued are well known and<br>
cause all of you to be as ashamed as I am.<br>
 <br>
Within the church, however, I have experienced some feelings of neglect<br>
and paternalism on the part of the leadership of the church when it<br>
comes to Latinos.  neglect in the sense that the church does not<br>
recognize the different needs of the different grups (for instance, Latino<br>
churches have as many people who are Spanish speakers as those who<br>
are English speakers --and here I refer to their first language--; its<br>
is imperative, then, to prepare pastors who are bilingual, and not<br>
to bringSpanish speakign pastors from Latin America.  It is easier to<br>
bring people from Latin America (because many of them want to come<br>
anyway due to economic pressures) than to prepare the US born and<br>
raised Latino youth.  I see this as a major source of neglect and a<br>
major cause of preventing further growth of the church among Latinos.<br>
 <br>
I also see some neglect in the way Latino affairs are handled.  The<br>
president (or the board) of a conference appoints a pastor who will<br>
be the coordinator of Hispanic ministries.  This person is in fact<br>
the 'president of Latino churches.  The church becomes extremely<br>
hierarchical with such structure and problems more often than not never<br>
pass beyond the coordinator.  The coordinator then finds himself in a<br>
position of incredible influence and power (his suggestion may cause<br>
the hiring/firing of pastors) and many times uses such power<br>
indiscriminately.  The president and the board of the conference needs<br>
to be more aquainted with the problems facing Latino churches to<br>
prevent this one-man rule.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
I also see PATERNALISM within the church.  Just one example: I was in<br>
Hinsdale church (IL) a couple of weeks ago; the Sabbath School was<br>
collecting material donations for the 'kids down there in the city,<br>
the poor kids of the city'. Now, when you correlate the fac that most<br>
Latino churches are in fact in the inner city (while most 'white'<br>
churches are in the suburbs), then since their early childhood<br>
children learn to correlate poor children with city children (and<br>
thus 'minority' children).  At an adult age, this attitude (and I<br>
am aware of the generalization I am doing, but I feel it's<br>
necessary to make my point) also affects the way in which church<br>
officials see the members, pastors and the church of the cities<br>
in general.<br>
 <br>
And, as we are all aware, paternalism only causes rejection on the part<br>
of those who are being 'paternalized' or, worse, it causes dependency.<br>
 <br>
 <br>
For this reason, many Latino churches have looked towards the black<br>
conferences searching for a different attitude. In states  other than<br>
Illinois, some pastors have talked about forming Latino conferences.<br>
 <br>
In conclusion, I agree with Tim in the idea that the church should<br>
be unified in matters such as administrative organization.  Yet in<br>
order to achieve this, it is necessary that all parties understand<br>
what theie role, contributions and responsibilites are and,<br>
more importantly, what they role was in the process that caused this<br>
de-unification in the first place.<br>
 <br>
Patricio navia.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
