<title>Mar_1992: re: South Africa votes</title>
<h1>re: South Africa votes</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 24 Mar 92 16:58:03 EST </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#76">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#76">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#76">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#76">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Steven Timm: "Re: South Africa Votes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Patricio Navia: "Re: South Africa votes"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0073.html">Steven Timm: "South Africa votes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0083.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: South Africa votes"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Now the next question.  When will all the American Black pastors who lobbied</i><br>
<i>&gt; so hard for this action of merging racially separate conferences wake up </i><br>
<i>&gt; and realize that they are calling for exactly the opposite here?</i><br>
<i>&gt; Why was apartheid unacceptable in South Africa, but required in the USA?</i><br>
<p>
Apartheid was a case of the politically dominant whites -forcing- the black<br>
population to be seperated from them in every way, shape, and form, where it<br>
was possible.  Here in the US, 'black' churches &lt;personally, I don't believe <br>
in the concept of 'race'.  Show me pictures of palest nordic person you can<br>
find and the darkest african, and I'll line up a host of pictures between them<br>
with differences so slight you'll be unable to tell me where one 'race' ends<br>
and another begins.  We are all one race.  But I digress...&gt;  want their own<br>
conferences because they feel the conference structure as it currently exists<br>
does not address their needs.  They feel that if they had their own conferences,<br>
Those conference leaders would see to it that the needs of their churches -were-<br>
addressed.  <br>
<p>
With apartheid, the dominant group forced the split.<br>
Here in our minority churches, many disaffected members want it.<br>
<p>
The tragedy to me is not that the minority churches want their own conferences,<br>
but that the existing structures have done so abysmal a job of caring for those<br>
churches that they would want to be seperate.<br>
<p>
Bob Moynihan                    Disclaimer:  Hewlett-Packard rarely shares my views,<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com                     so I don't speak for them, only for me.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
