<title>Mar_1992: Re: South Africa Votes</title>
<h1>Re: South Africa Votes</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 25 Mar 1992 09:53:10 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#77">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#77">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#77">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#77">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Steven Timm: "SDA Race Relations"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0076.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: South Africa votes"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0074.html">Steven Timm: "Re: South Africa Votes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Linda Carpenter asks what lobbying effort I refer to on the part of African <br>
American pastors in the South African issue.  In the period 1985-1987, and <br>
probably before that slightly as well, there were some who advocated cutting<br>
out all ties with the South African Seventh-day Adventists unless they<br>
integrated.  At Andrews University at that time, there were faculty <br>
pressing to drop Andrews University's affiliation with the South African<br>
Helderberg College.  At the 1985 General Conference session, the delegates<br>
from the (white/colored/indian) South African Union couldn't eat at the<br>
same place as everyone else for fear that there would be a disturbance.<br>
Of course, at that session, the GC statement on apartheid was voted,<br>
and in 1986, the South Africans formed a commission to try to racially<br>
unify their church.  The recommendations of that commission were<br>
unfortunately ignored, and the problem was only taken up again last year.<br>
<p>
People try to emphasize the difference between the South African situation<br>
and the US situation.  While in the political situation there are many<br>
differences, the church situation has a lot of striking similarities.<br>
(Although I must admit that no SDA in North America has been "necklaced"<br>
recently for his/her faith).  Here there is pressure from the Black leaders<br>
to remain separate.  This pressure also existed there, as they worried that <br>
mergers might lead to closing of some of the educational institutions which<br>
kept their tuition low so as to better serve Black students.  But the Black<br>
ministers had (correct me if I'm wrong) a good advantage in this because<br>
now the pay scale will be non-racial and all ministers will make the same <br>
money.  <br>
<p>
I have often heard it said by people in the regional conferences "It is <br>
better to have our own house than no house at all."  We must realize that<br>
at first Black SDA's formed their own churches, not because they wanted <br>
to, but because white churches, particularly in the South, would not<br>
accept them.  Oakwood College was formed for the same reason.  <br>
These institutions are born of segregation.<br>
<p>
If churches of different ethnic backgrounds have different agendas,<br>
we need to examine why this is so, and then start the kind of dialogue<br>
within our church that unifies our agenda once more.  Our church has no <br>
master plan for Chicago or Pittsburgh (the only 2 cities I know about <br>
firsthand) because the conferences refuse to cooperate.  When we see that <br>
neither conference (Illinois or Lake Region) has the money to do anything,<br>
then it's time to start thinking that maybe two conference offices in the <br>
same metro area is a luxury we can no longer afford.  Worse, maybe it's<br>
a liability we can no longer afford.<br>
<p>
The fact that there remains a color barrier within our church is shameful.<br>
But more shameful yet is the problem that so few people even want to <br>
try to bridge that barrier.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
