<title>Mar_1992: SDA Race Relations</title>
<h1>SDA Race Relations</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>20676LKC%MSU.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 25 Mar 92 16:02 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#78">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#78">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#78">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#78">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Danny Kumamoto: "CIA and SDA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Steven Timm: "Re: South Africa Votes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm wondering if I have Steve's original point correct.  That is, was it<br>
suggested that African American pastors exhibited inconsistent behavior in<br>
calling for a merger of churches in South Africa while continuing to insist<br>
upon separation based on race here in the U.S.?<br>
 <br>
Different agendas - well, I don't know about differing agendas, but there are<br>
certain issues that have served to separate us here in the U.S.  The issue of<br>
emotional outpouring in the worship service has always been, and remains, a<br>
big one.  I have noted (with some amusement) the concern over "celebration<br>
churches".  It doesn't appear to be a major issue in regional churches - as a<br>
friend of mine said this weekend; "practically all of our churches are<br>
'celebration churches'" in some form or another.  I don't understand the fuss;<br>
I've always felt free to be vocal and demonstrative in my worship.  I<br>
certainly am aware that many White brothers and sisters may not feel that way.<br>
 <br>
Let's see; interracial dating - another biggie.  I thought it might be a<br>
little different from my academy days of 10 years or so ago when it was MAJOR<br>
taboo, but from what I've heard, that is not the case.  This final bastion of<br>
prejudice seems to be very much intact in the SDA church.  A seminary student<br>
once remarked to me that he thought an African American friend of mine was<br>
absolutely wonderful and wondered why she hadn't been "snatched up" by some<br>
young man.  When I suggested that he ask her out, he turned bright red and<br>
indicated that he probably wouldn't have much of a church career with a Black<br>
wife. This occurred only a few months ago.<br>
 <br>
These are but two of the several issues that seem to divide the church along<br>
racial lines.  In my opinion it is not about the Hispanics, Native Americans,<br>
West Indians, African Americans, etc., having different agendas; it's about<br>
prevailing racial attitudes and how they stymie our spiritual, social, and<br>
economic growth.<br>
 <br>
Linda<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
