<title>Dec_1992: Re:  "Independent ministries"</title>
<h1>Re:  "Independent ministries"</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Dec 92 22:26:58 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#33">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#33">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#33">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#33">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Steven Timm: "Chopping off heads to cure the common cold"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Pam Harris: "Independent ministries"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">Ruben Gonzalez: ""Independent ministries""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben said:<br>
<p>
Being aware of the independant minstries in the US like Weimar college and<br>
Hartlands and Pr. Ron Spear's group etc which are by and large very supportive<br>
of the church (Even though they might not agree with everything that goes on).<br>
<p>
<p>
Incidently, Ruben, Hartland Institute is one of the independents specifically<br>
named in the NAD denounciation.  The other ministries were Hope International/<br>
Our Firm Foundation; Prophecy Countdown; Steps to Life Church in Wichita, Kansas;<br>
and Rolling Hills Church of Rolling Hills, Florida.<br>
<p>
Two other items of interest from the NAD article for those who haven't seen it<br>
or don't have access:<br>
<p>
1)  The article references the book "Issues:  The Seventh-day Adventist Church<br>
and Certain Private Ministries" numerous times with comments that more info<br>
about a specific problem could be found there.  It also contained the following<br>
statement about that book:  "We [the editors] also endorse circulating the<br>
book, "Issues:  The Seventh-day Adventist Church and Certain Private Ministries"<br>
in the North American Division, in order that all interested individuals may<br>
be able to clearly recognize the serious divisive problem caused by private<br>
organizations which attempt to establish a church within the Seventh-day<br>
Adventist Church."  At the end of the article, there is the following<br>
footnote:  "Copies of Issues:  The Seventh-day Adventist Church and Certain<br>
Private Ministries are now available at your Adventist Book Center.<br>
<p>
Now what this appears to be is a shrouded advertising gimmick to sale this<br>
book.  What better way to sale R&amp;H publications than to stir up a boiling<br>
pot by publishing the NAD condemnation of private ministries and then tell<br>
people to go buy this book and find out the details of why their doing so!<br>
<p>
2)  The article states that "Seventh-day Adventists consider themselves a<br>
divinely called movement, raised up to proclaim the good news of Christ's<br>
second coming and to help prepare the world for that glorious event."  SDAs<br>
supposedly fulfill this mission THROUGH the organized structure of the Church.<br>
The clincher on this point is this statement:  "In a few cases, private<br>
organizations have worked at corss-purposes with the denomination, have<br>
become destructively critical of the leadership of the Church, have undermined<br>
the confidence of members in the organized body of believers, and have<br>
drained away FUNDS which could have been used in accomplishing the mission of<br>
the Church, thus crippling the evangelistic outreach of the Church."<br>
<p>
Now this I don't understand.  Is the ONLY evangelistic outreach in the SDA<br>
church that of tithe-paid evangelists hired by the Church hierarchy?  I don't<br>
think this was ever the PRIMARY mode of evangelism propagated by EGW.  In<br>
fact, personal evangelism has ALWAYS been the most successful.  Is the<br>
evangelistic outreach of the SDA church REALLY crippled by these lost funds?<br>
Or is it a fact that so little of the tithe money goes for this purpose that<br>
now they've budgetted it out?  (Of course, the Division wouldn't think of<br>
trimming church hierarchy instead!  Having a top-heavy organization is<br>
more important than evangelism?)<br>
<p>
I've appreciated each and every comment on the net.  Thanks for your thoughts.<br>
<p>
----------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
Cheryl L. Berthelsen, Ph.D.		email:  cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu<br>
