<title>Dec_1992: Spiritual authority in the church</title>
<h1>Spiritual authority in the church</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  1 Dec 1992 09:46:27 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Steven Timm: "Re: principles of interpretation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Steven Timm: "Coming disruptions in SDAnet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Some of the issues in human relations that I have raised over the past <br>
semester have led me to examine the question of how spiritual authority<br>
should be applied in general.  The problem was best described in a <br>
talk I heard several years ago given by Dr. Calvin Rock, then and now a <br>
general vice-president of the church with responsibility for education and <br>
publishing.  <br>
<p>
<p>
His remarks were to this effect:  "I am an advisor to the General Conference<br>
director of education, who is an advisor to the union education offices,<br>
who are advisors to the conference education offices and boards, who <br>
are advisory to the local school board, who are advisory to the local school."<br>
<p>
He was only slightly exaggerating.  Technically with K-12 education, the <br>
buck does stop with the local conference because they own the school<br>
buildings and pay the teachers.  But the lines of authority are confused,<br>
and the problem is not unique to education.  The SDA church in one lawsuit<br>
argued that it was a pure hierarchy, and in another a grass-roots democracy,<br>
and won both of them. <br>
<p>
At the union level, here and in South Africa, we have seen local conferences<br>
of different color refuse to work together even when it was voted in union<br>
session that they must do so.  At the conference level, we have seen a lack <br>
of effectiveness in dealing with the challenge presented to the authority <br>
of the church by independent ministries.  And at the local church level,<br>
there has been a breakdown of church discipline as the pendulum swings<br>
towards permissiveness.  In addition we see local pastors and conference<br>
leaders paralyzed by the complaints of a few people who are resistant to <br>
change in any form.  ("If the Church Hymnal was good enough for Ellen G.<br>
White, it's good enough for me!")<br>
<p>
Some growing churches make coherent plans for accountability for ministry.<br>
The minister chooses a small group to disciple, meeting weekly (or more <br>
frequently) with them.  In turn, each member of this small group becomes<br>
the leader of his/her own small group.  The minister thus receives support<br>
from, and is accountable to, a group of people who have their finger<br>
on the pulse of the church.  This makes it much easier to build consensus.<br>
<p>
I should point out that without the blessing of the Holy Spirit, such <br>
a small-group plan is doomed to fail, and with the Holy Spirit, other<br>
plans can work as well.  But some plan is necessary.  It's my deep conviction<br>
that the surface issues we face in our church over music, worship styles,<br>
lifestyles, and scriptural interpretation all revolve around the authority<br>
vacuum we are presently experiencing.  I would appreciate it if SDAnet<br>
would join me in searching for solutions to this.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Steven Timm: "Re: principles of interpretation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Steven Timm: "Coming disruptions in SDAnet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
