<!-- inreplyto="9211302214.AA24062@susan.cs.andrews.edu" -->
<title>Dec_1992: Re: principles of interpretation</title>
<h1>Re: principles of interpretation</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  1 Dec 1992 09:25:11 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#7">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#7">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#7">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#7">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: Copyright on EGW CD-Rom"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Steven Timm: "Spiritual authority in the church"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0003.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: principles of interpretation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
David P. notes that some of the Bible writers in the NT (and Jesus himself)<br>
didn't have the qualms that we have today concerning proper exegesis.<br>
Nancy Vyhmeister asked for some examples.  The most obvious place to start<br>
is the book of Matthew.  Try sometime reading Matthew in a translation<br>
such as the New American Standard, where every quote from the Old Testament<br>
is highlighted, then look up the context of these quotes in the OT.  You<br>
will see Matthew's method of interpretation.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: Copyright on EGW CD-Rom"</a>
