<title>Dec_1992: NAD action on private organizations</title>
<h1>NAD action on private organizations</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 1 Dec 92 23:57:32 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#9">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#9">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#9">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#9">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Daniel R. Bidwell: "EG White CD"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: Copyright on EGW CD-Rom"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0038.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: were the apostles communist/marxist?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Although I am no longer a member of the SDA church, I still receive the<br>
Adventist Review regularly.  I don't know who's paying for it or having<br>
it sent to me, but I do read it with interest.  The December 3, 1992 NAD<br>
issue had an article about NAD action on private organizations which really<br>
caught my eye.  Here are my impressions--those of an outsider who has no<br>
knowledge or experience with the named organizations in the article.<br>
<p>
First, I was amazed at the seemingly unchristian attitude portrayed in the<br>
wording of the article.  Although it state specifically "this document is<br>
not presented in a spirit of combat or hostility" is reeks of that spirit.<br>
The words divisive or dissident appear in almost every paragraph.  There<br>
are strong words such as "accuse", "rival", "competition".  But the underlying<br>
motivition or thread in the article seemed to be that these private "divisive"<br>
organizations were successfully competing for tithe monies that the organized<br>
SDA church would like coming to their coffers.  Sample statements of this<br>
idea:  "They accuse the SDA church of activities which may encourage members<br>
to divert tithe to their private organizations rather than to the Church."<br>
"According to the Bible plan the Church is supported by tithes and offerings.<br>
When these private organizations seek or knowingly accept tithe for themselves,<br>
it thrusts at the heart of the individual Christian experience, for they are<br>
asking church members to switch loyalties away from God's plan to a rival<br>
plan."  "They threaten the viability of the Church when they encourage<br>
members to divert financial resources from the organized church to their<br>
private treasuries."<br>
<p>
I can understand the disappointment of SDA church members in the financial<br>
irresponsibility shown by Church leaders.  The Davenport Affair, the failure<br>
of Harris Pine Mills and numerous other financial blunders have left members<br>
wondering what they should do with their tithe.  At least these organizations<br>
seem to have a mission and use the money for gospel purposes.  What I don't<br>
understand is why this article can claim that an organized church setup in<br>
the way the SDA church is setup as "the Bible plan" or "God's plan".  For<br>
the Bible DOES NOT teach of any such plan or organization.  In the NT, the<br>
apostles were specifically chosen by Christ and replacement Apostles chosen<br>
by the remaining Apostles.  Nowhere does the Bible justify an elected<br>
leadership chosed by the an elite group.  Nowhere does the Bible teach that<br>
hierarchical leadership at Division, Union, Local Conference, Local congregation<br>
is "God's plan of church organization."  In the OT, religious leaders were<br>
chosen from the tribe of Levi and the tithing went to support them because<br>
they did no gainful employment to support themselves.  In the NT, the Church<br>
was financially organized as a community with all members owning assets<br>
jointly (a form of communism) and no individual owned anything outright.<br>
The present SDA organization doesn't resemble either of these two systems.<br>
<p>
I'd be interested in the observations of other SDAnetters on this article.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
