Steve Timm &amp; Net:<br>
<p>
Steve, <br>
<p>
enjoyed the Digest that I read last evening. I noticed that there were a<br>
few comments on Cheryl's "Steps in studying the Bible." In my opinion it<br>
was well done, concise, etc.<br>
<p>
The number #2 item: "Don't be afraid to challenge what you've been taught<br>
in the past." I thought that was very much on target because it is very<br>
easy to substitute tradition for truth. Also, because we do "proof text"<br>
ourselves into oblivion at times -- &lt;g&gt; -- it is probably good every so<br>
often to restudy our teachings. One of my favorite expressions is : "It is<br>
not important what I say, but what does the Bible teach!" I would hope<br>
that what I am teaching is Bible based, but what the Bible teaches is the<br>
all important thing.<br>
<p>
I am not trying to speak for Cheryl or put words in her mouth! -- Item #7<br>
which states that The Holy Bible is not the literal word of God is a<br>
correct statement. The way I perceived this statement was that the<br>
writer's of the Bible were inspired by the Holy Spirit -- "God Breathed"<br>
--but the words are their words.<br>
<p>
On another Note, Steve, I was not aware that you had a part in the "Lamp"<br>
software. Gary Russell sent me a copy (demo) of the Lamp. I never did get<br>
the Lamp because I was already involved in "Word Search."<br>
<p>
......Paul<br>
