<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm writes, "David P. notes that some of the Bible writers in the NT <br>
(and Jesus himself) didn't have the qualms that we have today concerning <br>
proper exegesis. Nancy Vyhmeister asked for some examples.  The most obvious <br>
place to start is the book of Matthew.  Try sometime reading Matthew in a <br>
translation such as the New American Standard, where every quote from the Old <br>
Testament is highlighted, then look up the context of these quotes in the OT. <br>
You will see Matthew's method of interpretation."<br>
<p>
You will also note that essentially all the quotations in the New Testament of<br>
Old Testament texts are quoted from the Septuagent(sp?) which is Greek <br>
translation and not from the original Hebrew.<br>
<p>
Ed Fargusson (Compuserve 72450,2430)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
