<title>Dec_1992: White Estate</title>
<h1>White Estate</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  2 Dec 1992 23:18:20 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Fred Christiansen: "Bible Search Software"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Computer Science student: "Goodbye !!!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;It sems that the E.G. White Estates is going to drag their feet about</i><br>
<i>&gt;allowing unix systems to access their CD rom.    &lt;DELETEED&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;All of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;original books are no longer covered under the copyright laws, but there</i><br>
<i>&gt;is still some question about whether the same material can be</i><br>
<i>&gt;copyrighted when put onto a newer form of media such as the CD.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
I don't know much about this so maybe someone can help be out. In the <br>
comment above it sounds like the E.G. White Estate is wanting to cash in<br>
on the newer form of media. If so, I thought the object here was to spread <br>
information not gain from the spreading of information. I guess I should<br>
really ask is who IS the E.G. White Estate?<br>
<p>
Thanks<br>
***********************************************************************<br>
* Alan Dare                     |  Internet : alan@hal.larc.nasa.gov  *<br>
* NASA Langley Research Center  |  Phone : 804-864-2161               * <br>
* MS 152E Hampton, VA 23665     |  FAX  : 804-864-7793                * <br>
*                                                                     *<br>
* We were in uncharted territory, making up history as we went along. *<br>
*                                                  Sara Connor        *<br>
***********************************************************************<br>
[Several conflicting statements have been made here about the copyright<br>
of the books themselves.  Ellen White's will dictated that a group of<br>
trustees should supervise the continued publication and translation<br>
of her writings, and profits earned from the royalties should be put back<br>
into supporting these efforts.  The trustees are members of the White Estate,<br>
which is housed at the offices of the General Conference in Silver Spring, MD<br>
and has set up research centers at various Adventist colleges around the <br>
world.  At first the estate was headed by Ellen G. White's son, then later<br>
by her grandson, but to my knowledge no relatives are currently involved.<br>
The trustees are appointed by and serve at the pleasure of the General <br>
Conference of SDA.  As to any conspiracy, one should not attribute to <br>
conspiracy that which may be explained by inefficiency and indecision.  With<br>
the release of the CD-Rom it is claimed that all manuscripts of whatever<br>
sort that E.G. White wrote are now available to the public.  SCT]<br>
