<title>Dec_1992: Re: Church authority</title>
<h1>Re: Church authority</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>04 Dec 1992 10:12:01 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#21">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#21">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#21">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#21">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Tony: ""Independent ministries""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">Randall A Helzerman: "NAD action on private organizations (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve made the comment that he attributes many of the "surface <br>
issues" such as lifestyle, standards, worship style etc. that<br>
the church is facing to a crisis in perceived church authority.<br>
<p>
I propose that the reason these issues have emerged is because<br>
of the way authority has been manifested in the past.<br>
<p>
Individuals who are governed by rules and regulations do not<br>
need to develop their own sense of ethics and principles. The<br>
sudden removal of the rules and regulations leaves that individual<br>
with no mature set of internalized principles and priorities.<br>
<p>
Rather than calling for a reversion to the rules and their<br>
extrinsic principles, it seems far more appropriate to aim<br>
towards maturity and responsibility within individuals. After <br>
all, one of the major differences between Catholicism and<br>
Protestantism (?) is that Catholics believe in Salvation through<br>
the organization, but protestants believe it's the individual's<br>
relationship with God that is important.<br>
<p>
It shouldn't be up to the church to act as our conscience.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<i>]</i><br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Tony: ""Independent ministries""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">Randall A Helzerman: "NAD action on private organizations (fwd)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
