<title>Dec_1992: NAD position on independent ministries</title>
<h1>NAD position on independent ministries</h1>
Gilbert Bailey (<i>gilbertb@lsid.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Dec 92 15:14:03 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Danny Kumamoto: "NAD action on private organizations"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Tony: ""Independent ministries""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seemed to me that the point the Church was trying to make<br>
is that the independent ministries mentioned were being dogmatic<br>
on interpretation of certain scripture details that the Church<br>
does not intend to define.  This gray area leaves room for many opinions,<br>
and by definition, one no more or less correct than the others.<br>
<p>
In 1888 the message of righteousness by faith was side tracked by<br>
differences of opinion in regard to the correct historical application<br>
of a prophecy (I've forgotten the details, but seem to remember to <br>
arguments were about the correct identification of the 10 kingdoms,<br>
or 'kings of the east'. I'll have to look up the details).<br>
It seems to me that any 'ministry' that spends the majority of it's<br>
time critisizing another for not holding the same opinions is side<br>
tracking the Church's mission.  Actions speak louder than words.<br>
<p>
Christ's second comming needs to be preached as imminent, and the good <br>
news of salvation shared with all who will listen.<br>
<p>
<p>
