<title>Dec_1992: Independent ministries</title>
<h1>Independent ministries</h1>
Pam Harris (<i>HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU</i>)<br>
<i>03 Dec 1992 23:24:45 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#32">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#32">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#32">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#32">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  "Independent ministries""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Steven Timm: "Unexpected album reviews"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I saw the Autumn Council report on independent ministries. Interestingly,<br>
Good News Unlimited (GNU) was crossed out of the list this year although<br>
the Review article seemed to include them. Perhaps the Review went to<br>
press before the final vote. Several of the groups are particularly<br>
ascerbic. I must disagree with Reuben about Ron Spear's group. It is<br>
NOT supportive of the church. Perhaps the church had to make such a<br>
obvious statement for legal reasons. The church may legally want to<br>
separate itself from some of the things these groups are doing and<br>
relieve itself of liability for lawsuits. In addition, aligning with<br>
some of the activities of these groups without an official disclaimer<br>
sends messages of approval to some of the church membership that the <br>
church officially sanctions the viewpoints of these groups. There<br>
may be other reasons besides the collection of tithe which drove the<br>
church to release an official statement about these groups.<br>
<p>
Pam Harris<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
