<title>Dec_1992: Chopping off heads to cure the common cold</title>
<h1>Chopping off heads to cure the common cold</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri,  4 Dec 1992 10:27:29 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#34">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#34">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#34">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#34">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Dave Buxton: "What are Catholcis like today (Was NAD topic)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0033.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  "Independent ministries""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Whenever I'm in Pittsburgh for a couple months, the reality is brought<br>
back to me that 95% of all the problems in the church are caused by <br>
poor communication.  When one considers who the leadership in the Washington<br>
Conference was at the time that Hope International--Our Firm Foundation<br>
got started, it's probable that the feud began with some interpersonal<br>
squabble which occured in the context of discussing some matter of faith<br>
or practice.<br>
<p>
Although I despise the tactics that are used by both sides, of carpet-bombing<br>
their opponent with all the quotes they can muster, I cannot fault them<br>
for propagandicating in the only way they know how.  For a good sixty years,<br>
this is the way it was done in the SDA church.  Denominational publications,<br>
contrary to what E.G. White and the Bible claim, claimed verbal inspiration<br>
for inspired writings.  By doing so they made these writings fair game to <br>
be used as weapons, and sowed the seed for dissent on the right which is<br>
occurring now and the dissent on the left of D. Ford and W. Rea which<br>
continues today.  We have sown the wind and now we are reaping the<br>
whirlwind.<br>
<p>
The SDA denomination was built around a consensus of people studying the<br>
Bible and building community out of a common understanding of truth.  <br>
We need to rediscover the path to building unity through consensus.  <br>
To say that the theological issues are not important is discrediting the <br>
Bible's place and Christ's place as the core of unity among SDA's. <br>
The theological differences are important, but I believe that consensus<br>
can be reached if the church leadership would come out from behind the <br>
fortress of authority and the opposition would stop carpet-bombing<br>
the denomination with missives.  <br>
<p>
I should also state that I think the reports of "the big bad hierarchy"<br>
and "Gulag mentality" are grossly overrated.  If everyone would stop<br>
being concerned with their own rights and having to win arguments,<br>
then the problem could be settled quickly, and we wouldn't have to have<br>
the inflated rhetoric which appears on both sides.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
