<title>Dec_1992: What are Catholcis like today (Was NAD topic)</title>
<h1>What are Catholcis like today (Was NAD topic)</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 04 Dec 92 07:56:10 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#35">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#35">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#35">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#35">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Lola: "announcing new arrival"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Steven Timm: "Chopping off heads to cure the common cold"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What are Catholcis like today (Was NAD topic)"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; &gt;   Catholic, as I find EGW defining it, is when ecclesiastic councils</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;   rule over church doctrine and seek to rule conscience. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I'm not so sure if this concept of "Catholic" is valid these</i><br>
<i>&gt; days.  </i><br>
<p>
I agree in that virtually all the Catholics with whom I have exchanged<br>
email have been surprisingly "Protestant" in their thinking.  They have<br>
told me they do not worship Mary, that they believe in Righteousness<br>
by faith and not works.  Quite often I had thought the newsgroup poster<br>
or the email writer was Protestant and then it turned out they were<br>
RCC.  So I think its fair to say that the gap between RCC and Protestant<br>
churches has narrowed considerably.  Catholics today are probably<br>
more Protestant perhaps than many of the Protestants back in Luther's<br>
day.<br>
<p>
Also, Carl Rehner (sp?) who is one of the leading Jesuit architects of<br>
ecumenical writes that there are those who are concerned for a grass<br>
roots rebellion among Protestants.  But he goes on to say, not to<br>
worry because Protestants have become as subservient to their church<br>
leaderships as Catholics are to their Pope.  Well, the RCC in this<br>
country are not nearly as subservient to their Pope as they are in<br>
other countries.  So, the parallel is probably true in the USA, but<br>
perhaps not as true as compared with RCC in say Rome or Spain.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
