<title>Dec_1992: Tolerance</title>
<h1>Tolerance</h1>
Malachi Robertson (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 6 Dec 92 3:08:40 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#37">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#37">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#37">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#37">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: were the apostles communist/marxist?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Lola: "announcing new arrival"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am not absolutely sure that is the right subject for this message, but<br>
here it goes anyway.<br>
<p>
I read something in the post subjected "Goodbey!" and it reminded me of my<br>
Sabbath school discussion today.  It centered around an EGW quote from the<br>
lesson for Thursday:<br>
 <br>
"Marked diversities of disposition and character frequently exist in the<br>
same family, for it is the order of God that persons of varied temperment<br>
should associate together.  When this is the case, each member of the<br>
household should sacredly regard the feelings and respect the right of the<br>
others.  By this means mutual consideration and forbearance will be<br>
cultivated, prejudices will be softened, and rought points of character<br>
smoothed.  Harmony may be secured, and the blending of the varied<br>
temperaments may be a benefit to each."<br>
<p>
Now this does not specifically address the race item brought up in that<br>
one letter, but the issue brought out from it does.  The time to work on<br>
getting along with other people of varied temperament is now.  And I think<br>
one could say the same about race.  What are those people going to do in<br>
heaven?  I don't think bigotry will get through the door.  Now is the time<br>
to fully submit our entire being to God.  If a sin is found by the nudging<br>
of the Spirit then by the Spirit's power it ought to be fought against. <br>
One thing that impressed me about Steps to Christ and Great Controversy<br>
was the stress on not holding back on any sin.  100% must be given up. <br>
The point I got was that if you see a sin in your life, then admit that it<br>
is a problem and agree with the Holy Spirit and right then put the problem<br>
before God.  <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
