<title>Dec_1992: Re: were the apostles communist/marxist?</title>
<h1>Re: were the apostles communist/marxist?</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Dec 92 10:13:04 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What should leaders provide?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Malachi Robertson: "Tolerance"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0009.html">cheryl berthelsen: "NAD action on private organizations"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[cheryl berthelsen writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; In the NT, the Church</i><br>
<i>&gt; was financially organized as a community with all members owning assets</i><br>
<i>&gt; jointly (a form of communism) and no individual owned anything outright.</i><br>
<p>
I've heard this in the US, in Europe, and in Africa.  However,<br>
I don't see Scripture as supporting anything close to communism.<br>
Let me elaborate:  Communism involves centralized ownership and control<br>
of assets, under the guise of representing the masses in so doing.<br>
However, I believe I can demonstrate that private ownership was maintained<br>
and private enterprise practised in NT times (quite the opposite from<br>
communism), notably in a manner that gave glory to God.<br>
<p>
  Acts 2:44 And all that believed were together, and had all things in common.<br>
<p>
I grant that this sounds at first blush like a form of communism, but I find<br>
that a closer examination of what "all things in common" means is revealed<br>
by studying the context which suggests something quite different (NIV and<br>
others have helpful renderings, btw).<br>
<p>
  v. 45 And sold their possessions and goods, and parted them to all men,<br>
  as every man had need.<br>
<p>
Observe that you cannot sell or share what you do not own (except as a<br>
representative of a corporate body, which I believe is disproved later).<br>
Note also that the selling or sharing ("parting") was done on an as-needed<br>
basis to individuals/families, not without exception a-priori into some<br>
corporate "kitty" (altho that also was done; see on) as a corporate communal<br>
form of property-holding would require.<br>
<p>
  Acts 4:32 And the multitude of them that believed were of one heart and<br>
  of one soul:  neither SAID any of them that ought of the things which he<br>
  possessed was his own; but they had all things common. [emph supplied]<br>
<p>
If you grab the last phrase, it does sound again like communal property.<br>
However, the prior phrases must be used to illuminate it.  Note the<br>
one-ness of spirit and love and compassion towards each other that they had,<br>
a direct fulfillment of Jesus' prayer in John 17.  It was this attitude,<br>
couple with an awareness of Deut 8:18, Ps 50:10, et al, and obedience to<br>
Prov 11:24,26, et al, that compelled them to view ("said") or consider<br>
(but not a legal fact) their possessions as not their own.  Specifically,<br>
not their own to use as they pleased but a trust to employ for God's glory<br>
(cf. 1 Cor 6:20; also Phil 2:6 in a modern translation, spec re "grasp").<br>
<p>
  v. 34,35 Neither was there any among them that lacked: for as many as were<br>
  POSSESSORS of lands or houses sold them, and brought the prices of the<br>
  things that were sold, and laid them down at the apostles' feet: and<br>
  distribution was made unto every man according as he had need. [emph suppl]<br>
<p>
Note again the clear legal situation:  private owners (not corporate<br>
representatives) selling to other private owners, then taking the money<br>
and turning it in for distribution on an as-needed basis (which, btw,<br>
given I Tim 5:8, is distinctly different from today's government welfare).<br>
These verses are then followed by the stories of Barnabas and Ananias &amp;<br>
Sapphira.  While the emphasis in the latter case is upon their duplicity<br>
and self-glorification, which dishonored God, both cases clearly indicate<br>
private ownership.<br>
<p>
As for private enterprise, see Acts 18:3 or John 21:3.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
