<title>Dec_1992: Re: What should leaders provide?</title>
<h1>Re: What should leaders provide?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  6 Dec 1992 23:08:23 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#39">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#39">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#39">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#39">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Steven Timm: "Re: The ten plus two commandments"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: were the apostles communist/marxist?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0043.html">Tim Swensen: "What should leaders provide?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Fred Christiansen made some timely comments about how one is to treat<br>
the leaders of the church (Paul's experience), and Tim Swensen has<br>
raised some<br>
interesting questions.  <br>
<p>
The essential with trying to reach the unchurched is that eventually you<br>
establish a church, and the problems in general of maintaining a church<br>
tend to distract from the primary mission of the church which is to<br>
spread God's love.  In general, people go to church to regain security<br>
as they face their fears of the afterlife.  "...so take my hand, and<br>
tell me what it costs to <br>
see the promised land...I'm getting sleepier."<br>
<p>
You will find that every organized religion has some method of "eternal<br>
security maintenance" after people first join their church.  For Islam<br>
it is prayer 5 times a day, for Catholics it's attending mass, for<br>
Baptists and the like it's continuing to believe hard enough to be<br>
saved, and for SDA's it has been the lifestyle (for so many years). <br>
Leaders tell people<br>
what to believe because most of the masses just ask what to believe.  It's<br>
neater to have a nice box of beliefs than to think them out for yourself.<br>
Maybe someday they will even make a computer program to make it easier to <br>
"Make believe, not war."  When the package of beliefs is "The Truth",<br>
an exclusive channel to Eternal Life (provided you work at it hard enough),<br>
it's even easier to feel comfortable in such a system.<br>
<p>
(We never have resolved on the net whether or not it is Christian to <br>
keep veteran church members feeling "lukewarm and fuzzy", but I digress).<br>
<p>
The difficulty we face now is that the pocket of the church, North America,<br>
is financially dependent on those who have come to expect their<br>
"lukewarm fuzzies"  from the church in return for the tithe.  Some of<br>
the more candid<br>
conference presidents admit that pastors are there to serve tithepayers.<br>
Because the leadership catered to the desires, rather than the needs,<br>
of the denomination in the past, the present leadership which by and large<br>
does want to address the needs finds itself in a dilemma.  If it dares to <br>
bite the hands that feed it, we will have a transition to the world <br>
of post-institutional Adventism sooner than anyone planned.<br>
<p>
The recourse being applied in response to the crisis is to threaten loss<br>
of the spiritual security blanket if the tithe is not paid to the<br>
organization which provides it.  It may work for some.  Ironically, even<br>
as all the concern about tithe is expressed, fiscal 1992 for the church<br>
was the first time we had been in the black for several years.<br>
<p>
With due respect to Fred's comments about spiritual leaders, we are not<br>
governed by a theocracy in the SDA church.  We should, however, apply<br>
the principle "Whosoever would be greatest among you, let him be your<br>
servant."  From my contacts with the leadership, it seems to me that<br>
they are trying very hard to do just that.  The leadership's job is to<br>
make available to the local church resources and services it could not<br>
provide for itself.  If they are slightly more visionary, they could<br>
also help to coordinate activities between other churches in the<br>
jurisdiction.  If slightly less visionary, <br>
then all I expect is for them to stay out of my way, and not hinder growth<br>
at the local level (they have done this admirably so far.)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
