<title>Dec_1992: Re: What are Catholcis like today (Was NAD topic)</title>
<h1>Re: What are Catholcis like today (Was NAD topic)</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  6 Dec 1992 22:15:35 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#42">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#42">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#42">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#42">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Tim Swensen: "What should leaders provide?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0041.html">Steven Timm: "The ten plus two commandments"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0035.html">Dave Buxton: "What are Catholcis like today (Was NAD topic)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave's comment about Catholics calls to mind my (former SDA) friend <br>
in South Africa.  She is feminist, lesbian, revolutionary (card-carrying<br>
member of African Natl. Congress), and yet she sees no conflict with<br>
being a Catholic and has even talked from time to time of entering a convent.<br>
Catholics of her stripe make a big deal about the fact that the various<br>
pronouncements of the pope on such things as abortion and the role of<br>
women have not been declared infallible.<br>
<p>
Many times in the general end-times persecution complex of SDA's, we<br>
look for signs of unity between Catholics and Protestants, and the union<br>
of both of these with spiritualism, because it is these three in<br>
conjunction and not the Catholics alone who will form the opposition to<br>
Christ at the end.  I would warn that it is not necessary for an<br>
opposition to be unified to do damage.  Consider the Sadducees and<br>
Pharisees of the time of Christ.  They hated each other.  But all that<br>
mattered was that they hated Christ for the same reasons that they hated<br>
each other, and they cooperated enough to get rid of Him.<br>
<p>
I think it will be the same way at the end of time.  In this case it<br>
will be antipathy towards the law of God and those who keep it that will<br>
be the temporary unifying factor.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
