<title>Dec_1992: What should leaders provide?</title>
<h1>What should leaders provide?</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Dec 92 15:10:05 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">David Plaisted: "independent ministries"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What are Catholcis like today (Was NAD topic)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0039.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What should leaders provide?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
Maybe some of you can provide some answers.  What is it that we expect our<br>
spiritual leaders to provide us?  What distinctions do we see in the roles<br>
of pastors, conference leaders, etc, vs. those of laypersons?  In what ways<br>
can we lighten the burdens our leaders bear?<br>
<p>
The premium we place upon knowing the scriptures for ourselves is certainly<br>
appropriate; but isn't it easy to let this spirit of independence spill over<br>
into contempt for group efforts and rejection of the concept of spiritual<br>
authority in general?  Come to think of it, what concept of authority do you<br>
folks subscribe to?  I've not studied this much, and I'd welcome some insights<br>
into this area.<br>
<p>
Relating to the present debate (certain independent ministries), what do we<br>
expect our leaders to do when organizations openly ask for tithe, imply that<br>
large numbers of our pastors are spiritually poisoning the flock from the <br>
pulpit, (I'm referring to Ralph Larson's article on tithe in Our Firm <br>
Foundation), and basically set themselves up as the true preservers of the<br>
original, pure SDA doctrine.  I really don't know what the best course of <br>
action is.  Does someone have a reference handy to some timely Scripture <br>
(beyond the counsels in Matthew) and EGW on this matter.  From what I am<br>
hearing on SDAnet, it sounds like the public confrontation method is not the<br>
way to proceed.<br>
<p>
Finally, I must take issue with Cheryl's insinuation that the book "Issues:<br>
The Seventh-day Adventist Church and Certain Private Ministries" is basically<br>
a ploy to rake in revenue for the ABC's.  Isn't this a bit cynical?<br>
<p>
Thanks for the replies,<br>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
