<title>Dec_1992: independent ministries</title>
<h1>independent ministries</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Dec 92 14:39:37 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#44">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#44">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#44">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#44">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Fred Christiansen: "Lessons from Acts 23"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Tim Swensen: "What should leaders provide?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to Pam Harris' comment that some of the ministries do<br>
not support the church, let me state that all of the named ministries<br>
(I think) encourage people to remain members of the organized SDA<br>
church.  None of these ministries actively solicit tithe.  I think<br>
most of these ministries spend more time promoting what they see as<br>
truth rather than attacking others.  On all three points the Review<br>
pamphlet gave a wrong impression.  So I would agree with Ruben that<br>
these ministries do support the official church organization, though<br>
some of them do accept tithe money and some of them do point out<br>
what they see as problems in the church.  Also, I think that the<br>
quotations from Firm Foundation given in that article gave a<br>
non-representative view of what the magazine is like.  I would hope<br>
people would actually look at the magazine and not make decisions<br>
based on what the article quoted.  Also, Hope International and<br>
Hartland did NOT support the ordination at Steps to Life, contrary<br>
to the implication in the article.  These ministries tend to represent<br>
the conservative viewpoint within Adventism.  Some may not agree with<br>
that.  But I think still it's important to be fair.  This lack of<br>
fairness is one of the things that disturbed me most about that<br>
Review pamphlet.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
