<!-- id="9212041827.AA02343@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Dec_1992: Lessons from Acts 23</title>
<h1>Lessons from Acts 23</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Dec 92 11:27:47 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#45">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#45">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#45">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#45">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0046.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Independent ministries"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0044.html">David Plaisted: "independent ministries"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
While reading the first verses in Acts 23 last night, I was impressed with<br>
how relevant they were to some of our current discussions; particularly,<br>
how to respond towards church authorities when you think they're in the<br>
wrong.  Note that I do not mean to infer that current church authorities<br>
are anything like Ananias or the council.<br>
<p>
Note the context:  Paul has been placed under arrest without charge,<br>
narrowly escaped being flogged with a cruel scourge, and is now before<br>
the Sanhedrin for, well, inquisition.  In ch.21 it had been alleged<br>
by enemies that he had acted contrary to God's laws.  Hence his opening<br>
statement:<br>
<p>
  v.1 And Paul, earnestly beholding the council, said, Men and brethren,<br>
  I have lived in all good conscience before God until this day.<br>
  v.2 And the high priest Ananias command them that stood by him to smite<br>
  him on the mouth.<br>
<p>
This council is now well in the groove of flouting Jewish law for the<br>
selfish purposes of preserving their position, having already done so<br>
with Jesus, his brother James, Stephen, and various other disciples.<br>
Paul's statement condemns them in what little conscience they have left.<br>
This is such an irritation that anger explodes, Ananias commanding<br>
"slap his mouth!" as if to right some insult to God.<br>
<p>
  v.3 Then said Paul unto him, God shall smite thee, thou whitened wall:<br>
  for sittest thou to judge me after the law, and commandest me to be<br>
  smitten contrary to the law?<br>
<p>
At this point Ananias is dead wrong and Paul, relative to the law, is<br>
dead right.  Thumbs down on Ananias, thumbs up for Paul.  Go for it!<br>
Sock it to him, pal!  You have a right to be righteously indignant!  So,<br>
we all line up on Paul's side and try to look, well, imposing if not tough.<br>
<p>
  v.4 And they that stood by said, Revilest thou God's high priest?<br>
  v.5 Then said Paul, I wist not, brethren, that he was the high priest:<br>
  for it is written, Thou shalt not speak evil of the ruler of thy people.<br>
<p>
Instead of saying, "And he's a lousy excuse for a high priest", or even<br>
"In God's sight he's no high priest of God because he has departed from<br>
God's laws", Paul apologizes.  Apologizes, so help me!  This seems totally<br>
opposite to what you or I might think was the righteous thing to do.<br>
Paul says "I'm sorry.  I was wrong.  I didn't know he was the high priest.<br>
The law says: ...".  I believe Paul is being genuine here, that he did not<br>
know the person speaking was the high priest; this is no protect-your-<br>
posterior dissembling.<br>
<p>
The verse that Paul quotes is Exodus 22:28 (not word for word, but the<br>
spirit of it).  The attitude and expression enjoined, that Paul demonstrated,<br>
finds resonance in David's attitude towards Saul (numerous refs, e.g.,<br>
1 Sam 24).  David understood (cf. Ps 105:15, Prov 21:1) that THOSE IN<br>
AUTHORITY RECEIVE THAT AUTHORITY FROM GOD AND ARE THUS DUE RESPECT IN<br>
*EVERY* WAY, even when doing wrong.  Jesus clearly understood this principle<br>
in His response to Pilate in John 19:11.  Further evidence from Paul<br>
on this principle:  I Tim 2:1-3, Rom 13:1-7, Tit 3:1,2.  From Peter:<br>
I Pet 2, esp v.11-17.<br>
<p>
That this principle re civil authority applies also to the church<br>
can be seen in this verse:  "Pay proper respect to this who work<br>
among you, THOSE WHOM THE LORD HAS CHOSEN to guide and instruct you"<br>
[emph supplied].  (I learned this from listening to tape of memory verses<br>
put to music by, I believe, Wayne Hooper.  Unfortunately, I cannot find<br>
the music book or the tape, both of which we have but buried away somewhere.<br>
I imagine it's the NIV rendering.  Can someone help me on this?)<br>
<p>
What then does the Bible say about responding to those in authority, when<br>
they do wrong, in order to rectify things?  I would like to encourage some<br>
discussion re this.  I'll post my Scripture findings after I see some responses.<br>
Note that I dearly hope to see Scripture-based material (cf. Isa 55 and 65:2).<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
