In your message about the additional commandments you adk about other<br>
items that we vow to uphold during baptism.  My wife and I had a lengthy<br>
discussion aboiut this topic after a recent baptism.  The vows stated <br>
that the person could not use or sell tobacco, alcahol, caffinated beverages<br>
or other unhealthy items.  This would obviously preclude a person from <br>
getting a job at a 7-11 or a grocery store or gas station or any other <br>
establishment that served or sold these items.  This would also include<br>
many resturants.  And if taken to extreame would even include any establishment<br>
that has a vending machine that dispenses such items.  <br>
<p>
We have definately come to a point that we don't have any tolerance for <br>
others beliefs on issues.  I am not a vegetarian although my wife is, and<br>
I get repeated attacks as to how unhealthy eatting meat is and that one of<br>
these days I will grow enough in my faith that I will want to give up <br>
flesh foods.  I enjoy a good steak still and the constant haranging of <br>
my fellow christians as to my dietary practices just angers me and makes <br>
me dig my heels in even deeper in regards to eating meat.  <br>
<p>
What ever happened to shareing the gospel of a crucified and risen<br>
Christ and his wonderful salvation instead of a new set of <br>
"phariseical" laws. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
