<title>Dec_1992: RE: What should leaders provide?</title>
<h1>RE: What should leaders provide?</h1>
ARKUSINSKI ANDY  (<i>/S=ARKUSINSKI_ANDY/O=MSMAIL/PRMD=SMITHS_IND./ADMD=TELEMAIL/C=US/@mailtalk.si.comARKUSINSKI ANDY </i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Dec 92 01:28:05 GMT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#52">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#52">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#52">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#52">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Marcus Stringer: "ADRA"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0051.html">Kwong-hoon Andrew Park: "Want to join you."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tim Swensen writes:<br>
<p>
[...]<br>
Relating to the present debate (certain independent ministries), what do we<br>
expect our leaders to do when organizations openly ask for tithe, imply that<br>
large numbers of our pastors are spiritually poisoning the flock from the<br>
pulpit, (I'm referring to Ralph Larson's article on tithe in Our Firm<br>
Foundation), and basically set themselves up as the true preservers of the<br>
original, pure SDA doctrine.  I really don't know what the best course of<br>
action is.  Does someone have a reference handy to some timely Scripture<br>
(beyond the counsels in Matthew) and EGW on this matter.  From what I am<br>
hearing on SDAnet, it sounds like the public confrontation method is not the<br>
way to proceed.<br>
[...]<br>
_______________________________________________________________________________<br>
This kind of situation has happened before.  A splinter group was preaching a <br>
different interpretation of scripture than the mainstream church held, and <br>
insisting that their interpretation was the correct one.  The church governing <br>
body had tried ordering them to stop, with no effect, and was now meeting to <br>
consider some rather drastic direct action.  You can read about it in Acts <br>
5:27-42.  I think the advice Gamaliel gave to the Sanhedrin was excellent then, <br>
and is equally applicable today.  "So in the present case I tell you, keep away <br>
from these men and let them alone; for if this plan or this undertaking is of <br>
men, it will fail; but if it is of God, you will not be able to overthrow them.  <br>
You might even be found opposing God!" [Acts 5:38,39]<br>
<p>
The mission of the SDA church is to bring the gospel, as presented in the three <br>
angels' messages, to the world.  The church leadership should spend their energy <br>
on that mission, and these other problems will take care of themselves.  If the <br>
assessment stated in the Review is correct, these groups will fade away.  But if <br>
a mistake has been made, then all the position papers and attacks that can be <br>
made will not prevail.<br>
<p>
(By the way, several months ago a similar insert appeared in the Southwestern <br>
Union Record.  It was written by the Conference President, and in my opinion the <br>
tone was such that it had no business appearing in any publication that claimed <br>
to be Christian.  I read the article while visiting in Texas, but I didn't keep <br>
it and can't provide a reference.)<br>
<p>
We get _Our Firm Foundation_ and it is in general a fine magazine.  I don't <br>
necessarily agree with all points, but the articles on church history, doctines, <br>
and EGW reprints are mostly excellent.  (I skip Ron Spear's editorials.)  On the <br>
other hand, I've seen some of John Osborne's tapes, and they're definitely not <br>
constructive.  <br>
<p>
I think the church leadership is harming themselves by their efforts to silence <br>
critics.  In most cases disfellowshipping and loss of ministerial credentials is <br>
based on refusal to submit to church authority, rather than on doctrinal or <br>
theological differences.  Yet the "dissidents" base their insubordination on <br>
theological reasons.  These issues should be thoroughly examined before further <br>
action is taken, like was done with Ford.  After all, Adventists take the Bible <br>
as the ultimate authority, not pronouncements from the church hierarchy.  (At <br>
least they used to.)<br>
<p>
Sorry I got a little carried away here.  You might guess that it's been a matter <br>
of some discussion at our house.  While I don't believe that the "Celebration" <br>
worship style is bad, or that I'm being hypnotized on Sabbath morning by a <br>
pastor trained in "neurolinguistic programming", I think at times style may be <br>
emphasized at the expense of substance and specialized techniques at the expense <br>
of presenting the gospel.  Neither side is entirely right or entirely wrong, and <br>
I try to keep my focus on Jesus rather than joining the fight on one side or the <br>
other.<br>
<p>
Andy Arkusinski<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
