<title>Dec_1992: Handling Divisive Issues Within the Church</title>
<h1>Handling Divisive Issues Within the Church</h1>
<i>ronswen@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Mon, 07 Dec 92 05:30:36 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#55">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#55">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#55">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#55">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0056.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Church leadership"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Tim Swensen: "ADRA"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have read with interest the many comments about independent ministries<br>
posted to SDAnet.  I admit ignorance about much of the goals and platforms of<br>
the dissident groups but I am no stranger to conflict within our Church<br>
family, having come of age during the time of Walter Rea, Desmond Ford and<br>
the Davenport scandal.   The apostles faced instances of dissention and error<br>
in the New Testament and I believe their experiences can help us today.<br>
<p>
First, with regard to the question of whether there is only one source of<br>
truth here on earth, the Bible is clear.  Only Christ can offer salvation ("I<br>
am the gate; whoever enters through me will be saved" John 10:9).  However,<br>
no man or system can control God's grace because it is free gift to all who<br>
place their trust in Him ("Therefore, since we have been justified through<br>
faith, we have peace with God through our Lord Jesus Christ, through whom we<br>
have gained access by faith into this grace in which we now stand.  And we<br>
rejoice in the hope of the glory of God." Rom 5:1-2). <br>
<p>
 Paul faced the problem of believers misplacing their allegences to the<br>
messengers rather than to the gospel message.  This is described in 1 Cor. 3<br>
where he says: "For since there is jealousy and quareling among you, are you<br>
not worldly?  Are your not acting like mere men?  For when one says, 'I<br>
follow Paul,' and another 'I follow Apollos,' are your not mere men?  What,<br>
after all is Apollos?  And what is Paul?  Only servants, through whom you<br>
came to believe-as the Lord has assigned to each his task.  I planted the<br>
seed, Apollos watered it, but God made it grow." ... "By the grace God has<br>
given me, I laid a foundation as an expert builder, and someone else is<br>
building on it.  But each one should be careful how he builds.  For no one<br>
can lay any foundation other than the one already laid, which is Jesus<br>
Christ.  If any man builds on this foundation using gold, silver, costly<br>
stones, wood, hay or straw, his work will be shown for what it is because the<br>
Day will bring it to light. (1 Cor. 3:3-6, 10-13).  Paul was a "slave of<br>
Christ" and gave him both the glory and the control of His message.<br>
<p>
This is not to suggest that the apostles did not correct one another.  Quite<br>
the contrary.  Consider the public correction administered to Peter by Paul<br>
on the issue of associating with gentiles: "When Peter came to Antioch, I<br>
opposed him to his face because he was clearly in the wrong.  Before certain<br>
men came from James, he used to eat with the gentiles.  But when they<br>
arrived, he began to draw back and separate himself from the gentiles...The<br>
other Jews joined him in his hypocrisy, so that by their hypocracy even<br>
Barnabas was led astray.  When I saw that they were not acting in line with<br>
the truth of the gospel, I said to Peter in front of them all, 'You are a<br>
Jew, yet you live like a gentile and not like a Jew.  How is it, than, that<br>
you force gentiles to follow Jewish customs?"  Gal 2:11-14.  Peter, also a<br>
loyal slave of Christ, accepted Paul's counsel even though it was<br>
administered in a public and probably humiliating fashion.  This is not<br>
seemingly the case with all teachers as is described in 1Tim.1.  Here Paul is<br>
instructing the believers to<br>
 "command certain men not to teach false doctrines any longer nor to devote<br>
themselves to myths and endless genealogies.  These promote controversies<br>
rather than God's work-which is by faith.  The goal of this command is love,<br>
which comes from a pure heart and a good conscience and a sincere faith. <br>
Some have wandered away from these and turned to meaningless talk.  They want<br>
to be teachers of the law, but they do not know what they are talking about<br>
or what they so confidently affirm"  and he states that the criteria for<br>
determining fitness for teaching is if the teaching "conforms to the glorious<br>
gospel" (1Tim.1:3-7,11)<br>
<p>
I would draw the following conclusions based upon these examples from the<br>
apostolic church.<br>
 1.  Since salvation is a free gift from God through Christ, we must not fall<br>
into another of the traps the Galations fell into, namely being more<br>
concerned about the messenger and subtle nuances of the message than about<br>
the transforming power of the grace of Christ.  Paul called himself a slave<br>
of Christ.  Perhaps we Seventh-day Adventists, both individually and as a<br>
church, would not suffer from such division if we all considered ourselves<br>
slaves of Christ and allowed our Master to fight his own battles.  (I am<br>
writing to myself as much to any reader or Church leader.)<br>
<p>
2.  When the goal is the teaching of "the glorious gospel", different<br>
messengers or groups will not conflict and when strains arise they are<br>
settled by appealing to the authority of the cross.  Spiritual pride will<br>
paralyze any progress toward spreading the gospel as we self-destruct in a<br>
paroxsym of hypocracy.  Unfortunately, our leadership nurtures this problem<br>
on occasion as do the leaders of the many of the antagonistic independent<br>
ministries.  To be honest, I have found it in my own heart at times.  We all<br>
need to appeal to the authority of the cross.  Now is not the time to allow<br>
the message of salvation by faith in Christ to be sidetracked by a modern<br>
version of the argument about the identities of the 10 horns in Daniel as<br>
happened in 1888.<br>
<p>
3.  Financial support through tithe paying is not addressed in these stories,<br>
but I would recommend that the Church focus on spreading the gospel and God<br>
will handle the financial details.  As Gamaliel wisely noted, movements which<br>
are of God flourish, the rest fade away and those independent ministries that<br>
are currently sapping the financial strenght of the church are a small amount<br>
of funds compared to the larger number of believers who have drifted away<br>
during our years of self-destructive paralysis.<br>
  <br>
Thank you for reading, this post got a little out of hand!<br>
Ron Swensen(Ron Swen@AOL.com)   <br>
<p>
3. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
