<title>Dec_1992: Baptism vows (Re: The ten plus two commandments)</title>
<h1>Baptism vows (Re: The ten plus two commandments)</h1>
Drew (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  9 Dec 1992 11:54:06 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">alan dare: "Re:  Baptism vows (Re: The ten plus two commandments)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Steven Timm: "Exam on Friday Night"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0063.html">alan dare: "Re:  Baptism vows (Re: The ten plus two commandments)"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Beng Tang writes:<br>
<i>&gt; Should baptism really be complicated by so many vows? One would think</i><br>
<i>&gt; that if a person has accepted Christ, he would have the Holy Spirit</i><br>
<i>&gt; and the bible to guide him in deciding what is right and wrong. I mean,</i><br>
<i>&gt; when Jesus or anyone else in the bible was baptised, did they have to</i><br>
<i>&gt; swear never to walk more than a mile on Sabbath or to always wash their</i><br>
<i>&gt; hands before eating? What is baptism all about anyway?</i><br>
<p>
I am inclined to agree with you here. I did not realise that there was a<br>
specific list of things an intending SDA committed themselves to (eg not <br>
smoking, and the other things someone else listed) before baptism.<br>
<p>
In the WCoG the procedure is less involved. (The following is from memory and<br>
is probably incomplete concerning the wording.)<br>
<p>
Minister: "&lt;Full name&gt; have you repented of your sins?"<br>
Person:   "Yes."<br>
Minister: "Do you accept Jesus Christ the as your Lord and Master, your<br>
           High Priest in heaven, and your soon coming King, and have you<br>
           accepted his sacrifice as atonement for your sins?"<br>
Person:   "Yes."<br>
Minister: "As you have done these things, then with the authority invested<br>
           in me as a minister of Jesus Christ, I hereby baptise you into<br>
           the name of the Father, and of the Son, and of the Holy Spirit."<br>
<p>
The person is then totally immersed in the water (sea, river, pool, bathtub!)<br>
wherever they might be. After coming up out of the water, the minister and the<br>
person kneel and the minister lays hands on the person's head and asks God in<br>
prayer to give the gift of the Holy Spirit the the person.<br>
<p>
Leading up to baptism the personal is counselled about the depth of the<br>
committment baptism entails, what keeping the commandments of God means, <br>
and so forth. But no documents are signed and no baptism certificate is<br>
issued.<br>
<p>
Given my background, I am intrigued at the steps involved when an SDA is<br>
baptised.<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<p>
[As I was saying earlier in my post, these vows are not universally <br>
followed anymore, and I was wondering how widespread from the <br>
regular formula the deviations actually are.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
