<title>Dec_1992: Discussion on what is necessary for baptism</title>
<h1>Discussion on what is necessary for baptism</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 13 Dec 1992 12:55:14 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#84">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#84">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#84">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#84">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Lola: "baptismal vows"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Chewing gum"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0091.html">Preacher: "Re: Discussion on what is necessary for baptism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The discussion on baptism is bringing out the point I had hoped it would,<br>
namely this.<br>
<p>
All sins are equal in the eyes of God, but not necessarily in the<br>
eyes of the church.<br>
<p>
God says:  "Don't sin"<br>
<p>
The church says "Don't get caught."<br>
<p>
Thus those things which SDA lifestyle terms "sin" and must be foregone<br>
before baptism are those of a nature where it is a continuing and<br>
visible mark of not being in harmony with the standards of the church.<br>
<p>
Now, believe it or not, there is actually Biblical justification for this<br>
type of view.  Does anyone know where it is?  (Hint, somewhere in <br>
1 Corinthians).<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
