<title>Dec_1992: baptismal vows</title>
<h1>baptismal vows</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>11 Dec 1992 16:08:48 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#85">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#85">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#85">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#85">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0086.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Chewing gum may be important to the chewer"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Steven Timm: "Discussion on what is necessary for baptism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I continue to be amazed at what some of our dear ministers and members<br>
believe is necessary in order to be baptized!  Somewhere along the way<br>
we've drifted from the biblical baptism into Christ based solely on<br>
your belief in Him and His saving grace -- now we have baptism into<br>
the church, based on your acceptance of a variety of doctrines and<br>
minutia that may have nothing to do with saving grace at all.<br>
<p>
I was baptized in the 60' (way before the 27 fundamental beliefs) and<br>
if I were to go up for rebaptism today I'm afraid I would be rejected<br>
as unsuitable!  Yet I have been and am an active member for all those<br>
years.  Here in our little church we had a man who wished for baptism<br>
after attending a series of meetings and for some unknown reason the<br>
pastor put him off, saying we have no baptismal tank in our church<br>
and so he should wait (makes no sense -- we're surrounded by other<br>
churches that have tanks, like the Baptists).  This man was so<br>
convicted that he went down to the local lake and baptized himself!<br>
I'll admit, that shows perhaps a bit of a misunderstanding of the<br>
whole baptism issue, but the strength of his conviction is what<br>
impressed me.  And the conviction was strong enough that he stuck it<br>
out and kept coming to church and was finally "officially" baptized<br>
about 6 months later at another series of meetings that had a portable<br>
tank.  At his official baptism, some dear old brother came up to this<br>
man's lady friend (who had been attending wi"th him regularly) and told<br>
her that if she didn't get baptized she would never be able to marry<br>
her friend!  Needless to say she was insulted, but she has stuck<br>
it out also and continues to attend, perhaps because the brother who<br>
insulted her attends church in another town.  Sometimes I wonder why<br>
God doesn't just skip us people and depend on the rocks crying out....<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
