<title>Dec_1992: Re:  Thanks for all</title>
<h1>Re:  Thanks for all</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Dec 92 20:14:09 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: Thanks for all"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Chew Gum (Chiclets) in the Church..."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0082.html">umpark@ccu.umanitoba.ca: "Thanks for all"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0089.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: Thanks for all"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Well I am glad for you. Praise God!<br>
	I live in a country which works a 6 and a half day week (Monday to<br>
noon on Sabbath) so Sabbath problems are not new to me either. I have<br>
frequently had to see teachers and heads of department about tests or<br>
exams on Sabbath. Thankfully, they have always so far let me take it on a<br>
different day. Now in the university, I miss 4 hours of lectures every week<br>
because they are on Sabbath, but have so far not had a test fall on Sabbath.<br>
I know of people who have failed exams because they didn't go for them when<br>
they fell on Sabbath. <br>
	Earlier this year, when I was still in the army, my Officer Commanding<br>
threatened to have me court-marshalled for insubordination when I would not<br>
do a physical fitness test on Sabbath. That had me really worried, but, and<br>
I thank God for this, he finally arranged for me to take the test on another<br>
date.<br>
	We may have trying times sometimes, on account of our beliefs, but<br>
I'm sure I for one, have not so far faced the trials others have had to.<br>
There are tales of Christians being killed because of their faith, the<br>
3 Hebrews in Babylonian exile went through the fiery furnace, and millions<br>
were murdered during the dark ages. Even today in some countries, Christians<br>
face death if they profess their beliefs. Furthermore, prophecy says that<br>
more trying times are ahead, a time of trouble such as never was since there<br>
was a nation, so I guess our little trials might in some way, prepare us<br>
for what lies ahead. One good thing aout problems is that it reminds you how<br>
much you need God and it strengthens your faith.<br>
	Well, once again, I'll say I am really happy that you got to take your<br>
test on Friday instead. May God bless you.<br>
						Beng Tang, Singapore.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
