<i>&gt;I have tried this before and it has not worked.  Lets see if it works</i><br>
<i>&gt;now.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;All sin is the same in the eyes of God.  This includes going sixty in a</i><br>
<i>&gt;fifty-five mph area.</i><br>
 <br>
I've alway's understood 'sin' to be 'transgression of the law', God's Law.<br>
This statement seems to equate speed limits on the same level as the<br>
Ten Commandments.  Speed limits are most often reasonable, and argueably<br>
should be respected,  but I wouldn't call breaking them 'a sin'.  If a<br>
government law requires Sabbath-breaking, it wouldn't be 'a sin' to disregard<br>
that law would it ?  The point is that not all of man's laws are God's and<br>
in a secular society, vis-versa.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;What I get a kick out of are the churchs ban on the selling of tobacco</i><br>
<i>&gt;but not on the selling of pork.</i><br>
<p>
Pork at least has some nutritional value, where the same can't be said for<br>
tobacco.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
