<title>Dec_1992: Stephen Hawking and SDA's</title>
<h1>Stephen Hawking and SDA's</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 17 Dec 1992 12:46:44 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#96">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#96">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#96">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#96">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0097.html">Raylene: "Positive effects of tithe loss &amp; recession to the Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0095.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Discussion on what is necessary for baptism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On last night, the final night of my stay in Berkeley, I attended a <br>
public lecture by Stephen Hawking, the British cosmologist of _Brief <br>
History Of Time_ fame.  In his public lectures and books he is very <br>
simple, straightforward, and accessible, partly because his computer<br>
voice system forces him to be.  (As a result I didn't personally learn<br>
anything I didn't already know.)  <br>
<p>
He was talking about "The Future Of The Universe", and used as an<br>
introduction some examples about predictions in general and the end of<br>
the world in specific.  He used the example of William Miller, whom <br>
he incorrectly labeled as the founder of the SDA church.  But he then <br>
correctly gave the reason that Seventh-day Adventists (and not Miller)<br>
used when Oct. 22, 1844 did not result in the coming of Christ.  Namely<br>
that we say that God is judging all those whose names are in the book <br>
of life.<br>
<p>
He then compared his own prediction of the end of the universe in ten billion<br>
years or so, and noted that he had the advantage that he would not be around<br>
to be scorned if it were found to be wrong.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
