<title>Dec_1992: Talking heads</title>
<h1>Talking heads</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 20 Dec 1992 21:52:38 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#98">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#98">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#98">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#98">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Steven Timm: "Financial status and mixed blessings"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0097.html">Raylene: "Positive effects of tithe loss &amp; recession to the Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0101.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Talking heads"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It was remarked by someone on this net (not me) that one of the first<br>
hallmarks of a self-absorbed church is long and protracted calls for the<br>
offering.  Lately it has become a sport in my church to wax long and<br>
eloquent, each elder in turn trying to outdo the other in finding a new<br>
twist to put on the offering call.  <br>
<p>
When hearing the long description the past Sabbath about why our church<br>
really needs a renovated office to the tune of $8000, it reminded me of<br>
a fundraising pitch on public radio  (Give today, or give next week, or <br>
pay in installments, or...) I almost expected that "Dial 621-6900" would<br>
be next.  I don't respond to public radio fundraisers even when they're<br>
on <br>
public radio--why must I be assaulted with one in my own church?<br>
<p>
[Editor's note:  we plan to give one of the offertory callers equal time<br>
if he so desires.  No personal attack is intended.  SCT]<br>
<p>
For fairness, I should also note that these extended offering calls are<br>
effective and giving is quite on the rise in our local church.<br>
<p>
The long offering call is only part of several long segments of talk in<br>
the worship service.  I measured 24 minutes of talk in the 75 minute<br>
service,<br>
not including the sermon, in a different week.  Most of this talk is not<br>
readings or worship-related.  This represent times when the audience is<br>
sitting and not participating in the worship service.  I think we can do<br>
better.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
