<!-- body="start" -->
After the last couple "Bah, Humbug" messages I sent out, I would like <br>
to send the greetings for the season.  Though I am sometimes critical or<br>
sarcastic, I cannot be pessimistic when I see the glow in the eyes of a<br>
child who is hearing the Christmas story for the first time.  We can be<br>
assured that our future is as bright as we are willing to let God make<br>
it.<br>
<p>
As Joseph and Mary were homeless in Bible times, so "Joe" of recent net<br>
conversation is homeless today, sleeping in an abandoned building without<br>
heat, light, or water.  Until he realizes that he holds the keys to his<br>
own destiny and the Lord helps him take control of his life, he'll<br>
probably stay that way.  Fortunately nobody at Shadyside had the gall to<br>
kick him out of the church during the Christmas season.  He gave this<br>
greeting to me, and I <br>
pass it on as his wish and mine  "God bless us, every one."<br>
<p>
Merry Christmas and thanks for all your support.  The next SDAnet messages<br>
will come on Jan. 1.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
