<title>Dec_1992: What's WRONG with ...? rhetoric.</title>
<h1>What's WRONG with ...? rhetoric.</h1>
Raylene (<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>23 Dec 1992 12:11:48 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#102">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#102">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#102">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#102">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Raylene: "What's WRONG with ...? rhetoric."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0101.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re:  Talking heads"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve, <br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The question "Does chewing gum have anything to do with one's salvation?"</i><br>
<i>&gt;is misplaced at best.  Contained within it is that only matters which have </i><br>
<i>&gt;to do with salvation are important to Christianity, and that if it </i><br>
<i>&gt;doesn't affect one's salvation, then it must be OK...</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;The question "What's wrong with...?" is always rhetorical and always</i><br>
<i>&gt;expects the answer "Nothing."  Only when veterans of the church answer</i><br>
<i>&gt;that question for people do we get into trouble.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;If we are worried more about God catching us for something we do than</i><br>
<i>&gt;what the actual effect of that action is on ourselves and others, then </i><br>
<i>&gt;we have a problem...</i><br>
<p>
When we are children, we quickly learn the question "What's wrong with...?"<br>
  "What's wrong with playing that game on Sabbath mum?"<br>
  "What's wrong with eating between meals anyway?"<br>
Some of these answers are obviously more easy to explain than others. The<br>
reality of the situation, however, is that we learned to ask the wrong<br>
question.<br>
<p>
There are a lot of things in life that aren't especially *wrong* but that<br>
don't benefit ourselves or anyone else - they aren't especially *right*.<br>
What I suggest is that the question we should be asking is "What's RIGHT<br>
with ...?" When asking that question, a whole range of better alternatives<br>
present themselves and it becomes more likely that one would follow the<br>
spirit of the law rather than the letter of it.<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
---*---<br>
<p>
ps. A happy Christmas and New Year to all SDAnetters!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
