<title>Feb_1992: Subject: Re: EGW and perfection.</title>
<h1>Subject: Re: EGW and perfection.</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>12 Feb 92 14:25:04 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#105">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#105">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#105">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#105">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0106.html">Steven Timm: "Personal / Private email.."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0104.html">Eric: "Anyone want a job--low pay, lots of satisfaction...."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0101.html">Steven Timm: "Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben I fear you are not giving a balanced view of EGW. Ellen also like<br>
we should, progressed in her christian experience. We many times credit<br>
Waggoner and Jones with giving us the message of Righteousness by Faith<br>
to the Advent believers in 1888. This is true but it was Ellen that<br>
"picked up the ball" of Righteousness By Faith and ran with it. <br>
<p>
Previously she had held the 10 commandments as the primary thing after<br>
1888 the cross of Christ and him crucified was primary and the<br>
commandments were a side issue. There are 2 paintings one depicts her<br>
views in the beginning -- 1800s -- where the 10 commandments were<br>
center stage. After she learned about Righteousness by Faith the<br>
painting was changed to reflect her thinking -- and a picture of Christ<br>
on the cross was center stage and the commandments were I believe in<br>
the left side and much smaller in size. All this communicated her new<br>
thinking of salvation. I believe I can get a copy of the pictures for<br>
you.<br>
<p>
For instance here is one quote from EGW:<br>
<p>
"We must seek to redeem the neglect of the past. We must come up from<br>
the lowlands of earth. We must not preach any more Christless sermons, <br>
or any long Christless lives." RH, July 16, 1889.<br>
<p>
Adventism was cold and formal because its laity was bombarded with<br>
"Christless sermons" that had guided the ministerial perspective.<br>
<p>
EGW again: "We may commit the keeping our souls to God as unto a<br>
faithful creator, not because we are SINLESS, but because Jesus died to<br>
save just such erring, faulty creatures as we ARE, thus expressing his<br>
estimatre of the value of the human soul. We may rest upon God, not<br>
because of our own merit, but because the righteousness of Christ will<br>
be imputed to us. We must look away from self to the spotless Lamb of<br>
God, who did no sin; and by looking to Him in living faith, we shall<br>
become like him." --"Effectual Prayer" Nov. 10,  Remarks to Ministers<br>
at 1883 General Conference.<br>
<p>
EGW: "Righteousness is obedience to the law. The law demands<br>
righteousness, and this the SINNER owes to the law; BUT HE IS INCAPABLE<br>
OF REMDERING IT. The only way in which he can attain to righteousness<br>
is through faith. By faith he can bring to God the merits of Christ, <br>
and the Lord places the obedience of His son to the sinner's account. <br>
Christ's rightewouness is accepted in place of man's failure, and God<br>
receives, pardons, justifies, the repentant believing soul, treats him<br>
as though he were rightwous and loves him as He loves His son. This is<br>
how faith is accounted righteousness."  EGW RH, Nov. 4, 1890<br>
<p>
Ellen White fully understood Justification. In 1889 Mrs. White drew<br>
from the illustration of jacob's ladder to illustrate the relationship<br>
between justification and sanctification. She told the beleivers at the<br>
Chicago campmeeting that Christ "IS YOUR PERFECTION." She went on to<br>
say that we could not "scale the battlements of heaven were it not for<br>
the fact that Christ is the ladder." Without Christ as the ladder or<br>
mediator, to continually make our efforts acceptable, we would be<br>
unable to ascend one inch toward heaven, through our most sanctified<br>
efforts. This is what she said:<br>
<p>
"While you appreciate the love of God, you will have living faith. You<br>
must climb up by Christ; he is the ladder. We could not scale the<br>
battlements of heaven were it not for th fact that Christ is the<br>
ladder. The base of the ladder rests upon the earth, and the top<br>
reaches into the higest heavens. The base of this divine ladder touches<br>
the earth. If it had stopped one inch sort of that, humanity could have<br>
never reached the first round; but it is the goodness of God that<br>
leadeth you to repentance, and the grace and mercy of God shines down <br>
on every round, for God is above the ladder. It's topmost round reaches<br>
into the heaven of heavens. The light of God's love brightens the whole<br>
length of the ladder, and every step upward is a step toward Him." <br>
--"Christ's Burden Is Light" sermon at Chicago April 6, 1889<br>
<p>
&lt;&lt;Paul&gt;&gt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
