<title>Feb_1992: Re: EGW and perfection.</title>
<h1>Re: EGW and perfection.</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 Feb 1992 11:00:24 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#101">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#101">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#101">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#101">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0102.html">Christine: "Re: New networkers list"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0100.html">Steven Timm: "How Adventists Can Stop Growing"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0074.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "EGW and perfection."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0078.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Subject: Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
----------------------<br>
A statement from Ruben Gonzalez<br>
<p>
	Upon consideration of the direction of this discussion with Paul<br>
regarding perfection and the nature of personal remarks<br>
which I find are unjustified, I publically announce my withdrawl from<br>
any further discussion of this topic in public on this net for the present<br>
time. I will be happy to continue the discussion personally via private email<br>
with any interested parties.<br>
<p>
Hoping in this way not to give any offensive to any nor to be a stumbling<br>
block to any, nor wishing to violate the charter of this Net.<br>
I believe what I have already posted on this matter being <br>
enough evidence of my position.<br>
<p>
I believe withdrawing is the best policy, and can not see further<br>
benefit in continuing. I do this in all sincerety and in full confidence<br>
in the position I have presented before you regarding the matter in question.<br>
<p>
However since some have gotten the incorrect idea that I make sinlessness<br>
a prerequisite for salvation. I would state that this is something I have <br>
niether said nor implied. This opinion is founded purely upon the forceful<br>
nature of EGW's statements who not only tells us of the possibility<br>
but the importance of attaining. I know that I am the furthest from attaining<br>
however I trust in the Lord who is mighty to save. I let you all judge<br>
for yourselves the truth based on the texts I have previously provided.<br>
<p>
I would further say that I have never intentially taken any scripture<br>
nor statement from EGW out of context. I believe they speak quite<br>
well for themselves and do not need my assistance. Sometimes however<br>
these statments need to be brought out into the open for people to see<br>
and evaluate for themselves.<br>
<p>
If in any way I have been uncourtious or demonstated an unchristian attitude<br>
to any involved in this discussion I submit my most humble apology. <br>
<p>
Sincerely,<br>
Ruben.<br>
<p>
[I thank Ruben for this graciousness.  When debates start getting personal<br>
it's hard to know where to cut them off.  This marks only the fourth or <br>
fifth post I have rejected in the history of SDAnet.  It follows<br>
that any arguments of that nature from the other side will be cut.<br>
When any discussion on perfection resumes, I want the inspired writings<br>
to be used neither as a means of attack nor as a target of attack.<br>
SDAnet is not in place to foster old-style doctrinal debates which have <br>
plagued Adventism for years.  We are here to foster real communication<br>
and understanding.  Some of that happened in the perfection thread, <br>
unfortunately not enough.  If your  post begins with the name of some<br>
person, it should probably be addressed to that person privately, and<br>
if you don't know how to do that, I can tell you.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
----------------<br>
