<!-- name="Ruben Gonzalez" -->
<!-- email="ruben@ee.uts.edu.au" -->
<!-- subject="Subject: Re: EGW and perfection." -->
<!-- id="9202100013.AA05655@europa.ee.uts.edu.au" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Re: EGW and perfection." -->
<title>Feb_1992: Subject: Re: EGW and perfection.</title>
<h1>Subject: Re: EGW and perfection.</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 10 Feb 92 11:13:43 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#78">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#78">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#78">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#78">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Paul Gates: "Pastors, etc."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Russell Grau: "Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0101.html">Steven Timm: "Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0085.html">Patricio Navia: "Re: Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl Berthelsen writes :<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;You have found quite a collection to "prove" that perfection (cease to</i><br>
<i>&gt;sin) is not only possible but perhaps even "required".  This theory is</i><br>
<i>&gt;probably sound. </i><br>
<p>
Well my intention was not to "prove" anything other than to<br>
indicate EGW's position on the perfection question, considering<br>
Paul indication that she taught the opposite. When I "prove" any doctrine<br>
I do so purely from the bible which also teaches the same.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;But we don't have a single instance in humanity where</i><br>
<i>&gt;perfection was ever attained.  Jesus may be an example.  However, he</i><br>
<i>&gt;never sinned PERIOD, so how could he cease to sin. </i><br>
<p>
The bible clearly sets before us 3 people whom it says attined perfection,<br>
Noah, Job and Daniel by association (in Eze). Further more we are<br>
told of 2 who were translated to heaven without seeing death<br>
Enoch and Elijah (EGW tells us they had attained it). Now the wages<br>
of sin is death so that if they did not die it is because they had<br>
overcome all sin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;None the great</i><br>
<i>&gt;apostles and NT Bible writers claimed to have reached perfection.  Even</i><br>
<i>&gt;EGW herself never claimed such.  </i><br>
<p>
EGW teaches us that those who are closest to attaining, will consider <br>
themselves the most unworthy and the furthest from attaining. Because<br>
they will see God's own absolute perfection in clearer light and realise<br>
how far away they are from God's absolute perfection. So that the person who<br>
truely is perfect will never consider themselves to be thus and if they<br>
do it is because they have not attained anything but self-righteousness. <br>
So what we have here is a hypothetical<br>
possibility but extremely improbable.  Particularly if those who seemed<br>
to live on a higher spiritual plane than most could not attain it.  So,<br>
it is essentially a moot point.  Whether or not perfection is attained<br>
does not seemed to be the acid test of whether we are saved.  So why<br>
worry about?  I think that the day I start feeling like I've attained<br>
perfection, I'm in serious trouble with self-righteous pride.<br>
<p>
"He he has the most knowledge, knows how little knowledge he really has."<br>
<p>
Let us see what Paul says about himself in Phil 3:12-15<br>
<p>
"Not as though I has already attained either were already perfect but I follow <br>
after if that I may apprehend that for which also I am apprehended of Christ<br>
Jesus. Bretheren I COUNT NOT MYSELF TO HAVE APPPREHENDED: but this one thing I <br>
do, forgetting those things wich are behind, and reaching forth unto those <br>
things which are before, I press toward the mark for the prize of the high <br>
calling of God in Christ Jesus. LET US THEREFORE AS MANY AS BE PERFECT, be <br>
thus minded..."<br>
<p>
<p>
Now listen to what Paul says, first he says he isn't perfect, but he<br>
strives to be. Then he tells us that this is the way he considers himself to<br>
be, so that he may already be perfect but considers not to have attained.<br>
That this is in fact what he means is borne out by the last sentence in<br>
which he tells all those who are already perfect to consider themselves<br>
not to have attained as he himself does but to strive further.<br>
<p>
God is the only one who can judge perfection as He is the only one<br>
who knows the motives and the heart. So that of course we will<br>
never expect to say anyone truely perfect to claim that they are<br>
because that would mean that they would be taking upon themselves<br>
God's perogative of Judging. The bible teaches us to judge not<br>
because our judgement is faulty not only with respect to our judgements<br>
of others but also with respect to our own condition.<br>
<p>
"The heart is deceitful above all things and who can know it" Prov 13<br>
"Judge not, lest ye be judged"<br>
"Let the man who thinketh he walketh take heed lest he fall."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;So what we have here is a hypothetical</i><br>
<i>&gt;possibility but extremely improbable.  Particularly if those who seemed</i><br>
<i>&gt;to live on a higher spiritual plane than most could not attain it.  So,</i><br>
<i>&gt;it is essentially a moot point. </i><br>
<p>
<p>
This however is your opinion not supported neither by EGW nor the bible.<br>
<p>
1 John 2:1 "My little children, these things I write unto you, that ye sin not.<br>
            And if any man sin we have an advocate with the Father, <br>
            Jesus Christ the righteous." <br>
<p>
2 Tim 3:16 All scripture is given by inspiration of God, and is profitable for<br>
           doctrine, for reproof, for correction, for instruction in<br>
           righteousness: (KJV)<br>
2 Tim 3:17 That the man of God may be perfect, throughly furnished unto all<br>
           good works. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Phil 4:13 I can do all things through Christ which strengtheneth me. (KJV)<br>
<p>
1 Thes 5:23 And the very God of peace sanctify you wholly; and I pray God your<br>
            whole spirit and soul and body be preserved blameless unto the<br>
            coming of our Lord Jesus Christ. (KJV)<br>
           every thought to the obedience of Christ; (KJV)<br>
<p>
Gal 5:16 This I say then, Walk in the Spirit, and ye shall not fulfil the lust<br>
         of the flesh. (KJV)<br>
<p>
<p>
Rom 8:3 For what the law could not do, in that it was weak through the flesh,<br>
        God sending his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh, and for sin,<br>
        condemned sin in the flesh: (KJV)<br>
Rom 8:4 That the righteousness of the law might be fulfilled in us, who walk<br>
        not after the flesh, but after the Spirit. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Heb 6:1 Therefore leaving the principles of the doctrine of Christ, let us go<br>
        on unto perfection; not laying again the foundation of repentance from<br>
        dead works, and of faith toward God, (KJV)<br>
<p>
Jude 1:24 Now unto him that is able to keep you from falling, and to present<br>
          you faultless before the presence of his glory with exceeding joy,<br>
<p>
<p>
Matt 1:21 And she shall bring forth a son, and thou shalt call his name JESUS:<br>
          for he shall save his people from their sins. (KJV)<br>
<p>
If <br>
1 Cor 10:13 There hath no temptation taken you but such as is common to man:<br>
            but God is faithful, who will not suffer you to be tempted above<br>
            that ye are able; but will with the temptation also make a way to<br>
            escape, that ye may be able to bear it. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Then God has made sure that we need not sin (which is what falling into<br>
temptation is) unless we choose to.<br>
<p>
Gal 2:20 I am crucified with Christ: nevertheless I live; yet not I, but<br>
         Christ liveth in me: and the life which I now live in the flesh I<br>
         live by the faith of the Son of God, who loved me, and gave himself<br>
         for me. (KJV)<br>
<p>
Then will Christ who lives in me, commit sin ? If I am dead and the<br>
new man (Christ) dwells in me whose works  will I do ?<br>
<p>
The bible emphatically urges us on towards perfection tells us that God<br>
is able to supply our every need.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Whether or not perfection is attained</i><br>
<i>&gt;does not seemed to be the acid test of whether we are saved.  </i><br>
<p>
the attainment of perfection is not a condition of salvation<br>
but if we are not progressing towards it, it is because we are not<br>
permitting God to work in our lives. If this is the case then we are<br>
rejecting God's transforming Spirit, and in rebellion with God will<br>
(who desires and commands us to be perfect). If this is our state<br>
then we are not saved. It like faith and works. Works do not save<br>
us but the absence of works proves that we have not been saved because<br>
we don't have genuine faith but presumption.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;So why worry about?  </i><br>
<p>
The reason is because if we are truly interested in glorifying our<br>
creator we well let Him tranform our lives in such a way that <br>
the world will see Christ in us "Christ in you, that is the hope<br>
of glory" Col 2:17<br>
<p>
When Christ is manifest in our lives then we will be true witnesses<br>
and people will be drawn to Jesus, We will then be ready to receive<br>
the latter rain and the seal of God. The loaud cry will go out to<br>
the world and Christ will come to take us home. Is this reason good enough?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I think that the day I start feeling like I've attained</i><br>
<i>&gt;perfection, I'm in serious trouble with self-righteous pride.</i><br>
<p>
Yep, I agree.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<p>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
