<!-- name="Steven Timm" -->
<!-- email="st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- subject="John Osborne" -->
<!-- id="kdcI11y00WB7Qp6Vw9@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Feb_1992: John Osborne</title>
<h1>John Osborne</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 18 Feb 1992 12:20:01 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#109">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#109">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#109">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#109">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0110.html">Steven Timm: "Vegetarian recipes"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0108.html">Kenroy: "Re: New networkers list"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
There are rumors racing around the globe that John Osborne has been<br>
caught doing some rather nasty deads.  These rumors have, for example,<br>
been getting eagerly promoted around the churches in my conference,<br>
and around the globe.<br>
<p>
Many of these rumors spring from problems related to the firing of one<br>
of John's employees, who took some of John's files with him and handed<br>
them over to the local conference.<br>
<p>
John Osborne has been able to prove to that conference that their<br>
alegations against him are false.  But the rumors persisted and even<br>
increased.  John's friend's around the world started urging him to bring<br>
a defamation of character suite against the propagators of these false<br>
rumors.  He finally has, with the result that the rumors have mostly<br>
dried up at the source, but they continue to be promoted farther out on<br>
the grape vine.<br>
<p>
While I don't happen to like some of the 'style' with which John Osborne<br>
preaches I do find a high percentage of what he has to say to be warnings<br>
worth heading.  I wish he would stick closer to simply presenting his<br>
material and quit trying to defend himself and to anticipate what the<br>
"bretherin" will do next.  And more recently he has shifted his style<br>
quite a bit.  A lot of people accuse him of distoring the truth.  But<br>
what can you say when the cameras were running.  There are times when<br>
I'm glad the video information is presented, but could pass on some of<br>
his commentary.  But that does not mean the content of what the video<br>
cameras captured on tape and audio did not happen.  If there are<br>
distortions, I find them to be at least a magnitude greater on the part<br>
of those seeking to discredit him.  Take for example videos of the<br>
Milwaukie church.  People protest that his video footage is unfair and<br>
distorting reality.  But, I have been at the home of one of their church<br>
elders watching videos of church services taken by the 'friends' of<br>
Milwaukie.  I have seen worse footage taken by those promoting the<br>
Milwaukie style than I have seen from John Osborne, trying to point<br>
out the problems.  I don't have to take someones word for it.  I've<br>
seen/heard the video footage from both sides.<br>
<p>
Dave (David E. Buxton)<br>
<p>
[Some background information:  John Osborne is the producer of an anti-<br>
celebration video that  has had rather wide circulation.  I have not seen<br>
this video, perhaps there is in fact more than one.  He is from Florida,<br>
if I mistake not.  It's difficult to know what to do about rumors<br>
on SDAnet, because now 80 people on SDAnet have heard these rumors<br>
and a seed of doubt has been planted about John Osborne's integrity. <br>
Sometimes a defensive strategy only works to spread the rumors farther.<br>
Previously I only had reason to doubt his judgment.  SDAnet is not a rumor-<br>
spreading device, we are an organization which posts the truth as we<br>
know it.  It's disturbing that those who preach "love, acceptance, and <br>
forgiveness" are forced to sink to Osborne's level to counter his arguments.<br>
The point we should keep in mind is that however repugnant or corrupt <br>
the messenger may be, we should still evaluate his message for truth <br>
contained therein.  We are not excused from getting out of the building if <br>
the fireman yells "fire" in a rude tone of voice.  On the other side, <br>
those who generate false fire alarms should not be surprised if some <br>
animosity is created.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
