<title>Feb_1992: Perfection:  How should we then live?</title>
<h1>Perfection:  How should we then live?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 13 Feb 1992 01:03:21 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#98">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#98">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#98">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#98">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Kenroy: "Re: New networkers list"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0097.html">Paul Gates: "Perfection (Goals and Objectives)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Some things that everybody should consider before posting any more rounds<br>
in the "perfection" discussion.<br>
<p>
I don't care if you have fifty pages of quotes backing up your post,<br>
either pro or con.  I hope that all of us are beyond the stage where we <br>
are using the Bible and Ellen White like so many bowling balls, trying <br>
to see how many points we can score in the debate.  But as I read some of <br>
the posts, I'm afraid that the debate is degenerating into this.  So<br>
far it seems everybody is, in good faith, using the best understanding of <br>
the Bible and EGW that they have, and I cannot fault or censor them for this.<br>
<p>
But I urge you to take the time to consider the following questions:<br>
<p>
1) Could both sides be right?  Just because the two sides claim their<br>
views are mutually exclusive doesn't mean they are.<br>
<p>
2) Could both sides be wrong?  If so, then a compromise between two<br>
wrong extremes is by definition also wrong.<br>
<p>
I think in this case both sides are right and both sides are also wrong.<br>
Furthering the war will not decide who's right, only who's left.<br>
<p>
3)  Are people trying to use "creeping inspiration" here?  <br>
"Ellen White said this, and she's inspired.  Now, I'm quoting her, so<br>
you'd better pay attention to me, too."  Be very careful about making<br>
claims about Ellen White that she did not make for herself.<br>
<p>
4)  What does it matter to the heathen Chinese?  If the arsenal of <br>
theological terms we are using in this debate were not available,<br>
how would you tell someone who was just learning about Jesus how they<br>
should live?<br>
<p>
5)  Don't all of us really want to be perfect, anyway?  Why fight it?<br>
It is, after all, our goal to reflect the image of God.  Sanctification<br>
and perfection are just as much a gift of God as salvation and justification.<br>
Why are we so reluctant to take what He offers?<br>
<p>
6)  How will whatever theory you are putting forth on perfection help <br>
you love God and others better?<br>
<p>
7)  Is this whole battle just one over definitions of terms, and everyone<br>
is just trying to come to agreement?  If so, then let's continue,<br>
we are getting somewhere.<br>
<p>
We are here to communicate, not to preach at each other.  If we keep<br>
the above things in mind, we can avoid some bruised egos and theological<br>
warning flags.  (On the other hand, some of us could stand to have egos<br>
bruised a lot more often than they are.)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
