<title>Feb_1992: Re: Subject: Re: EGW and perfection.</title>
<h1>Re: Subject: Re: EGW and perfection.</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 10 Feb 1992 11:57 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#84">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#84">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#84">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#84">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Patricio Navia: "Re: Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Testing Prophets - EGW in Vision"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben,<br>
<p>
I prefer to see the work of Christ in my life as a learning, growing<br>
experience rather than an attaining, accomplishing experience.  My<br>
approach to my graduate studies is the same.  I'd rather feel that I<br>
am learning what I need for my future career than accumulating A's.<br>
I'd wish I could think like my professor and solve problems like my<br>
professor rather than obtain just knowledge.  In other words, having<br>
a relationship with my Savior is so much more important than constantly<br>
evaluating my grade in the course we are taking on this earth.  I came<br>
up with a parable over the weekend which I believe represents what I<br>
believe is God's plan and truth.<br>
<p>
We are all enrolled in Salvation 101.  This class is *SO* important to<br>
our futures that we all must pass to take the next course in life.  At<br>
our first lecture, our professor announces that everybody in the class<br>
can pass and that there is not reason any should fail.  During each<br>
lecture he will reveal some of the questions AND the answers that<br>
will be on our final exam.  After class, we all meet for lunch to talk<br>
about this.  Some bring out the college catalog which clearly states<br>
that to pass, you must get 100% on the final.  Others say they've heard<br>
that there really never is a final exam.  We are told such so we will<br>
learn the material, but there is no final exam--ever.  Some point to<br>
statistics which show a high failure rate and in fact, this professor<br>
actually tries to see how many he can flunk.  Some of us, anxious and<br>
confused, decide to go talk with the professor and find out the facts<br>
for ourselves. As the term goes by, those who think that the final<br>
exam doesn't really exist quit coming to lecture.  Those you think<br>
that they must get 100% faithfully tape record all lectures and commit<br>
them to memory word for word.  Those of us who know we can't possibly<br>
succeed are found discussing and talking over the theory with the<br>
professor in his office after hours.  We learn from the close relationship<br>
we develop with him that he's not the ogre many have made him out to<br>
be.  He really cares about his students and will do everything he can<br>
to help them succeed.  What's important to him is that we learn what<br>
we need so we are prepared for the next course.  And if he get to know<br>
him, we will understand what is important to him.  The day of the final<br>
arrives.  Those who felt the final wasn't really going to happen, don't<br>
show up.  Those who have faithfully memorized his lectures, come<br>
confident that they can't lose.  After all, wasn't every question and<br>
every answer contained in his lectures.  The rest of us come with<br>
anxiety and doubts, but we at least know that the professor won't have<br>
any trick questions because he really cares about us.  As we leave<br>
the exam room, we realize that we had learned a great deal from the<br>
class, but not enough to pass the final with 100%.  The TA comforts<br>
us as we leave.  She says, don't worry about it.  The professor grades<br>
the exams himself. Any answers that you left blank or answered incorrectly<br>
are answered by the professor himself.  Those who really got to know<br>
will realize that he knows that you all have deficiencies.  In fact,<br>
he knows that you really do know the answers for the exam because you<br>
talked about them many times in him office.  Just because you couldn't<br>
produce them for the final, doesn't mean you aren't prepared for the<br>
next course.  We sigh with relief when we realize that we have a chance<br>
afterall.  Unfortunately, those who didn't bother to show up for the<br>
exam didn't have an exam paper for the professor to fill in for them.<br>
Those you didn't get to know the professor and didn't spend time with<br>
him, must have their papers graded based the the answers they gave<br>
on the exam alone for they had no opportunity to demonstrate that they<br>
knew the principles in outside class discussions.<br>
<p>
Cheryl Berthelsen<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
