<!-- body="start" -->
Well Ruben, you finally said it! I have been waiting! Maybe you said it<br>
before and I missed it. You said, "When Christ is manifest in your<br>
lives...." You are now getting close to the truth.<br>
<p>
I really cannot figure out why you are so hung up on this business of<br>
sinlessness and perfection. Was this my fault? Did I say something that<br>
triggered this?<br>
<p>
Check out the message I left for David Plaistad. Since I give my life<br>
over to the Holy Spirit everyday and am in tune with him, I am counting<br>
on Him to take care of perfection and sinlessness in my life. And from<br>
all indications he is doing a fabulous job! <br>
<p>
It is a waste of time to try to prove your point of perfection and<br>
sinlessness when you are just choosing the scriptures and quotations<br>
that agree with you. If I can get over to the GC I could supply you<br>
with 40 pages (no exaggeration) of quotations from EGW that would shed<br>
an entirely different light on to what you are saying. As you probably<br>
know you have got to keep EGW in context and know the basis and reason<br>
of what she is saying. You just cannot pick out a comment here and<br>
there just because it agrees with your theology.<br>
<p>
I am not denying the fact that our goal is perfection but I do not<br>
think we will reach absolute perfection till Jesus comes. I am not<br>
denying your scriptures and quotations necessarily I am just saying<br>
what you are claiming is possible by works, I am saying is possible<br>
through the working of the HS in our lives.<br>
<p>
I agree 1000 % with Cheryl's parable. Why don't you meditate on it for<br>
a few days. I believe it would be worth the time.<br>
<p>
&lt;&lt;Paul Gates&gt;&gt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
