<title>Feb_1992: Perfection (Goals and Objectives)</title>
<h1>Perfection (Goals and Objectives)</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 10 Feb 92 15:36:23 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#89">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#89">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#89">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#89">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0090.html">Paul Gates: "Great Youth Success in Chicago"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0088.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Re: EGW and perfection"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Some of you may find this usefully illustrative and some may not.<br>
<p>
A few years ago I took a several day seminar in project management.  One<br>
of the things defined was the difference between goals and objects.<br>
Here is how the seminar speaker illustrated his terms.  NASA had as its<br>
goal the exploration of outer space.  Clearly not something that could<br>
be measured as there is no way of determining when outer space has<br>
been completely explored, or adequately explored.  It takes defineable<br>
objectives, else you make no progress against your goals.  One of the<br>
objectives that NASA established was to place a man on the moon, within<br>
'x' number of months, under 'y' dollars AND bring that man back alive.<br>
Objectives are measureable.  Do we abandon our goals because they are<br>
not measureable, because they don't seem achievable?  No.  We need to<br>
identify some clear objectives in order to make our goals meaningful.<br>
<p>
That brings us to the question:  If perfection is our goal; then what<br>
should be our objectives?  If a closer relationship with Jesus is our<br>
goal, what should be our objectives?  Daniel made a habit of openly<br>
praying three times a day, and landed in the lions den.  Daniel also<br>
purposed in his heart not to indulge in the kings food.  Paul speaks<br>
of "I die daily".  Jesus clearly spent many hours in prayer and in<br>
a thorough study of the scriptures.  By beholding Him we become changed.<br>
Faith grows like a mustard seed, from tiny beginnings into something<br>
that can move mountains; clearly not something that happens over night.<br>
<p>
If the focus of our attention is on perfection, we are overwhelmed and<br>
many simply discard and discredit such a goal right out of hand.  So<br>
many don't even try.  Or perfection is pursued in many humanly peculiar<br>
ways.  But if perfection is our serious goal and so we set out to<br>
identify our objectives -- better still, to plead for the Holy Spirit<br>
to point out the defects in our characters that need to be worked on;<br>
and God's plan that we need to be responsive to.<br>
<p>
It is God who judges a man/woman perfect.  Ellen White warns that we are<br>
not the judge in such matters.  We are not to be announcing that we<br>
are 'saved', or that we are 'perfect'.  And yet perfection is to be<br>
our goal.<br>
<p>
Dave (David E. Buxton)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
