<!-- id="920212192443_70516.420_EHC49-1@CompuServe.COM" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Feb_1992: Perfection (Goals and Objectives)</title>
<h1>Perfection (Goals and Objectives)</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>12 Feb 92 14:24:43 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#97">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#97">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#97">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#97">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Steven Timm: "Perfection:  How should we then live?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Paul Gates: "Subject: Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
David, I believe there is truth is what you are saying about perfection<br>
etc. In growing up in the Adventist church I did not relate Dan. 7:10; <br>
Eccl. 12:14; Ps. 1:5 as a part of the assuring good news of the<br>
gospel. <br>
<p>
However, I discovered that David had a different feeling. He actually<br>
welcomed God to judge him. There are a number of texts to sight on this<br>
but I mention one: Ps 96:11-13 and we could sight Ps 51:3,4 as well. I<br>
believe David comprehended the terribleness of his sin and the reality<br>
of being judged by God. But he also understood the message of<br>
righteousness by faith.<br>
<p>
Scripture consistently upholds the seriousness of sin and the<br>
certainty of the judgement, however, it also reveals that the Lamb of<br>
God, our substitute, has been accepted in our place.<br>
<p>
You are on track when you say, we should allow the Holy Spirit to show<br>
us where we need to change, etc.<br>
<p>
In my study through this I had some questions when I read Christ's<br>
Object Lessons, page 155: "Those who accept the Saviour, however<br>
sincere their conversion, should never be taught to say or to feel that<br>
they are saved." What I did not understand was that in such statements<br>
EGW was refuting the erroneous belief of "once saved always saved." I<br>
thought she meant that one could never have the present assurance of<br>
salvation. How tragic that I did not see in the very same paragraph<br>
God's assurance that we can "give ourselves to Christ and know that He<br>
accepts us." And of course 1John 5:13 tells us that we may know that we<br>
have eternal life.<br>
<p>
I think I have mentioned it before that I found the same glorious<br>
revelation in the words of Ellen White:<br>
<p>
"If you give yourself to Him and accept Him as your Saviour, then, <br>
sinful as your life may have been, for His sake you are accounted<br>
righteous. Christ's character stands in place of your character, and<br>
you are accepted before God just as you had not sinned." Steps to<br>
Christ, p. 62<br>
<p>
 From my study of the Bible I have come to the conclusion that our focus<br>
should not be on perfection and sinlessness. Our focus should be on<br>
Jesus Christ and developing a relationship with Him first! Then through<br>
the Holy Spirit -- the HS will direct our lives and point out sin and<br>
weaknesses in our life. Of course we need to give the control of our<br>
lives to the Holy Spirit. Each morning when I awake, my first prayer is<br>
for the Holy Spirit to direct and take charge of my life for that day<br>
and I pray that I will be so filled with the HS that I will do and say<br>
only what he would wants me to do. My wife and I have discovered that<br>
our lives certainly go a lot better when we pray a prayer like that.<br>
<p>
Some will not agree I know with me on this next point. I understand<br>
what 1John 3:4 says that sin is the trangression of the law but sinning<br>
is just an outward syptom of an inward problem which is simply breaking<br>
off that connection with Jesus Christ through the H.S. To say it<br>
another way, sinning is an end result of breaking that contact we have<br>
with the spirit.<br>
<p>
There are 4 things we need to consider that I would be happy to discuss<br>
further. The fours things: <br>
<p>
Vision: Personal encounter with God and a clear understanding what He<br>
wants to do in and through us.<br>
<p>
Presence: This involves the integration of His presence into every area<br>
of our lives and everything that we do. If more of us realized that we<br>
really have his presence with us through the Holy Spirit there would be<br>
a lot less sinning going on and we would be more careful as to what we<br>
watch on TV or what movies we attend, as well as what we do with his<br>
holy time.<br>
<p>
Gospel: Knowing what Christ has done and is doing for us, as well as<br>
its application to how we work with ourselves and those around us. For<br>
instance if we have a good relationship with Christ through the Holy<br>
Spirit, our relationship with our wives and families are going to be<br>
better and with those about it. Simply we have a better relationship<br>
because our relationship with Christ is what it should be.<br>
<p>
When all of this finally dawned on me my relationship with my wife sky<br>
rocketed. Our relationship was always good but then it got better. <br>
Frequently daily I am telling my wife how much I love her and what a<br>
wonderful relationship we have had for 39 years. I have remarked to<br>
Evelyn, that when we got married I must not have loved her because I<br>
live her so much more now! &lt;&lt;Smile!&gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
The 4th word is Lordship: This is the willingness to submit ourselves<br>
personally and corporately to God's control in all that we are have and<br>
do.<br>
<p>
In conclusion my experience as a pastor and educator has been that in<br>
the Adventist church most problems in the church and in our lives can<br>
boil down to gospel, lordship or both. We struggle with either the<br>
integration of the gospel in our lives and ministries or with the<br>
failure to submit to Christ's lordship. And the best ansers to both of<br>
these problems are vision and presence. A vision of God and what He<br>
want to do, combined with a sense of His presence, transforms the way<br>
we live and function.<br>
<p>
A strong deterrant (spelling?) against me sinning is the fact that I<br>
know I have His presence with me. If I am tempted to have an "affair" <br>
with the girl next door during the day when my wife is working, what am<br>
I going to do with his presence? Am I going to say, "Holy Spirit, you<br>
stay here while I go next door, I know you wouldn't be comfortable<br>
tagging along with me this time." No I am not going to think it even. I<br>
do not want to break that relationship with the HS. And further more I<br>
know it would not be pleasing to Him. My whole life is bent on pleasing<br>
him incidently. <br>
<p>
How about Joseph? He said to Mrs. Potiphar, "How can I do this great<br>
sin against God? I just feel that Joseph knew what relationships were<br>
all about.<br>
<p>
Some of the rules and regulations that we Adventists have grown up with<br>
just touch the "tip of the iceberg." We should be more concerned about<br>
the principle involved than the "letter of the law." And of course Alan<br>
Thompson in his book "Inspiration" deals with this concept.<br>
<p>
Success to you and God bless,<br>
<p>
&lt;&lt;Paul Gates&gt;&gt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
