<title>Feb_1992: Subject: Re: EGW and perfection.</title>
<h1>Subject: Re: EGW and perfection.</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>12 Feb 92 14:25:30 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#96">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#96">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#96">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#96">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0097.html">Paul Gates: "Perfection (Goals and Objectives)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0095.html">Paul Gates: "Subject: Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0101.html">Steven Timm: "Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0105.html">Paul Gates: "Subject: Re: EGW and perfection."</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben: Phil 3:12-15: From the greek I would translate it this way:<br>
<p>
"I don't mean to say that I am perfect, I haven't learned all I should<br>
even yet, but I keep working toward THAT DAY when I will finally be all<br>
that Christ saved me for and wants me to be." <br>
<p>
That is the 12th verse and it is very plan to see that Paul is<br>
referring to the 2nd coming of Christ as a time of reaching<br>
perfection. Every time Paul refers to "THAT DAY" he is referring to the<br>
2nd coming.<br>
<p>
Now to continue with verse 13: "No, dear borthers, I am still not all I<br>
should be but I am bringing all my energies to bear on this one thing: <br>
Forgetting the past and looking forward to what lies ahead.<br>
<p>
v. 14: "I strain to reach the end of the race and receive the prize for<br>
which God is calling us up to heaven because of what Christ Jesus did<br>
for us."<br>
<p>
v. 15: "I hope all of you who are mature christians will see eye-to-eye<br>
with me on these things, and if you disagree on some point, I believe<br>
that God will make it plain to you  --<br>
<p>
v. 16 "if you fully obey the truth you have.<br>
<p>
Rubin, a loose translation would be, Hey guys, I'm not perfect yet, but<br>
that's my goal and I know when Christ comes I will attain it. You<br>
fellows hang in there and if you disagree with me I know the Lord will<br>
make it plain."<br>
<p>
The scripture doesn't in one tittle or iota indicate that Paul will<br>
reach perfection in this life but he along with the rest of us can<br>
strive for it and make progress in our daily walk.<br>
<p>
Paul is not saying those who are perfect or who have reached<br>
perfection, he is simply saying I want all "mature" christians to keep<br>
striving for perfection like I am and we will attain it at "that day." <br>
or at the 2nd coming.<br>
<p>
It would appear you are taking scripture out of context and making it<br>
say something that was not intended. Even the SDA commentary doesn't<br>
agree with you!<br>
<p>
A final note would be that Paul was trying refute perfectionism.  These<br>
people in Paul's day were going on the assumption that once they were<br>
baptized that they were perfect and nothing more was needed but Paul<br>
was saying, "People, even I am not perfect even though I am striving<br>
for that state, that is my goal."<br>
<p>
I've got to break for lunch.<br>
<p>
<p>
&lt;&lt;Paul&gt;&gt;<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
