<title>Feb_1992: Presidential Politics and Religious Liberty</title>
<h1>Presidential Politics and Religious Liberty</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 20 Feb 1992 00:19:23 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#111">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#111">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#111">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#111">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Presidential Politics and Religious Liberty"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0110.html">Steven Timm: "Vegetarian recipes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0112.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Presidential Politics and Religious Liberty"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
For those of you who live elsewhere than the USA, we are in the middle of <br>
a presidential campaign here.  Seventh-day Adventists have often had <br>
worries about the religious liberty views of a president.  The worries<br>
about Kennedy proved to be unfounded, and the programs such as school <br>
prayer proposed by Reagan never got off the ground.  <br>
<p>
I did not suspect that we would have candidates in the race with worse<br>
religious liberty positions than Bush, but we certainly do.  Pat<br>
Buchanan with his Jesuit education and his call "we've aided everybody<br>
else, now it's the turn of Irish Catholics" scares me.  Jerry Brown<br>
is also Jesuit-educated, though it seems he may have forgotten some<br>
of his lessons.  Tom Harkin is another Jesuit product.   <br>
<p>
[Yes, yes, I know--so are several SDA's including a Bible teacher of mine<br>
whom I love and respect for leading me to Christ.  But I'm still scared <br>
of the above people.]<br>
<p>
Probably none of the above three candidates will win.  Does anyone have<br>
any idea of the record of Tsongas, Clinton, or Kerrey?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
