<title>Feb_1992: Re: EGW and perfection</title>
<h1>Re: EGW and perfection</h1>
Daniel D Deavours (<i>ddd42961@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 10 Feb 92 18:08:44 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Dave Buxton: "Perfection (Goals and Objectives)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">David Plaisted: "Possibility of not sinning"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I prefer to see the work of Christ in my life as a learning, growing</i><br>
<i>&gt;experience rather than an attaining, accomplishing experience.  My</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;We are all enrolled in Salvation 101.  This class is *SO* important to</i><br>
<i>&gt;our futures that we all must pass to take the next course in life.</i><br>
<p>
	I've been following this thread pretty closely, and I think I<br>
finally found some time to put my $.02 worth in.  I think Ruben's<br>
statements have been very reflective of what I believe.<br>
	I have to disagree with the parable, Cheryl.  I hope you don't<br>
take anything personally, as we always seem to get on opposite sides<br>
of the debate ;-).  I'll try to be brief and hit some main points about<br>
what I think.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;our first lecture, our professor announces that everybody in the class</i><br>
<i>&gt;can pass and that there is not reason any should fail.  During each</i><br>
<i>&gt;lecture he will reveal some of the questions AND the answers that</i><br>
<i>&gt;will be on our final exam.  After class, we all meet for lunch to talk</i><br>
<p>
	Contrast Romans 5:18.  "Consequently, just as the result of one<br>
trespass was condemnation for all men, so also the result of one act of<br>
righteousness was justification that brings life for all men."  I would<br>
put the emphasis on _all men_.  I think that Jesus was the one who has<br>
already taken our final exam and passed.  The trials and temptations that<br>
come in life are not to test whether Jesus really did save us, but rather<br>
to strengthen our faith that he DID.  Reference James 1:2-4, "Consider it<br>
pure joy, my brothers, wehn you face trials... so that you may be mature<br>
and complete, not lacking in anything."  (Please correct me if I'm barking<br>
up the wrong tree here.)<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;The rest of us come with</i><br>
<i>&gt;anxiety and doubts, but we at least know that the professor won't have</i><br>
<i>&gt;any trick questions because he really cares about us.  As we leave</i><br>
<p>
	Contrast James 1:6-8.  "But when he asks, he must believe and<br>
not doubt, because he who doubts is like a wave of the sea, blown and<br>
tossed by the wind.  That man should not think he will receive anything<br>
from the Lord; he is a double-minded man, unstable in all he does."  I<br>
think that  James is saying it is a pretty serious offense to doubt God,<br>
especially about our salvation.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Just because you couldn't</i><br>
<i>&gt;produce them for the final, doesn't mean you aren't prepared for the</i><br>
<i>&gt;next course.  We sigh with relief when we realize that we have a chance</i><br>
<i>&gt;afterall.</i><br>
<p>
	I think the focus of salvation 101 has gone from faith to works.<br>
That is, _you_ are taking the final, it is _your_ holiness that gives you<br>
the right to pass the final.  Where you fail, God will just wink his eye<br>
and pretend it never happened.<br>
	I would have to rewrite the parable, personally, for it is not<br>
God who gives the exams (trials.)  His relationship to us is more than<br>
a Teacher, but more as a Father who spends all his time, energy, and most<br>
valuable rescorces to give us every advantage to pass the trials.  Even<br>
when we do do pass through trials, it is not victory by our strength and<br>
effort.  "...I no longer live, but Christ lives in me."  Gal. 2:20.<br>
<p>
	Hmm, perhaps we're talking about two different things, and I<br>
interpreted your parable incorrectly.  If so, please let me know.<br>
<p>
Dan Deavours<br>
zeos@uiuc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
