<i>&gt;&lt; Steve's concerns about Jesuit candidates</i><br>
<p>
I have two books by Malachi Martin who is an ex-Jesuit and now a<br>
prophesor at the Pontifical University.  I also have some news<br>
clippings from Canada.  It would seem that the Jesuits are no<br>
longer the "Pope's Men" as they used to be.  They have been too<br>
good at snubbing the Popes and so John Paul has been grooming<br>
a couple of groups to replace them.  Also, according to Malachi<br>
Martin the Jesuits are now much too strong on Marxist politics.<br>
One of the key candidates for a close relationship with the Papacy<br>
is the Opus Dei, often referred to as the Papal Maffia.  They do<br>
not wear clarical garb, much preferring to dress like laymen and<br>
get into a lot of trouble in Canada for their infiltrating activities.<br>
Even the pro Catholic press of Canada has at times spoken its<br>
concerns about the Opus Dei and its rough tactics.  One of their<br>
key statements of their founding father was - in my words - "Why is<br>
it that when we forcibly rescue someone from commiting suicide we get a<br>
lot of supportive aclaim, but when we forcibly rescue someone from<br>
killing his own soul we get into trouble for it?"<br>
<p>
It is much easier to identify a Jesuit or former Jesuit than the Opus Dei.<br>
<p>
Dave<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
