<title>Feb_1992: congregationalism</title>
<h1>congregationalism</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 Feb 92 12:49:20 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#118">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#118">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#118">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#118">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0119.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Congregationalism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0117.html">McCluskey G: "Southwestern Adventist College and net access"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0121.html">Paul Gates: "Re: congregationalism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I chatted last week with a good friend who is currently in New York City.<br>
He is a credentialed SDA minister from Trinidad, but has not worked for<br>
the denomination since he has been in the US (about 5 years now).  He<br>
told me about a church that he and several other Caribbean ministers<br>
started up in NYC.  They formed an independent church -- no formal<br>
affiliation with the denomination, all tithes and offerings retained in<br>
the local church (I believe).  They cared for the needy among them.  If<br>
some were out of work, then the church gave them subway money so they<br>
could go out and look for new jobs.  If families were so strapped that<br>
their kids had no allowance, then the church would give the kids a little<br>
pocket money every week.  Some families had their rent paid by the church<br>
during times of emergency; others got groceries.  Plus they saved over<br>
$100,000 toward buying a permanent meeting place.  The church grew very<br>
rapidly, and was vibrant and missionary-minded.<br>
 <br>
Recently they joined the denomination officially, mainly because of the<br>
desire to have a church building of their own.  I'm not sure of the details<br>
here, but it seems to have killed the spirit, according to my friend.  He's<br>
now firmly committed to independent ministry and congretational churches.<br>
 <br>
Any thoughts?  My first impression was that it sounded like the church after<br>
Pentecost to a degree.  Is there a limit to the need for organization?<br>
Have we grown the the point where the beauracracy is now holding us back<br>
rather than helping us move on?  (I'm suddenly unsure of how to spell<br>
bureaucracy -- I think the second attempt is better!)<br>
 <br>
With the posting of the article by the Methodist who said he could tell<br>
the church how to stop growing, I wondered whether there is a magic size<br>
of some sort.  As long as we're a small group, we keep our peculiarity and<br>
continue to grow rapidly (at least percentage-wise).  As we get larger<br>
we grow more diverse, less peculiar, and our percentage-wise growth<br>
necessarily drops.  I think the same could be said for individual<br>
congregations as well.<br>
 <br>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
