<title>Feb_1992: Re: Congregationalism</title>
<h1>Re: Congregationalism</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 Feb 1992 16:24:25 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#119">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#119">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#119">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#119">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Congregationalism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Lola: "congregationalism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Lola raised some interesting posts about congregationalism, also <br>
reminding me of a post of Dennis Grumling on this topic to which I <br>
never responded.<br>
<p>
I don't think that size and diversity are necessarily limits to growth.<br>
The fastest-growing churches in the country are the so-called<br>
"megachurches" which can have thousands of members.  What limits growth<br>
is if a congregation<br>
turns inward, develops a narrow vision, and starts getting comfortable<br>
feeling "big enough."<br>
<p>
"Local church first" is a buzzword that is becoming more popular for <br>
conference leaders to mouth.  The wishes of congregations are now<br>
being taken into account more often when hiring pastors and planning <br>
outreach activities.  <br>
<p>
I think it would be a shame to focus on the local church to the exclusion <br>
of the world church.  We are organized together, partly to spread the <br>
gospel to those areas of the world that still need to hear it.  Even <br>
foreign missions is becoming congregationalized, with congregations<br>
sponsoring individual missionaries.  It is fine to personalize it so <br>
long as we don't disorganize it in so doing.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
