<title>Feb_1992: Re: Congregationalism</title>
<h1>Re: Congregationalism</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>72450.2430@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>28 Feb 92 01:27:10 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#120">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#120">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#120">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#120">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0121.html">Paul Gates: "Re: congregationalism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0119.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Congregationalism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have been exposed to congregationalism to some degree and have decided that <br>
it is neither better or worse than our structure. The problems they have are <br>
just different than the ones we face. For instance, in congregational churches<br>
more local resources are involved in caring for the pastor: e.g. medical <br>
coverage, tax issues, salary issues, etc. Also it is more difficult for <br>
congregational churches to have an effective mission program without the aid <br>
of outside organizations.<br>
<p>
That is not to say that congregationalism is without its good points. Often <br>
there is a more personal feeling to congregational churches. Lola pointed out <br>
the results of the change in New York. I think Steve's comments hit the nail <br>
on the head. When churches join organizations they often expect the <br>
organization to fulfill their responsibilities. The problem as described by <br>
Lola is that the energy shifted from caring for the immediate needs of the <br>
local people to caring for the needs of a world of people. I am sure that <br>
resources which had previously been used to help locally were now going into <br>
the organization which can help the rest of the world.<br>
<p>
Believe me, I know that the organization absorbs a lot of money. There are <br>
probably areas where we could save money if we put our minds to it. The <br>
problem in the church, however, is not much different than the problem faced <br>
by the leaders of our country. To cut spending means to take money away from <br>
someone who believes that they need it. One person's pork barrel is another <br>
man's livelihood. <br>
<p>
The bottom line for me is that I don't believe congregationalism will save the<br>
mission of our church. I agree with Steve that putting the local church needs <br>
first to the exclusion of the world church would not be good. We will all have<br>
to bite the bullet and accept that it costs money to do things. We might have <br>
to accept that to have money for one project may mean doing away with another.<br>
I personally pastor three congregations in the San Francisco Bay Area. Some of<br>
my church members are upset by that, but in other parts of the world pastors <br>
have many more churches than that. Where are our priorities? What can we <br>
reasonably expect from the organization?<br>
<p>
Ed Fargusson, Compuserve 72450,2430<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
