<title>Feb_1992: Health Messages of 1850-1877 by nonSDA religious leaders</title>
<h1>Health Messages of 1850-1877 by nonSDA religious leaders</h1>
Cheryl Berthelsen (<i>CBERTHEL@cc.utah.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 1 Mar 1992 00:56 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#123">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#123">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#123">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#123">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0122.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Congregationalism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Some SDAs point to the health principles advocated by Ellen White as <br>
being unique and far ahead of the thinking of her time.  I would like <br>
to share some passages with you that were written by a nonSDA <br>
religious leader between 1851 and 1877.  (EGW's first health vision <br>
dates to 1860s)  He talks of the dangers of tobacco, alcohol, coffee, <br>
and tea, advocates a vegetarian diet and simplicity in diet, sleeping <br>
and living in fresh, pure air.  He evens talks of prenatal influence of <br>
alcohol and narcotics and the effect of an unbridled appetite on the <br>
spiritual, mental, and physical life.  He speaks of the need for <br>
exercise, eating well-baked bread, drinking fresh cool water, and <br>
many health principles that SDAs usually attribute to being uniquely <br>
Ellen White's.  It is probably this claim by SDAs who haven't <br>
explored the literature of her time that has lead me to personally <br>
reject the idea that "the health message" is a sign of prophetic <br>
inspiration.<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
"Satisfying the appetite brings to an end the pleasure of eating; and <br>
where food is partaken of chiefly to gratify the pleasurable sensation <br>
derived from eating, disease is engendered, and true misery springs <br>
out of this unwise gratification.  Some healthy, strong-constitutioned <br>
person can eat large quantities of food with apparent impunity; but, <br>
in so doing, the tax they place upon their systems will ultimately <br>
bring disease and death.  8:139<br>
<p>
"The constitution that a person has should be nourished and <br>
cherished; and whenever we take anything into the system to force <br>
and stimulate it beyond its natural capacity, it shortens life."  7:337<br>
<p>
"Let the mother impregnate her system with these narcotic <br>
influences when she is bringing forth a family on the earth, and what <br>
does she do?  She lays the foundation of weakness, palpitation of the <br>
heart, nervous affections, and many other ills and diseases in the <br>
system of her offspring that will afflict them from the cradle to the <br>
grave."  13:276<br>
<p>
"Mankind would not become attached to these unnecessary articles <br>
were it not for the poison they contain.  The poisonous or narcotic <br>
properties in spirits, tobacco and tea are the cause of their being so <br>
much like by those who use them." 13:276<br>
<p>
"Then let us seek to extend the present life to the uttermost, by <br>
observing every law of health, and by properly balancing labor, <br>
study, rest, and recreation, and thus prepare for a better life." 11:132<br>
<p>
"So we see that almost the very first teachings the first Elders of this <br>
Church received were as to what to eat, what to drink, and how to <br>
order their natural lives that they might be united temporally as <br>
well as spiritually.  This is the great purpose which God has in view <br>
in sending to the world, by his servants, the Gospel of life and <br>
salvation.  12:158<br>
<p>
"This is the duty of the human family, instead of wasting their lives <br>
and the lives of their fellow-beings, and the precious time God has <br>
given us to improve our minds and bodies by observing the law of <br>
life, so that the longevity of the human family may begin to return."  <br>
14:89<br>
<p>
"Do you think they will stuff themselves then with tea and coffee, <br>
and perhaps with a little brandy sling before breakfast and a little <br>
before going to bed, and then beef, pork, mutton, sweet meats, and <br>
pastry, morning, noon and night?  No; you will find they will live as <br>
our first parents did, on fruits and on a little simple food, and they <br>
will never overload the stomach."  12:37<br>
<p>
"If the people were willing to receive the true knowledge from <br>
heaven in regard to their diet they would cease eating swine's flesh. . <br>
. Fish is as healthy as food as we can eat, if we except vegetables and <br>
fruit, and with them will become a very wholesome diet."  12:192<br>
<p>
"The Americans, as a nation, are killing themselves with their vices <br>
and high living.  As much as a man ought to eat in half an hour they <br>
swallow in three minutes, gulping down their food like the canine <br>
quadruped under the table, which, when a chunk of meat is thrown <br>
down to it, swallows it before you can say "twice"."  13:153-154<br>
<p>
"Good pure air is the greatest sustainer of animal life.  Other <br>
elements of life we can dispense with for a time, but this seems to be <br>
essential every moment; hence the necessity of well ventilated <br>
dwellings-houses, especially the rooms occupied for sleeping.  You <br>
can live without water and food longer than you can without air, and <br>
water is of more importance than meat and bread."  8:168<br>
<p>
"The out-door air is what the people need for health, it is good for <br>
them to camp out.  Close houses are injurious to the health; if our <br>
houses were every one of them levelled to the ground, and we were <br>
obliged to live in our wagons and tents, the people would be <br>
healthier, from year to year, than they are now.  Good houses are <br>
comfortable and very convenient, and please our feelings, and are <br>
tolerably healthful when properly ventilated."  2:284<br>
<p>
"We should have plenty of pure, fresh air.  If children are kept in <br>
close bedrooms, they become puny and weakly.  Let them sleep <br>
where they can have abundance of pure air, in well-ventilated <br>
rooms, or out-of-doors, in the summer time, in a safe place;  it will be <br>
most beneficial for their health."  12:218<br>
<p>
"Do you know that it is your privilege so to live that your minds may <br>
all the time be perfectly within your control?  Study to preserve <br>
your bodies in life and health, and you will be able to control your <br>
minds."  8:135<br>
<p>
"My mind becomes tired, and perhaps some of yours do.  If so, go <br>
and exercise your bodies."  6:148<br>
<p>
"As for health, it is far healthier to walk than to ride, and better <br>
every way for the people."  4:103<br>
<p>
"Mothers, keep the children from eating meat; and let them eat <br>
vegetables that are fully matured, not unripe, and bread that is well-<br>
baked, not soft."  19:67<br>
<p>
------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<p>
So, are you curious about who wrote these health messages?  These <br>
were spoken by the Mormon leader and prophet, Brigham Young, <br>
who was also the first governor of the Utah territory.  Surprised?  <br>
Yea, I was too.  The numbers after each item are the volume and<br>
pagesof the "Journal of Discourses" where these can be found.  MY<br>
source was the book, "Discourses of Brigham Young" compiled by<br>
John A. Widtsoe published in 1954.  I invite your comments, either<br>
via private email or SDAnet postings.<br>
<p>
Cheryl Berthelsen<br>
cberthel@cc.utah.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
