<title>Feb_1993: Food laws</title>
<h1>Food laws</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>24 Feb 1993 10:10:44 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#223">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#223">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#223">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#223">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0224.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Church&lt;-/-&gt;State"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0222.html">April Grabast: "Re: The "Sharing Scripture" SS lesson"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0226.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Food laws"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAs do *not* officially see the food laws as still binding.<br>
<p>
Our dietary practices have more to do with general health principles<br>
than with staying kosher. That's the official line, anyway. Individual <br>
SDAs may disagree.<br>
<p>
The process of growth and maturity as a people of God has taken us<br>
beyond the "Mummy said not to touch" stage to the "it's dangerous and<br>
painful to pick up a hot saucepan" stage. There are many things in<br>
the ceremonial law that are good sense, even in a civilized society.<br>
Other things were specifically given to deal with the problems of<br>
being a desert nomad, or the politics of living in an imperfect<br>
theocracy or under some despot king.<br>
<p>
By the way, when I referred to the people of God, I was thinking in<br>
the long-scale historical sense, from Sinai right through to the<br>
twentieth century.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0224.html">Marcus Stringer: "RE: Church&lt;-/-&gt;State"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0222.html">April Grabast: "Re: The "Sharing Scripture" SS lesson"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0226.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Food laws"</a>
</ul>
