<title>Feb_1993: Three Angels, Environment, Etc...</title>
<h1>Three Angels, Environment, Etc...</h1>
David E. Johnson (<i>71172.2044@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>31 Jan 93 19:24:16 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#0">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#0">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#0">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#0">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Steven Timm: "Digest missed its course"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One of the more disturbing things lately is the resurgence of a *very* <br>
narrow view on the Three Angels message, Mark of the Beast, etc.. The <br>
ENTIRE Christian message is that salvation (justification, sanctification, <br>
glorification) is accomplished by Christ ALONE. The essence of ALL false <br>
religion is that you can do it yourself. Conversly everything about my <br>
behavior, relationships to others and relationship to God's creation is <br>
rooted in Christ. To make part of salvation by faith and part by your own <br>
works is exactly the problem referred to in the Apocalypse as "Babylon", <br>
and many correctly identify entities such as the Roman church with Babylon. <br>
Much more sobering is how easily all of us can fall into the trap!<br>
Could you be an environmentalist and worship the beast? Sure. But I don't <br>
think that you can "remain faithful to Jesus" and "worship Him who made the <br>
heavens, the earth [and] the sea..." and *not* retain an environmental <br>
sensibility. It seems to me that we worry far too much about losing the <br>
distinctiveness of Adventism, and not nearly enough about being faithful to <br>
the Gospel. They aren't anywhere near incompatible considering the <br>
incredible breadth of perspective Adventism gives to the Christian life <br>
(sanctuary, health, death, liberty, etc.)<br>
On another point, it seems that the defenders of KJV and the Textus <br>
Receptus as the most accurate texts need to both lighten up and take some <br>
time looking at history and archaeology. The procedures used by the United <br>
Bible Society in their Greek New Testament which attempt to collate all <br>
mss., with understandable weight toward older sources seems a sound one. In <br>
addition to copious footnotes, they also produce a companion volume which <br>
explains why they chose certain readings, and leave the alternates well <br>
documented. I fail to see any "Jesuit" conspiricy unless you want to <br>
believe that they are out spiking the caves and have a lock on <br>
*interpreting* these manuscripts. Absurdities like this aside, it is <br>
wonderful to see the efforts of the wider scholastic community in forcing <br>
the hand of the few who have had a lock on *access* to some of the Dead Sea <br>
scroll materials.<br>
Until the more recent translations (NIV, NRSV, etc) became widely used in <br>
our churches it seemed that most of the pastors sermon time was taken up in <br>
explaining the Elizabethan language of the KJV into understandable terms. <br>
This wasn't always based on greek scholarship, either. To those of us with <br>
NIV's in our laps (or access to Greek texts), it was not time well spent. <br>
We wanted the preacher to get directly to the point about the text. IMHO, <br>
the quaint language of the KJV tends to make too many people view God the <br>
same way. Quaint and irrelevant.<br>
To paraphrase a famous LA resident, can we get on with it?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
