<title>Feb_1993: Textus Receptus &amp; Erasmus etc</title>
<h1>Textus Receptus &amp; Erasmus etc</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>02 Feb 1993 08:59:57 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#2">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#2">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#2">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#2">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Bible versions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Steven Timm: "Digest missed its course"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One book which I have found interesting reading is<br>
<p>
Carson, D.A., "The KJV Debate: A Call For Realism", ...<br>
<p>
Carson is a well known Baptist writer/theologian who believes in verbal<br>
inspiration (qualification: he defines carefully what he means by "verbali<br>
inspiration before saying that), and he has written this book to counter<br>
certain elements in the evangelical community who were/are strongly pro<br>
TR and pro KJV. <br>
<p>
One interesting fact that I didn't previously know is that Erasmus was<br>
missing the last page of Revelation from his Greek original. He was hence<br>
forced to translate this passage back from the Vulgate latin into Greek for<br>
his printed version. He also chose to translate back for a few other passages<br>
where he was in doubt over the accuracy of his Greek manuscripts.<br>
<p>
The other thing was that the name "Textus Receptus" was taken from a short<br>
preface written by the two gents who prepared the Greek text from which the<br>
KJV was translated. The phrase seems to lend itself more intrinsic authority F<br>
than that, just from the way it sounds!<br>
<p>
And as for Catholic influence, Erasmus never actually left the RC church,<br>
although he pointedly disagreed with the Vulgate in many places.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
