<title>Feb_1993: Thoughts on Bible Translations</title>
<h1>Thoughts on Bible Translations</h1>
Warren C Trenchard (<i>70711.3366@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>01 Feb 93 02:03:47 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Australia"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Bible versions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have followed with interest the discussion on Bible translations.  Let me<br>
offer a few comments.<br>
<p>
Bible translations fall into two general type.  The static translations attempt<br>
to render the underlying original languages in a more or less literal way. <br>
They tend to be word for word translations, as much as possible.  Those<br>
who look to the Bible to establish the technical details of their doctrines<br>
and those who employ the proof text method of Bible study generally<br>
prefer such translations.  Examples of this type include the Authorized<br>
Version (King James Version of 1611), the English Revised Version<br>
(1881), the American Standard Version (1901; essentially equals the<br>
modern New American Standard Bible), the Revised Standard Version<br>
(1946-52; to a lesser extent the New Revised Standard Version), and the<br>
New King James Version.  The more recent of these translations often<br>
make good study Bibles.<br>
<p>
On the other hand, the dynamic translations try to convey the meaning of<br>
the original languages at the level of ideas, often unpacking the meaning of<br>
ancient metaphors with modern equivalents.  Some see these translations as<br>
less accurate than their counterparts.  However, translation is rarely as<br>
simple or simplistic as a word for word enterprise.  Words work together<br>
in groups, like sentences and paragraphs, to convey meaning.  One can<br>
make a powerful case for extending the task of translation beyond the<br>
atomistic confines of words to the broader context of sentences and<br>
paragraphs, to the translation of ancient ideas and images into a modern<br>
setting.  Examples of this type include the New English Bible, Today's<br>
English Version (equals the Good News Bible), and, to some extent, the<br>
New International Version.  These translations make for good general<br>
reading.<br>
<p>
Some translations seem to fall somewhere in between these main types.<br>
<p>
Besides their approach to translation, the biblical versions also differ in<br>
another very important respect, the nature of their underlying texts.  From<br>
my perspective, this is more significant than the type of translation.<br>
<p>
For the Old Testament, before the discovery of the Dead Sea Scrolls less<br>
than fifty years ago, the closest manuscripts to the original documents were<br>
prepared in the tenth century A.D.  With the Qumran and other<br>
manuscripts we have moved at least one thousand years closer to the<br>
originals.  Many of these documents exhibit a form of text that is<br>
unaffected by later editing and standardization.  No translation of the Old<br>
Testament before these discoveries can compare to those since in the<br>
quality of their underlying texts.<br>
<p>
While the situation with regard to the New Testament is less dramatic in<br>
the sense of newsworthiness, the results are no less significant.  Until the<br>
English Revised Version, translations of the New Testament were based on<br>
edited texts that traced their origin to the work of Erasmus in the early<br>
sixteenth century.  He based his texts on a few Medieval manuscripts. <br>
Even though his successors added the readings of many other late<br>
manuscripts, the essential nature of the text did not change.  This is the<br>
text that came to be known as the Textus Receptus, the Received or<br>
Standard Text.  Most specialists on the text of the New Testament consider<br>
this form of text to be not only late, but edited and standardized.  It shows<br>
clear signs of efforts to settle textual differences by compromise. <br>
Beginning in the nineteenth century with the discovery of some great<br>
manuscripts from the fourth and fifth centuries and continuing to the<br>
present with the steady find of even earlier and more primitive papyrus<br>
manuscripts, we now have available a wealth of New Testament textual<br>
material that brings us much closer to the original writings than was<br>
possible in the seventeenth century.  One fragment of the Gospel of John<br>
dates to within fifty years of the autograph!  I join the majority of students<br>
of the New Testament text in the view that some of these early<br>
manuscripts are not only closer in time to the original New Testament<br>
writings but are also more faithful to the original readings of these texts.<br>
<p>
Therefore, I feel that the most important criteria in judging the quality of a<br>
particular translation of the Bible is the nature of its underlying original<br>
texts for both the Old Testament and the New Testament.  Accordingly, I<br>
would consider as superior in this regard only those translations which are<br>
based on the best available texts and that positively reflect the current state<br>
of Old and New Testament textual studies.  For me, this would not include<br>
any translation made before the last half of the present century.<br>
<p>
Let me say a few words about the Authorized Version.  First of all, I<br>
acknowledge the important role that this translation has played in the<br>
history of the English language, in the life of the Church, and in the<br>
experiences of countless Christians.  It is truly a classic.  However,  one<br>
should recognize that it was far from the first translation in English and<br>
that it did not receive immediate acceptance.  It was based on late Hebrew<br>
texts for the Old Testament and the flawed Textus Receptus for the New<br>
Testament.  Incidently, the same texts lie behind the New King James<br>
Version, which has been merely rendered in a more modern form of the<br>
language.  While, for me, this is sufficient to disqualify the AV (KJV) as<br>
the translation of choice, the decision is strengthened by its antiquated<br>
vocabulary and its old grammatical characteristics.  Notable among the<br>
latter are the ancient forms of verbs and the use of the second person<br>
singular pronouns, e.g., "thou."<br>
<p>
God did not inspire the biblical writers to produce a classic or a document<br>
with a special celestial language.  The Bible was written in the<br>
contemporary language of ancient common people and was intended to be<br>
understood by them.  It can best convey its message to us if we have it in<br>
a form that is not only as true as possible to the original but also as clear<br>
as possible in our contemporary language.<br>
<p>
Warren C. Trenchard<br>
Internet: 70711.3366@compuserve.com<br>
CIS: 70711,3366<br>
<br>
