<title>Feb_1993: "Spaceship Eden"</title>
<h1>"Spaceship Eden"</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  1 Feb 1993 17:21:42 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">David Plaisted: "Bible versions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Re: Australia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I first heard this model explained when I was a student of S. Clark Rowland<br>
(a silent member of SDAnet).  Recently he wrote it up and put it in the <br>
National Association of Adventist Physicists Newsletter.  I present it here<br>
with his permission, as he wrote it up.  He expressed the concern that this <br>
model ought not to become the new orthodoxy.  I replied that nothing I have<br>
said on this net so far has become new orthodoxy, and that there is no reason<br>
to think that this statement will be so accepted.  Without further ado...<br>
<p>
Science and Faith--The Interface   (From N.A.A.P.)<br>
 "An 'Impossible' Model" by S. Clark Rowland<br>
<p>
I have heard it said, within SDA church circles, that it is impossible to come <br>
up with a model which is totally consistent with both the best scientific<br>
data and our traditional understanding of earth origins.  Any time someone<br>
expresses such an opinion, it becomes a challenge.  To show that such is <br>
indeed possible, I present the _Spaceship Eden_ model.<br>
<p>
The complete traditional understanding of creation week is assumed.  Adam <br>
has been named as the representative of this earth on the heavenly council.<br>
The Creator calls a meeting to introduce him to the other members.  Since<br>
it is a significant trip, he is instructed to take Eve with him.  Of course<br>
they need a vehicle in which to make the trip.  It is commonly held in SDA<br>
circles that the Garden of Eden was transported to heaven at the time of Noah's<br>
flood so, being transportable, we assume that the Garden of Eden was used as a<br>
spaceship to transport Adam and Eve to a meeting of the heavenly council<br>
soon after the creation week.  Not knowing where the council meeting may <br>
have been held, we assume that it was perhaps one tenth of the distance across<br>
the universe and that they travel at speeds approaching the speed of light.  <br>
We then assume that the meeting took place, lasting perhaps a couple of weeks.<br>
During the meeting, all representatives are able to tour the Garden of Eden<br>
and meet Adam and Eve.  At the end of the meeting, _Spaceship Eden_ takes<br>
off for the return trip to earth.  <br>
<p>
Meanwhile back on earth, at least a few microbes have been left around the <br>
perimeter of the garden when it was removed.  With this raw material,<br>
the devil began an intensive genetic engineering program immediately upon<br>
their departure.  In time he was amazingly successful.  Due to time dilation,<br>
a short trip of a few months in Spaceship Eden would correspond to a time<br>
period on earth of a few billion years.<br>
<p>
Upon the arrival of Spaceship Eden back on earth, Adam and Eve find that the <br>
flora and fauna on the earth is a reasonable approximation to that in the <br>
garden.  Some time passes and the fall takes place.  For Adam and Eve, the time<br>
from creation to the fall would have been very short, perhaps a few months. <br>
On the earth that same time interval would have been several billion years.<br>
<p>
I concluded that I had done what had been said to be impossible. The one<br>
who had said it agreed.  He then asked, "Why don't you publish it?"  My<br>
response was, "Because I don't want it to become the new orthodoxy."  It<br>
had been my intention not to describe how events transpired but rather <br>
to demonstrate that acceptance of the best scientific models in no way<br>
threatens faith.  If it is this easy to construct a model which is consistent<br>
with both the most literal theological traditions concerning origins <br>
and with the best scientific understanding of origins, then we have no <br>
reason to be fearful of innovative model building.  It is unlikely that <br>
a definitive model will ever be produced but the door is open for <br>
creative expression.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
