<title>Feb_1993: Bible versions</title>
<h1>Bible versions</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 1 Feb 93 12:52:48 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#7">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#7">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#7">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#7">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Dave Thomas: "Re:  "Spaceship Eden""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Steven Timm: ""Spaceship Eden""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
			    Bible Versions<br>
<p>
	This recent discussion on Bible versions has been very<br>
interesting to me.  I read Wilkinson's books about the Bible versions<br>
and some other books and a friend of mine studied this further.  The<br>
situation is that 90% of the manuscripts follow the Textus Receptus<br>
(on which KJV is based) and 10% or less the Vaticanus (or whatever it<br>
is called).  It's true that the Vaticanus etc. are older.  However,<br>
since the Receptus texts are more numerous and widely distributed,<br>
it's reasonable to suppose that they come from an earlier source.<br>
There's no good evidence for some kind of standardization among them.<br>
The texts that were most heavily used tended to wear out faster; those<br>
that remained were those that were less used.<br>
<p>
	We do have some evidence of very early texts; some of these<br>
come from quotes in the early church fathers.  These quotes sometimes<br>
follow the Textus Receptus and sometimes not, as far as I have<br>
learned.  So this shows that the Receptus was not a late invention.<br>
Also, the early Bible fragments that have been found, contain mixtures<br>
of the Receptus and the other version (Vaticanus?).  So there's no<br>
clear evidence that one version is older than the other based on the<br>
age of the manuscripts alone.<br>
<p>
	Now, who were all these people who wrote those Receptus<br>
manuscripts?  It wasn't the Roman Catholics, because they favored the<br>
Vaticanus and related versions.  The preponderance of the Receptus<br>
versions tells us some very significant things about the history of<br>
Christianity.  It shows that there was an active and widely<br>
distributed community of Christians who were dedicated to the<br>
Scriptures and not affiliated with the Roman Catholic church.  They<br>
were also very influential, because my understanding is that some of<br>
these Receptus texts were from royal families.  This shows that there<br>
was a separate stream of Christianity from earliest times unaffiliated<br>
with Roman Catholicism.<br>
<p>
	Why don't we know more about these people?  The early<br>
Protestants mentioned that after every persecution, the Roman church<br>
did all it could to destroy the manuscripts of those they persecuted,<br>
especially their Bible manuscripts.  That might say something about<br>
why it's harder to find older Textus Receptus manuscripts.  The Great<br>
Controversy also mentions this, about the fact that few records remain<br>
of the true history of Christianity.<br>
<p>
	So how did the text become changed?  Well, from now on, it's<br>
mostly speculation.  But there was a considerable Gnostic influence in<br>
early Christianity.  They tended to deny the deity of Christ, I am<br>
told.  (And the importance of the law?)  The Vaticanus and related<br>
versions tend to minimize the texts dealing with the divine nature of<br>
Christ, as you can verify by comparison.  Apparently the Gnostics were<br>
very powerful and in order to win their support the Roman Catholic<br>
church incorporated their manuscripts.  I suppose the very early<br>
manuscripts represented an intermediate stage when the Gnostic<br>
influence was only beginning to be felt and so you have a mixture of<br>
the true and the false.  This paragraph is largely based on what my<br>
friend told me, who researched this part of the story some.<br>
<p>
	I would also mention that Ellen White strongly supports texts<br>
like ``Blessed are they that do his commandments'' that are rendered<br>
in the modern versions as ``Blessed are those who have washed their<br>
robes.''  (Rev. 22:14) At least, that is my impression.<br>
<p>
	Of course, the two versions are really not very different.<br>
But, when it comes to the Word of God, even a small change is<br>
significant.<br>
<p>
	Dave P.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
