<title>Feb_1993: Why is Bible Version important?</title>
<h1>Why is Bible Version important?</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  2 Feb 1993 00:45:46 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#11">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#11">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#11">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#11">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Lawrence Turner: "faculty position"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Australia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have been quite surprised to see the groundswell of support for the <br>
King James Version.  I have seen arguments from other fundamentalist<br>
groups on the net with much less sophisticated logic, but never heard<br>
such arguments from the mouth of Adventists before.  At the same time,<br>
I suppose I have asked for the comments since I have been at least as vocal.<br>
This leads me to ask--why is this question so important to me?  (all long-<br>
term readers of SDAnet know this is a subject near and dear to my heart<br>
that comes up frequently.)<br>
<p>
Would my faith be different if the following verses were not in my Bible?<br>
John 15:4<br>
Mark 16:9-20<br>
<p>
Would my faith be different if the following books and chapters were in my <br>
Bible?   (In my N.R.S.V. they are)<br>
<p>
Daniel 13-15<br>
Wisdom of Solomon<br>
Baruch<br>
Sirach<br>
<p>
To me, unless I wish to postulate the infallibility of the Bible because<br>
I intend to use it as a rhetorical club, it should not matter if John 15:4<br>
is in my Bible or not.  Having said this, I pull out my own favorite <br>
rhetorical club, Selected Messages Vol. 1, and give some advice.<br>
<p>
pg. 16<br>
"Some look to us gravely, and say 'Don't you think there might have <br>
been some mistake in the copyist or the translators?"  This is all <br>
probable, and the mind that is so narrow that it will hesitate and <br>
stumble over this possibility or probability would be just as ready to <br>
stumble over the mysteries of the Inspired Word, because their feeble<br>
minds cannot see through the purposes of God."<br>
<p>
pg. 17<br>
When men, in their finite judgment, find it necessary to go into an <br>
examinatio of scriptures to define that which is inspired and that which<br>
is not, they have stepped before Jesus to show Him a better way than He<br>
has led us......<br>
<p>
    Men should let God take care of His own Book, His living oracles, <br>
as He has done for ages.   ...<br>
<p>
pg. 20<br>
There is not always perfect order or apparent unity in the scriptures.<br>
The miracles of Christ are not given by exact order, but are given,<br>
just as the circumstances occurred, which called for this divine revealing<br>
of the power of Christ.<br>
<p>
pg. 21 <br>
<p>
It is not the words of the Bible that were inspired, but the men that <br>
were inspired.  Inspiration acts not on the man's words or his expressions<br>
but on the man himself.<br>
<p>
<p>
----------<br>
I discuss this topic, not because I have any particular version to push,<br>
but because I feel that the attitude towards inspiration is the main <br>
divisive factor in the church today.  Liberals, conservatives, and fence-<br>
sitters all can misunderstand it, and we need to start talking while we <br>
can still at least understand each other's terms.  I don't expect everyone<br>
to view inspiration like I do.  If people need to believe in a verbally-<br>
inspired Bible to have any faith at all, I don't want to shake their faith.<br>
<p>
To our defenders of the KJV:  In the light of the statements above, <br>
what is the reason to defend the "textus receptus?"  David Plaisted has<br>
mentioned one possible doctrinal error, Rev 22:14, are there others<br>
we should be aware of?  Could it be that if we draw the line at defending<br>
the literal and legal truth of the Bible, some people will never learn<br>
the spiritual truth by experiencing it and living it.  After all, the Bible<br>
is not true because a set of letters have been preserved on paper for lo<br>
these 2000 years.  It's true in the greatest sense because its teachings<br>
lead to the way of salvation.<br>
<p>
As a postscript, I believe that we're going to find out that a lot more <br>
about the Bible was true and inspired than we ever thought could be.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
