<title>Feb_1993: Thoughts on Bible Translations</title>
<h1>Thoughts on Bible Translations</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 2 Feb 93 12:30:02 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Thoughts on Bible Translations"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Lawrence Turner: "faculty position"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0014.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Thoughts on Bible Translations"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;.....</i><br>
<i>&gt; Until the</i><br>
<i>&gt; English Revised Version, translations of the New Testament were based on</i><br>
<i>&gt; edited texts that traced their origin to the work of Erasmus in the early</i><br>
<i>&gt; sixteenth century.  He based his texts on a few Medieval manuscripts. </i><br>
<i>&gt; Even though his successors added the readings of many other late</i><br>
<i>&gt; manuscripts, the essential nature of the text did not change.  This is the</i><br>
<i>&gt; text that came to be known as the Textus Receptus, the Received or</i><br>
<i>&gt; Standard Text</i><br>
<p>
<p>
Can you provide evidence of this fact. I have evidence directly to the contrary.<br>
I was going to bring it in today but I unfortunately left it at home.<br>
<p>
The Textus receptus did not originate with Erasmus, its lineage can be traced<br>
back through the Waldenisan bible to earliest times. Neither was Erasmus's<br>
edition based on just a *few* Medieval manuscripts. Please substantiate<br>
this claim.<br>
<p>
There is ample evidence to prove that Erasmus had at hand and was aware<br>
of *ALL* the variant readings which were introduced by Codex B (Vaticanus)<br>
and the Siniaticus.  <br>
<p>
In fact the revised version itself was based on heavily edited texts<br>
and on some of questionable character. Not to mention that most of<br>
the revised version was exclusively translated from just codex B completely<br>
ignoring the weight of evidence which lies against many of its errors.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Most specialists on the text of the New Testament consider</i><br>
<i>&gt; this form of text to be not only late, but edited and standardized.  It shows</i><br>
<i>&gt; clear signs of efforts to settle textual differences by compromise.</i><br>
<p>
please substantiate this claim, who are these specialists ?<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; Beginning in the nineteenth century with the discovery of some great</i><br>
<i>&gt; manuscripts from the fourth and fifth centuries and continuing to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; present with the steady find of even earlier and more primitive papyrus</i><br>
<i>&gt; manuscripts, we now have available a wealth of New Testament textual</i><br>
<i>&gt; material that brings us much closer to the original writings than was</i><br>
<i>&gt; possible in the seventeenth century. </i><br>
<p>
<p>
By this you refer to the vaticanus and the Sinitaticus MSS which as I have<br>
mentioned originate from Constatine and the gnostic philosopher Origen.<br>
Which belong to the same family as the Latin Vulgate. By which I mean<br>
that they contain exactly the same errors. In fact as I have mentioned they<br>
bring us not closer to the original material, but rather remove us further<br>
away from it due to its origin. Again I state that *all* of the variant<br>
readings found in these two MSS were available to Erasmus and he rejected<br>
them. The tranlators of the AV were also agare of these MSS and rejected<br>
them also. The AV is the bible of the reformation, it is this bible that incited<br>
the hatred and opposition of the RCC not the other translations based<br>
on the Vulgate and its derivatives. I wonder why ?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I join the majority of students</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the New Testament text in the view that some of these early</i><br>
<i>&gt; manuscripts are not only closer in time to the original New Testament</i><br>
<i>&gt; writings but are also more faithful to the original readings of these texts.</i><br>
<p>
How can you verify this, do you have the original texts by which to make<br>
this judgement ?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It is truly a classic.  However,  one</i><br>
<i>&gt; should recognize that it was far from the first translation in English and</i><br>
<i>&gt; that it did not receive immediate acceptance. </i><br>
<p>
What do you mean by this ? How do you judge acceptance? By whom was it not<br>
immediately accepted ?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It was based on late Hebrew</i><br>
<i>&gt;texts for the Old Testament and the flawed Textus Receptus for the New</i><br>
<i>&gt; Testament.                         ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^</i><br>
<p>
Please substantiate this statement. If you can not please withdraw it.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
