<!-- body="start" -->
First a response to some of Ruben's points, then some of my own.<br>
Ruben asked in his post for a flaw in the "Textus Receptus".  I have<br>
already documented one, namely the added phrase in 1 John 5:8.<br>
<p>
Ruben also claims the AV to be the "Bible of the Reformation."  This<br>
is substantially untrue.  The Authorized Version, or "King James Version"<br>
as Americans know it, was promulgated in 1611.  By this time most of the<br>
great reformers such as Luther, Tyndale, Coverdale, and Calvin were<br>
already dead.  The Authorized Version was produced at the behest of the <br>
king and enjoyed the blessing of the Crown save during the reign<br>
of James the II, a Catholic.  At the time of James I, the Church of <br>
England was already under fire from the Puritans from being too papal.<br>
<p>
Now, a word in defense of the Textus Receptus and the Authorized Version<br>
(which after all, I myself frequently use.)  The story in the gospel of <br>
John of the woman taken in adultery appears as a footnote in some modern<br>
translations because some of the manuscripts Ruben has been railing against<br>
do not include it.  But in recent years writings of early church fathers<br>
have been found that refer to the story.  These writings suggest that <br>
the story was removed from some copies of the manuscript because the church<br>
fathers feared that it would encourage adultery and fornication.<br>
So here we have at least one case where the TR and AV prevail against <br>
the modernists.<br>
<p>
Has anyone heard more about the fragments 7Q4 and 7Q5 from the Qumran<br>
caves, dated AD60 or earlier, that some scholars allege to have New <br>
Testament fragments in their markings?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
