<title>Feb_1993: Re: Thoughts on Bible Translations</title>
<h1>Re: Thoughts on Bible Translations</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  2 Feb 1993 09:24:55 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#16">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#16">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#16">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#16">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Ted Ashton: "Re:  "Spaceship Eden""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0015.html">Steven Timm: "Updated directory"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0013.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Thoughts on Bible Translations"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[from Ruben Gonzales]<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; First a response to some of Ruben's points, then some of my own.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Ruben asked in his post for a flaw in the "Textus Receptus".  I have</i><br>
<i>&gt; already documented one, namely the added phrase in 1 John 5:8.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Could you give me the source of this information regarding this, I would<br>
really like to follow it up.<br>
[I found this in Alden Thompson's book _Inspiration_.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Ruben also claims the AV to be the "Bible of the Reformation."  This</i><br>
<i>&gt; is substantially untrue.  The Authorized Version, or "King James Version"</i><br>
<p>
Sorry, my mistake, I meant the Textus receptus (not the AV) was the bible<br>
of the reformation. To the extent that Calvin, Luther etc used it the the<br>
exclusion of all other versions.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
