<title>Feb_1993: Fact time on translations</title>
<h1>Fact time on translations</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 3 Feb 93 13:23:34 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#19">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#19">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#19">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#19">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0020.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Copyrighting means "not inspired?""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0018.html">GRUMLING DENNIS : "KJV"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
Its time to supply the facts.<br>
<p>
Now Steve wrote from A.Thompsons book _Inspiration_<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; In the compilation of that work, Erasmus noted that 1 John 5:8 as translated</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the Vulgate had an addition which did not appear in the Greek manuscripts:</i><br>
<p>
Which are these Greek MSS in which this did not appear ? Could you identify<br>
them for me please.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The part between the asterisks evidently was added quite some time later.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Erasmus did not want to include it, but the Church fathers insisted that</i><br>
<i>&gt; he should.  </i><br>
<p>
Which church fathers are these, most of them died around 1000 years before<br>
Erasmus. I would really like to sus this one out.<br>
<p>
Let me just say that there is ample evidence to show that the Jesuits attempted <br>
at every turn to corrupt Erasmus's writings, his letters and his books, by <br>
changing or forging or destroying them. [Froude, Life of Erasmus, pp271,272]<br>
Whether this is the situation with regard to the above episode or not may<br>
not be so easy to tell.<br>
<p>
At any rate we all know and accept that Erasmus' text has some errors. No one<br>
will dispute that the point is that Erasmus text corrected the errors of the<br>
previous versions and both he and his scholarship was endorsed by EGW.<br>
<p>
All of the modern translations contain the very errors that Erasmus corrected<br>
according to EGW, because they are mainly based on just two MSS which come<br>
directly from the RCC and Constantine and are of the same family as the LAtin<br>
Vulgate. The Textus receptus which Erasmus published was not the fruit of his <br>
own hands, it was the dominant and principle text at the time and had<br>
been since at least 350AD. It was the same text as treasured by the Waldenisans<br>
(which EGW tells us was pure, uncontaminated and came directly from the apostles), it was the same MSS treasured by the Copitcs and the Greek Church<br>
for over 1000 years. And it is the one verified by the church fathers themselves<br>
<p>
REv 22:14 church fathers quote - "do His commandments"<br>
Tertullian (AD200) Cyprian (248-258) and Tertonius (390) first time <br>
wash robes is quoted is by Athanasius, bishop of alexandria (326-373)<br>
so the textus receptus reading predates even the earliest manuscripts.<br>
<p>
Another tradition of texts - the eastern texts (Syriac) in Aramaic the language <br>
most of the NT was spoken in. these texts generally confer with<br>
the Textus receptus as also does the Coptic version, in fact Even the Vatican <br>
manuscript in Greek has rev 22:14 as per the KJV.<br>
<p>
The traditional text (Textus Receptus) held sway in the Greek church from about <br>
312-1453 AD.<br>
<p>
Dr.F.C. Cook (Chapilan to the Queen of England, who was invited to sit on the re<br>
vision committe, but refused) has this to say regarding the translation of hte <br>
KJV.<br>
<p>
"That textus receptus was taken in the first instance, from late cursive <br>
manuscripts; but its readings are maintained only so far as they agree with<br>
the earliest and best Greek and Latin Fathers, and with the vast majority of <br>
unical and cursive manuscipts." Revised Version of the first three Gospels, p226.<br>
<p>
The cursive MSS were those written in a cursive style and typically date<br>
later than the unical ones which were written in capital letters.<br>
<p>
Lets see the verdict of the RCC regarding these and other versions.<br>
Dr. Kenrick, Catholic Bishop of Philadelphia says in his preface to an English <br>
translation of a catholic bible in 1849<br>
"Since the famous manuscripts of Rome Alexandria, Cambridge, Paris and Dublin <br>
were examined...A verdict has been obtained in favor of the Vulgate. At the <br>
reformation the Greek text as it then stood, was taken as a standard, in <br>
conformity to which the versions of the reformers were generally made; whilst <br>
the LAtin Vulgate was depreciated, or dispised as a mere version."<br>
<p>
Now we see why men prefer the other manuscipts because they support the Vulgate.<br>
<p>
<p>
That Erasmus was aware of the variant readings of the Vaticanus (codex B) we <br>
read.<br>
<p>
"A correspondent of Erasmus in 1533 sent that scholar a number of selected <br>
readings from it (Codex B) as proof of its superiority over the Received Greek <br>
Text" Sir Fredrick Kenyon, "Our Bible" p133. <br>
<p>
This correspondent was none other than Professor Paulus Bombasius at Rome. <br>
[S.P. Tregelles, On the printed Text of the Greek test., p.22]<br>
<p>
{Sorry for stealing your `[` Steve }<br>
<p>
One can not claim that these "older and more reliable" texts were unknown<br>
to either ERasmus or the KJV translators, they knew them, and rejected them<br>
as corrupt.<br>
<p>
What matters anyway, the vast majority of the manuscipts in Greek are <br>
practically all the Recieved Text. The Textus Receptus did not originate with <br>
Erasmus all he practically did was publish it and make it accessable<br>
<p>
Dean Burgon an eminent authority says<br>
"The one great FACT, which especially troubles him, (Dr, Hort), and his joint <br>
Editor, -(as well it may)- is the traditional Greek text of the New Testament <br>
Scriptures. Call this text Erasmian or Complutensian., --the Text of Stephens, <br>
or of Beza, or of Elzevirs, -- call it the 'Received', or the traditional Greek <br>
text, or what ever other name you please; --the fact remains, that a text has <br>
come down to us which is attested by a general consensus of ancient copics, <br>
ancient fathers, ancient versions... Our readers cannot have yet forgotten his <br>
(Dr Hort's) virtual admission, that beyond all question the Textus Receptus is <br>
the dominant Graeco-Syrian Text of A.D. 350 to A.D. 400." in Revision Revised, <br>
p.269.<br>
<p>
And mind you Hort hated the Textus REceptus he wrote <br>
"Think of that vile textus receptus" Life of Hort Vol1, p214.<br>
<p>
<p>
"The popular notion seems to be, that we are indebted for our knowledge of the <br>
true texts of scripture to the existing unicial entirely; and that the essence <br>
of the secret dwells exclusively with the four or five oldest of those uncials. <br>
By consequence, it is popularly supposed that since we are possessed of such <br>
uncial copies, we could afford to dispense with the testimony of the cursives <br>
altogether. A more complete misconception of the facts of the case can hardly <br>
be imagined. For the plain truth is THAT ALL THE PHENOMENA EXHIBITED BY THE <br>
UNICAL MANUSCRIPTS ARE reproduced by the cursive copies." [emph. mine] Burgon <br>
and Miller, "The Traditional Text" p.202.<br>
<p>
Dr. Sdrivener says regarding this<br>
"A Judge is not impartial if he rejects the testimony of eighty-nine out of a <br>
hundred witnesses. It is a law of evidence that the very few are to be suspected<br>
 rather than the very many." "Bibliotheca Sacra" p.35<br>
<p>
Sidney  Collett in his "The Scripture of Truth" when writing about the Siniatic <br>
manuscript that was found by Dr. Tischendorf stated :-<br>
"Dr. Tischendorf believed that this and the Vatican manusicrpt were two of the <br>
fifty copies of the Bible which were made in Greek by command<br>
of emperor Constantine about hte year AD 331, under the supervision of Bishop <br>
Eusebius, the historian of Ceasarea,." p.28<br>
<p>
There is a host of authorities which share the conviction regarding the <br>
origin of these two MSS.<br>
Eusebius was a disciple of Origen and these texts were largely the result<br>
of ORigens work. Its is from the version of Eusebius that Jerome produced<br>
the Vulgate.<br>
<p>
Origens view of scripture was "The scriptures are of little use to those who<br>
understand them as they are written" McClintock and Strong, _Origen_<br>
everyone knowns that Origen was infactuated with Greek philosophy and Plato.<br>
<p>
Abbo Martin, a well known CAtholic textual critic claims that the Vaticanus and <br>
the Siniaticus were "fabricated" by Origen and others. (see Schaff, "Companion <br>
to the Greek Text")<br>
<p>
<p>
How can anybody knowing that any bible Translated from RCC MSS wilfuly endorse<br>
them as being superior. Both of the MSS used to the exclusion of all others<br>
in the translation of all modern bibles (NIV,RSV,NEB etc) use these two texts <br>
both of which were found on Roman Catholic property. how very fitting.<br>
<p>
Let me just give you some facts about these two manuscripts :<br>
<p>
Facts about he Vaticanus<br>
<p>
it omits 	Gen 1:1 to Gen 46:28<br>
		Ps 106 to Ps 138<br>
		Matt 16:2-3<br>
		Heb 9:14-13:25<br>
		All of Revelation<br>
It leaves out of the gospels :<br>
		237 words<br>
		452 clauses<br>
		748 whole sentences<br>
(2556 omissions in all)<br>
That these appear to be oversights of the scribe is evident from the fact that <br>
the "same scribe has repeatedly written words and clauses twice over" <br>
(Dr. Scrivener, "Introduction", Vol.1, p.120) Obiously this piece of <br>
writing was not considered to be of major importance unlike the textus<br>
receptus which was painstakingly copied and verified.<br>
Dr. Hskier says " That B (Codex B = Vaticanus) is guilty of latches, of a <br>
tendancy to 'improve,' and of 'sunstroke' amounting to doctrinal bias. That <br>
maligned Textus Receptus served in large measure as the base which B. tampered <br>
with and changed, and that the Church at larrge recognised all this until the <br>
year 1881 -- when Hortism, in other words Alexandrianis,, was allowd free play" "Codex B and Its Allies", part 1, p.465/<br>
It contains the Apocrypha and such is completely Roman Catholic<br>
It was available to the translators of the KJV but they refused to use<br>
it because it was unreliable and contrary to the bulk of evidence.<br>
<p>
In fact I can go throught the NIV comparing it to the Douay (Vulgate)<br>
and show where it differs from the KJV is does so to agree with the Vulgate, in fact it parallels it. This bible and all those based on it lead stright<br>
to Rome. Instead of using the bible the SoP endorses as fixing the errors<br>
in the Vulgate we may as well go and use the Vulgate directly because<br>
that is what the Vaticanus is.<br>
<p>
<p>
Facts about the Siniaticus<br>
<p>
it contains almost all of the N.T. but added to it is the "Shepherd of Hermes",<br>
"Bel and the Dragon", and the Epistle of Barnabas" (which I think has been shown<br>
 to be a forgery). It has been heavily altered, changes "brought in by at least <br>
ten different revisers....the greater part belonging to the sixth or seventh <br>
century.." Dr. Scrivener "A Full Collation of the Codex Siniaticus," p.XIX, <br>
Introduction<br>
<p>
Mr Philip Mauro adds " Thus there are internal evidences that lead to the <br>
conclusion that it was the work of a scribe who was singularly carless, or <br>
incompetent or both..." Which Version" p.45<br>
<p>
It appears to be very unreliable and is deemed so by many authorities.<br>
<p>
Why is it that the editors of the NIV and these other bibles and those who<br>
push them on the people don't tell them of these facts.<br>
<p>
Just so you can get an idea of the quality of these "most reliable and oldest<br>
texts" I want to quote to you a litte from them found in the Epistle of Barnabus<br>
<p>
"But he adds neither shalt thou eat the hare. To what end? To signify this to<br>
us: thou shalt not be an adulterer; nor liken thyself to such persons. For the<br>
hare every year multiplies the places of its conception; and so many years it <br>
lives, so many it has. Neither shalt thou eat of the hyena; that is again, be<br>
not an adulterer, nor a corrupter of others; neither be like such. And wherefore<br>
so ? Because creature every year changes its kind and is sometimes male and <br>
sometimes female." Epist. Barnabus 8:7-8<br>
<p>
What utter garbage, and this is what those two "most reliable and oldest <br>
manuscripts contain. They don't seem to be so reliable to me.<br>
<p>
Another example the NIV leaves out MArk 16:9-20 on the evidence of these<br>
two MSS however every single other unical MSS contains these verses except<br>
these two Catholic manuscripts. How much evidence does one need.<br>
<p>
Dean Burton says "The impurity of the TExts exhibited by Codices B and Aleph is <br>
not a matter of opinion, but a matter of fact. These are two of the least <br>
trustworthy documents in existence" Revision Revised pp315<br>
<p>
Both MSS are well preserved and little used, obviously indicating  the little <br>
confidence with which they were held.<br>
<p>
The NIV just like the RSV are almost singularily based on the Vaticanus and the <br>
Sinitaticus.<br>
<p>
<p>
Just a few more notes :<br>
<p>
"Ye shall not add unto the word which I command you neither shall ye diminish<br>
from it." Deut 4:2<br>
<p>
"And if any man shall take away from the words of the book or this prophecy,<br>
God shall take away his part out of the book of life" Rev 22:19<br>
<p>
"Every word of God is pure and is a shield unto them that put their trust in <br>
Him"  Prov 30:5<br>
<p>
"Man shall not live by bread alone but by *every* word of God." Luke 4:4<br>
<p>
Here are some of the Verses omited by the NIV based on the Vaticanus text<br>
ignoring all the evidence to the contrary.<br>
<p>
matt 18:11<br>
matt 17:21<br>
matt 23:14<br>
mark 7:16<br>
mark 9:44<br>
mark 9:46<br>
mark 11:26<br>
mark 15:28<br>
luke 17:36<br>
luke 23:17<br>
john 5:3,4<br>
acts 8:37<br>
acts 15:34<br>
acts 24:7<br>
acts 28:29<br>
Rom 16:24<br>
<p>
It is interesting to note that all of these modern bibles are copyrighted.<br>
What does a copyright mean ?<br>
<p>
"The legal protection given to authors and artists to prevent reproduction of <br>
their work without their consent. The owner of a copyright has the exclusive <br>
rith to print, repaint, publish, copy and sell the materical covered by the <br>
copyright."<br>
<p>
<p>
All these bibles self-condem themselves because as the copyright says, it is<br>
a mans work and it belongs to man.<br>
<p>
Now how does that go for God's Word, God's word is not copyrightable, <br>
copyrighted bibles by their own admission are not God's Word but mans word.<br>
<p>
2 Tim 2:9 "Wherein I suffer trouble, as an evil doer, even unto bonds; but *the <br>
Word of God is not bound*"<br>
<p>
Gods word is not bound by any copyright, if it were bound it would'nt be<br>
God's Word, would it ?<br>
<p>
The issue is not whether the Textus Receptus has a few errors (which are minor<br>
in comparison with those of all other translations). The issue is whether<br>
or not we are to use the manufactured and corrupted Catholic manuscipts<br>
or whether to use the text preserved by the church in the wilderness in its<br>
purity. Which do not lead back the RCC though the smooth waters of <br>
ecumenicalism as the others do.<br>
<p>
And this is only a little of the matterial I have.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
