<title>Feb_1993: Copyrighting means "not inspired?"</title>
<h1>Copyrighting means "not inspired?"</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 2 Feb 93 23:08:49 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#20">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#20">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#20">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#20">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Warren C Trenchard: "On the Text of the New Testament"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Fact time on translations"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0030.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: Copyrighting means "not inspired?""</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm curious about one comment Ruben made:<br>
<p>
"It is interesting to note that all of these modern bibles are copyrighted.<br>
What does a copyright mean ?<br>
<p>
"The legal protection given to authors and artists to prevent reproduction of<br>
their work without their consent. The owner of a copyright has the exclusive<br>
rith to print, repaint, publish, copy and sell the materical covered by the<br>
copyright."<br>
<p>
<p>
All these bibles self-condem themselves because as the copyright says, it is<br>
a mans work and it belongs to man.<br>
<p>
Now how does that go for God's Word, God's word is not copyrightable,<br>
copyrighted bibles by their own admission are not God's Word but mans word.<br>
"<br>
<p>
That's a very interesting comment for you must infer then that all of EGW's<br>
writings are also "man's word" because they were copyrighted.<br>
<p>
I have to disagree that copyright per se means that the work is not the<br>
Word of God.  We need to very careful with these comments.  If an translator<br>
did not copyright does that means he/she professes their work to be God's<br>
word?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
