<title>Feb_1993: On the Text of the New Testament</title>
<h1>On the Text of the New Testament</h1>
Warren C Trenchard (<i>70711.3366@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>03 Feb 93 02:46:40 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#21">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#21">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#21">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#21">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Russell Yonkers: "How about a new more acurate translation then"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Copyrighting means "not inspired?""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On the Text of the New Testament<br>
<p>
One thing that puzzles me about the current discussion is the authorities cited.  I have yet to<br>
see the name of a scholar who is generally considered to be a first order authority on New<br>
Testament textual criticism.  (Lest anyone get excited about the word "criticism," it simply<br>
means "rigorous analysis.")  While I would certainly not classify myself among such<br>
luminaries, I do know who these scholars are, having studied New Testament textual criticism<br>
at the University of Chicago with one of the editors of the new "Textus Receptus", i.e., The<br>
Greek New Testament, Third Edition (United Bible Societies) and having worked in the<br>
discipline for over twenty years.<br>
<p>
The international dean of New Testament textual critics is unquestionably Bruce Manning<br>
Metzger, the devote gentleman scholar now retired from Princeton.  No serious discussion in<br>
the field of New Testament textual criticism can ignore his book, The Text of the New<br>
Testament, or his related works.  Other giants in the field in this half of the century include<br>
Matthew Black of St. Andrews and Kurt Aland of Munster.  They not only participated with<br>
Metzger in the editing of the UBS text mentioned above, but have also written extensively on<br>
the subject.  Among the most influential younger scholars are Eldon J. Epp and Gordon Fee. <br>
All these scholars would reject any notion of the superiority of the text that lies behind the<br>
Authorized Version.  Incidentally, Metzger is the chief editor of the New Revised Standard<br>
Version.<br>
<p>
I have been challenged to produce evidence for some of my previous remarks and, in one<br>
case, to withdraw them if I cannot.  While I consider the tone of latter to be unfortunately<br>
confrontational and forensic, I will nevertheless provide a few responses.  A full discussion of<br>
all the complex material would not be appropriate in this nontechnical context.  Therefore, I<br>
will not lay out the demanded evidence, though this would certainly be possible.  Rather, I<br>
will merely cite some of Metzger's published views.  (Quotes are from the second edition of<br>
his book, noted above.)<br>
<p>
On the work of Erasmus, Metzger writes "For most of the text he relied on two rather inferior<br>
manuscripts from a monastic library at Basle, one of the Gospels (see Plate XV) and one of<br>
the Acts and Epistles, both dating from about the twelfth century.  Erasmus compared them<br>
with two or three others of the same books and entered occasional corrections for the printer<br>
in the margins or between the lines of the Greek script.  For the Book of Revelation he had<br>
but one manuscript, dating from the twelfth century, which he had borrowed from his friend<br>
Reuchlin.  Unfortunately, this manuscript lacked the final leaf, which had contained the last<br>
six verses of the book.  For these verses, as well as a few other passages throughout the book<br>
where the Greek text of the Apocalypse and the adjoining Greek commentary with which the<br>
manuscript was supplied are so mixed up as to be almost indistinguishable, Erasmus depended<br>
upon the Latin Vulgate, translating this text into Greek.  As would be expected from such a<br>
procedure, here and there in Erasmus' self-made Greek text are readings which have never<br>
been found in any known Greek manuscript--but which are still perpetuated today in printings<br>
of the so-called Textus Receptus of the Greek New Testament." (pp. 99-100)  "Thus the text<br>
of Erasmus' Greek New Testament rests upon a half-dozen minuscule manuscripts.  The<br>
oldest and best of these manuscripts (codex 1, a minuscule of the tenth century, which agrees<br>
often with the earlier uncial text) he used least, because he was afraid of its supposedly<br>
erratic text!" (p. 100)<br>
<p>
Metzger proceeds to trace the controlling influence of Erasmus' "inferior" (p. 103) work, with<br>
its "spurious passage" (p. 101) in the third edition found in 1 John 5:8, upon the editions of<br>
Estienne (or Stephanus) and through him to Beze (or Beza) and the Elzevir brothers.  It was<br>
in the preface to the second edition of the Elzevir work that the expression "Textus<br>
Receptus", with the meaning "commonly received, standard text" (p. 106) appeared.  He<br>
concludes his remarks on this period of the history of the printed text in this way: "So<br>
superstitious has been the reverence accorded the Textus Receptus that in some case attempts<br>
to criticize or emend it have been regarded as akin to sacrilege.  Yet its textual basis is<br>
essentially a handful of late and haphazardly collected minuscule manuscripts, and in a dozen<br>
passages its reading is supported by no known Greek witness." (p. 106)<br>
<p>
Far from withdrawing my earlier remark about the "flawed Textus Receptus", I confidently<br>
join Metzger in repeating it with heightened crescendo.<br>
<p>
I am tempted to review the reasons why most scholars consider the type of text of the New<br>
Testament reflected in the Textus Receptus to be inferior to other forms of the text, but I will<br>
mercifully resist.  However, I must remind one respondent that the number of manuscripts<br>
supporting a particular reading, obviously extensive for later periods, is not considered to<br>
significant in deciding among variants.  The principle of most text critics is that you do not<br>
count manuscripts.  You weigh them.  That is, you examine the readings in the light of<br>
generally accepted observations on how texts change through transmission and copying, with<br>
the reasonable assumption that the changes generally move the text farther from the reading<br>
of the original.<br>
<p>
Warren C. Trenchard<br>
Internet: 70711.3366@compuserve.com<br>
CIS: 70711,3366<br>
<br>
