<!-- body="start" -->
Russell Yonkers asks "If the 'textus receptus' is as good as Ruben says it <br>
is, why not make a new modern translation based on it?"  This is exactly <br>
what was done with the New King James version.<br>
<p>
Ruben raised a question to me which I cannot answer since I do not have<br>
the source material available.  Namely, in which manuscripts does the<br>
second <br>
half of 1 John 5:8 not appear?  I am not well acquainted with the manuscripts<br>
and do not have any against which to compare.  I got this story from<br>
Alden Thompson's book but I do not even have that with me right now.<br>
If anyone can help I'll be grateful.<br>
<p>
In Ruben's message there was a long list of verses that are missing or<br>
footnoted in the NIV.  I checked in my NASB where all of them are<br>
footnoted <br>
as well, and in the NRSV.  So here are three recent modern translations<br>
which take the same approach to the text, as Ruben has alleged.  <br>
<p>
However, looking at those verses, I fail to see a doctrinal conspiracy<br>
in leaving them out.  You could take away every one of those verses and <br>
the Bible will still teach the Sabbath, the state of the dead, the second<br>
coming, name any doctrine you will.  I fail to see any true doctrines<br>
which have been stripped or any false doctrines added, with the possible<br>
exception<br>
of the reading of Rev 22:14 which has already been mentioned.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
