<title>Feb_1993: KJV</title>
<h1>KJV</h1>
GRUMLING DENNIS  (<i>LIBDKG@orion.depaul.edu</i>)<br>
<i>2 Feb 93 21:19:00 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#24">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#24">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#24">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#24">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0025.html">Malachi Robertson: "Daniel 9"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Steven Timm: "More on Bible translations"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I wasn't exposed much to the KJV as a child since I grew up in South America.  <br>
We had the debate about whether to use the Reina y Valera that Ruben mentioned, <br>
or the 1960 revision thereof.  Well, the original dates from 1569 and was <br>
revised by Valera in 1602, so you can imagine that the language is of the same <br>
style as the KJV.  Adventists in Argentina didn't seem to have much problem <br>
with accepting the revision.  They understood that the new version was easier <br>
to understand and that the younger generation now had an alternative.  Many of <br>
the older generation kept using the original because of habit and feeling <br>
comfortable with the words.<br>
<p>
A note to Ruben.  The Reina y Valera you find so accurate is a Catholic <br>
translation.  Not until the 1960 version sponsored by the International Bible <br>
Society did protestants have much say other than in leaving out the Apocrypha <br>
in their printings.<br>
<p>
I become concerned when we start making sweeping generalizations, or trying to <br>
make everything cut and dried.  Jesuits are not hiding under every bed, nor <br>
taking over the seminary--I should know, my dad is the Dean.  It is time that <br>
we all remembered that knowledge is best acquired first hand.  I would not call <br>
myself a scientist if I accepted what others say without checking it out <br>
myself, going to the sources, comparing other data, etc.  The same is true for <br>
the Bible.  Read as many versions as you can get your hands on, in as many <br>
languages as you are able.  You will multiply the ways the Word can reach your <br>
mind and heart, and the Holy Spirit will guide your understanding.<br>
<p>
Having given my pedigree, please let me add another warning.  Just because <br>
something purports to come from the Seminary doesn't necessarily make it an <br>
official communique, nor the truth.  Just as in any other academic institution, <br>
the faculty at the Seminary have their differences of opinion--sometimes <br>
marked.  They publish and present in different forums and sometimes debate each <br>
other verbally or in writing.  Until someone can show me that appointment to <br>
the seminary faculty endows one with the gift of prophecy, I will take what I <br>
hear and check it out in the Bible.<br>
<p>
On another topic entirely.  The abortion debate seems to be waning, and I do <br>
not mean to start another round of discussion in which people who already know <br>
what they think try to convince other people of equally fixed opinions.  My <br>
concern is this:  what are we doing as individuals and as a church to make <br>
abortion unnecessary?  What about the physical, financial, emotional support of <br>
the women/families with unplanned pregnancies?  What about family planning?  <br>
You see, I work as a nurse-midwife at a teen clinic.  We don't do abortions, <br>
but I provide family planning and prenatal care (among a lot of other things) <br>
to poor minority and-- oh dear!--unmarried teens.  I think that as SDA's we're <br>
so uncomfortable with the idea of non-marital sex that we don't even want to <br>
touch the issue, but we need to address it.  Some of the kids turning up in my <br>
clinic are SDA's.<br>
<p>
Ideas about practical christianity much appreciated.<br>
<p>
Heidi Vyhmeister Grumling<br>
 <br>
c/o<br>
Dennis K. Grumling<br>
Bitnet:  LIBDKG@DEPAUL<br>
Internet:  LIBDKG@ORION.DEPAUL.EDU<br>
