<title>Feb_1993: Daniel 9</title>
<h1>Daniel 9</h1>
Malachi Robertson (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 3 Feb 93 17:00:34 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#25">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#25">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#25">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#25">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Malachi Robertson: "Translations and EGW and RCC"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0024.html">GRUMLING DENNIS : "KJV"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here is what William Shea had to say about Daniel 9 and the verse in<br>
question (which I think was 26).  He quotes the RSV phrase "And the people<br>
of the prince who is to come shall destroy the city and the sanctuary". <br>
Shea takes the word for prince and sees it as fitting a pattern in the<br>
text.  In verse 25 one has Messiah Prince together, then in verse 26 the<br>
duo of words is split up.  As my own oberservation and one I think that<br>
Steve was running into is that the He who is cut off in the midst of the<br>
week appears to be the same Prince just mentioned in verse 26.  If one<br>
views the Prince to be the Messiah then there is no confusing the person<br>
cut off in the middle of the week as some Roman.  Shea also adds that the<br>
Romans come into the picture as the desolator mentioned later on.  Then to<br>
attempt to explain the verse that has the people of the Prince leading to<br>
the end of the city and sanctuary, Shea notes that while the Romans are<br>
the actual destoryers, the Jews themselves (the people) were the once who<br>
precipitated the destruction through their rebellion (against God and<br>
Romanv vassals).  He also points out how in 26 the end of the city and<br>
sanctuary are foreshadowed so to speak and in verse 27 the final part the<br>
end of the city and sanctuary come.  Just glancing at Maxwell I think his<br>
view of things is different than Shea's.  I hope this has been helpful. <br>
The source used here has been DARCS vol. 3 70 Weeks, Leviticus, Nature of<br>
Prophecy with the specific article being "The Prophecy of Daniel (:24-27"<br>
by William Shea pp. 75-118. <br>
Ian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
