<title>Feb_1993: Copyrights on EGW</title>
<h1>Copyrights on EGW</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  3 Feb 1993 22:41:31 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#27">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#27">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#27">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#27">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0028.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Discussions of theories and evidence"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Malachi Robertson: "Translations and EGW and RCC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Ruben Gonzales]<br>
Hi all,<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; That's a very interesting comment for you must infer then that all of EGW's</i><br>
<i>&gt; writings are also "man's word" because they were copyrighted.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
	I think you will find that EGW's original texts are not copyrighted,<br>
only the editorial changes to those texts are. That is what the<br>
copyright notice<br>
on the books represent.<br>
<p>
[No, try again.  The initial works were copyright.  Some, but not all<br>
of the copyrights have expired by now.  A large amount of royalties<br>
have been paid to the EGW estate over the years.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<p>
As far as the point I made regarding copyright, which I know seems absurd at<br>
first glance, how about looking past the initial reaction at what the effect<br>
of the copyright really has on scripture.<br>
<p>
If in Tyndales, or Luther's day the scriptures had been copyrighted there would<br>
have been no reformation would there ?<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
