<title>Feb_1993: Discussions of theories and evidence</title>
<h1>Discussions of theories and evidence</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>04 Feb 1993 12:09:29 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#28">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#28">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#28">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#28">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Copyrights and God's Word"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Steven Timm: "Copyrights on EGW"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Carson in his book "The KJV Debate: A Plea for Realism" makes the following<br>
statement:<br>
<p>
...This theory is being presented in popular literature to pastors<br>
and laymen everywhere, may of whom have never read a rebuttal at the<br>
same level and who are not equipped to do the more advanced work that<br>
demonstrates the theory to be false.<br>
<p>
Here Carson is referring to a list of theses used by promoters of the<br>
TR to show the superiority of the TR and its derivatives, and to <br>
denigrate more recent Bible versions which use Alexandrian texts as<br>
well as the Byzantinne texts. The books "Which Bible?", "God wrote<br>
only one Bible" and numerous tract-type publications are among those<br>
Carson sees as being one-sided amongst other things.<br>
<p>
Unfortunately the problem of theories being presented etc. etc. is not<br>
restricted to the debate of Bible versions. There are many instances<br>
particularly in this day and age of media hype where this is done, be<br>
it by politicians, companies, or whoever. It's quite easy to oversimplify<br>
an issue and maybe paint certain parties as imbeciles when you are<br>
determined to back only one side of that issue.<br>
<p>
Even Christians can be guilty of this. Pick any debate such as the<br>
origins issue, this Bible versions discussion, probably the abortion<br>
discussion (I don't know about that SDAnet series, because I was away<br>
when it was on), anything you like, and you will find this being done.<br>
<p>
The discerning individual is forced, then, to either reserve judgment<br>
or to do some eclectic reading of their own, since the most 'convincing'<br>
arguments are usually those which ignore part of a complex issue.<br>
Unfortunately none of us have time to fully investigate some of these<br>
things, particularly when it is realized that various individuals have<br>
devoted their entire lives to the study of any given one of them.<br>
<p>
Fortunately we also have some help...'If anyone lack wisdom, let him<br>
ask of God...'<br>
<p>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
