Hi all,<br>
<p>
	Russell says :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; This was done at great expense ot the companies involved and they</i><br>
<i>&gt; need to try to protect thier investment so that they can make a profit and </i><br>
<i>&gt; stay afloat.  These are produced by companies that need to make money. </i><br>
<p>
This is a very good point. Lets just consider the factors of marketing for a <br>
moment.<br>
<p>
I personally don't think God's Word is to be made into a commodity, neither<br>
do I believe in making a profit out of God's Word, that amounts to Simony<br>
in my books. (And beleive the the publishers of the modern translations<br>
are making a killing)<br>
<p>
If you had to produce an item, for sale is it not true that you would market<br>
it in order to please the vast majority and make them buy. Even if this meant<br>
leaving out important features and introducing gimmicks into it to help it sell?<br>
<p>
In our case the market it ecumenical, what implications does this have on our<br>
product.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
