<title>Feb_1993: Re: More on Bible translations</title>
<h1>Re: More on Bible translations</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Feb 93 13:33:13 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#31">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#31">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#31">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#31">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Steven Timm: "On the Text of the New Testament"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: Copyrighting means "not inspired?""</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0041.html">David E. Johnson: "More on Bible translations"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
	Steve rightly says that he "fail to see a doctrinal conspiracy<br>
in leaving them out" [some verses].<br>
<p>
The point was not in that there was a conspiracy in leaving them out but they<br>
were omitted from the Siniaticus and Vaticanus because of the poor quality<br>
of the scribe and the texts themselves.<br>
<p>
However there is a conspiracy and now I will reveal it. I will present<br>
three readings of each selected verse, KJV, Douay, and NIV you can judge for<br>
yourselves.<br>
<p>
MAtt 5:44<br>
<p>
KJV 	"But I say unto you, Love your enemies, _bless_them_That_curse_you_, do <br>
	good to them that hate you, pray for those that despitefully use you,<br>
	and persecute you."<br>
DOUAY	"But I say unto you, Love your enemies, ***************************, do <br>
	good to them that hate you, pray for them that persecute and<br>
	calumnate you."<br>
NIV 	"But I tell you, Love your enemies, ***************************, <br>
	and pray for they that persecute you."<br>
<p>
<p>
The phrase _bless_them_That_curse_you_ is omitted from both the Douay and NIV,<br>
the DOUAY is a direct transaltion from the Vulgate.<br>
<p>
Luke 2:33<br>
<p>
KJV	"And _Joseph_ and his mother marvelled at those things which were <br>
	spoken of him." <br>
DOUAY	"And his father and his mother were wondering at those things which were<br>
 	spoken concerning him."<br>
NIV	"The child's father and his mother marvelled at what was said about him."<br>
<p>
Once again the NIV follows the Douay and gives Jesus a human father!<br>
<p>
Luke 4:8<br>
<p>
KJV	"And Jesus answered and said unto him, _get_thee_behind_me,_Satan_: for<br>
	it is written, Thou shalt worship the Lord thy God, and him only shalt<br>
	thou serve."<br>
DOUAY	"And Jesus answering him said to him, *****************************<br>
	It is written, Thou shalt adore the Lord thy God, and him only shalt<br>
	thou serve."<br>
NIV	"Jesus answered, ******************* *****************************<br>
	It is written, Thou shalt adore the Lord your God, and serve him only."<br>
<p>
The reason why the Douay omitted the words _get_thee_behind_me,_Satan_ is <br>
because Rome hates them because Jesus later used these words regarding Peter<br>
(MArr 16:23) and so this verse destroys Romes notion of Peter as the rock.<br>
Why then does the NIV omit them, is it for the same reason ? The NIV follows<br>
in the footsteps of Rome because it is based on the Vaticanus and Siniaticus.<br>
<p>
1 Cor 15:47<br>
<p>
KJV	"The first man is of the earth, earthy: the second man is _the _Lord_<br>
	from heaven."<br>
DOUAY	"The first man was, of the earth, earthly: the second man *********<br>
	from heaven, heavenly."<br>
NIV	"The first man was of the dust of the earth, the second man *********<br>
	from heaven."<br>
<p>
Who is this man ? why does these other two versions hide the fact it is the <br>
Lord himself?<br>
<p>
Eph 3:9<br>
<p>
KJV	"And to make all men see what is the fellowship of the mystery, which <br>
	from the beginnning of the world hath been hid in God, _who_created_<br>
	_all_things_by_Jesus_Christ_."<br>
DOUAY	"And to enlighten all men that they may see what is the dispensation<br>
	of the mystery, which has been hidden from eternity in God, <br>
	who created all things."<br>
KJV	"And to make plain to everyone the administration of this mystery, which<br>
	for ages past was kept hidden in God who created all things.<br>
<p>
Here we have a denial of the fact that it was Jesus who created all things.<br>
Now this is a key scripture for confirming Jesus as teh creator and establishing<br>
his pre-existance.<br>
<p>
I could go on, there are many more verses like this, that support the Vulgate<br>
and its multitude of errors, I will if I get a request, otherwise I think<br>
the point is suitably demonstrated.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
