<title>Feb_1993: On the Text of the New Testament</title>
<h1>On the Text of the New Testament</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  3 Feb 1993 22:50:08 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#32">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#32">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#32">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#32">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0033.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Scholars, intellectuals and believers"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: More on Bible translations"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0037.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: On the Text of the New Testament"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; One thing that puzzles me about the current discussion is the authorities </i><br>
<i>&gt; cited.  I have yet to see the name of a scholar who is generally considered </i><br>
<i>&gt; to be a first order authority on New Testament textual criticism.</i><br>
<p>
I believe you will find this to be true only because none of the authorities<br>
cited are contempory ones, as in they are all dead.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; [...whole lot of current authorities cited... .]</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
It might be interesting if you could tell us the affiliations of these<br>
authorites, and how enthusiastic they are personally regarding the<br>
ecumenical movement and its Roman trend.<br>
<p>
Remember the two most eminient authorities (in their day) Westcott and<br>
Hort also hated the Textus Receptus and the reason we well know, becuase<br>
they were Romanists through and through.<br>
<p>
It is well to say that these current scholars reject the notion of the <br>
superiority of hte Textus Receptus, but saying so means nothing at all to me,<br>
so did Westcott and Hort and friends. When it comes to current scholars<br>
it would be well to know their theological leanings.<br>
<p>
I don't share your feelings that requesting evidence is confrontational.<br>
Without supporting evidence opinions are of no weight, and to a large extent<br>
useless. I ask for evidence because only in this way can one learn and bring<br>
to light the truth which many times is buried under the traditions of men.<br>
<p>
As for Metzger's attack on Erasmus and his work, I am affraid it is his word<br>
against the word of many others.<br>
<p>
Now you may not have heard of Dr.F.C. Cook but considering his position as<br>
the Chaplan to Q.E. and being invited to sit on the Revision committee, I would<br>
suspect that he has sufficent authority to comment. You read his testimony<br>
supporting the T.R. I can get you many others like his if you like, but I need<br>
not, EGW who has the highest authority in this respect confirms his word.<br>
Now if an an SDA I am to choose between the Spirit of Prophecy and a <br>
current (protestant/Catholic/liberal/ecumenical, whichever fits) scholar<br>
you know which one I will choose.<br>
<p>
You quote from Metzger that various readings found in the KJV are not supported<br>
by any other Greek text. is he here refering to Rev 22:14, I hope he is not<br>
for in that case he would be grossly in error. As for Erasmus' supposed use of <br>
only a "handful of late and haphazardly collected minuscule manuscripts"<br>
I think<br>
once again I should quote from Dr Cook<br>
<p>
<p>
"That textus receptus was taken in the first instance, from late cursive <br>
manuscripts; but its readings are maintained only so far as they agree with<br>
the earliest and best Greek and Latin Fathers, and with the vast majority of <br>
unical and cursive manuscipts." Revised Version of the first three<br>
Gospels, p226<br>
<p>
Who are we to believe ? In the current ecumenical atmosphere I know who I will<br>
believe. Metzger calls Erasmus' work  "inferior" EGW endorses this same<br>
work saying it corrected the errors of the existing texts. Whom should we <br>
believe ?<br>
<p>
Ganted that EGW never had such as distinguished title recognised by the world<br>
but she had another title recognised in heaven. <br>
<p>
<p>
I have shown that all other texts originate from and are supported by<br>
and in turn support the RCC and the Latin Vulgate. This family of texts<br>
sets itself understandibly against the T.R. which does not originate from<br>
the RCC. We know how the RCC views the scripture, we have but one of two<br>
roads to take, the one that leads to Rome, or the road of the Reformation.<br>
<p>
[You have not shown this.  You have asserted it many times but this is <br>
not the same.  You have not shown that the Sinaiticus/Vaticanus codices are<br>
the primary ones used in the modern translations.  You have not shown where<br>
the modern translations follow the Vulgate, only asserted.  You have<br>
not shown that any of the changes that you listed save Rev. 22:14 make<br>
any doctrinal difference whatsoever.  You have not shown that Erasmus<br>
was free from RCC influences in compiling the TR.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The principle of most text critics is that you do not count manuscripts.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; You weigh them.  That is, you examine the readings in the light of generally </i><br>
<i>&gt; accepted observations on how texts change through transmission and copying, </i><br>
<i>&gt; with the reasonable assumption that the changes generally move the text </i><br>
<i>&gt; farther from the reading of the original.</i><br>
<p>
What this  in effect is saying, is that one must take the testimony of<br>
the Vaticanus and ths Siniaticus over and above the testimony of all<br>
other texts. In this case then do you think the Apocrypha including<br>
such masterly works as "Bel and the Dragon" and the Epistle of St. Barnabus<br>
(which you have all had a change to admire) should be found in all bibles ?<br>
<p>
As for antiquity why is it then that while Rev 22:14 is quoted as per<br>
the KJV back in 200AD before the date of these other two MSS which have a <br>
wrong readings it is ignored and preference given to the clearly erroneous<br>
texts ?<br>
<p>
I do not think that one has the right to ignore the bulk of testimony which is<br>
to the contrary, and choose a singluar reading just because it suits the <br>
translator(s) best.<br>
<p>
This principle raises some interesting questions then in light of the <br>
two MSS which have been endosed by some as being more reliable and older.<br>
Let me quote some more for you regarding these texts, which are set up in<br>
opposition to the T.R.<br>
<p>
Dr. Scrivener says speaking of the 2556 omission in the Vaticanus<br>
"..That no small proportion of those are mere oversights of the scribe seems <br>
evident from the circumstance that this same scribe has repeatedly written <br>
words and clauses twice over, a class of mistakes which Mai and the collators <br>
have seldom thought fit to notice, insomuch as the false addition has not been <br>
retraced by the second hand, but which by no means enhances our estimate of <br>
the care employed in copying this veneranle record of primitive Christianity"<br>
			"Introduction", Vol.1. p.120<br>
<p>
Dr Scrivener published a book regarding the Siniaticus entitled<br>
"A full Collation of the Codex Siniaticus," and in his introduction he writes :<br>
"The Codex is covered with such alterations {obviously of a textual nature}<br>
brought in by at least ten different revisers, some of them systematically<br>
spread over every page, others occasional or limited to separate portions<br>
of the manuscript, many of them being comtemporaneous with the first writer,<br>
far the greater part belonging to the sixth or seventh century." p.XIX<br>
<p>
Here is a quote from Philip Mauro regarding the quality of the Siniaticus,<br>
"But there are other characteristics of this old MS which have to be taken into<br>
consideration if a correct estimate of its evidential value is to be reached.<br>
Thus, there are internal evidences that lead to the conclusion that it was the <br>
work of a scribe who was singularly careless, or incompetent, or both. In <br>
this MS the arrangement of the lines is peculiar, there being four columns<br>
on each page, each line containing about twelve letters - all capitals run <br>
together. There is no attempt to end a word at the end of a line, for even<br>
words having two letters as en, ek, are split in the middle, the last letter<br>
being carried over to the beginning of hte next line, though there was ample <br>
room for it on the line preceeding. This and other peculiarities give us an <br>
idea of the character and competence of the scribe"  "which Version", p.45<br>
<p>
Here is a bit more about the reliability of the Siniaticus from Dr. Scrivener<br>
"This manuscript must have been derived from one more ancient, in which the <br>
lines were similarly divided, since the writer occasionally omits just the <br>
number of letters which would suffice to fill a line, and that to the utter<br>
ruin of the sense; as if his eye had heedlessly wandered to the line <br>
immediately below. Instances of this want of care will be found Luke 21:8;<br>
22:25. perhaps John 4:45; 12:25, where complete lines are omitted; John 19:26; <br>
Heb 13:18 (partly corrected); Apoc 8:16; 19:12; 22:2, where the copyist passed <br>
in teh middle of a line to the corresponding portion of teh line below. It must<br>
 be confessed, indeed, that the Codex Siniaticus abounds with similar errors of<br>
 eye and pen, to an extent not unparalleled, but hapily rather unsusual in <br>
documents of first rate importance."  "Collation on the Codex Siniaticus" P.XV<br>
<p>
Now in light of these observations in transmssion and copying how can anybody<br>
state that these texts are more reliable. And even if they were faithful to<br>
the original MS from which they eminate that would only further condemn<br>
them because as I have demonstrated they originate with Origen, Constantine<br>
and Esubius who were most interested in purverting the scriptures in order<br>
to facilitate the ecumenical movement at the time of uniting Christianity<br>
with pagansim.<br>
<p>
These text support the readings of the LAtin Vulgate (obviously) and<br>
so by EGW's own condemnation we know that they are not more relyable but<br>
more erroneous than the T.R. which _corrected_ these errors.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
