<title>Feb_1993: Scholars, intellectuals and believers</title>
<h1>Scholars, intellectuals and believers</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>04 Feb 1993 15:46:15 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#33">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#33">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#33">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#33">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Reina y Valera"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Steven Timm: "On the Text of the New Testament"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Believe it or not, there are many scholars in the world who do their<br>
darndest to discover the truth about something, rather than merely<br>
using their title as a "scholar" or an "intellectual" to advance a<br>
previously held belief or theory.<br>
<p>
<p>
It is unfair to fire a broad accusation at a range of scholars to the<br>
effect that their own theological position or belief will necessarily<br>
influence their work, and possibly invalidate it. There have been<br>
demonstrable instances where this *has* occurred, such as early<br>
attempts to 'gnosticize' the scripture, or to promote aryan views.<br>
This does not, however, imply that all or even the majority of<br>
scholars operate this way.<br>
<p>
Whether or not Westcott &amp; Hort, Fee and others were Romanists,<br>
whether or not they were all supporters of the ecumenical movement<br>
I do not know. Judging their scholarship and professionalism is<br>
another thing altogether.<br>
<p>
Remember - Erasmus *never left* the Catholic church, not even<br>
after four or five editions of his printed Greek scripture.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
