<p>
*From          Dan Wheeler &lt;WHEELER@UCBEH.BITNET&gt; Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990<br>
*From:         Dan Wheeler &lt;WHEELER@UCBEH.BITNET&gt;<br>
*Subject:      Being moderator from VMS or Unix systems<br>
*Date:         Sun, 23 Feb 1992 12:17:00 EST<br>
<p>
I'm trying to switch a list over to being moderated.  The<br>
LISTSERVer sends the messages to me with a "moderator paragraph"<br>
at the top instructing me to forward the message back to the list<br>
if it is ok.  I have access to either a Vax/VMS or Unix system.<br>
<p>
With VMSmail, when I FORWARD the message back to the list, it<br>
converts the incoming mail header to text.  In other words, it<br>
goes back with a new header on it and a blank line before the old<br>
header.  The information in the original header is lost to the<br>
LISTSERVer and the big, ugly header appears in the text.<br>
<p>
On the Unix system, I use ELM.  The FORWARD command does<br>
essentially the same thing: the incoming header is converted to<br>
text.  The BOUNCE command sends the message on with the original<br>
header intact.  But for some reason, the LISTSERVer does not<br>
remove the "moderator paragraph."  I have attached below a sample<br>
of a message (as posted to the list) which was sent back by the<br>
editor using the ELM command BOUNCE.<br>
<p>
Does anyone have any useful suggestions?  How do other people act<br>
as list editors from non-VM/CMS systems?<br>
<p>
                          Peace,  Dan<br>
<p>
&lt;&lt;  Daniel D. Wheeler          Internet:  Dan.Wheeler@UC.Edu  &gt;&gt;<br>
&lt;&lt;  University of Cincinnati     Bitnet:  wheeler@ucbeh       &gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
