<title>Feb_1993: Re: On the Text of the New Testament</title>
<h1>Re: On the Text of the New Testament</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Feb 93 17:54:40 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#37">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#37">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#37">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#37">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Copyrights and God's Word (fwd)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Steven Timm: "Fwd: unix listserv - file 4"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0032.html">Steven Timm: "On the Text of the New Testament"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I have shown that all other texts originate from and are supported by</i><br>
<i>&gt; and in turn support the RCC and the Latin Vulgate. This family of texts</i><br>
<i>&gt; sets itself understandibly against the T.R. which does not originate from</i><br>
<i>&gt; the RCC. We know how the RCC views the scripture, we have but one of two</i><br>
<i>&gt; roads to take, the one that leads to Rome, or the road of the Reformation.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; [You have not shown this.  You have asserted it many times but this is </i><br>
<i>&gt; not the same.  You have not shown that the Sinaiticus/Vaticanus codices are</i><br>
<i>&gt; the primary ones used in the modern translations. </i><br>
<p>
<p>
That the Siniaticus/Vaticanus is the primary text used in the RSV is beyond<br>
contention. Most of the quotes I have presented are direct arguments<br>
against Westcott and Hort's text which relied almost exclusively on<br>
these to MSS. Dr. Cook's testimony is particularly relevant since he was<br>
chosen to sit on the review committee and he refused, later publishing<br>
his views in his book "Revised Version of the First three Gospels."<br>
<p>
"But it is precisely on this ground that I have throughtout maintained<br>
the wrongfulness of the innovations introduced into the Revised Version,<br>
so far as they affect leading facts and great words recorded in the first<br>
three gospels. The reader need but look at the passages enumerated in the<br>
classification given above, p.136 seq., to be convinced that so far from<br>
resting upon the consentient testimony of ancient manuscripts, Versions,<br>
and Fathers by far the greater number of innovations, including those which<br>
give teh severest shocks to our minds, are adopted on the authority of<br>
two manuscripts (Vaticanus and Siniaticus), or even of one manuscript, against<br>
the distinct testimony of all other manuscripts, unicial and cursive." p.227<br>
<p>
I do not thing anybody will disagree that the Vat. and Sin. MSS were those<br>
principly used by Westcott and Hort in the RSV. If someone still doubts<br>
I can bring further testimony to bear. <br>
<p>
It can be simply shown that the other new translations are also derived<br>
from Westcott and Hort's Greek text simply by comparing the variant readings<br>
if they agree with this text then they are derived from it because<br>
as has been repeatedly demonstrated all the other MSS disagree with many<br>
of the variant readings it contains. This can be further demonstrated by<br>
taking note of the omissions, if a version omits the same text as the<br>
Westcott and Hort text then it is derived from it.<br>
<p>
Lets see the NIV has a note after Mark 16:8 it says<br>
"The two most reliable early manuscipts do not have Mark 16:9-20"<br>
<p>
Which two MSS do we think these are ? Well we are not left to ponder too much<br>
because if we go to the Note in the NKJV alongside this same passage we read<br>
<p>
"They are lacking in Codex Siniaticus and Codex Vaticanus, although nearly<br>
all other manuscripts of Mark contain them."<br>
<p>
How very interesting, so the only authority the Translators of the NIV had<br>
to omit these verses was the Vat. and Sin. MSS. Do you think that is good<br>
enough a reason to "take away the words of this book" ?<br>
<p>
<p>
Granted that maybe instead of saying all I should have said most, but the fact<br>
still remains. <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; You have not shown where</i><br>
<i>&gt; the modern translations follow the Vulgate, only asserted. </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
 <br>
You have seen in my other post how the newer translations<br>
parallel the Latin Vulgate. Would you like some more evidence ?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; You have</i><br>
<i>&gt; not shown that any of the changes that you listed save Rev. 22:14 make</i><br>
<i>&gt; any doctrinal difference whatsoever. </i><br>
<p>
Are you suggesting that removing the condition of keeping the commandments<br>
for salvation makes _no_ doctrinal difference ?<br>
<p>
The verse as it reads in the new translations is meaningless, so what if I do<br>
the washing, that will have no impact on salvation. Note that the changed <br>
version does not say "wash their robes in the blood of the Lamb" had it<br>
said this then it would have at least made some sense.<br>
<p>
The amount of difference it makes, even though it is important still does<br>
not alter the fact that the Word of God was willfully altered. Even if this<br>
was the only occurance this would be sufficent, to look at the text suspiciously.<br>
<p>
What does Dan 7 say regarding those who whould "think to change the times and<br>
the laws" ?<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; You have not shown that Erasmus</i><br>
<i>&gt; was free from RCC influences in compiling the TR.  SCT]</i><br>
<p>
No you are right in this point I have not, I believe EGW's testimony suffices<br>
for me in this regard. Also the point that he was in continual trouble with<br>
the RCC endorses it. Of course he may not be compeletely free was Martin Luther<br>
or Tyndale, to what extent any of us are free from the environment we live<br>
in and our own history is very hard to tell. The point is that EGW tells us<br>
that God used him to do a work, and that work was to supply a bible cleared<br>
from many of the errors present in the Vulgate.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
