<title>Feb_1993: Copyrights and God's Word (fwd)</title>
<h1>Copyrights and God's Word (fwd)</h1>
Randall A Helzerman (<i>helz@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Feb 93 1:25:54 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Getting rich"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: On the Text of the New Testament"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I personally don't think God's Word is to be made into a commodity, neither</i><br>
<i>&gt; do I believe in making a profit out of God's Word, that amounts to Simony</i><br>
<i>&gt; in my books.</i><br>
<p>
Hey Ruben, _Simony???_  Lighten up!  I can sympathize with your desire in <br>
getting God's word out as cheaply as possible.  In fact, I've got an Uncle <br>
who has spent the last 20 years full-time printing Bibles gratis.<br>
<p>
However, just think for a moment what it would require for there to be<br>
_no profit_ made out of a Bible.<br>
<p>
Printers work gratis.<br>
Paper makers work gratis.<br>
Timbercutters work gratis.<br>
Chainsaw dealers work gratis.<br>
The people who make the screws which go into chainsaws work gratis.<br>
etc. etc. etc.<br>
<p>
The free-market is simply a device to get large groups of people who<br>
don't even know each other to nevertheless cooperate together.  What's<br>
more its the most efficient method so far invented.  And the engine of <br>
the free-market is the profit motive.  There are people, like my uncle,<br>
who operate for reasons other than pure profit and greed, but even he<br>
needs to eat and that requires money which requires that _somebody_<br>
makes a profit to donate to him.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If you had to produce an item, for sale is it not true that you would market</i><br>
<i>&gt; it in order to please the vast majority and make them buy. Even if this meant</i><br>
<i>&gt; leaving out important features and introducing gimmicks into it to help it</i><br>
<i>&gt;  sell?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; In our case the market it ecumenical, what implications does this have on our</i><br>
<i>&gt; product.</i><br>
<p>
Here again I think you're shadow boxing.  The neat thing about God is that<br>
he doesn't have to rely on man's institutions in order to preserve the<br>
integrity of his word.  God won't let his word get conformed to the<br>
tastes of people; he transforms the tasts of people to his word.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
