<title>Feb_1993: More on Bible translations</title>
<h1>More on Bible translations</h1>
David E. Johnson (<i>71172.2044@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>04 Feb 93 02:59:04 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Russell Yonkers: "who I am"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Erasmus"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0031.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: More on Bible translations"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve writes:<br>
<i>&gt;Ruben raised a question to me which I cannot answer since I do not have</i><br>
<i>&gt;the source material available.  Namely, in which manuscripts does the</i><br>
<i>&gt;second half of 1 John 5:8 not appear?  I am not well acquainted with the </i><br>
manuscripts<br>
<i>&gt;and do not have any against which to compare.</i><br>
<p>
I've nearly decided that there is no point in arguing with Ruben, as we <br>
clearly have different perspectives on the issue... Every doctrine can be <br>
supported by a host of other texts and by the internal (theological) <br>
consistency of scripture. We need to be less fixated on the words, and and <br>
more fixed on the Word. I am all for an accurate rendition of scripture in <br>
any language (including Greek, Hebrew and Aramaic), but I am more for clear <br>
understanding and practice of its principals. The bottom line: keep <br>
reading, and read widely. The modern translations won't grease the path to <br>
hell, and are far more likely to help you ask questions and probe for <br>
answers to the bigger questions of life.<br>
<p>
Your question on 1Jn 5:8 is phrased better if you ask "What manuscripts do <br>
contain the second half of 1Jn 5:8?". Bruce Metzger, in "A Textual <br>
<p>
only 4; and comments that had the early church fathers known it, they would <br>
have certainly used it in the Trinitarian controversies... These 4 (in the <br>
arcane cataloging of Greek scholarship) are:<br>
<p>
ms. 61, 	16th century, held in Dublin.<br>
ms. 629,	14/15th century, held in the Vatican.<br>
ms. 88,	12 century, held in Naples. The passage in question is <br>
"written in the margin in a modern hand".<br>
ms. 635,	11th century, the passage is written in the margin "in a <br>
17th century hand".<br>
<p>
Metzger has two additional books, "The Text of the New Testament, its <br>
Transmission, Corruption, and Restoration" (Oxford, Clarendon Press 1964), <br>
and "The Early Versions of the New Testament, their Origin, Transmission, <br>
and Limitations" (Oxford, Clarendon 1975) that may help if you can find <br>
them.<br>
<p>
I have often wished for a CDROM containing these original manuscripts, as <br>
well as the early historical sources. What some spent years collating could <br>
be done in minutes, leaving the time for more serious issues in textual <br>
reconstruction. Unfortunately some issues (style and dating) aren't <br>
resolved without access to at least facsimile copies of the works. For <br>
another step out on the limb, how about additional CDROMs with facsimiles <br>
of EGW's works? Interesting issues of editorial process...<br>
<p>
Hope this helps<br>
<p>
Dave J<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
