<title>Feb_1993: Ruben, commandment keeping and just. by faith</title>
<h1>Ruben, commandment keeping and just. by faith</h1>
Russell Yonkers (<i>ryonkers@mis.mi04.zds.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Feb 93 8:06:18 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Cam Litvin: "RE: Translations and EGW and RCC"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Russell Yonkers: "who I am"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was reading one of Rubens messages this morning and saw a very interesting<br>
and troublesome point made.  This had to do with a verse that tells us that<br>
we are only able to claim salvation by keeping the commandments. (This is a<br>
paraphrase and if I am wrong feel free to correct me Ruben)  I have been<br>
reciently doing some in depth studies into rightousness or justification<br>
by faith and find that the statement of the necessity of keeping the <br>
commandments for salvation is in sharp contradiction to a true understanding <br>
of rightousness by faith.  As a matter of fact the idea of being able to do<br>
things for our salvation is in the same vain as the theology of the Catholic<br>
church.  I don't want to make this a extremly large letter or dissertation on<br>
the subject mainly do to the fact that I need to get back to work soon but<br>
I have started a manuscript that I would be happy to send to anyone on this <br>
topic.  <br>
<p>
This primary point however is that according to scripture we are not saved<br>
in the least by what we do short of simply accepting the work of Christ on <br>
the cross.  This is amply shown both in scripture and in the writings of <br>
EGW.  God did ALL the work that brings us to salvation.  This is also what<br>
is refered to when it says in scripture that no unholy or unclean thing will <br>
enter the new jeruselum (sp).  We are made clean through the shed blood of <br>
Jesus Christ and it is in this that we are no longer unclean or unholy.  This<br>
is the gospel that was protected by the Waldensians and restored to prominance<br>
by the Reformation.  It is also the message that we need to proclaim if we<br>
are indeed the true continuation of the reformation that we claim.  <br>
<p>
This is not to be viewed as an excuse to continue in sin and do whatever <br>
we want.  But our lives after salvation is the work of sanctification and <br>
growth not the work of justification and salvation.  We are told over and over<br>
that our lives will be a constant struggle against Satan until Jesus comes<br>
again but that there can be victory.  This only can come however through the<br>
work of the Holy Spirit AFTER our salvation and acceptance into Gods courts!<br>
<p>
I have probably just opened a huge debate, however it is only through discussion<br>
and debate and study that we can ever discover the truth.<br>
<p>
As I have said, if anyone would like a copy of the manuscript that I am working<br>
on just email me and I will be happy to send it out.  I would saw however that <br>
this material is copyright by me and hopefully will be a book some day soon.<br>
(I have to have some way to feed my wife and 6 kids!)  So I would appriciate <br>
it be treated as such. ... Well since it is such a small section of the whole<br>
it probably wouldn't be such trouble if it is disseminated.  However please<br>
keep all references to author intact (that I would appriciate).<br>
<p>
YHS Russell<br>
<p>
__________________________________________________________________________<br>
"If we allow christians to pray at high school graduations then we also<br>
need to allow buddists, hindus, muslims and satanists the same rights.<br>
This is the true meaning of religious freedom and why seperation of<br>
church and state is so important."<br>
__________________________________________________________________________<br>
