<title>Feb_1993: Bible versions</title>
<h1>Bible versions</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Feb 93 13:27:17 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#45">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#45">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#45">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#45">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0046.html">David Plaisted: "second attempt to post this, in case you didn't get it : Bible versions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Cam Litvin: "RE: Translations and EGW and RCC"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0003.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Bible versions"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Since so many words are flying about this, let me add some more.<br>
The moderator of the newsgroup Soc.religion.christian said that<br>
there were still some very competent scholars who support the<br>
superiority of the Textus Receptus (in the general sense, not in<br>
the specific version of Erasmus).  Also, I think one's view of<br>
the Bible influences the discussion.  Modern (``liberal''?)<br>
scholars view the books of the Bible as having a late origin, I<br>
believe, and not representing literal truth.  I view the books<br>
as having an early origin and representing literal narratives, in<br>
general.  So this has a tremendous influence in how you look at<br>
the Bible versions.  Does  the Bible just represent the early Christian<br>
community's attempt to symbolically portray spiritual reality?  Or<br>
is it a literal narrative dating from early times?  In the former<br>
case I suppose you look for an authentic statement of the community,<br>
which could arise much later.  In the latter case you look for the<br>
earliest versions which most closely approximate the truth.  In<br>
the former case the writings of the church fathers etc. might not<br>
be relevant because they don't necessarily represent what the<br>
community thinks.  In the latter case they are evidence of what<br>
the earliest manuscripts said.  And so on ...<br>
<p>
I would like to see the basis on which the modern scholars weigh<br>
the manuscripts instead of counting them.<br>
<p>
I'd hate to have some of the apocrypha in the Bible.  I think it<br>
waters it down with some questionable material and calls its<br>
credibility into question.<br>
<p>
I'm thankful that we can trust in the Lord!!!<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
