<title>Feb_1993: second attempt to post this, in case you didn't get it : Bible versions</title>
<h1>second attempt to post this, in case you didn't get it : Bible versions</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Feb 93 13:19:01 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Adventism &amp; Romanism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">David Plaisted: "Bible versions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to Warren Trenchard's comments, I would recall what the<br>
Jews said about Jesus.  ``Which of the leading men have believed in<br>
Him?'' or words to that effect.  A friend of mine has looked into some<br>
of the supposed best scholars treatments of the Bible versions and<br>
found some surprising arguments.  For example, one said that historical<br>
evidence is to be discounted.  By this he means, it doesn't matter which<br>
versions the church fathers quoted or which versions appeared in<br>
early lectionaries (church services).  But, that's important evidence<br>
about the ages of the versions.  If I accepted the opinions of most<br>
leading scholars I would believe that Jesus never rose from the dead<br>
and that there is no life after death.  This includes the scholars in<br>
the leading seminaries.  I heard once that over 90 percent of the<br>
studets graduating from leading seminaries no longer believe in the<br>
literal resurrection of Christ.  This includes the new preachers in<br>
Protestant and Catholic churches, I understand.  You can imagine what<br>
influence this is having on the churches.  And, as Adventists, we<br>
are sending our seminary students to other universities to get<br>
advanced degrees, from where this kind of teaching can easily come<br>
into our own church.  So, when you understand the situation in the<br>
seminaries and universities of the land, and realize how few there<br>
are who really believe the Bible is inspired or that the miracles<br>
reported in the New Testament really occurred, it's not surprising<br>
when their opinions do not seem to accord with our perception of<br>
reality. I would also comment that in the last days, the leading<br>
men of education and culture will be supporting the mark of the<br>
beast, according to my understanding of the prophecies of the<br>
book of Revelation.  Will we follow the opinions of the leading<br>
scholars then, or the Word of God?  On the other hand, we should<br>
not discount the opinions of the scholars also, if their arguments<br>
make sense.  Thus the need to dig deeper than to say that all the<br>
leading scholars support a particular point of view.<br>
<p>
        Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
