<title>Feb_1993: Adventism &amp; Romanism</title>
<h1>Adventism &amp; Romanism</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>05 Feb 1993 09:51:38 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#47">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#47">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#47">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#47">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Fred Christiansen: "pregnant teens"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0046.html">David Plaisted: "second attempt to post this, in case you didn't get it : Bible versions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here is a quote I found interesting...<br>
<p>
"If Adventism is not ardent evangelicalism or typical cultism then how<br>
shall it be classified? The evidence supports Dr. Lindsell's judgment<br>
that it is similar to Romanism. Like Romanism Adventism has added to<br>
the Scripture a body of tradition it seems reluctant to break. Like<br>
Romanism Adventism depreciates the completeness of Christ's work of<br>
atonement, and like Romanism Adventism adds to grace the necessity<br>
of human works as a condition of salvation. Needless to say, both<br>
Adventism and Romanism assert the deity of Christ, His atonement for<br>
sinners, and His resurrection from the dead. In other respects their<br>
systems may not be analogous except in asserting that the Pope changed<br>
the day of worship, but these are highly significant.<br>
<p>
The error of Romanism and Adventism resembles that of the Galatians."<br>
<p>
Lewis, Gordon R., "The Bible, the Christian, and Seventh-Day Adventists",<br>
    Presbyterian and Reformed Publishing Co., New  Jersey, 1966<br>
<p>
It's always interesting to hear the perspective of an "outsider" who<br>
has been looking in! I think the small booklet I have is actually a<br>
reprinted chapter from a larger book entitled "Confronting the Cults"<br>
by the same author.<br>
<p>
Anyone wishing to take up on any of his points will need to read the rest<br>
of his material first, since I have presented a small part of the <br>
conclusion only. His discussion was actually quite balanced, although<br>
clearly most SDAs would not like EGWs writings referred to as "tradition".<br>
That term has usually been reserved for the Catholic church.<br>
<p>
I must say, however, that in the light of the current discussion on Bible<br>
versions, there seems to be a certain portion of the SDA church which has<br>
as their creed "sola scriptura, except where it contradicts one of our<br>
previously held doctrinal beliefs, in which case it has been translated <br>
wrongly or deliberately corrupted by the Devil himself". I guess an outsider <br>
has the right to view that as "a body of tradition it seems reluctant to <br>
break"! Now I am not criticizing that creedal position, but I do think<br>
that there is a difference between "sola our interpretation of the KJV"  <br>
and "sola scriptura" which does need to be acknowledged.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
