<title>Feb_1993: pregnant teens</title>
<h1>pregnant teens</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Feb 93 10:29:21 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#48">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#48">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#48">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#48">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0049.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Where did EGW endorse the textus receptus?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0047.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Adventism &amp; Romanism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0056.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: pregnant teens"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Heidi Vyhmeister Grumling writes:]<br>
<i>&gt;what are we doing as individuals and as a church to make</i><br>
<i>&gt;abortion unnecessary?  What about the physical, financial, emotional support of</i><br>
<i>&gt;the women/families with unplanned pregnancies?  What about family planning?</i><br>
<i>&gt;You see, I work as a nurse-midwife at a teen clinic.  We don't do abortions,</i><br>
<i>&gt;but I provide family planning and prenatal care (among a lot of other things)</i><br>
<i>&gt;to poor minority and-- oh dear!--unmarried teens.  I think that as SDA's we're</i><br>
<i>&gt;so uncomfortable with the idea of non-marital sex that we don't even want to</i><br>
<i>&gt;touch the issue, but we need to address it.  Some of the kids turning up in my</i><br>
<i>&gt;clinic are SDA's.</i><br>
<p>
God bless you, Heidi!  Really!  (Cf Ruth 4:11 and similar)  I have<br>
considerable concerns about the pro-lifers who picket abortion clinics<br>
because I see it as un-Christ-like, not redemptive, and at least not<br>
God's best (As for the abortion clinic bombers, they are as badly<br>
confused as those who join the KKK or Aryan organizations; they do gross,<br>
inestimable damage to God's reputation).  However, I have great respect<br>
for the evangelicals who work at crisis pregnancy centers, for families<br>
who provide home havens (physical, finanacial, emotional support).<br>
<p>
Perhaps now is a good time for this story:  When our second child was<br>
born in Minnesota, in 1981, my wife shared a room with an unmarried,<br>
19 yr old mother.  They became acquainted and kept in touch afterwards<br>
for several years.  Shortly after leaving Waconia's hospital, the room-mate<br>
called us and invited us to her baby's dedication.  So, on that Sunday, we<br>
attended her Reformed Church of America (as I recall the denomination).<br>
<p>
After the typical church service preliminaries, the pastor got up and invited<br>
Sherrie and baby Melissa (as I'll call them) to come up.  The pastor then<br>
mentioned that he'd spent time counseling and talking with Sherrie, and one<br>
of the decisions Sherrie made was that she would address the church.  Sherrie<br>
stepped up to the mike and talked about how she'd had feelings of rebellion<br>
against God, her family, etc during her high school years, how she had gotten<br>
involved with a young man as a way of escape, then finally found herself<br>
pregnant.  She then apologized to her family and her church for how she had<br>
dishonored them and especially God.  During this time, many hearts were<br>
touched with sympathy and compassion; several women (not of her family, btw)<br>
left their seats to go stand beside her, put their arms around her.  It was<br>
a moving experience.<br>
<p>
When it was time for the baby to be dedicated, the pastor spoke of the<br>
unique needs of single mothers and asked the congregation to seek out<br>
ways that they could help her (e.g., clothes, baby sitting while the<br>
mother went to school, etc).  Many hands went up.  And from our continuing<br>
contacts, many of those church members were faithful to their pledge.<br>
<p>
Amen!  And let us all be as Christ-like!<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
