<title>Feb_1993: How to discern inspiration</title>
<h1>How to discern inspiration</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 4 Feb 93 23:36:02 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Warren C Trenchard: "The Text for the Last Time"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Steven Timm: "The inspiration discussion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Now that we've had the battle of the translations, let's get back to the<br>
topic that started all this.  We were discussing inspiration and I brought<br>
up the fact that there are translation errors so I do not believe in<br>
word inspiration of the Bible.  This essentially means that I do not<br>
believe that the ENGLISH words of the KJV or any other translation is<br>
the inspired word of God based on the actual words used.  I DO BELEIVE<br>
that it is the word of God so long as it's translated correctly.  Well<br>
how can I know when something is translated correctly or not.  This is<br>
where the essential ingredient of the Holy Spirit fits into the equation.<br>
We have all been promised the gift of the Holy Spirit to guide our lives<br>
if we truly wish that guidance and live a life that does not drive away<br>
that light, we may know from within, for ourselves, what the truth is.<br>
Does it matter if there are errors in the written word?  Isn't God<br>
faithful to His promise to lead us to light and salvation?  We don't have<br>
to depend on an ancient language scholar to dissect the truth for us.<br>
<p>
I read the pages referenced by Ruben in the GC and did not find any<br>
direct endorsement of any particular version of the Bible or any translation.<br>
What I did find on those pages was the reason Tyndale, Luther, and Wycliffe<br>
gave so much to provide scripture for the common man in his native tongue.<br>
Tyndale said:<br>
	"While I am sowing in one place, the enemy ravages the field<br>
	I have just left.  I cannot be everywhere.  Oh! if Christians<br>
	possessed the Holy Scriptures in their own tongue, they could<br>
	of themselves withstand these sophists.  Without the Bible it<br>
	is impossible to establish the laity in the truth."<br>
<p>
	"Christians must read the New Testament in their mother tongue."<br>
<p>
If this was so important and essential during the Reformation, would it<br>
not apply now to modern Christians?  Every man is better off with a least<br>
some version of scripture than no scripture at all.  Are some translations<br>
better than others?  Who really knows but does it matter?  The Holy Spirit<br>
has used incompetent and inadequate vessels to spread the truth throughout<br>
the ages.  Isn't He just as able to reveal truth to a sincere soul now?<br>
<p>
I believe the root of the translation debate has more to do with support<br>
of cherished doctrines.  If you take God's Word in any form, translation,<br>
or language, you cannot miss the essentials of salvation.  And isn't that<br>
the purpose of God's Word in the first place?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
