<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="05 Feb 93 00:39:00 EST" -->
<!-- name="Warren C Trenchard" -->
<!-- email="70711.3366@compuserve.com" -->
<!-- subject="The Text for the Last Time" -->
<!-- id="930205053900_70711.3366_DHJ60-1@CompuServe.COM" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Feb_1993: The Text for the Last Time</title>
<h1>The Text for the Last Time</h1>
Warren C Trenchard (<i>70711.3366@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>05 Feb 93 00:39:00 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#55">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#55">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#55">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#55">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0056.html">Scott  Bechtel: "Re: pregnant teens"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0054.html">cheryl berthelsen: "How to discern inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
THE TEXT FOR THE LAST TIME<br>
<p>
It must be obvious to everyone by now that some of us could go on forever on the issues of<br>
the text of the New Testament and the quality of the Bible Translations.  I, for one, do not<br>
intend to do so.  Having laid out my positions on some issues in this regard, with these<br>
present remarks I will rest my case, leaving the verdict of public opinion to the jury of<br>
reasonable readers.<br>
<p>
ANOTHER AUTHORITY<br>
In my reference to several contemporary authorities on New Testament textual criticism and<br>
the translations, I forgot to mention two distinguished Adventists, Sakae Kubo and Walter<br>
Specht.  Their book, So Many Versions? (Zondervan--my copy is the revised and enlarged<br>
edition of 1983), is an excellent source of information on the Bible translations of the 20th<br>
century.  With PhDs in New Testament textual criticism, they offer a well informed survey of<br>
the quality of these versions, free from superstition and supposition.  I highly recommend this<br>
easy reading book.<br>
<p>
THE MSS OF 1 JOHN 5:7-8<br>
On the question concerning the MS support of the long reading in 1 John 5:7-8, Dave J.<br>
correctly reflects the view of Metzger (A Textual Commentary . . .), writing on behalf of the<br>
whole United Bible Society's Greek New Testament editorial team.  However, it is interesting<br>
to observe that in the textual notes to this passage in both The Greek New Testament, Third<br>
Edition (Corrected) (1983) and the related Novum Testamentum Graece (1979), some<br>
additional Greek witnesses are cited as well.  These minuscules include<br>
<p>
      221  (marginal note on a 10th C. MS),<br>
      429  (marginal note on a 14-15th C. MS),<br>
      918  (16th C.), and<br>
      2318 (18th C.!).<br>
<p>
Both editions of the text also list 636 (marginal note on a 15th C. MS) rather than 635, which<br>
is listed by Metzger in both The Text of the New Testament (subtitled, Its Transmission,<br>
Corruption and Restoration) and A Textual Commentary on the Greek New Testament.  This<br>
is curious, since Metzger is also one of the editors of both the above mentioned editions.  I<br>
will try to remember to ask him about this monumental (?) problem, when I see him next.<br>
<p>
THE AUTHORITY OF ELLEN WHITE IN TEXTUAL CRITICISM<br>
For some, the critical ingredient in this debate seems to be the writings of Ellen White on the<br>
subject.  Let me offer an opinion on the her role in the issues of the text of the New<br>
Testament and the validity of Bible translations.  In my view, Ellen White was no more an<br>
authority on technical questions concerning Old and New Testament textual criticism and the<br>
validity of Bible translations than she was on the details of history during the Reformation<br>
and certain other periods.  The latter is confirmed by the changes to the latest edition of the<br>
Great Controversy, published during her lifetime and under her control.  She was not even an<br>
authority on the technical interpretation of the Bible.  She herself refused to allow her earlier<br>
writings on the meaning of the "daily" sacrifice in Daniel 9 to settle a dispute on the issue<br>
late in her life.  Her writings on the law in Galatians show clear evolution.  In her little<br>
known book, The Miracles of Jesus (It also appears in one of the volumes of Spirit of<br>
Prophecy.), she placed the Stilling of the Storm AFTER the Walking on the Water, contrary<br>
to the order of these events in the Synoptic Gospels.  She even mentions that the disciples<br>
should not have been afraid during the storm, since Jesus had on an earlier occasion come<br>
walking to them on the water.  However, this reflection is missing in the account in The<br>
Desire of Ages, because she relates the two incidents in the biblical order, with the Stilling<br>
coming BEFORE the Walking.  One could cite numerous such examples.  In these matters<br>
she simply appears to have reflected the views of those whom she read and with whom she<br>
associated.  It seems clear to me, therefore, that Ellen White, while fulfilling an important<br>
divinely inspired mission, was not an authority on everything she wrote, nor should we treat<br>
her as such.<br>
<p>
<p>
Warren C. Trenchard<br>
Internet: 70711.3366@compuserve.com<br>
CIS: 70711,3366<br>
<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
