<title>Feb_1993: Sex and the single college student</title>
<h1>Sex and the single college student</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri,  5 Feb 1993 18:08:46 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#61">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#61">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#61">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#61">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0062.html">Cam Litvin: "Re: Pregnant Teens (Scott's comment)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Cam Litvin: "EGW and Erasmus"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0066.html">David Klein - EECS: "Teenagers, sex, relationships &amp; the church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seems to me that the church has historically followed a forensic <br>
approach to sex by emphasizing what happens if you "get caught."<br>
While this approach has plenty of Biblical support, I think an additional<br>
emphasis is necessary.  We have to show people what either sex or the desire<br>
for it is doing to their relationships on a day by day basis.  If they can't<br>
see how they are hurting themselves on a daily basis, the fear of<br>
getting caught won't matter to them either, nor will the threat of hell<br>
fire.<br>
<p>
Some general principles I try to live by (fortunately there are no<br>
ex-girlfriends of mine on the net to tell you differently):<br>
<p>
1)  In my relationships I should see the beauty of my partner<br>
    as something to be preserved and protected.<br>
<p>
2)  I'm not ready to be with the special *someone* until I don't have<br>
    the urge to be with just *anyone*  (In other words, you're not ready<br>
    to live together until you're able to live alone.)<br>
<p>
3)  Intimacy is a expression of love to the partner, not something to be <br>
    extracted from the partner.<br>
<p>
4)  If you have to scheme about how to convince your partner to perform<br>
    an act, you're probably not ready to do that.<br>
<p>
5)  If you are working closely with someone else towards a common goal,<br>
    particularly if prayer is involved, a relationship will develop<br>
    whether you want it to or not.  Plan before you relate.<br>
<p>
6)  Physical and emotional attachment should not precede the general building<br>
    of common ground in a relationship.  <br>
<p>
7)  I have found it interesting to have a person that knows both people in <br>
    the couple talk with them about how they relate to people.  For several <br>
    of my engaged or quasi-engaged friends I have pointed  out things they <br>
    hadn't noticed about their partner.  Though I am not now nor have I <br>
    ever been engaged, I have benefitted from the advice of other people<br>
    pointing out behaviors I never knew I was doing.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
