<title>Feb_1993: Science and religion</title>
<h1>Science and religion</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat,  6 Feb 1993 00:59:18 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">David Klein - EECS: "Teenagers, sex, relationships &amp; the church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Danny Kumamoto: ""Spaceship Eden""</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Models such as the "spaceship Eden" model sit at the interface of science<br>
and religion and thus are often accused of being neither scientific nor<br>
religious.  There are various levels of intervention by God and various<br>
levels of testability these imply.<br>
<p>
The first we may call "pernicious intervention."  This would include<br>
creating the world a few weeks ago with a remembered past.  Other examples<br>
would be placing fossils in the rocks to give false appearance of age,<br>
or creating stars a large distance away with their light on its way to us<br>
so we would get it within 6000 years.  If we choose to make religious <br>
postulates of this type  (I do not think we should), then we must also <br>
believe that observation of the natural world is likely to give the<br>
wrong answers.  Although it is not wise to postulate that such things<br>
have <br>
happened, an omnipotent God certainly could do any of these things.<br>
<p>
The second we call "gap theory" which suggests that the time between<br>
"In the beginning God" and "Let there be light" was long.  This <br>
opens the door to much scientific testability but leads one down a <br>
slippery slope in scriptural interpretation.<br>
<p>
The third type of intervention is actions which may not be observable<br>
from the evidence now but were certainly observable at the time and <br>
would not have violated any laws of nature.  The Flood is a violent<br>
singularity which would fit into this category.  Rowland's Spaceship <br>
Eden model is a similar idea which is not currently testable because<br>
we do not have the Garden of Eden with which to experiment.<br>
<p>
The fourth type of intervention is creation _ex nihilo_.  The method<br>
by which God creates a subatomic particle is well understood, and doing<br>
more complex systems is in principle an engineering task.  In practice<br>
it involves processes so complex that we do not know whether any physical<br>
laws are violated or not.  (And if these laws are only violated for<br>
a short period of time, we could never tell anyway.)  <br>
<p>
It's my personal prejudice that God always operates within the laws of <br>
nature, and that in fact the laws of nature are another representation <br>
of the law of God.  The caveat is that we do not know what all these laws<br>
may be.<br>
<p>
We should not be in a hurry to mesh our belief to the current scientific<br>
belief.  The Catholics tied their belief to the writings of Aristotle and <br>
were thus forced to condemn Galileo for suggesting the earth goes around<br>
the sun.  Only late last year did they forgive him for speaking against<br>
the church (more than 300 years later.)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
