<!-- inreplyto="IfQjByy00YUoNIf4QX@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<title>Feb_1993: Teenagers, sex, relationships &amp; the church</title>
<h1>Teenagers, sex, relationships &amp; the church</h1>
David Klein - EECS (<i>dklein@eecs.wsu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 5 Feb 93 23:34:48 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#66">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#66">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#66">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#66">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Woody Baker: "Re: How about a new more acurate translation then"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Steven Timm: "Science and religion"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0061.html">Steven Timm: "Sex and the single college student"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0080.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Teenagers, sex, relationships &amp; the church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
After reading the various messages about sex, I have a few questions<br>
to pose.<br>
<p>
1.  Where is our church when it comes to teaching our teenagers about sex?<br>
<p>
  The reasons for this question come several sources.  My parents are both<br>
doctors and at times in the past I have been employed in their offices.<br>
It surprized me to find that the ratio of SDA teenage girls to girls from<br>
the rest of the community who came who came in with the "flu" and went out<br>
knowing that they were pregnant.  Most often the SDA girls commented that<br>
they had not realized that they could get pregnant from their activities.<br>
This was generaly not the case with girls from the community. They knew<br>
what they were doing, for the most part, but had figured one time<br>
unprotected wouldn't get them pregnant.<br>
  Also I had a chat with a young lady in a youth sabbath school class a<br>
few summers ago that still bothers me.  She was the kind of person who<br>
was generally happy and smiling.  On this particular Saturday morning<br>
she was pretty destracted and seemed upset.  I asked a few questions and<br>
eventually found that she had had sex with a young man in the city park<br>
the night before.  When I told that she had had sex, she said that no,<br>
that couldn't have happened to her, she wasn't that kind of person.  The<br>
point being, she didn't even know what sex was!  She was from a good,<br>
functional SDA family and was a pretty straight person, but no one had<br>
ever taken the time to explain the facts of life to her.<br>
  Perhaps I should reword the question.  Perhaps it should be, <br>
<p>
What responsiblity does our church, as a whole, have toward making sure<br>
our youth know about sex.<br>
<p>
2.  Do we, as a church, do ourselves a disservice with the victorian view<br>
    we take of sex out side of marriage?<br>
<p>
  This is a personal experience type question and by stating it, I'm not<br>
suggesting that we condone sex outside of marriage.  Here is how it worked<br>
with me: I was brought up hearing that sex was bad.  I heard this more <br>
from teachers and other adults who were uncomfortable with a 10 year old<br>
who read his parents anatomy and gynecology books then from my parents.<br>
When I actually had sex, I found that, physically, it was a great deal of<br>
fun.  And being at the age where being a little rebellion was "Cool" I<br>
tried to have it as much as I could.  And when I got caught, all I heard<br>
from the church was that I had sinned and was evil and should repent.<br>
But to my rebellious eye, there was nothing wrong with my activitys.  So,<br>
I just said "To hell with the church."  But I'm not a very good rebel.<br>
And I tormented myself with what I had done being evil.  Problem was, I<br>
still liked sex, still do.  But after having it, I would have a massive<br>
guilt trip.  It took a somewhat drunk Baptist girl to point out to me that<br>
God didn't want to roast me if I slipped.  But I still have a lot of<br>
mental baggage from those days.  And I still have hard feeling toward<br>
the church on this issue.  The point of all this is that I wasn't able<br>
to be morally stable until I figured out that God doesn't blast you<br>
forever if you fail.  Why couldn't the church have said as much.<br>
<p>
Which brings me to:<br>
<p>
3.  Is it possible to have a very close relationship, outside of marriage,<br>
    that does not include sex.<br>
<p>
  My girl friend and I are presently dealing with this one.  She knows my<br>
background and has had her own experiences.  So we have always tried to<br>
base our relationship on the non-physical aspects of being close to <br>
someone.  Also, we have developed a set of guidelines and placed some<br>
mental no trespassing signs on pertinant areas of the human anatomy.  I<br>
suppose the best thing we have that has kept us from destroying our<br>
relationship (by allowing it to become purely physical) is mutual trust.<br>
We both assume the responsibility of saying No.  And we both trust the<br>
other person to keep a lid on the sex drive.  Is it easy?  NO!  Will it<br>
last?  I hope so.  Would our system work without us both agreeing to it?<br>
I doubt it.  Believe me, there are times when it takes the both of us<br>
to keep out of trouble.  Finally, you'll note that God isn't mentioned<br>
in this paragraph until now.  That's because you aren't thinking about<br>
Him when you are all hot and bothered.  God comes in before, (Give me<br>
strength Lord.) and after, (Thanks for Your power to resist.) but not<br>
during unless you are an exceptional person.<br>
<p>
In closing, I know that I would have the problems I had in #2 above<br>
knowing what I know now.  But where was the church when I didn't know?<br>
Does the church promote, mention, or even suggest anything like #3?<br>
And why is it that when something comes up of the sexual nature, our<br>
church family seems to follow the words of a song:<br>
<p>
		"Two hearts get entangled<br>
		 Dirty minds, they go to town<br>
		 Everyone's got an angle<br>
		 Little lies get spread around"<br>
<p>
David<br>
-----------------<br>
David Klein<br>
dklein@eecs.wsu.edu<br>
<p>
"If you must believe something, believe this: I will fail you."<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
