<title>Feb_1993: Data and information about sex</title>
<h1>Data and information about sex</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat,  6 Feb 1993 16:00:10 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#68">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#68">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#68">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#68">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0069.html">David Plaisted: "control of sex"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Woody Baker: "Re: How about a new more acurate translation then"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This is a subject that comes up frequently in the youth class I teach.  <br>
Several of our young people have decisions to make on a regular basis,<br>
and it seems that so far they have made wise decisions.  Twice now<br>
I have invited Heidi Grumling (nurse midwife/pregnancy counselor/<br>
sometime contributor to this net) to talk with my class.  <br>
<p>
Whenever she comes to visit, she brings a bunch of pamphlets about various <br>
stuff  (birth control, avoiding disease, etc.)  But most of the questions <br>
don't center around this technical information.  They're more interested <br>
in the human interest stories, how young Chicago teenagers cope with this <br>
problem, etc.<br>
<p>
At one point this statement would not have been true, but now it is true<br>
that the young people are getting enough information about the plumbing.<br>
(They are also getting misinformation from their friends, and that needs to <br>
be countered.)  What is needed is emotional preparation to be willing to <br>
make the tough choices they will have to make, and decide before trouble <br>
happens that they aren't going to get into it.  Because, lets face it,<br>
even *inside* marriage there's a lot of people that still aren't emotionally<br>
ready for intimacy.<br>
<p>
In my last post I said we need to help young people see what their attitudes<br>
and actions are doing to themselves, but I didn't say what that was.<br>
I need help putting that into words.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
