<!-- sent="Sun, 7 Feb 93 12:52:20 -0500" -->
<!-- name="David Plaisted" -->
<!-- email="plaisted@cs.unc.edu" -->
<!-- subject="control of sex" -->
<!-- id="9302071752.AA04024@plaisted.cs.unc.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Feb_1993: control of sex</title>
<h1>control of sex</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 7 Feb 93 12:52:20 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#69">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#69">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#69">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#69">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0070.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Ruben, commandment keeping and just. by faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Steven Timm: "Data and information about sex"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One aspect of this topic that has not been mentioned is the<br>
influence of our diet and health practices on our sex drive.<br>
I believe that the health counsels of Ellen White, if followed,<br>
would do a lot towards helping us to keep this under control.<br>
A simple, natural diet helps to restrain the ``animal passions.''<br>
Also, I think getting plenty of sunlight  helps to milden our<br>
disposition, and outdoor exercise has a similar effect.<br>
High fat and sugar and protein intake tends to have the opposite<br>
effect.  I can't give scientific evidence for this but it has<br>
been borne out in my own experience and seems to be supported<br>
by the testimonies of Sister White.  There seems to be a<br>
similar correlation with the control of temper.  Of course,<br>
this doesn't mean that the temptation will go away.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
