<title>Feb_1993: Re: 7th day Adventist Church</title>
<h1>Re: 7th day Adventist Church</h1>
TANG BENG YONG (<i>med10014@nusunix2.nus.sg</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 8 Feb 93 21:01:43 +0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#73">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#73">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#73">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#73">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0074.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Re: 7th day Adventist Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0072.html">Steven Timm: "Re: 7th day Adventist Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
concerning sex,<br>
<p>
Dear Steve,<br>
<p>
     in your last message, you said:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;In my last post I said we need to help young people see what their attitudes</i><br>
<i>&gt;and actions are doing to themselves, but I didn't say what that was.</i><br>
<i>&gt;I need help putting that into words.</i><br>
<p>
     Perhaps, we need to help our people (not just young people, who<br>
seem to be always regarded with suspicion with respect to such matters) be<br>
aware of WHAT their attitudes are.<br>
<p>
     As we near the close of the age, the world gets morally more and<br>
more corrupt. I personally feel that a lot of it is thanks to the mass<br>
media, which seem to be getting more and more corrupting in their<br>
influence. Here in Singapore, the formerly "strict" censorship of films<br>
and TV is getting more liberal suddenly and exposing our people to even<br>
stronger immoral influences, and this has an adverse effect on the moral<br>
norms of society. Even before this, the kinds of ideals and norms and<br>
role-models portrayed in the media in things like soap operas and such,<br>
were very different from Christian ideals and principles. The media would<br>
have us believe, for example, that it is good and normal for young<br>
children to have boy-girl relationships of a type not befitting their<br>
level of maturity. Now lots of kids in school are obsessed with having<br>
boyfriends or girlfriends. When I was a kid of 12 or 13, which wasn't<br>
that long ago, I remember that we were interested in such things too,<br>
but not to the same extent.<br>
<p>
     Well, as society degenerates, we as God's people need to guard our<br>
ideas and thoughts because of the very subtle and pervasive non-Christian<br>
influences which surround us. While we are in the world, let us take care<br>
NOT to revert back to being of the world.<br>
<p>
     How can a young man keep his way pure? By guarding it according to<br>
(God's) word. -Ps 119:9<br>
<p>
     The best answer to avoid getting the wrong attitudes is to spend<br>
time with God in prayer and bible-study and to strengthen our faith by<br>
Christian fellowship. We are influenced, to a degree, by all with whom<br>
we choose to associate. Let us then associate with Jesus so that we will<br>
benefit from the influence of His character, and perhaps thereby influence<br>
our peers.<br>
<p>
     Also, if one really wants to live a life of self-control amidst<br>
the temptations to impurity, it is necessary not to expose oneself<br>
unnecessarily to temptations. While we draw on the resources of divine <br>
strength to fight temptation, we should not go where we are not called to <br>
go and where we know there will be a bad influence. To do that is just<br>
asking for it, we are week and we will fall. For example, we should<br>
choose what we watch on TV and what sorts of literature we read. A lot<br>
of people say they can watch "adult" films because they are adults and<br>
are able to decide what to see and they are mature enough to know the <br>
difference between right and wrong. As far as I'm concerned, if something<br>
is considered morally unfit for children to watch or read, I don't want to<br>
see it either. Actually, even the stuff the world considers to be o.k.<br>
for childrens' consumption is riddled with unchristian messages and ideas.<br>
<p>
     Well, just my two-cents worth on this matter.<br>
<p>
     regards,<br>
<p>
     Beng Tang, Singapore.<br>
<p>
<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
