<!-- body="start" -->
On Feb 8, 12:09pm, Ruben Gonzalez wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Ruben, commandment keeping and just. by faith</i><br>
<i>&gt; ...</i><br>
<i>&gt; I have previously discussed this some time ago, and those who remember will</i><br>
<i>&gt; know that this is not the case. I do not believe in salvation by works.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Salvation is by faith alone, however faith = trust and obey. So that</i><br>
<i>&gt; the saving faith is that faith that obeys. For this reason the translation</i><br>
<i>&gt; of Rev 22:14 is correct because it exemplifies that type of faith necessary</i><br>
<i>&gt; for salvation. For this very reason Rev 22:14 (KJV style) is unpopular</i><br>
<i>&gt; with evangelicals.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Ruben.</i><br>
<i>&gt;-- End of excerpt from Ruben Gonzalez</i><br>
<p>
Where does this definition of faith come from ("faith=trust &amp; obey")?  I have<br>
read that the Greek word for faith is the same Greek word for believe, but one<br>
is a noun and the other is a verb.  So if faith is "believing" then how does<br>
trust and obediance fit into the definition?<br>
<p>
To me salvation at its simplest form is accepting Christ into your life and then<br>
from that day onward, developing the relationship with him.  If one is truely<br>
seeking to develop this relationship, then how on earth can Christ reject you?<br>
I also believe that any true relationship will exhibit actions that fall into<br>
line with God's requests.  But these actions (obediance to God's law, etc) come<br>
as a _result_ of this relationship, and not the cause for or the method of<br>
achieving the relationship.  If the actions are not exhibited, then more work is<br>
required at developing the relationship (prayer, Bible study, communion with God<br>
in nature, etc), not at working harder on keeping the law thru obedience.  You<br>
will fail at this later approach.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
<p>
