<title>Feb_1993: Teens and sex</title>
<h1>Teens and sex</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 8 Feb 93 11:29:25 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#78">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#78">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#78">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#78">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0079.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Teens and sex"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Ruben, commandment keeping and just. by faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Probably the two biggest factors in the temptation for teens to engage in<br>
sexual activity are peer pressure and poor self-esteem.  Many young people<br>
give into temptation because they don't feel very good about themselves.<br>
Sexual experiences give them the false impression that somebody cares about<br>
them.  This is from the young lady's view.  I'm not sure if this is a factor<br>
with the young men.  When young people are taught that they are magnificent<br>
creatures, made in the image of God, and worth enough to God for Jesus to<br>
redeem us, the develop healthier attitudes about who they are.  Unfortunately,<br>
many homes are dysfunctional and the parents are not able to convey love and<br>
trust so young people don't really get healthy attitudes about who they are.<br>
<p>
"In the olden days" when I was a teen, we were taught not to have sex because:<br>
	1.  You might get VD<br>
	2.  You might get pregnant<br>
	3.  You won't have a normal sex life in marriage<br>
These scare tactics don't work.  I like the approach the LDS Church uses now.<br>
(Actually, they've always used this.)  Young people should no engage in<br>
premarital sex so they can be worthy of a temple marriage.  Having a temple<br>
marriage is declares to the world that the couple has saved themselves for<br>
their future spouse and they have victoriously overcome sexual temptation.<br>
<p>
Many teens engage in sexual activity along with drugs or alcohol.  So the<br>
sexual activity is actually a component of their rebellion.  Why do so many<br>
teens get pregnant even when birth control is very available now days?  First,<br>
many won't buy it because it indicates pre-meditated sin.  Others rationalize<br>
that if they aren't on birth control, they might use that as their "excuse" to<br>
say no.<br>
<p>
I think the best thing any religion can do for their teens is to help them<br>
feel good about themselves and teach them that it's healthy and OK to say NO!<br>
Many young ladies find themselves in a pickle.  They don't want to have sex<br>
but they're having trouble saying NO.  I think it would be really great if<br>
we had "hotlines" to allow young people to call and get help before they<br>
succomb.  They could be offered suportive advice in how to say no, the easiest<br>
way to do it, how to avoid situations where they will feel trapped.  Much is<br>
the sexual tempation arrives after other standards of behavior have already<br>
been violated.  The couple is alone, unchaparoned, at a home where the parents<br>
are gone for the evening, or in a situation where they can get enough privacy<br>
.  If young people were taught to avoid these situations, that staying with<br>
people, other couples, away from secluded situtations, they may not have to<br>
face the temptation of saying no.<br>
<p>
That's my two bits.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
