<title>Feb_1993: Re: Teenagers, sex, relationships &amp; the church</title>
<h1>Re: Teenagers, sex, relationships &amp; the church</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 8 Feb 93 11:06:04 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#80">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#80">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#80">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#80">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Bruce,, commandment keeping and just. by faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0079.html">TANG BENG YONG: "Teens and sex"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0066.html">David Klein - EECS: "Teenagers, sex, relationships &amp; the church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[David Klein - EECS writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; 1.  Where is our church when it comes to teaching our teenagers about sex?</i><br>
<i>&gt;[..]</i><br>
<i>&gt; What responsiblity does our church, as a whole, have toward making sure</i><br>
<i>&gt; our youth know about sex.</i><br>
<p>
It is my belief that it is the responsibility of parents to teach their<br>
children about sex.  If parents don't know how, then the schools/the<br>
church can organize seminars in which they can be coached (but that<br>
responsibility should not be arrogated or usurped). Secondly,<br>
schools and the church can reinforce Biblical principals.<br>
<p>
Perhaps my experience was not common.  My parents taught me the facts<br>
of life in an age-appropriate matter; that is, more and more specifics<br>
as I grew up.  They also bought me a copy of "On Becoming A Man".  It<br>
wasn't exactly a page-turner kind of book, but it did provide further<br>
info and did let me do some learning on my own (it could well be argued<br>
that that book is quite dated (ahem!) and that newer books are better<br>
now, but I'm just relating my experience).  Health classes in grade<br>
school and academy gave anatomical details whilst open discussions<br>
in academy classes dealt with related topics (we had lots of discussions,<br>
esp after one of the girls became pregnant and finished the year via home<br>
study; even History and Bible teachers let us have discussions, btw).<br>
There were also films that talked about VD and then a panel of doctors<br>
answered questions, both questions and answers being specific, no holds barred.<br>
By the time I was in college, Wittschiebe's book, God Invented Sex, was out.<br>
<p>
That's the sex part.  What about romance and dating and keeping your<br>
"hormones" under control?  That aspect is fuzzier in my memory and my<br>
recall is that it was not treated as well.  I can relate to the struggles<br>
of getting "hot and bothered" for it surely happened to me.  Without<br>
detailing, I trust it suffices to say that I praise God for His<br>
intervention as a result of the intercessory prayers of my parents, keeping<br>
me from foolishness (in the sense of Proverbs).  Given that, we're attempting<br>
to address this with our teenage daughter (one now, one soon to be).<br>
I will simply list some of the resources we've found helpful:<br>
<p>
1) "Dating with Integrity":  Right off I cannot recall the author, but<br>
the publisher is Wolgemuth &amp; Hyatt and is recent enough to still be<br>
on the bookshelves at your Christian bookstore (not ABC, but your<br>
evangelical bookstore).  Friends recommended this one to us.<br>
2) "Youth, Do You Dare?", Colin Standish, Hartland Publications.  If you're<br>
spooked about anything from Hartland, fine, pass on to the next.<br>
3) Institute in Basic Life Principles seminar, by Bill Gothard.<br>
<p>
In addition:  No titles, sorry, but I understand that Tony Campolo and<br>
Josh McDowell have materials out addressing these issues.  Corrie ten Boom<br>
also treats sex and singleness at various points in her books.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 2.  Do we, as a church, do ourselves a disservice with the victorian view</i><br>
<i>&gt;     we take of sex out side of marriage?</i><br>
<p>
I'm thankful that I was taught by word and example that hugging and kissing<br>
and nurturing and complimenting and praising and supporting, etc. we're<br>
parts of the glue that keep a marriage together.  My parents also never<br>
hid from me, e.g., that the reasons why Mr &amp; Mrs X were divorcing and<br>
leaving town were quite complex, but included in them, as far as they<br>
could discern, was that Mrs X (or Mr N, in another case) was unresponsive<br>
to romance and sex and that Satan had taken advantage of that to lead<br>
Mr X into an affair with his office secretary.  You get the idea ...<br>
<p>
I was taught that sex/romance is like fire.  Under control (of the Spirit)<br>
it provides warmth and contentment; out of control, it destroys, whether<br>
in a fire storm or by slowly creeping.  I was never taught that it was<br>
bad, altho some of my friends had been. (Do you suppose this could be<br>
related to why parents will say to a child guilty of naughty behavior,<br>
"You were bad!" (their person) rather than "That was a naughty thing<br>
to do." (the act)?  An over-simplification that leads to a wrong conclusion.).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; [..] until I figured out that God doesn't blast you</i><br>
<i>&gt; forever if you fail.  Why couldn't the church have said as much?</i><br>
<p>
Good point.  I think the problem is that people give more focus to<br>
sexual sins than is appropriate, particularly if they ignore other<br>
weighty matters.  Why?  Consider this:  Every general knows you<br>
can defeat your foe if you can surround him, or least attack front<br>
and rear.  I see Satan attempting to destroy God's plans for sexuality<br>
by encouraging libertine sexuality on the one hand whilst encouraging<br>
"sex is bad" among Christians on the other.  For example, you have probably<br>
encountered those who feel that the "original sin" was sexual, or that sex<br>
is only for having children, not for marital pleasure (despite the msgs<br>
in Song of Solomon and Proverbs); or you may have encountered this:<br>
1) New converts have told my pastor-father that they knew they should<br>
not have sex anymore with their unbelieving spouse.  He would then<br>
share 1 Pet 3, 1 Cor 7 (and others) and assure them that they had<br>
an opportunity to develop a deeper relationship with their spouse.<br>
2) An older "saint" told my mother, shortly after she and my father married,<br>
that she must never, never have intercourse on the Sabbath.  When<br>
asked Scripture to support this, she was unable to give any, just that<br>
that was how she had been taught.  [I suspect a misconstrual of Is 58:13.]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; And why is it that when something comes up of the sexual nature, our</i><br>
<i>&gt; church family seems to follow the words of a song?</i><br>
<p>
Let change to following God's ways start with each of us.  And that<br>
will change the church.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  ".. I have set before you Life and Death, blessing and cursing;  therefore
      choose Life, that both you and your children may live"  Deut 30:19
</pre>
