<title>Feb_1993: Re: Evolution vs. Creationism</title>
<h1>Re: Evolution vs. Creationism</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 08 Feb 1993 13:11:58 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#82">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#82">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#82">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#82">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Steven Timm: "administrators id"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Bruce,, commandment keeping and just. by faith"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0059.html">Steven Timm: "Evolution vs. Creationism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hmm.  I have struggled over creation vs evolution for a long long time.  The<br>
key thing that you have to remember when dealing with this topic, is that<br>
"the only absolute truth is GOD, all other truth is relative" (Asa Thoreson<br>
Philisophical Biology, Andrews U). This means that, you HAVE to make some<br>
core assumptions on any topic.  The core assumption underlying evolution, is<br>
the "uniformatarian principle"  knock it out, and you kill evolution.  The<br>
core assumption underlying creation is "there is a prime mover, who is GOD".<br>
My position is that we have to take either of these on FAITH. (there is no<br>
physical "proof" of either one).  Scientists as a rule, get really hostile<br>
when you remind them that many of the principles that they consider absolutes<br>
are being taken on faith.  It matters not whether you are a creationist, or<br>
evolutionist, you still have to accept a core set of beliefs with no concrete<br>
proof of them.  "Truth" changes.  What was "true" yesterday may not be "true"<br>
tommorow.  Remember, once it was "truth" that the world was flat, and that<br>
the universe revolved around the earth.  It was "true" that the atom was the<br>
smallest particle of matter. (now we know about charms, quarks, pi-mesons<br>
and a whole zoo of sub-atomic particles).  Keeping this principle in mind<br>
can help you deal with these things.<br>
Hope this helps.<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
<p>
woody@knapper.cactus.org
woody@chinacat.unicom.com (temporary) is forwareded to woody@knapper
</pre>
