<title>Feb_1993: Re: Responses to Link Hudson's question from SDAnet</title>
<h1>Re: Responses to Link Hudson's question from SDAnet</h1>
Paul Hudson Jr (<i>hudson@athena.cs.uga.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 9 Feb 1993 18:48:57 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#84">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#84">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#84">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#84">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Ruben, commandment keeping and just. by faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Steven Timm: "administrators id"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0076.html">Steven Timm: "Responses to Link Hudson's question from SDAnet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; The question about Ellen White and prophecy points to a common misconception </i><br>
<i>&gt; about prophecy. We tend to always think of prophecy in terms of prediction. If</i><br>
<i>&gt;  </i><br>
<i>&gt; one studies prophecy and prophets in scripture, I think you will find that </i><br>
<i>&gt; prophets communicate messages from God to man. Many prophets never predicted </i><br>
<i>&gt; anything. Predictions within prophecy come only as they relate to a specific </i><br>
<i>&gt; message and usually in a conditional manner, i.e. if you don't change your </i><br>
<i>&gt; course then this will be the result.</i><br>
<p>
I understand that prophecy need not be predicting the future.  However,<br>
those who are considered to be prophets often do have some insight into<br>
the future.  God said that he will do nothing except he shows it to His<br>
prophets.  <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Ed Fargusson (Compuserve 72450,2430)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Two points.  Some folk think prophets make only prophecies (predictions</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the future); however, my understanding is that a prophet is one who</i><br>
<i>&gt; has a message from God (which can include stuff about the future); and,</i><br>
<i>&gt; yes, EGW did write a lot of what could be considered commentary.</i><br>
<p>
What is the SDA criteria for prophethood.  I am a Charismatic/Pentecostal.<br>
I have known many people to prophecy powerful prophecies.  Once I heard<br>
someone prophecy what I had just thought.  Another time, someone told me <br>
something specific that I had just prayed for earlier that day.  Yet, we<br>
do not use the term "prophet" for anyone who prophecies, except maybe in the<br>
most general sense of the term.  <br>
<p>
Like White, most Charismatics/Pentecostals that many consider to be prophets<br>
don't claim to be prophets.  David Wilkerson says that he is not a prophet.<br>
I don't know if Paul Cain says that he is not one, but he doesn't claim the<br>
title.  (Most men of God with gifts of this caliber are too humble to <br>
try to claim titles for themselves.)  Paul Cain often does predict the future,<br>
or whow supernatural knowledge.  For example, instead of giving a word of<br>
knowledge "someone has a pain in their leg" the Lord often gives him the <br>
person's name.  He has also predicted future events.  When he went to meet<br>
with John Wimber, he said that one the day he arrived in California there <br>
would be a local earthquake, and on the day he left there would be a <br>
world renouned earthquake elsewhere on earth.  Sure enough, there was a<br>
local earthquake and the Armenian earthquake.  These were given as signs,<br>
and, from what I hear, the Lord often gives Paul Cain signs.  <br>
<p>
The reason some call Paul Cain a prophet (after witnessing him minister)<br>
is because they see a well developed prophetic gift.  There are many people<br>
who prophecy, even if it is just once.  But we don't generally call them<br>
prophets.  Occasionally pastors and teachers prophesy.  Was White's main<br>
work prophetic?<br>
<p>
Link Hudson.<br>
<p>
