<title>Feb_1993: Re: Creation vs Evolution  NOT</title>
<h1>Re: Creation vs Evolution  NOT</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>10 Feb 1993 10:11:21 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#87">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#87">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#87">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#87">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">Steven Timm: "Inspiration: questions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0086.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Bruce,, commandment keeping and just. by faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This is (I hope) to be my only post on this topic, and it is already one<br>
more than I had originally intended! <br>
<p>
Viewing the origins issue as "Creation Vs Evolution" invariably results in<br>
a person thinking that it's either one extreme or the other. That is, we<br>
must choose between special creation ex nihilo, 6000 years ago as many<br>
Christians claim is taught by Genesis 1 and 2, and atheistic evolution<br>
over billions of years. The next step down this path is to assert that<br>
because no-one is able to state a viable mechanism for atheistic evolution<br>
then it is clearly wrong, and therefore recent creation must be the answer.<br>
<p>
This is an oversimplification which in my opinion is worth avoiding altogether.<br>
One reason why I have a certain amount of distaste towards the "Creation<br>
Science" movement is because they like to approach things this way.<br>
<p>
It is worth noting that "scientific truth" is merely that which provides<br>
the most useful model available at any given time. Hence the assertion that<br>
because scientists keep changing their mind on truth, they must be wrong,<br>
is quite ridiculous. Science and pragmatism are closely aligned, in that<br>
both define truth as "what works". If something comes along that works<br>
better, great! No problem! (In principle of course...in practice, there<br>
are "conservatives" and "liberals" amongst scientists too).<br>
<p>
My own approach to the origins issue is to base everything on my belief<br>
that "God is the ultimate originator and sustainer of all things". On<br>
this point, at least, I think most Christians can agree. It would make<br>
things much less problematic if we could simply stop there!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
