[From Paul Johnston via Sharon Johnston's account  sj1j@andrew.cmu.edu]<br>
<p>
Ruben, I didn't mean to frighten you.  Because I spoke favorably of my<br>
neighborhood Episcopalian parish, you strongly suggested that I was<br>
consorting with the dragon of Revelation 12.<br>
   I nevertheless like worshipping there when I can.  I'm very fond of<br>
the rector.  The organist and his wife are personal friends of mine.  If<br>
it helps, let me assure you...<br>
   * I am active in my local SDA congregation.  I've been Sabbath School<br>
superintendent.  I teach a Bible class.  I've now been asked to assist<br>
in pastoral visitation.  I've spent my fair share of time on the church<br>
board.  I've been on the nominating committee three times in seven years.<br>
   * If pedigree mattered, I'd tell you I'm a sixth-generation Adventist<br>
with roots in Battle Creek.  But I won't.<br>
   * From infancy to my earliteen years, I was in the Far East with my<br>
missionary parents.  It's still difficult not to see my work and my very<br>
existence in terms of mission.<br>
   * I seriously consider the pastoral ministry.<br>
   But Ruben, you haven't answered my question.  This is what I thought<br>
was the most important issue in my latest communique on SDAnet.  I think<br>
our denomination has an identity crisis.  I'll repeat the question.  "Do<br>
you think our denomination can find a niche?  Survive?  Thrive?"<br>
   I'd also be interested in your response to some merely sociological<br>
questions.<br>
   1.) Do you think the Seventh-Day Adventist Church is, or should be, a<br>
fundamentalist denomination?  How do you define fundamentalism,<br>
especially as it addresses biblical interpretation?<br>
   2.) What, in your mind, characterizes a sect or cult?  Compare or<br>
contrast SDA's you know (include yourself if you'd like) with your<br>
understanding of what makes a person a cultist.<br>
   3.) Can an Adventist be sure enough about the superiority of his<br>
doctrine to call someone else's religion false?  Can you or I be that<br>
sure and still be humble?  (Remember we Adventists learned about the<br>
Sabbath from another denomination.  Are we that open to change--that<br>
open to admitting error--today?)<br>
   This isn't an IQ test or anything.  It's not a political correctness<br>
exam.  There are no correct answers.  But your answers will give me a<br>
better basis for understanding where you're coming from.  It would be<br>
enlightening to hear the analyses of others on our diverse network.<br>
   Please, Ruben, don't worry about my overactive apostate gland.<br>
