<title>Feb_1993: A backslider returns</title>
<h1>A backslider returns</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  9 Feb 1993 22:03:34 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#89">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#89">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#89">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#89">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0090.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Inspiration: questions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0088.html">Steven Timm: "Inspiration: questions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
After a 18-month absence, I returned.  The place was mostly as I left it,<br>
a few things were better.  Nobody challenged me and said "why were you gone",<br>
just welcomed me back as if I belonged.<br>
<p>
I returned for the same reasons I had gone there in the first place.  There <br>
were good social opportunities with many people my own age.  The music was<br>
of a contemporary nature and I could express myself my own way.  The <br>
teaching was improved and extended to one-hour classes.  Everyone believed <br>
in having good health and no one drunk or smoked.  <br>
<p>
Most importantly, I felt my need of the place.  They hadn't changed the<br>
standards they had before, in fact they were tougher.  There was still<br>
the dress code, the rules, and the large percentage of your income they <br>
wanted.  They seemed to know nothing of grace--for every bit of progress<br>
I made, they said I had to work at it.  The usual weekend morning service<br>
wouldn't be enough, I also had to come to various weekday meetings.<br>
<p>
By now it may be clear to you that I am not talking about my church, <br>
but about my health club.  It doesn't hurt to realize from time to time that <br>
we're much more like a club than we want to admit.  Perhaps the reason <br>
we don't attract more people is that we don't charge enough admission<br>
and we let people off too easily.  For examples, take the Willow Creek<br>
Community <br>
Church of So. Barrington, IL.  They will not let you become a member of that <br>
church unless you are involved with leading out a small group ministry <br>
for at least a year.  And people are standing in line to do just that.<br>
<p>
It's probably premature to have a divine worship service at church based <br>
on high-impact aerobics as the major form of worship.  But I have seen <br>
an Adventist health club work successfully before as a witnessing tool,<br>
and I am trying to get some people around the Chicago area to think big.<br>
<p>
The church's first function is the hospital for sinners.  But too often <br>
it becomes the hospice for saints.  What will it take to change our church<br>
from spiritual hospice to spiritual health spa?  What are the equivalents<br>
of spiritual high-impact aerobics?  spiritual weight training?<br>
spiritual exercise bikes?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
