<title>Feb_1993: Re: Inspiration: questions</title>
<h1>Re: Inspiration: questions</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue,  9 Feb 1993 22:44:46 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#90">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#90">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#90">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#90">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Steven Timm: "Works of confusion"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Steven Timm: "A backslider returns"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul's question  "Do you think the church can find a niche?  Survive?<br>
Thrive?"  seems to be a general one.  I will take a stab:<br>
<p>
I believe the church has found a niche and is surviving, and that in the long<br>
run may inhibit its thriving.<br>
<p>
All religions are in the business of delivering security, and the SDA church<br>
is no different.  In fact, since we offer an exclusive "we are the best"<br>
type of deal, SDA's tend to find more security from denominational identity<br>
than Christians at large.  The deal is simple:  Keep the commandments,<br>
and pony up the tithe, and you're in.  <br>
<p>
The result is that today 90% of all resources of the church go to maintain<br>
the existing institution.  (this, by the way, is low compared to other <br>
denominations.)  Some conferences admit openly that their ministers are <br>
there to serve the tithe-payers. (Illinois and Pennsylvania, for two)<br>
 The rest structure their policy that way anyway.  This constituency<br>
of tithe-payers is naturally very wary of anything which would affect their<br>
perceived security within the church, and thus the conference leadership<br>
is very wary of offending them.<br>
<p>
Reaching the unchurched and providing security to the churched are <br>
mutually exclusive goals, and any organization can only expect to do one<br>
of those two well.  The SDA church has focused on the latter, as have<br>
most mainline denominations.  (I speak here of N. America's church).<br>
As an honored veteran of one of my two local churches put it, "if these<br>
new youth are going to take our seats, they may as well not come."<br>
This on the first day in 10 years that the church had been filled to<br>
standing-room only!<br>
<p>
Paul was wondering about the global niche of the church.  This is natural<br>
when there is only one church in town and it needs to reach as many<br>
people as it can.  In their particular case, the pastor has chosen to<br>
focus on attracting upscale baby-boomers, extracting a horrible cost in<br>
increased<br>
classism and splits between haves and have-nots.  <br>
<p>
In a larger metropolitan area, SDA churches still try to reach out to<br>
cover the metro area and pick various niches in a topical way.  Precious<br>
few<br>
SDA churches are community churches, fewer are family churches.<br>
In the Chicago suburbs, we have a right-wing 1888 message church, a <br>
country-hayseed church, a 1970's-blah church, a black church, a Korean <br>
church, a Filipino church, a hospital church, a liberal<br>
second-generation ethnic-traditional worship church, and several others.<br>
 At my church,<br>
we cover 49 suburbs plus the city, and 75% of our members drive past some<br>
other SDA church to get to ours.  So cooperation between churches and <br>
conferences could lead to reducing overlap in services provided<br>
and make sure that our group of churches is better positioned to meet needs.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
