<title>Feb_1993: Re: making money on religion</title>
<h1>Re: making money on religion</h1>
McCluskey G (<i>glenm@usl.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 10 Feb 93 09:32:19 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#95">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#95">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#95">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#95">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Steven Timm: "Re: EC and Sunday Law"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0094.html">McCluskey G: "Re: EC and Sunday Law"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0058.html">AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu: "making money on religion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0099.html">McCluskey G: "Re: making money on religion"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Well, well, for once I agree with Ruben on something!  I also do not</i><br>
<i>&gt; think that people should get rich selling Bibles or any other article</i><br>
<i>&gt; of religion.  Guess how this makes me feel about the way we run our</i><br>
<i>&gt; literature evangelism work?  No, I realize that most L.E.s are not</i><br>
<i>&gt; rich -- on the contrary, they sometimes are starving because they rely</i><br>
<i>&gt; on commission and the books are so over-priced that almost nobody can</i><br>
<i>&gt; afford to buy them anymore!  When will the higher-ups see that if we</i><br>
<i>&gt; really want to spread the Good News, then we must make it affordable.</i><br>
<i>&gt; I'm for putting L.E.s on salary and lowering the price of the books to</i><br>
<i>&gt; within reach of at least the middle class, if not lower!</i><br>
<p>
Perhaps another perspective would be useful here.  First of all, few<br>
book authors get rich.  I work with at least one author (of techical<br>
books).  Royalties are about 10% of list price, and if you sell 25K<br>
copies of a $20 paperback you make $50K.  This certainly beats<br>
starving, but it's poor compensation for the amount of time spent.<br>
<p>
Another point is that a publisher may use large profits from one book<br>
to subsidize some other important, but loss-making book.  For example,<br>
I would guess that Pacific Press etc. use profits from "Desire of<br>
Ages" to subsidize some of the really obscure EGW books.  Another<br>
example would be a seminal event like publication of the Dead Sea<br>
Scrolls;  these are very important but will never compete with James<br>
Dobson and Chuck Swindoll for popularity.<br>
<p>
Glen McCluskey<br>
glenm@usl.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
