<title>Feb_1993: Re: EC and Sunday Law</title>
<h1>Re: EC and Sunday Law</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 10 Feb 1993 10:28:08 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#96">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#96">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#96">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#96">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0097.html">Woody Baker: "Re: 7th day Adventist Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0095.html">McCluskey G: "Re: making money on religion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Several people wrote in and asked for more information.  The article is <br>
"The Sunday Absurdity" in the Jan/Feb 1993 issue of Liberty, by <br>
David N. Marshall.<br>
<p>
He opens the article by noting that this article first appeared in _The<br>
Economist_  (A British newsmagazine) but unfortunately does not give <br>
a reference to which issue.  Evidently the European Commission originally<br>
prepared a draft that mandated a weekly rest day without saying which <br>
day it should be.  The European Parliament amended the draft to designate<br>
Saturday-Sunday as the period of rest.  The cabinet, it appears, <br>
under pressure settled on Sunday.  <br>
<p>
The Christian Democrats of Germany and the trade unionists of Germany are<br>
specified by _The Economist_ for pushing this plan.  Liberty notes<br>
that Catholic prelates have also been pushing for the same in the past<br>
few years especially.  The rest of the Liberty article is essentially<br>
analysis and unfortunately does not give any details on how imminent<br>
the passage of such a law might be.<br>
<p>
It does note that the strongest sunday-closing laws in Europe are currently<br>
enforced in Germany.  In England, France, Holland, and Ireland (the only <br>
countries mentioned) Sunday laws are on the books but not enforced.  It also <br>
notes that France, Italy, and Belgium, are intervening in favor of the <br>
Sunday law.<br>
<p>
We need more information.  Any European correspondents are strongly encouraged<br>
to contribute.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
