<title>Feb_1993: Teens and sex</title>
<h1>Teens and sex</h1>
Richard Mazzaferri (<i>mazz@shockley.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 93 1:06:06 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#98">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#98">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#98">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#98">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0099.html">McCluskey G: "Re: making money on religion"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0097.html">Woody Baker: "Re: 7th day Adventist Church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0117.html">ronswen@aol.com: "Re: Teens and sex"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl Berthesen writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; "In the olden days" when I was a teen, we were taught not to have sex because:</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	1.  You might get VD</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	2.  You might get pregnant</i><br>
<i>&gt; 	3.  You won't have a normal sex life in marriage</i><br>
<i>&gt; These scare tactics don't work.  I like the approach the LDS Church uses now.</i><br>
<i>&gt; (Actually, they've always used this.)  Young people should no engage in</i><br>
<i>&gt; premarital sex so they can be worthy of a temple marriage.  Having a temple</i><br>
<i>&gt; marriage is declares to the world that the couple has saved themselves for</i><br>
<i>&gt; their future spouse and they have victoriously overcome sexual temptation.</i><br>
<p>
Sure, the scare tactics have almost entirely negative effects - they feed<br>
rebellion in those who would be rebellious, and those who are too scared to<br>
rebel often end up carrying that over into marriage, with unhealthy <br>
consequences.  Those who end up doing it for other reasons are often <br>
consumed by guilt and the pressures of trying to lead a double life -<br>
one for public consumption and a different life in private.<br>
<p>
I see a potential problem with the temple marriage philosophy, as<br>
admirable as it is.  I know far too many girls who have been raped at <br>
some stage - far, far too many - and it still makes me feel ill every <br>
time I hear of another case.  The problem is, when all this heavy emphasis <br>
on purity (especially when talked about in terms of purity = virginity) <br>
exists, it makes people who have been raped feel unworthy, impure, defiled,<br>
left out, sick in the stomach, deceitful because they don't feel they can <br>
honestly pipe up with the declaration of virginity that is almost expected <br>
etc.  How do you handle this? <br>
<p>
The second problem is one that SDAs have too - those who have not lived<br>
up to the standards required for a temple marriage (LDS) or those who<br>
have been caught (SDA) become something like second class citizens.<br>
In the SDA case, this means that lots of people tend to end up living<br>
double lives (one for public consumption, one for what they do - or used<br>
to do - in private.)  This tends to either bottle up a lot of guilt, or<br>
create continuing anxiety about being caught and having one's name<br>
dragged through the mud, or just split people into almost two<br>
personalities.  None of these options is healthy.  Where did Christ's<br>
unconditional love go?<br>
<p>
I feel we (SDAs, and probably most Christian churches) put far too much <br>
emphasis on sexual immorality as a socially unacceptable sin (don't get <br>
caught or else your name will be dragged through the mud...)  The other <br>
dimension to the problem is that the people most strenuously advocating <br>
no pre-marital sex are often those who experimented with it themselves <br>
in their younger days.  The whole thing would probably be far better <br>
handled if we left more room for people to make mistakes and bad<br>
choices.  This would reduce the attractiveness of the activity to those<br>
who just want to rebel in the biggest possible way, and reduce the guilt<br>
and hiding in shame problems of those who do it for other reasons.<br>
<p>
There _must_ be room for people to make mistakes.  Allowing people such<br>
room is _not_ the same as condoning an activity.  Unfortunately, this<br>
seems to be a distinction that most people never make.  (This could be<br>
a topic for a whole new post.  I just don't feel like starting it.<br>
Someone push me for it and I will :-)<br>
<p>
The best (and I mean the absolute best) presentation I have ever heard<br>
on this area was by Dr. Danielle Florida at the recent Adventist<br>
Students Association (A.S.A.) "Theological Symposium" at Avondale<br>
College.  (Must remember to post something about this - nothing else<br>
like the Symposium occurs anywhere else in the world.)<br>
    Dr. Florida works at a sexual health clinic, so is eminently <br>
qualified to talk about the matter! This talk was sensible, factual, <br>
very open and very non-judgmental.  I believe the non-judgmental stance<br>
is far more effective than the anti-sex railing which is more usually<br>
seen and less often makes any connection with the audience.  I also<br>
appreciate being treated as an adult - given information with which to<br>
make my own decisions.  On the other hand, the audience was composed of<br>
Uni. students aged 18 up.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Many teens engage in sexual activity along with drugs or alcohol.  So the</i><br>
<i>&gt; sexual activity is actually a component of their rebellion.  Why do so many</i><br>
<i>&gt; teens get pregnant even when birth control is very available now days?  First,</i><br>
<i>&gt; many won't buy it because it indicates pre-meditated sin.  Others rationalize</i><br>
<i>&gt; that if they aren't on birth control, they might use that as their "excuse" to</i><br>
<i>&gt; say no.</i><br>
<p>
I once advocated that all SDA men (I assume unmarried?) should carry <br>
condoms, for the sake of playing devil's advocate in a discussion.  While <br>
I wasn't entirely serious, I wasn't entirely flippant either.  There are <br>
valid points to be made for both sides of the argument, depending perhaps <br>
on how pragmatic or idealistic one is.  I'm tempted to say more, but I'm <br>
not sure how controversial I can commit to being given my current workload.<br>
So, for all you Americans (and now Tony ;-), go figure.<br>
If someone pushes me hard enough, I'll post some more.<br>
<p>
    Mazz.<br>
<p>
Have you ever noticed that replies to your posts only leave in the bits<br>
they disagree with?  It can be a bit disconcerting on the net.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
