<title>Feb_1993: Sunday Absurdity</title>
<h1>Sunday Absurdity</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 10 Feb 1993 17:01:33 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#100">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#100">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#100">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#100">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0101.html">Steven Timm: "Providing Security"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0099.html">McCluskey G: "Re: making money on religion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As soon as I saw the post on the _Ministry_ article, "The Sunday<br>
Absurdity" (January-February 1993, pp. 23-24) I immediately did a search<br>
of the Expanded Academic Index in our online catalog (not yet available<br>
to the net, but I'm exploring that possibility).  This is an index of<br>
about 1500 current periodicals in all areas.  Sure enough, the<br>
_Economist_ article is cited, "Never on a Sunday," (Europe's Blue Laws)<br>
(editorial), October 19, 1991 (v321, n7729), p. 16--hardly new news.<br>
The abstract says, "The European Community has introduced a directive<br>
that bans Sunday working, declaring that it is a health and safety<br>
measure.  German Christian Democrats and tradue unionists brought about<br>
the directive, which may become widely unpopular."  While it should be<br>
noted that this index is largely U.S.-oriented, this was the only<br>
article in the entire database (of over 1 million citations) with the<br>
subject heading "Sunday legislation--Europe."  I have not taken the time<br>
to try other remote databases that might have more information on this<br>
topic.  <br>
<p>
It might be worth noting that most of Western Europe is quite secular in<br>
orientation, and it's an unlikely place for a universal religious Sunday<br>
law to begin.  Actually, I find the whole notion of a universal Sunday<br>
law to be a quaint 19th century relic, and SDA eschatology in this<br>
regard in much need of revision.  My perception of world religion is<br>
that much of the "Christian" world is secular (including the U.S.,<br>
though religion here has more influence that in most other Western<br>
countries), but the majority of the world population is<br>
non-Christian--Communist, Hindu, Buddhist, Islamic, Jewish, secular, etc.,<br>
hardly people likely to establish a Christian law.  Actually, I'm<br>
curious how missionaries to non-Christian societies handle this issue.<br>
In Israel (not to mention strong Islamic societies), the notion must<br>
seem ludicrous.  I suspect this idea was based on a 19th century world<br>
view, with Europe ascendent and most of the world a part of one or<br>
another European empire.  In addition, I think it worth noting that<br>
many societies are getting more tolerant of minorities (with the glaring<br>
exception of Yugoslavia)--including religious ones (witness Spain, as<br>
but one example).  Certainly the trend in the U.S. is toward repeal of<br>
blue laws along with a definite trend toward a multi-cultural,<br>
heterogenous society [something which I believe is behind some of the<br>
desperate attempts of the religious right to prevent this trend].<br>
<p>
I really didn't mean to start a general discussion of Sunday laws (but<br>
merely to provide information).  For what it's worth, there it is.<br>
Needless to say, these are my personal views and do not necessarily<br>
reflect the position of my employer (or, for that matter, the "holy"<br>
Seminary!).<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise,<br>
Head Reference Librarian<br>
Andrews University<br>
(brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
