<title>Feb_1993: Providing Security</title>
<h1>Providing Security</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 10 Feb 1993 18:36:44 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#101">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#101">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#101">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#101">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0102.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Bruce,, commandment keeping and just. by faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0100.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Sunday Absurdity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[From Tim Swensen]<br>
SDAnet:<br>
<p>
I must disagree with Steve when he says that "Reaching the unchurched and <br>
providing security to the churched are mutually exclusive goals, and any <br>
organization can only expect to do one of those two well."  Come to think of<br>
it, I disagree that the SDA church should be primarily in the business of <br>
providing security for its members.  Put bluntly, our security is in Christ<br>
alone.  The church is composed of humans.  Sooner or later each of us is <br>
likely to be profoundly disappointed or hurt by someone in the church -- <br>
perhaps even by someone in its leadership.  Unless Christ is the foundation <br>
of our security, we will have a hard time dealing with this.<br>
<p>
Reaching the unsaved (could I have said "unchurched" instead?) is the primary <br>
reason Jesus instituted the Christian church.  ("Go ye into all nations....")<br>
Reaching out to the unconverted and seeing them accept Christ is crucial<br>
to the health of the local congregation and should in no way hinder our <br>
sense of security in Christ, but rather should draw us closer to him.  This <br>
assumes, of course, that our affection for the church is based on our love<br>
of Christ and the pleasure we derive from worshiping and working with others <br>
who love Him as well.  If, on the other hand, our attachment to the church <br>
derives primarily from our enjoyment of its amenities (nice organ, soft pews, <br>
beautiful windows, etc...) then it may indeed bother us that the "uncultured" <br>
are sitting with us in the pew.  I pray that we love the church for the former<br>
reason and not the latter!<br>
<p>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
[I agree with Tim about what the motives of the church should be.  <br>
I was speaking only to the case of what are the motives now.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
