<title>Feb_1993: Bruce,, commandment keeping and just. by faith</title>
<h1>Bruce,, commandment keeping and just. by faith</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 93 11:17:11 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#102">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#102">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#102">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#102">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Bruce Holm: "EC and Daniel 2 prophecy"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0101.html">Steven Timm: "Providing Security"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0086.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Bruce,, commandment keeping and just. by faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt; Is this salvation by works, or what ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;No, but it definitely takes work to build a relationship with anyone, including</i><br>
<i>&gt;God.  I define work as the putting forth of effort or the expenditure of energy</i><br>
<i>&gt;The difference here is working at a relationship, not working at salvation.</i><br>
<p>
I don't really see the diff. 'cause the end point of working at the relationship<br>
is to get salvation anyway, isn't it ?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The</i><br>
<i>&gt; salvation part is a free gift to all who would accept Christ and start a</i><br>
<i>&gt; relationship with Him. </i><br>
<p>
Isn`t this  a bit like saying that the salvation part is a free gift to all<br>
who accept Christ and obey him ?<br>
<p>
I can't really see the difference between working at obedience and working <br>
at a relationship, its still working and the ultimate object of the work is <br>
the same, salvation.<br>
<p>
Yes one can argue that one can obey without a good relationship, but I think<br>
you will find that that type of obedience is a whitewash. One can also<br>
have a relationship without any obedience, in which case the relationship<br>
is a farce. It seems to me like you sort of need both things simultaneously.<br>
<p>
But of course you know how the bible tests whether a relationship is good or<br>
not, don't you ? "By their fruits ye shall know them...a good tree does not<br>
bring forth good fruits neither does a good tree bring forth bad fruits."<br>
<p>
When the bible talks here about a tree it is talking about relationships, just<br>
look up John 15 about the vine for confirmation of this point. <br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;By the way, what was out of context?...your comments or mine?  I believe my</i><br>
<i>&gt;comments were relavent and in the context of the subject line.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;--Bruce</i><br>
<p>
My quotation of your comments were out of context.<br>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
