<title>Feb_1993: Re: Inspiration: questions</title>
<h1>Re: Inspiration: questions</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 93 11:48:43 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#105">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#105">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#105">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#105">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0106.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Pastoral roles in the SDA church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0104.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: EGW quote"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0088.html">Steven Timm: "Inspiration: questions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi,<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Ruben, I didn't mean to frighten you.  Because I spoke favorably of my</i><br>
<i>&gt; neighborhood Episcopalian parish, you strongly suggested that I was</i><br>
<i>&gt; consorting with the dragon of Revelation 12.</i><br>
<p>
Sorry, its just that I am very disturbed by some rather unfortunate<br>
ecumenical moves within the SDA church. And I'm not necessarily referring to<br>
individuals.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;    But Ruben, you haven't answered my question.  This is what I thought</i><br>
<i>&gt; was the most important issue in my latest communique on SDAnet.  I think</i><br>
<i>&gt; our denomination has an identity crisis.  I'll repeat the question.  "Do</i><br>
<i>&gt; you think our denomination can find a niche?  Survive?  Thrive?"</i><br>
<p>
Sorry, I didn't realise the question was directed specifically at me.<br>
<p>
As for anwering the question, my reply is best outlined in G.C. I think<br>
to answer it a little more specifically that this crisis is somewhat <br>
reflected in the history of Israel at the time of Ezekiel, and at the<br>
time of Christ's first advent. So I think our denomination will ride out<br>
the crisis the same ways as Israel did on these occasions in the past.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;    I'd also be interested in your response to some merely sociological</i><br>
<i>&gt; questions.</i><br>
<i>&gt;    1.) Do you think the Seventh-Day Adventist Church is, or should be, a</i><br>
<i>&gt; fundamentalist denomination?  How do you define fundamentalism,</i><br>
<i>&gt; especially as it addresses biblical interpretation?</i><br>
<p>
No I don't think the SDA church is or should be fundamental. Fundamentalism<br>
is taking every single word as being inerrant, which I disagree with.<br>
I also disagree with libral scriptural interpretation, such that the clear<br>
bible meaning is distorted or lost. EGW says that we should take the bible<br>
as it reads. This means free from the trandition of men, and their philosphy.<br>
Irresepective of who they may be. Interestingly the traditions of men <br>
encompasses culture, because that is what culture simply is.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;    2.) What, in your mind, characterizes a sect or cult?  Compare or</i><br>
<i>&gt; contrast SDA's you know (include yourself if you'd like) with your</i><br>
<i>&gt; understanding of what makes a person a cultist.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
I personally think the SDA church was better off when it was considered<br>
a sect (ie before 1953 and that nice episode with Dr W.Martin). As to what<br>
characterises a cult, I really havn't though too much about it.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;    3.) Can an Adventist be sure enough about the superiority of his</i><br>
<i>&gt; doctrine to call someone else's religion false?  Can you or I be that</i><br>
<i>&gt; sure and still be humble?  (Remember we Adventists learned about the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Sabbath from another denomination.  Are we that open to change--that</i><br>
<i>&gt; open to admitting error--today?)</i><br>
<p>
Well if I wasn't sure of SDA theology I would leave the church immediately.<br>
Why stick around if you don't even know if its the truth or not, heck, what a <br>
waste. As to whether SDAs can be sure enough regarding this point, isn't this<br>
the whole concept of Adventism, to call people out of Babylon. If we don't<br>
know whether Babylon is Babylon or not, or if we don't know what to call them<br>
out into then what's the point of Adventism. Can we be sure and humble, yes<br>
I can't necessarily see any conflict between the two, however as with all <br>
things the track of perdition lies very close to the track of salvation.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;    This isn't an IQ test or anything.  It's not a political correctness</i><br>
<i>&gt; exam.  There are no correct answers.  But your answers will give me a</i><br>
<i>&gt; better basis for understanding where you're coming from.  It would be</i><br>
<i>&gt; enlightening to hear the analyses of others on our diverse network.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
Did I pass ?? <br>
It should have been multiple choice, they're mor fun that way.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;    Please, Ruben, don't worry about my overactive apostate gland.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
<p>
he, he, this I'll have to remember.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
