<title>Feb_1993: Pastoral roles in the SDA church</title>
<h1>Pastoral roles in the SDA church</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>11 Feb 1993 14:27:32 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#106">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#106">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#106">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#106">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0107.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Iron and clay"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0105.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Inspiration: questions"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0115.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Pastoral roles in the SDA church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have often thought that the pastor's major role should be to act as a<br>
"shepherd to the flock", ministering to the church members and equipping<br>
*them* for outreach. There is a Biblical reference to back this up, but<br>
I can't think of it right now.<br>
<p>
What do you think? We tend to expect too much of our pastors, seeing them<br>
as evangelists, counsellors, preachers as well as shepherds. Many fill some<br>
of these roles well, but rarely are all of them filled by one person.<br>
Besides, laying it all on the pastor turns the congregation into an audience.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
