<title>Feb_1993: Things for the board to help with</title>
<h1>Things for the board to help with</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 10 Feb 1993 23:20:39 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#109">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#109">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#109">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#109">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0110.html">Steven Timm: "Symposium on networking in the SDA church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0108.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "EC and Daniel 2 prophecy"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I already have three volunteers for the board, which is good because I <br>
didn't specify what the tasks of the board would be as yet.  More <br>
volunteers are still welcome. <br>
<p>
At this point in time I don't envision that the board would ever physically<br>
get together in one place and meet.  That's what E-mail is for.  I do <br>
think it will be helpful to discuss new services that could be offered<br>
in addition to the discussion service that is here now.<br>
<p>
Some of these could include:<br>
<p>
A on-line library:<br>
LISTSERV software incorporates this feature automatically, so this would <br>
fit more naturally into SDA-L, except that SDA-L's days on LLUVM are<br>
numbered.  As soon as Enoch Hwang gets around to it (ten minutes to<br>
forever),<br>
it will move to La Sierra and a brain-dead Unix LISTSERV.<br>
<p>
Another ways to accomplish this goal would be an anonymous ftp site<br>
with associated mail server.  I'm not allowed to do this at CMU.<br>
<p>
A World Wide Web or Gopher server<br>
Both of these packages are near-incredible ways to access information,<br>
both text and graphics, all over the world, distributed among many <br>
platforms.  <br>
<p>
A fast SDA news capability--online connections for up-to-the minute news.<br>
<p>
On-line reference access to SDA research material such as library holdings.<br>
<p>
A newsgroup on Usenet<br>
------<br>
The board would make decisions on new services to be offered, <br>
provide guidance in finding new computing resources if they are needed,<br>
and help find ways to generate publicity for SDAnet.  <br>
<p>
Now, once everyone knows this, do those who wanted to be on the board<br>
still want to be, and did any who haven't volunteered yet want to do so?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
