<!-- body="start" -->
Yes, there's a difference.<br>
<p>
As children, we learned that doing certain things could get us cookies,<br>
an extra hours worth of TV, a bicycle or any number of things.<br>
Now there is nothing wrong with those things in and of themselves,<br>
except maybe the cookie, the type of show one watches,  how one<br>
uses the bicycle, or the motives behind the deed.<br>
<p>
The same is with salvation.  Many will say in that day, well didn't we do<br>
*this* and didn't we do *that*?  We can pursue "salvation" (escape from<br>
hell) by doing all the right things.  But if our motives are off track, <br>
from the<br>
one, and only gate/way, the person of Jesus Christ, we are just as lost,<br>
as any "idolater", "sexual immoral", "greedy", "boastful", "liars."  And since<br>
I too am a SINNER saved by *grace* (a grant and not a loan = for you<br>
students) can't read a persons motive/heart, I leave the judging up to <br>
God.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
