&lt;Tim Swensen writes:&gt;<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Reaching the unsaved (could I have said "unchurched" instead?) is the primary</i><br>
<i>&gt;reason Jesus instituted the Christian church.  ("Go ye into all nations....")</i><br>
<i>&gt;Reaching out to the unconverted and seeing them accept Christ is crucial</i><br>
<i>&gt;to the health of the local congregation and should in no way hinder our</i><br>
<i>&gt;sense of security in Christ, but rather should draw us closer to him.  This</i><br>
<i>&gt;assumes, of course, that our affection for the church is based on our love</i><br>
<i>&gt;of Christ and the pleasure we derive from worshiping and working with others</i><br>
<i>&gt;who love Him as well.  If, on the other hand, our attachment to the church</i><br>
<i>&gt;derives primarily from our enjoyment of its amenities (nice organ, soft pews,</i><br>
<i>&gt;beautiful windows, etc...) then it may indeed bother us that the "uncultured"</i><br>
<i>&gt;are sitting with us in the pew.  I pray that we love the church for the former</i><br>
<i>&gt;reason and not the latter!</i><br>
<p>
<p>
	Your post is good.  However, I'd like to add that our affection can also be<br>
	obsessed with the letter of laws, neglecting the law's spirit.  Some call it<br>
	legalism.  In this, even the "very elect" can be deceived.  	There's an<br>
	excellent newspaper editorial which I clipped about the late Thurgood<br>
	Marshall's unending passion and love for the law, it's spirit.  If I <br>
find it I'll post<br>
	later... WITH copyright reference of course.<br>
<p>
	When I was at Southern College, and that majestic pipe organ was played,<br>
	sometimes my mind would wonder in worship to the instrament or musician.<br>
	Maybe we should not panic when this happens, but with Christ's help, try to<br>
	look deeper into the direction of the One these things (hopefully) are <br>
uplifting.<br>
	I _dare_ anyone to contemplate the goodness, righteousness, justice,<br>
	forgiveness and "eternalness" of God, while in the presence of nature,<br>
	or even in the huge stained-glass sanctuaries of our college, or university<br>
	campuses (organs and all), WITHOUT being spiritually moved.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
