<title>Feb_1993: Re: Teens and sex</title>
<h1>Re: Teens and sex</h1>
<i>ronswen@aol.com</i><br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 93 03:37:41 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#117">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#117">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#117">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#117">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Steven Timm: "We have enough board members"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Ron Vyhmeister: "Neural networks"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0098.html">Richard Mazzaferri: "Teens and sex"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I am convinced that we within the Adventist subculture and the wider<br>
Christian community need to maintain our healthy (and even romantic!) notion<br>
of lifelong monagamy.  In addition to being given to us in the New Testament,<br>
it has proven to be the only prudent behavior in today's world of AIDS and<br>
other sexually transmitted diseases.  Where we fail miserably is in opening<br>
lines of communication between the generations which allow frank discussion<br>
of why this notion is so valuable.  Teens have many reasons for experimenting<br>
with sex ranging from desire, to curiosity, to asserting independence, to<br>
love, to peer pressure, to fear of losing a loved boyfriend/girlfriend etc. <br>
Teens will accept advice from adults but will reject out of hand<br>
paternalistic commands not accompanied by thorough explanation of the reasons<br>
why they are given.  After all, teens are formulating their own values and<br>
are challenging all values instilled by previous authority figures. <br>
<p>
I have no teenagers in my house.  Instead, my exposure to the issue is both<br>
personal as I formulate my own sexual behavior and professional as a<br>
gynecologist.  The following are some medical reasons why it is exceedingly<br>
unwise for teens to engage in sex outside of a committed monogamous<br>
relationship.<br>
1.  Sexually transmitted diseases:  Sexually active teens have a very high<br>
prevalance of STD's.  Human Papillomavirus (HPV), the virus which causes<br>
genital warts has been isolated in as many as 50% of women undergoing<br>
treatment in college student health service clinics.  Clearly, the rate of<br>
infection would be similiar if not higher in sexually active college men. <br>
This virus is also implicated in cervical carcinogenesis and has been found<br>
in &gt;90% of cervical cancer tumors.  Fortunately, the vast majority of HPV<br>
infections do not progress to cancer, but many of them do cause pap smear<br>
abnormalities necessitating frequent treatment.  2-3 million new cases of<br>
genital warts are diagnosed each year in the US.  To put this into<br>
perspective, in a non-epidemic year there are about 15 million cases of the<br>
"flu".  Thus, sexually active teens are roughly 1/7 as likely to get HPV as<br>
the flu.  (I realize the epidemiology is crude in this example, but hopefully<br>
the point was made that HPV is very common.)  A second scourge is Chlamydia,<br>
a tiny bacteria which can infect women without any symptoms.  This organism<br>
is particularly effective at damaging the fallopian tubes and uterus causing<br>
scarring and potential infertility.  This agent is unfortunately the MOST<br>
common agent spread sexually with about 5 million victims yearly in the US. <br>
(There are more cases of Chlamydia than there are pregnancies each year in<br>
the US!)  Chlamydia can also infect men, usually causing a white discharge<br>
and painful urination.  The most frightening STD, HIV virus infection is<br>
fortunately rather rare with typically 4/1000 Americans carrying the virus. <br>
The risk is actually higher however because most of the carriers are<br>
aggregated within the reproductive years.  Although most cases are still<br>
concentrated among gay men or IV drug users, heterosexual contact is the most<br>
rapidly growing route of infection.  Clearly the risk is low but not zero and<br>
the infection currently is incurable and eventually fatal.  Gonorrhea is<br>
transmitted to about 1/2 million new victims per year with similiar<br>
consequences as Chlamydia.  Of course, there are more diseases to consider<br>
but I think I have made my point regarding STD's!!!<br>
<p>
2.   Pregnancy: The US has the highest rate of unwanted pregnancy in the<br>
developed world despite having access to virtually all modern contraceptives.<br>
 Christian and Adventist teens are obviously not immune to this epidemic.  It<br>
has been estimated that out of the 4.5 million pregnancies yearly, 3.0<br>
million are unexpected and of that 50% proceed to abortion.  Regardless of<br>
your position on the abortion debate, all would agree that 1.5 million<br>
abortions, most ofwhich would be preventable by adequate contraceptive<br>
practice, are a national tragedy.  Teens are at particular risk of pregnancy<br>
for several reasons: <br>
  a. poor planning-many teens refuse to get or use contraceptives because<br>
this would admit to planning to have sexual relations.  Premeditated sex is<br>
"worse" than impulsive sex.  For this reason, many teens are unprepared for<br>
the inevitable consquences.  Unprotected midcycle intercourse carries a 17%<br>
risk of pregnancy.  Teenage women need to be told that contraceptive<br>
techniques are available which can be taken AFTER intercourse which will<br>
reduce the risk to about 2% if they have had unprotected sex, however this<br>
must be taken within 2 days of intercourse.<br>
  b. irregular ovulation-In many teenage women the pituitary and ovary are<br>
still maturing.  This causes irregular and often unpredictable ovulation and<br>
menses.  This makes it even more difficult than usual to predict when she is<br>
at highest risk for getting pregnant.<br>
  c. feeling of invincibility (i.e. "it can't happen to me").  Unfortunately,<br>
this illusion is not shattered until pregnancy occurs for many teenage women.<br>
<p>
3.  Cervical cancer.  Women who initiate sexual activity early seem to be at<br>
a greater risk for cervical cancer.  This is probably related to the HPV<br>
virus infecting a cervix that is not yet mature.  In the immature cervix<br>
there is a greater area of tissue which is rapidly replicating.  This<br>
apparently places the young woman at increased risk.<br>
<p>
4.  Psychological/developmental factors.  I don't have hard data on these<br>
risks, however Pediatricians I have spoken to are convinced that the average<br>
American young person achieves biological maturity several years before<br>
psychological maturity.  This adds to the difficulties in responsibly using<br>
their sexuality adding to the problems listed in #1 and #2.<br>
<p>
Teens may hear all of this information and be overwhelmed, but there is<br>
compelling reasons why the smart teens will either avoid sex or, if having<br>
sex, will take appropriate measure to minimize the risks associated with<br>
non-monogamous sex.  Much of this info is equally appropriate to any age, not<br>
just to teenagers of course.  As an aside, many teens or singles practice<br>
what has been called "serial monogamy" which means that they are having<br>
sexual relations with only the person they are dating at the time, but when<br>
the current relationship dissolves, a new partner is taken as the next<br>
relationship begins.  This practice, rather than being somewhat safe is<br>
probably more risky than "sleeping around" where persons have intermittent<br>
encounters with more than one partner.  The reason for this is that most<br>
sexually transmitted diseases are not exquistely infectious.  That is,<br>
repeated exposure to any sexually transmitted agent increases the probability<br>
of transmission.  As a consequence, persons practicing "serial monogamy"<br>
maximize the chance that they will acquire any STDs from their previous<br>
partner and then pass it along to the next partner.<br>
<p>
For those of us within the Christian and Adventist community, we have God's<br>
word asking us to submit all of us, including our bodies, to Jesus.  This is<br>
exceedingly difficult to do, particularly in romantically tempting<br>
circumstances.  Regardless of the medical risks, our goal is to follow what<br>
God asks us to do.  The health risks simply remind us that His requests are<br>
in our own best long term interest and are given to us because He loves us! <br>
<p>
Way back at the beginning of this post (remember!!!) I lamented the lack of<br>
communication between generations regarding reasons for abstinence.  I hope<br>
SDA academies are willing to be frank about the consequences of poor choices<br>
regarding sexuality before those consequences occur rather than waiting to<br>
discipline students who have made poor choices.<br>
<p>
Thanks for reading,<br>
Ron Swensen<br>
(ron swen@aol.com)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
