<title>Feb_1993: Networking symposium</title>
<h1>Networking symposium</h1>
Harvey Brenneise (<i>brneise@edmund.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 1993 14:20:27 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#119">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#119">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#119">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#119">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Dan Gill: "re: networking and the SDA church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Steven Timm: "We have enough board members"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think the symposium is an excellent idea.  We already communicate over<br>
the net, so more of that, while helping refine ideas, might not break<br>
new ground.  There is something to be said for eye-to-eye contact (in<br>
reading e-mail I often miss the non-verbal cues and communication).<br>
If it's important to communicate with those not on the net (and I think<br>
it is), an actual (rather than virtual?) symposium might be more useful.<br>
It seems that a lot of people (including myself) still need education on<br>
what is possible before implementation can begin.  I can think of a<br>
number of potential audiences:<br>
<p>
Church leaders.  I don't think most of them have any idea of what's<br>
going on here (at least if my casual conversations at the GC are any<br>
indication).  However, I believe a number of them might be quite<br>
interested.  For example, I understand that Folkenberg is quite<br>
interested in new technology.  For this group, a meeting at the GC (much<br>
as I hate to suggest it!) might be best.  This could include editors and<br>
some educators.<br>
<p>
Editors.  A subgroup of the above.  I spoke to the Adventist Editors<br>
International meeting last year in MD, and I know there's interest in at<br>
least some of these issues.  They are scattered around the country, but<br>
they do have an annual conference (this year in Madison or Milwaukee,<br>
WI, I believe).  <br>
<p>
Educators.  An obvious group, though there is no obvious conference or<br>
place.  Years ago, there used to be quinquennial meetings of SDA<br>
educators, but that was lost in budget cuts (unfortunately).<br>
<p>
Librarians (of course!).  Many of these issues are of interest to us,<br>
and some have already been discussed at our annual Conference<br>
(Association of SDA Librarians).  This summer the meeting will be at<br>
Canadian Union College, next summer here at Andrews, 1995 at Newbold<br>
just prior to GC in Utrecht.  I expect that ASDAL would gladly<br>
co-sponsor something of this type.  We have found that (exclusive of<br>
travel) meetings can be held quite inexpensively on SDA campuses in the<br>
summer.<br>
<p>
Given our international network membership, I am sure that if we were to<br>
have an actual meeting, we would still want to include discussions on<br>
the net, as I am sure many individuals would not be able to attend an<br>
actual symposium.<br>
<p>
These are just a few ideas that come to mind.  We must be careful that<br>
we don't limit ourselves to "blue sky" thinking but remember the need<br>
for educating people (particularly those who control the money we want<br>
to spend!).<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise<br>
Head Reference Librarian, Andrews University<br>
Internet: brneise@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
