<title>Feb_1993: re: networking and the SDA church</title>
<h1>re: networking and the SDA church</h1>
Dan Gill (<i>dangle@netcom.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 93 15:07:29 -0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#120">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#120">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#120">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#120">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0121.html">Russell Grau: "Re: control of sex"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0119.html">Harvey Brenneise: "Networking symposium"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve,<br>
<p>
I have been a long time user of the internet and for the last 4 months<br>
I have been without a connection due to a job change.  I just got my own<br>
connection from a local supplier.  I felt completly lost with out<br>
a connection to the outside world!<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;For some time I have wondered whether or not it would be feasible to </i><br>
<i>&gt;hold a symposium on the benefits and potential benefits of electronic</i><br>
<p>
Most people who have never really used or had access to the data highways<br>
don't understand just how many there are.  First is just the ability to<br>
send e-mail quickly and at a _very_ low cost to the end user.  My dad,<br>
who lives in Colorado, I got hooked up through Denver U and now we<br>
can send mail for free.  And it gets there much faster than US SNAIL mail.<br>
<p>
The bigger items, however, are on-line database access.  I have often thought<br>
how nice it would be to have the EGW stuff ftp'able.  I figure one day if no<br>
one else does, I'll get the CD and make it available.  The church could also<br>
provide forums, on various topics, plus transcripts from import events.<br>
<p>
Users then would also have access to usenet news.  This is, in some cases,<br>
where the trenches are.  Talk.religion.misc, and soc.religion.christian<br>
have been covering some very interesting threads for the few years I've<br>
been reading them.  I have made some on-line friends across the world<br>
from reading posts and responding to them.<br>
<p>
As for the initial investment to get started, it would be small.  Most of<br>
our universities and institutions already have access.  It would merely mean<br>
expanding the scope of services provided and allowing access to the "public".<br>
<p>
I would be behind this kind of adventure all the way, I'd even consider<br>
being in front of it. 8-)<br>
<p>
Thanks,<br>
<p>
dan<br>
