<title>Feb_1993: Re: control of sex</title>
<h1>Re: control of sex</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctshp.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 1993 14:48:34 -0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#121">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#121">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#121">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#121">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0122.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "What is a Cult"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Dan Gill: "re: networking and the SDA church"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;One aspect of this topic that has not been mentioned is the</i><br>
<i>&gt;influence of our diet and health practices on our sex drive.</i><br>
<i>&gt;I believe that the health counsels of Ellen White, if followed,</i><br>
<i>&gt;would do a lot towards helping us to keep this under control.</i><br>
<i>&gt;A simple, natural diet helps to restrain the ``animal passions.''</i><br>
<i>&gt;Also, I think getting plenty of sunlight  helps to milden our</i><br>
<i>&gt;disposition, and outdoor exercise has a similar effect.</i><br>
<i>&gt;High fat and sugar and protein intake tends to have the opposite</i><br>
<i>&gt;effect.  I can't give scientific evidence for this but it has</i><br>
<i>&gt;been borne out in my own experience and seems to be supported</i><br>
<i>&gt;by the testimonies of Sister White.  There seems to be a</i><br>
<i>&gt;similar correlation with the control of temper.  Of course,</i><br>
<i>&gt;this doesn't mean that the temptation will go away.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;	Dave Plaisted</i><br>
<p>
I know that this won't be popular, but, how about controlling<br>
our access to the TV?  There is such a culture in the TV that<br>
is influencing our young people, how about teaching them when<br>
to actually turn the channel?  How about teaching them to deal<br>
with the "evil" that TV can be?<br>
<p>
How about just recognizing that evil for what it is?  The TV<br>
ads and their scantily clad ladies and men are ruses to <br>
inflame youthful passions (and those of us in that are only<br>
a few years removed from their youth also!!).  Tell them that<br>
the women and men on the television and in the theater are<br>
NOT the real people they purport to be.  That they are actors<br>
just reading a script.  That real men and women do not react<br>
in the manner that they do.<br>
<p>
Real preparation for a real world.  Perhaps that should be <br>
our motto in teaching our youth, both in sabbath school and <br>
in our acadamies.<br>
<p>
Russell E. Grau<br>
internet: reg@celltech.com<br>
AOL : russellgen@aol.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
