<title>Feb_1993: What is a Cult</title>
<h1>What is a Cult</h1>
<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i><br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 93 15:19:42 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#122">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#122">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#122">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#122">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0123.html">patricio d navia: "Re: Inspiration: questions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0121.html">Russell Grau: "Re: control of sex"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0124.html">Woody Baker: "Re: What is a Cult"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The question of "what is a cult church" really boils down to a cult being<br>
any church that the mainline churches are uncomfortable with with<br>
regards to their theology.  Its not mainline theology.  As I recall,<br>
that is basically what I found near the beginning of Walter Martin's book.<br>
And other "cult" critics would basically agree.<br>
<p>
By that definition the Protestant Reformers were a bunch of cultists<br>
simply because the Catholic Church was "the church" of that erra.<br>
Also, early Christians were cultists in the context of Judaism.  So,<br>
really, being a cultist is not necessarily a bad thing.<br>
<p>
Those who are members of the mainline churches can look down from their<br>
balconies and think of us as cultists.  But the Bible tells me that<br>
the majority will go out through the broad gate, only a few entered<br>
the ark, etc.  So, if cultist means "in a minority" doctrinally, then<br>
that sounds like a plus -- but of course no proof at all of truth.<br>
Holding a majority position does not make it wrong, but urges caution.<br>
Holding a minority position does not make it right, either way, check<br>
it out thoroughly.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
