<title>Feb_1993: Re: What is a Cult</title>
<h1>Re: What is a Cult</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 11 Feb 1993 21:44:01 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#124">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#124">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#124">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#124">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0125.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0123.html">patricio d navia: "Re: Inspiration: questions"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0122.html">davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com: "What is a Cult"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The most current definition of "cult" that I have found, runs along<br>
the line of.."A cult denies the divenity of Christ, and swears allegance<br>
to a particular person"  Some examples:<br>
Jim Jones, L.Ron Hubbard, Moons followers etc.  The PRIMARY reason that<br>
some people label Adventists as a Cult, is because of our emphysis on<br>
EGW and inspiration.  They see a paralell between that, and Mary Baker<br>
Eddy, J.J, L.R.H etc.   However, the first part of the definition<br>
disqualifies S.D.A's as being a cult.  If you've been sensitive to church<br>
directions, you will notice a de-emphysis of EGW has been taking place for<br>
about the last 10-12 years in the Adventist church.  We have been distancing<br>
ourselfs from this, in order to diminish the force of the "cult label".<br>
I am not going to get into the issue of inspiration vs non-inspiration,<br>
but EGW has not played to well to the world the way many Adventists have<br>
mis-used what she has written.  How many times have you been "hit over<br>
the head" with EGW??!  The Adventist church is a thinking mans church.<br>
Unfortunatly, we tend to forget that new christians need to be fed the<br>
milk of the word, not the meat, and thus "think" them right out the back<br>
door.  I drove by the River Bend Baptist church today, here in Austin,<br>
and could not help contrasting it to our church.  The church campus<br>
covers about 10 acres, with at least 5 of those in parking lots, and is<br>
generaly packed full on Sunday.  It has a large sign out front advertising<br>
the fact that it is a "healing fellowship of Baptists".  On the other hand<br>
we have a church sitting on a couple of acres, that can seat 300 or so, and<br>
we have 200 people on the books, with around 50 regulars.  We are doing<br>
something wrong as a church (both globally and locally).<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
<p>
woody@knapper.cactus.org
woody@chinacat.unicom.com (temporary) is forwareded to woody@knapper
</pre>
