<title>Feb_1993: Is running a campaign appropriate?</title>
<h1>Is running a campaign appropriate?</h1>
Randall A Helzerman (<i>helz@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Feb 93 6:54:59 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#125">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#125">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#125">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#125">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0126.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Thinking man's church?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0124.html">Woody Baker: "Re: What is a Cult"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0128.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'd like some good advice from you Adventists on the net.<br>
<p>
     I was recently asked if I might be willing to serve as the<br>
campaign manager for Steve Dillon, who is running for Secretary of<br>
State for Indiana in 1994.  I was of course very honored, but its not<br>
a straightforward decision.  Here are some questions I have for you<br>
all:<br>
<p>
1.  Is it proper for Adventists to be doing this sort of thing? <br>
<p>
2.  What are the relevent EGW quotes on the subject?  Do you think they<br>
    hold for today or were just for her time?<br>
<p>
3.  Steve Dillon will be running not as a Democrat or Republican, but a<br>
    Libertarian.  I believe that the Libertarian Party is the best party<br>
    in America today and I'm proud to call myself a Libertarian, but I<br>
    am a Seventh-day Adventist first and a Libertarian second.  Do you<br>
    think it would help, hinder, or have no effect whatsoever on the<br>
    reputation of the SDA church to have one of its members being both<br>
    a visible, activist Adventist and a visible, activist Libertarian?<br>
<p>
Thanks for all your responses, and please pray for me as I consider<br>
this decision.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
