<title>Feb_1993: Thinking man's church?</title>
<h1>Thinking man's church?</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Feb 93 13:29:47 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#126">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#126">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#126">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#126">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0127.html">Marcus Stringer: "Book question"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0125.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0132.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Thinking man's church?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Just wanted to respond to what woody said:<br>
<p>
        "The Adventist church is a thinking mans church."<br>
<p>
Actually, this points out one of the problems with the SDA Church at present.<br>
The role of women in the church remains nebulous.  They still haven't decided<br>
to ordain women even though women can perform the same duties as men.  The<br>
church fails to offer a supportive program for single parents (almost always<br>
women).  Many SDA churches still won't let a woman say congregational prayer<br>
or speak from the platform.  Some won't let them teach a Sabbath School class<br>
in the adult division (they can teach kids but not adults!).  The church doesn't<br>
know what to do about single women (without kids).  There's no formal program<br>
for women that has a spiritual or social thrust.  Most SDA churches no longer<br>
have Dorcas Societies which mostly offered service opportunities for elderly<br>
women.  The church rarely addresses women's issues in sermons, sabbath school<br>
quarterlies, or church publications.<br>
<p>
In fact, the SDA church as an organization seems to believe that only men can<br>
think.  So yes, the Adventist church is a thinking man's church.  Unfortunately,<br>
with more than half the members being women, it is failing to address the<br>
needs of women in any meaningful way.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<p>
