<title>Feb_1993: Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?</title>
<h1>Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Feb 93 12:29:02 -0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#128">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#128">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#128">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#128">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0129.html">MARK BILBY: "Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0127.html">Marcus Stringer: "Book question"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0125.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0129.html">MARK BILBY: "Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi,<br>
<p>
On Feb 12,  6:54am, Randall A Helzerman wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; 1.  Is it proper for Adventists to be doing this sort of thing?</i><br>
<p>
Why not?  It's high time that SDAs become leaders in the community.  Why always<br>
leave that up to others of varying beliefs?  View it as a terrifica opportunity.<br>
But along with it will be tremendous temptations!  You should ask yourself how<br>
strong a person you think you can be with God's help?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; 2.  What are the relevent EGW quotes on the subject?  Do you think they</i><br>
<i>&gt;     hold for today or were just for her time?</i><br>
<p>
Principles obtained from EGW writings are relevant for today.  But don't always<br>
take her at face value...she wrote once that you shouldn't buy a bicycle.  That<br>
doesn't mean no one should buy one, but at the time they cost a great deal<br>
(still can today if you get into the big leagues).  The principle (+/-) is don't<br>
buy something that costs alot more than you can afford that isn't absolutely<br>
critical.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; 3.  Steve Dillon will be running not as a Democrat or Republican, but a</i><br>
<i>&gt;     Libertarian.  I believe that the Libertarian Party is the best party</i><br>
<i>&gt;     in America today and I'm proud to call myself a Libertarian, but I</i><br>
<i>&gt;     am a Seventh-day Adventist first and a Libertarian second.  Do you</i><br>
<i>&gt;     think it would help, hinder, or have no effect whatsoever on the</i><br>
<i>&gt;     reputation of the SDA church to have one of its members being both</i><br>
<i>&gt;     a visible, activist Adventist and a visible, activist Libertarian?</i><br>
<p>
The effect you have as a highly visible SDA is entirely up to you.  You can<br>
correctly represent the church buy honoring God's laws as interpreted by our<br>
church or you can disregard them.  I would see the Sabbath issue as prominent in<br>
my mind as a big hurdle for you to work out.  But if you can be up front with<br>
them and get in writing a statement that allows you to avoid work on the<br>
Sabbath, that can be a terrific witness for others, especially if God can work<br>
through you and bless your work.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;-- End of excerpt from Randall A Helzerman</i><br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<p>
