<title>Feb_1993: What is a cult?</title>
<h1>What is a cult?</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Feb 93 15:37:20 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#130">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#130">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#130">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#130">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0131.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: Thinking man's church?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0129.html">MARK BILBY: "Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0154.html">Steven Timm: "Re: What is a cult?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was going to disagree with Woody's definition of a cult (don't believe in<br>
God) so I decided to reseach it a bit.  I found a recent book (1986) which<br>
examines both the definition of a cult and discusses the major cults in America.<br>
<p>
        Melton, J. Gordon.  ENCYCLOPEDIC HANDBOOD OF CULTS IN AMERICA.<br>
        New York: Garland Publ, 1986.<br>
<p>
What defines a cult depends on the perspective one is using.  Melton presents<br>
three definitions:  the social science definition, the Christian polemicist<br>
definition, and the secular anti-cultist definition.<br>
<p>
SOCIAL SCIENCE DEFINITION OF A CULT<br>
<p>
        Social scientists distinguish 3 types of religious bodies:  churches,<br>
sects, and cults.  A Church is defined as a large religious denomination<br>
characterized by their inclusive approach to life and their identification<br>
with the prevailing culture.  A sect is a body of believers that has broken<br>
away from a church.  They tend to follow the denominations in most patterns<br>
but are more strict in doctrine and behavioral demands placed upon members.<br>
Sects emphasize their separation and distinctiveness from the larger culture<br>
and typically focus on dress codes, moral conduct, personal piety, and anti-war<br>
activities.  A cult according to sociologists is "religition innovation within<br>
culture".  Cults don't follow cultural norms and may be exagerated sects.<br>
<p>
CHRISTIAN POLEMICISTS DEFINITION OF A CULT<br>
<p>
        They define a cult as deviation from orthodox faith.  One of the first<br>
was Jan Karel Van Baalen (1938).  He divided religion into two basic groups:<br>
those who ascribe to humans the ability to accomplish their own salvation and<br>
those who ascribe that ability to God.  Josh McDowell and Don Stewart:  "A<br>
cult is a perversion, a distortion of Biblical Christianity, and as such,<br>
rejects the historical teachings of the Christian Church."  Any group of<br>
believers that departs from orthodox Christianity is considered a cult.<br>
(Walter Martin is of this group).  Unfortunately, this group doesn't consider<br>
cults of NonChristian origin to be cults because their definition is intricately<br>
tied to Christianity.<br>
<p>
SECULAR ANTI-CULTIST'S Characteristics of a Cult (Marcia Rudin)<br>
<p>
1.  cult members swear total allegiance to an all-powerful leader who they<br>
    believe to be the Messiah<br>
2.  Rational thought is discouraged or forbidden<br>
3.  Deceptive recruitment techniques<br>
4.  cult weakens the follower psychologically by making him/her depend upon<br>
    the group to solve his/her problems<br>
5.  manipulates guilt to their advantage<br>
6.  cult leaders make all career and life decisions of members<br>
7.  cults exist only for their own material survival and make false promises<br>
    to work to improve society<br>
8.  members work fulltime for the group for little or no pay<br>
9.  members are isolated from the outside world and any reality testing it<br>
    could provide<br>
10. cults are antiwoman, antichild, and antifamily<br>
11. cults are apocalyptic and believe themselves to be the remnant who will<br>
    survive the soon-approaching end of the world<br>
12. cults follow "ends justify the means" philosophy<br>
13. cults, particularly in regard to their finances, are shrouded in secrecy<br>
14. there is frequently an aura of or potential for violence around cults<br>
<p>
Interestingly, this book does NOT cover the Seventh-day Adventist Church.  The<br>
author apparently does not consider it to be a cult.  By the Christian<br>
polemicist definition, the SDA church certainly qualifies as a SECT.  Some may<br>
think that the SDA church also has some of the characteristics of a CULT from<br>
the secular anit-cultist definition:  anyone who has ever worked for the SDA<br>
church may attest that they work fulltime for the group for little pay.  #11<br>
certainly applies with "remnant" being a favorite word for SDAs.  And some may<br>
think that guilt is manipulated to the church's advantage.  But 3/14 doesn't<br>
qualify the SDA as a cult.  Ironically, J. Gordon Melton's companion book,<br>
BIOGRAPHICAL DICTIONARY OF AMERICAN CULT AND SECT LEADERS (1986) includes<br>
entries for William Miller, Ellen Gould Harmon White, and other SDA leaders.<br>
(Probably as a SECT).  He also points out that both the Jehovah's Witnesses<br>
and the Worldwide Church of God began as splinter groups from the SDA Church.<br>
The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day Saints, the Church of Christ<br>
Scientist, and many others are still designated CULTS is his books.<br>
<p>
Hope this is helpful in the discussion of What is a cult?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
