<title>Feb_1993: Re: Thinking man's church?</title>
<h1>Re: Thinking man's church?</h1>
Bruce Holm (<i>bruceh@wv.mentorg.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 12 Feb 93 16:37:37 -0800</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#131">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#131">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#131">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#131">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Thinking man's church?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0130.html">cheryl berthelsen: "What is a cult?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think that you may not be aware of some SDA churchs.  I can only speak based on<br>
what I have seen in our local church and those I have visited...<br>
<p>
On Feb 12,  1:29pm, cheryl berthelsen wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Thinking man's church?</i><br>
<i>&gt; ...</i><br>
<i>&gt; They still haven't decided</i><br>
<i>&gt; to ordain women even though women can perform the same duties as men.</i><br>
<p>
I think they have decided since I know of women pastors of large churches.  I<br>
could be wrong on this.  Its only a matter of time before more women will come<br>
through the channels of theology training and you will start to see more and<br>
more women in minister roles.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The</i><br>
<i>&gt; church fails to offer a supportive program for single parents (almost always</i><br>
<i>&gt; women).</i><br>
<p>
What kind of support do you have in mind?  I agree that they need to be accepted<br>
as any other fellow Christian brother/sister.  In our church I believe they are.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Many SDA churches still won't let a woman say congregational prayer</i><br>
<i>&gt; or speak from the platform.</i><br>
<p>
Our little suburban church lets woman speak from up front.  The Outreach person<br>
is a woman and speaks up front often.  Our church had a missionary woman have<br>
the serman time just recently.  And I would also imagine that if any qualified<br>
woman wanted to have the serman, they could.  Fact is, I don't think too many<br>
woman or men in our church are anxious to get up and give the serman...they<br>
leave that up to the pastors, who do happen to be male.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Some won't let them teach a Sabbath School class</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the adult division (they can teach kids but not adults!).</i><br>
<p>
Of the three adult SS classes in our little church, two are lead by woman and<br>
the third is the pastor's class.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The church doesn't</i><br>
<i>&gt; know what to do about single women (without kids).</i><br>
<p>
What should they do?  They don't do anything special for single men either.  I<br>
am aware of a "singles" group in our area that is fairly active and advertises<br>
in many of the local church bulletins about activities.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; There's no formal program</i><br>
<i>&gt; for women that has a spiritual or social thrust.</i><br>
<p>
None for men either.  So why should women have special programs that don't exist<br>
for the men either?  Maybe both are needed?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Most SDA churches no longer</i><br>
<i>&gt; have Dorcas Societies which mostly offered service opportunities for elderly</i><br>
<i>&gt; women.</i><br>
<p>
Our church does have such a thing but it is called Community Services and is<br>
VERY active in local community service.  They are tied in with a half dozen<br>
other local churchs (of other faiths) who also help out in a joint effort for<br>
the benefit of the community.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The church rarely addresses women's issues in sermons, sabbath school</i><br>
<i>&gt; quarterlies, or church publications.</i><br>
<p>
Again, I don't see men's issues addressed in sermons, SS Quarterlies, and church<br>
publications either.<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; In fact, the SDA church as an organization seems to believe that only men can</i><br>
<i>&gt; think.</i><br>
<p>
I think this is abit of an overstatement.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; So yes, the Adventist church is a thinking man's church.  Unfortunately,</i><br>
<i>&gt; with more than half the members being women, it is failing to address the</i><br>
<i>&gt; needs of women in any meaningful way.</i><br>
<p>
Unfortunately, the SDA church comes from a predominantly male oriented<br>
historical past (in terms of roles in church activity leadership positions).<br>
 But this is not really of SDA origin as much as it is from the conservative<br>
puritan background that our early pioneers were part of.  100-150 years ago,<br>
much of society operated with the notion that women were to take a back seat to<br>
the man...to be seen and not heard, etc.  This was not unique to SDAs.<br>
<p>
Yes, the SDA church has been abit behind the pace of society at large, but that<br>
is typical of them in many other areas, too.  Look at the churchs view on<br>
Sabbath observance, music, entertainment, dress codes, etc and compare then and<br>
now.  There is still room for progress, but I think they have come along way.<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;-- End of excerpt from cheryl berthelsen</i><br>
<p>
