Why don't you move down here to Texas?  Lets see... We have 3 women <br>
adult SS teachers, 2 ordained women elders, and a couple of SS superintendants<br>
plus over half of the church board is made up of women.<br>
<p>
Our church has a rather unique sabbath school setup, that works EXTREMELY<br>
well for us.  We have 2 adult SS classes, with 8 rotating teachers.  The<br>
teachers rotate on a weekly basis.  I am the swing teacher, that is, I fill<br>
in for other teachers if they can't make it.  One of the women elders<br>
(June Ayers) also is a teacher, and she has found the load heavy enough, that<br>
she has decided to swap off with me for half of her scheduled rotations.<br>
<p>
Our women elders are precisely equal to our male elders in both duties,<br>
responsibilities, and other areas.  It is great.<br>
<p>
Please note that I did not say "the thinking males church".  Perhaps<br>
"the thinking peoples church" would have been much more appropriate<br>
for what I meant.  As a church, we tend to drop heavy doctrines on people<br>
when they are trying and struggling with just realizing what Christian<br>
living is about.  We tend to feed the new members with much more than<br>
the "milk" of the word.  True, sometimes we find a true intellectual<br>
and they can handle it, but the majority can't, and as a result we lose<br>
way to many out the back door.  The net result is a slow accumulation<br>
of intellectuals in the church.<br>
<p>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
