<title>Feb_1993: Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?</title>
<h1>Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 13 Feb 1993 21:54:47 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#134">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#134">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#134">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#134">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0135.html">a11111arne@attmail.com: "Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0133.html">Susan Harrington: "Re:  Thinking man's church?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0125.html">Randall A Helzerman: "Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yeah for the Libertarians.  I've voted Lib in the last 4 elections (except<br>
that I voted for Perot this time.)<br>
<p>
I feel, and it is my understanding that we are to try to make the world<br>
a better place.  If this includes running for government, where you might<br>
have some influence, then do it. If I had a chance I would run for congress<br>
or other office.  I see no conflict with ones christian experience.  However,<br>
one would not be representing God correctly, to run a negative campaign.  It<br>
is never appropriate to deliberately hurt someone's feelings. This might be<br>
considered a mitigating circumstance.  I have run for city council several<br>
times, and very nearly got elected the first time.  I belive that I can/could<br>
change some things for the better, if I could get on the city council.<br>
<p>
It is important however, that you stand up for your principles.  Let me give<br>
you an example.  I worked for 18 months selling computers and laser printers<br>
for a store here in town.  I told my boss up front, that I would NOT be doing<br>
any show duty from sundown Fri. thru sundown Sat.  Additionaly, I told him that<br>
I absolutly would not attend any function for any reason where alcholic drinks<br>
were served or consumed.  I was sucessfully able to maintain this in spite<br>
of some pressure.  I found that he was accommodating.  I did attend a christmas<br>
party once.  He arranged to have the happy hour/cocktail bar open about 30 to<br>
45 minutes late, so I would be able to enjoy some of the food.  when the bar<br>
opened, I left.  I would not like to think of the kind of pressure that one<br>
might be subjected to when running a public campaign, but just as I think<br>
it is our duty as Christians to vote, and attempt to make the world better,<br>
I think that if you can successfully maintain your Christian experience and<br>
hold public office, by all means do so.  If you are asked to manage a<br>
campaign, go for it, if you think you can do it, and just stick to your<br>
principles.<br>
<p>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
<p>
woody@knapper.cactus.org
woody@chinacat.unicom.com (temporary) is forwareded to woody@knapper
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
