<title>Feb_1993: Women on women</title>
<h1>Women on women</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>15 Feb 1993 16:26:49 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#136">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#136">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#136">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#136">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0137.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "The "thinking x's church""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0135.html">a11111arne@attmail.com: "Re: Is running a campaign appropriate?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0152.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Women on women"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Clearly I am not in a position to *properly* understand what it is like<br>
to be a female SDA. But I'd like to say two things anyway.<br>
<p>
1)	In my church women contribute a great deal; maybe they don't<br>
	appear up front *quite* as often as men, but it must be close.<br>
	We had a woman head elder for a while, and she did a superb<br>
	job coordinating, managing and leading our church of &gt;1000<br>
	over the time she had that office. <br>
<p>
2)	Most of the negative comments I have heard regarding the<br>
	ordination of women, or even regarding women leading out<br>
	in worship etc., have come from women. I don't think it was<br>
	due to societal role-sustaining either.<br>
<p>
One thing which does need to be addressed is the representation of<br>
women in the governing of the worldwide church. This issue goes further<br>
than just a women's thing, though.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
