<title>Feb_1993: The "thinking x's church"</title>
<h1>The "thinking x's church"</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>15 Feb 1993 16:36:29 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#137">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#137">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#137">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#137">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0138.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Can Satan read my mind? (Or yours?)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0136.html">PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "Women on women"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On what do we base the claim that the SDA church is the thinking person's<br>
church??<br>
<p>
Is it because we encourage each other to search the Scriptures for new<br>
light? Is it because we are so open to new ideas regarding issues such<br>
as origins? Is it because we are so creative in thinking up new ways<br>
to reach out to others, and eagerly adopt promising and innovative<br>
schemes? Or maybe because we encourage our youth to question their<br>
faith, search things out for themselves, and turn their inherited<br>
Adventism into Christianity?<br>
<p>
Yes, we are making progress, but we have a *long* way to go. <br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
